text: smells of oak , dried cherries , figs , smeels quite tasty ... nots of dark chocolate , run , raspberry syrup .  at the downtown chicago rock bottom , they named it rooftop pilsner for its rooftop dining area ( with a fine view of all the much taller yuppie condos surrounding it ) . they had to brew this in a hurry following the may windstorm that blew their rooftop taps open , draining all of their serving tanks ! pretty good for a style which we 've all had bad examples of . fizzy head leaves a golden yellow color underneath . no off-flaveors to speak of . nice citrsy hop aroma which i found to be a little stronger after a scoop of salsa . a decent session beer .
terrific retention , heavy lace . gorgeous lager .  id love for this to have a heavier mouthfeel , but this is a darn good session beer for a cold night .

aroma is intense with apple cider , yeast , and a touch of alcohol . smells exactly like hard cider . no hops . starts out nicely sour and tart , balanced by apple cider sweetness , phenolic esters , followed by a peppery warm wave of alcohol , fennel and anise .  m : the body is medium with a low carbonation and a tooth rotting sweetness . so unbearably sweet and sugary without any sort of balance .

this is an interesting concept , iam surprised there hasnt been more forays into melding the two styles.i poured into a weizen glass rather than my nonic for appearance and it poured nicely , hazed burnt orange tinged golden with a fluffy one and a half finger white head that left a broken ring of lace as it settled slowly.love the in your face citric hop aromas , really fresh , slight toasted wheat malt and clove as well.the mouthfeel was much thinner than expected and seemed to take a little of the flavor away , somewhat watery with decent shot of resiny/citric hop on the palate , toasted wheat malt again comes thru a little as well.if the mouthfeel was amped up a little this beer would be great but alas it isnt and the beer is just `` pretty good '' .  m-moderate carbonation , medium-bodied beer , with a noticeable hoppy dryness .
clear lava body with an active sudsy brilliant lavender head which recedes to a persistent half-pinkie of foam .  mouthfeel is way too light for what i was expecting .

clear yet dark purple mahogany without any carbonation under a cloud like frothy khaki surface of the moon cratered pour into me pint . plenty of visible lattice lace in the pint . liquid dessert appearance . it looks good , but this is all down hill from here .  m - average carbonation .

440 ml nitro can poured into a seidel yields a turbid , frothy drink that settles into a clear , pale copper body capped with a thick finger of glossy , creamy ivory foam that stubbornly refuses to recede and coats the glass in translucent sheets of lacing . glorious .  typical mouthfeel for a lager i guess , although i do n't know a lot about what this style should be like .

smells wonderfully complex . imitation vanilla extract mixed with bock malt , milk chocolate , alcohol , and black licorice .  light body and a bit watery , but the munich possesses a david-like flavor that surprises those who order it expecting something more saccharine .

a - a moderate pour released a gushing head . the loose bubbles hung on for a long time leaving some loose lacing . great appearance after the overflow mishaps .  very light and summer-appropriate . could drink several . definitely a solid brew .

it poured light orange in color with a very active white head nearly overflowing from the glass . great head retention with some thick sheets of lacing as i drank it .  like most light lagers , the only character to the smell and flavor comes from the malt , hops and water . there is a clear attention to the quality of ingredients , and a successful attempt at balance and smoothness . the mountain-filtered water imparts nothing offensive on the palate .
poured a deep dark lipton tea amber with a full head of white foam that slowly melted to very respectible lacing .  the body is a little thin for my likes .

very nice . taste : way too sweet , full of brown sugar . mouthfeel : medium-thin body with medium carbonation overall : way too sweet , and although the smell is truly fantastic , i couldnt finish it . without added sugar , probably a very nice warming winter brew , with the sugar , better stay away from it .  this is a good straightforward ale . light golden yellow color , a little fizzy but nothing a little harder pour into the glass did n't take care of . lighter flavor but has a nice balance for whats there . nice little hop background that comes through the nose.it 's drinkable also .

pours thickly with a great deal of body , very dark reddish mahogany , looking opaque black in the glass . nice frothy head of fine bubbles , dark tan , that dissipates and leaves thin lacing all the way down . great appearance set the bar high , but it was all downhill after the pour .  feels a bit watered-down in the mouth , but flavor is there and we 're not talking corona . a little fizzy .

a : pours a dark , cloudy orange with three fingers of off-white head that recedes into a dense cap with good lacing .  mouthfeel : light and highly carbonated and a bit sour and tart overall : honestly this is my first experience with fantome and it is just awful .

bottle poured into pint glass a : finger sized head head that lasts on top of a dark brew s : peppermint , liquorish , dark malts and alcohol . t : excessive bitterness for a porter making this beer more of a stout than a porter .  m : thin and light with average carbonation .
very strong retention with lots of webby lace . beautiful !  medium thin body .
very pleasing smell . t : again , very sweet and boozy .  [ postscript : 18 months later , and another 6-pack of this enjoyed , the mouthfeel was much less sticky , but way too carbonated .

gorgeous though , one of the most visually appealing beers i 've seen .  it has abrasive bitterness from the start on through the finish , increasing in intensity and lasting well on into the aftertaste with stinging astringency . yes , there 's some raisin , toffee , and booze on the taste as an undercurrent that shows through on the finish pretty well ... .but absolutely nothing approaches the hoppiness here .
anyway ... pours a wondferul dark gold , amber with a thick thick creamy lacing head . beautiful .  mouthfeel - medium..maybe a little on the more watery side , but still creamy-ish .

it 's as delicious smelling as it is complex . with the president set by the nose , the taste is a small disappointment , even though it carries through with the same elements in varying degrees . while it has a couple rough patches , it 's an enjoyable weizenbock .  slightly creamy body , though it falls flat at the front of the palate . it could use ( i ca n't believe i 'm saying this ) a bit more carbonation . or more body .

the retention was impressive as the head turned rocky after a while and the lacing was equally respectable .  ( from notes ) i picked this beer up while living in dublin , i poured it from a .5l can into a pint glass ... a : a nice roasted dark brown nearly black color , with a tannish head , decent lacing ... s : the smell is pretty weak but i am getting some faint burnt malt and slight coffee ... t : the taste is about the same except more fully roasted flavor ... m : smooth and watery ... d : a decent beer from guinness , but once you have had their special export to belgium , you wonder why they make anything else .

awesome smell ... this one really shows off a great bouquet of hops . about as good as it gets here . still good , with the great hop character , but not quite as good as the nose .  good carbonation and a softly crisp , dryish , smooth medium-light bodied mouthfeel . thin , watery , sweet pale malts , sort like if you dunked a slice of white sweet bread into a glass of water , light lemony flavor with an even lighter amount of hop spiciness , a very , very mild bitterness towards the end , and a dryish sweet malty finish .

this is one of the nicest smelling glasses of beers i 've ever had the good fortune to stick my nose into . sweet caramel , dark fruit , some bready yeasty goodness .  well carbonated and only a mild body . expecting and would have liked something a little thicker .

nice thick , vicious look to this ; above average lacing & some head retention s : green bananas , dark fruit , fusel booze and brown bread . t : dark fruit , candi sugar , & green bananas up front , pretty much mimics the nose , some doughy notes plus green appleskins .  feels light , but not as light as a lager and lightly carbonated .

i 've never had this on tap , and as such , feel that canned beer always has a metallic flavor the appearance is excellent with a nice cascade effect as it 's poured with an attractive clear copper color . good head retention as well .  that smokiness carries over abundantly into the taste . the lesser side of this is the feel ... bit to far on the light end of things . overall though , solid rauchbier , though probably my least favorite so far of the aecht schlenkerla rauch 's .

appearance : one of the prettiest beers i have ever seen . arrives in a root beer mug with a coffee brown body and a frothy tan head that would outdo anything starbuck 's puts on top of its lattes ; plenty of lacing all the way downt the side of the glass smell : vague but noticeable brown bread roasted malt nose taste : very bready at the start with a subtle , but fruity , hops kick that joins mid-palate ; the finish has a nice coffee flavor , too mouthfeel : light/medium bodied with low carbonation drinkability : very nice balanced flavor profile ; just a little light on the mouthfeel  mouthfeel : light bodied with moderate carbonation , slightly drying leaving that coffee dryness on the palate .
pours black wit a nice tan halo that laces nicely down the glass .  mouthfeel : the weight and carbonation do well , nothing bad to say about it , nothing extraordinary .
smells great but i feel a little let down by the taste .  the carbonation felt on the high side to me .

33cl bottle poured into an imperial pint glass a- jet stealthy black body with creamy tan head . fantastic head retention and lacing s- harsh roasted malt .  really malty tasting , also was considerably less sweet then i had expected . smelled a bit like cocoa and malt . was really lite for a porter . not bad but not my favorite porter out there . it may have been better had i let it breathe , still not a bad porter though .

what a great looking beer , so dark and the head is big and beautiful and sticks around with some lacing .  but overall , mouthfeel was ok. after having a couple bottles of this in the past , felt this was a terrific sixtel to kick off the summer .

very rustic labeling , i like it . the smell is unique . it has a ton of citrus an coriander , it almost smells like a wild witbier .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with low to medium carbonation . smooth , easy to drink , but gets kind of muddy in the finish like some of the other nognes i 've had , which kind of makes my mouth feel dirty , but good winter beer nonetheless .

it smells great . it has this gumballhead mixed with ipa aroma to it . the content is very deceptive .  light bodied , without much of a mouthfeel , just a very slight slickness left on the tongue . other than the mouthfeel , this was a pretty decent example of the style .

i got a chance to try this at cobblestone 's last night -served chilled in a pils glass . the beer is downright beautiful , dare i say elegant looking in the glass ? the pale is brilliant golden with amber hues and has great clarity with thick sturdy cap of snow white . the lace clings in rings and bead is fine , good retention all around .  mouthfeel is average , not too thin , and i think appropriate for this beer .
s - delicious smell , lots of tropical fruits and some piney resin . the finish is good , and the carbonation is very pleasing .  mouthfeel : a little thin , but not watery .
nitro can produces a mega creamy , beige coloured head that sticks around forever and leaves lots of lace .  mouthfeel was on the thin side , but a creamy finish evened it out to average at best .
a : deep copper color , clear , great rocky head s : malty nose , dry , oxidation noticeable but not incredibly bad for 24 years !  its has a light mouth feel for a stout .
a : pours a bright clear golden color with a huge fluffy white head . lots of chunky lacing left behind .  m : pretty darn thick and syrupy .

pours an opaque black with one finger of frothy mocha head and speckles of sticky lacing on the tulip .  the mouthfeel on a doppelbock is a tricky thing -- too thick and you wo n't be able to drink your half-liter bottle , let alone your full liter mass .

ample white , creamy cover has a good amount of stickiness and lace , nice . aroma - juicy pineapple , grapefruit , and a resiny pine as well . taste - fair biscuity malt base , followed immediately by a stiff resiny smack of hops .  mouthfeel is ok , but a bit to thin for what i expect from a stout .

and it smells fantastic ! a truly great smelling beer . t- wow .  t & m : slightly alcoholic bite at first . very fizzy taste of citrus with a somewhat sour lemony wheat taste . d : very fizzy so will fill ( bloat ) you quickly . exemplary of the style .
appearance - perfect light color with a think almost chewable yeasty head .  m - thin on the mouth , ok carbonation .

appearance - pours a very dark , rich brown , almost black , with a finger of dense , khaki-colored head .  i thought i did n't like saisons until i tried this one . kind of a mild coconutty taste , almost pina colada like ? i 'm going to revisit this one for sure whenever i get a chance .

aroma is of bitter orange peel and spicy yeast . smell is wonderful . upon sipping , the first thing that struck me was the medium to heavy body on this one .  deep red-brown color with amazing billowy off-white head : thick and lasting with good lacing s : hoppy and malty balance with yeasty notes and spices t : orange and nutmeg maltiness with a hoppy bitter finish m : a little thin , but this is towards the end of its season by now .

reviewed from notes a - poured into a standard pint glass a wonderous midnight black that had a one finger mocha head resulting in massive , massive side lacing .  moderate to thin mouthfeel , carbonation is ok . my only problem with this is the mouthfeel was n't as creamy as i was expecting , but overall , a very nice stout .

a : slightly hazy orange light copper color with pillowing white head . great head retention especially considering the abv .  the taste ends with a really nice strong bitterness that lingers on the palate for quite awhile . the carbonation seems to be moderate perhaps a little more on the high scale but seems to be average for the style .
the color is beauitful and the head looks nice sitting on top of the glass .  mouthfeel : medium bodied . low carbonation .

pours with a brownish-red body topped by a thick off-white head with good lace left on the glass .  maybe some floral hops and a quite malty after taste which i didnt mind at all . the whole mix is very plain .

pours a beautiful crystal-clear golden hue with a rush of carbonation bubbles racing to the service . a very inviting looking brew . looks more like a pilsner than my image of a marzen , but still appealing visually .  it tastes excellent as it has a nice coffee and roasted taste which compliment that big hops very well , this beer is very drinkable as it doesnt have that `` back of your throat dryness '' that some ipas tend to exhibit . you could drink this all night if you were an ipa fan .
the appearance is stellar on this one . it 's a cloudy red color with a reddish tan head to it .  carbonation is a little too pronounced .

appearance : dark brown to black with large pillowy head after an aggressive pour . the head recedes more slowly than i would have thought leaving nice lacing .  flavor and mouthfeel both lighter than expected , especially for a stout . medium-high carbonation .

poured a slight hazed well blonde of course with a huge blooming white head that caught me off guard almost overflowing the glass and it took its sweet time coming down leaving a soap-scum like trace behind.love the hops in the nose citrus oil dominates with underlying pine and lightly toasted grain , a grainy lighter mouthfeel not watery just on the thinner side.bright flavors of floral hop and citrus not overly complex by any means a light toastiness underneath the hops but not much in malt complexities but it goes down oh so easily for 7.5 % alc let me tell ya.hmm a good beer if not complex , a good summer quaffer and the biggest blonde ale i have had to date .  overall : mouthfeel is about standard , nothing special .

s- lots of cinnamon , pumpkin , nutmeg , and citrus . very aromatic t- lot of natural pumpkin , ginger , and nutmeg , cinnamon , seltzer like taste , and quite a bit of graininess . o- an okay pumpkin ale , the flavor was not nearly as robust as the aroma though .  the body is quite a bit thinner now after a couple of years of age . the finish is a bit astringent and dry . the astringency almost has a pine/ spruce thing going on that contributes to drying out my mouth after each sip .

a - espresso brown with a one finger cream/tan head with impressive retention and a nice amount of lacing .  m : a little thinner than i am used to for imperial stouts , but it still has a heavy body . the mouthfeel is n't is a little sharp from high carbonation , would love a creamier texture here .

a hazy orange gold with a nice thick white head that leaves decent lacing on the glass smell is of piney and citrusy hops followed by some pale/caramel malts .  the body is a bit thinner than i would like , but then again this is a porter , not a stout , so viscosity is not a foremost requirement .
poured a silky black with a nice creamy off-white head . did n't leave much lacing .  moderate carbonation and a light , slightly watery mouthfeel .

from the hand pump into an imperial nonic this brew appears a dark brown that displays some ruby clarity when held to the light . a beautiful fluffy tan creamy head sits atop the brew with a finger 's strength and it retains perfectly throughout the duration of the experience .  there is a slight floral hop scent to go along with the malt aroma that you would expect from a beer this dark . this is a flavorful lager . it 's malty without being sweet and there is just enough hoppyness to leave a bite on the tongue .

pours yields a hazy light golden brew with a substantial head of thick white foam with really fantastic retention and a lot of lacing as it goes down .  m : nothing wild here ... medium-bodied with moderate carbonation ; hoppy finish , yet sweet and not dry .

thats no fun ... a- the beer pours out a glowing golden orange colored body with a minuscule off white head . the head quickly becomes no more than a crown but leaves behind a solid wall of lacing . pretty nice .  it is perhaps on the thin side and sweet side and is not too complex , but has good character that hold up well .

smells sweet with bubblegum and marshmallows with a little hint of lime , but the sweetness is contained with an awesome , herbal spiciness . if you just pour this one into your glass and just look at it and smell it , you wont be disappointed . sadly , the flavor isnt all too hot .  thin body , decent carbonation .

11.2-ounce brown bottle poured into a tulip glass . pours a nicely clear copper-brown with a huge billowing head of beige foam that shows excellent retention , leaving fat patchy rings of lacing down the sides of the glass , settling to a thick cap that holds out until the finish .  taste- almost the same as the smell with a malt/roasted taste up front with a strong coffee finish . overall i like this brew . one of the most significant coffee smelling and tasting brews i 've had . good stuff
fantastic belgian lacing left behind as the head dies down . truly a perfect looking beer , this is just sexy .  mouthfeel is thin and creamy smooth .
this beer pours a beautiful head .  it 's a little too thin for my taste , but like i said i could easily drink this all night and this is why .
cloudy dark amber color with a huge frothy head and excellent lacing .  thin bodied but slightly creamy .

superb appearance !  mouthfeel was medium with a faint taste of saaz hops on the tongue . pale lager ? ! ? i might have gone with pilsner , which is a lager , plus the label mentions both ale and lager , further confusing things . the finish was unpleasant with a harsh metallic taste lingering well after the swallow .

the nose also shines.. it 's belgian sweetness accented by a unique floral combination of spicy zings and zips . for a lighter , saison style beer , this showcases alot of the darker , overripe belgian-associated fruits in the nose like figs and dates . also , a dark brown sugar syrup aroma wafts ... competes fiercely with the scents of a flower garden . this is one outrageously complex nose to wrestle with . thick and spicy ... that 's the best way to describe this . a base more suited to a bspa allows for a silky , syrupy , stomach-warming beer that insists on sipping for enjoyment . very floral character is perfumy in the way that hops are n't , and the bitterness associated can be quite jarring . almost like eating the non-edible petal of something aromatic like a rose . perhaps not the most drinkable beer due to three floyds ' patented excess , but a noble effort at a style- applause-worthy .  nose ... oh , that great `` red '' smell ... hops and spice with some sweentess thrown in for good measure , west coast floral represented well , just a great pleasant hop aroma caresed by cinnamon.. delish.. mouth etc ... carbonation then the real bite of spice and hops , a little watery at times but the flavor is fantastic , refreshing and crisp as it gets toward the end of the glass.. very enjoyable verdict ?

bottle , with santa claus on the label , a : pours a dark , turbid brown , with a huge , voluminous white head , almost like a duvel in size , which leaves generous lacing .  m : the body is medium with a moderate to high level of carbonation .

the aroma is wonderful , which was my favorite aspect of the beer .  poured chilled in large pint glass a : black , no head , not many carbs , not much lacing s : malty , hoppy , sharp in the nose ; persistent t : sophisticated dark , charcoal , nearly burned in flavor ; very hoppy ; tastes heftier than the 7 % abv . very powerful , superb black ale .

great lacing & head retention s : breadyness & pine & not much else , even that fades over time t : follows the nose , some caramel & vanilla as well up front , along with some woody hops .  mouth feel is medium bodied , but i think it could use a bit more carbonation .

pours a deep , cherry-oak color with a almost burnt-orange head . also has two-fingers of solid foam , with intricate lacing .  to me , this beer is more like a porter than a stout . not very creamy . the tart cherry flavor is at first a bit exciting to the tongue , but it gets old quickly . i ca n't see having more than one of these at a time . the smell of the cherry is nice the whole way through .

incredible retention . the beer is a very dark brown and looks is opaque .  appearance : nut brown , creamy white head that forms a skim coat smell : smoky ( obviously ) , very much like smoked pork : greasy and slightly metallic ; some noble hops are evident but not prominant ; tinny and some very faint fruity esters taste : predominantly smoky , with the same sort of tinny metallic character as in the nose ; no bitterness , omly smoke mouthfeel : medium body , perhaps a little on the lighter side ; little apparent carbonation ; kind of flat and a little watery this si the marzen 's little brother .

s : smells very good , of cranberries , of course , and ripe apples , a full smell that hits you as soon as you open the bottle . there is a nice cranberry undercurrent of flavour there , but it is too damn sweet to be very appealing , almost like soda pop .  m : carbonation balance is nothing special .

the fine and dense head got smooth and aired and it lasted nicely on the hazy and active golden color body .  i instantly fell in love with this blond , frothy , pilsner-style beer . i had it on tap at a pizzeria chain with a seriously respectable draught list ( brixx in chapel hill , nc ) . scrimshaw has the best possible hop character as far as i am concerned -- floral without being too aggressive or bitter . some belgian-style lacing on the glass . dangerously drinkable . i 've had it from a bottle since ( okay , a few bottles ) , and it is just as great . i plan on making this the beer of summer 2011 , as it is important to have a plan .

at least four fingers of towering , foamy , white head , and great lacing- one side of my glass looks like it has a head of its own .  mf : a bit flat , could use a boost in the carbonation department .

12 oz bottle poured into a pilsner glass . my weizen glass was dirty . ) a : opaque orange-yellow with honey highlights and a tall creamy white head . hills and valleys of lacing cling to the sides of the glass .  this harp was brewed in canada by moosehead . this is a very satisfying beer ; especially when all the over-hopped , over-malted , extreme productions . become too much ... which is the true beauty of this harp . it is straight forwardly flavorful without making great demands on the palate . lively with a clean finish . this is the first harp i have sampled in a few years , and is easily the most tasty i have ever encountered .

s : the first think i can think of when i smell this beer is chocolate covered coffee beans . it is one of the best smelling beers to me .  in terms of style , the mouthfeel was flawless . however , since it is packaged as a winter brew i feel it falls short of the mark . imo , the carbonation is too coarse , or the body a bit too thin , for a `` winter warmer '' .

this one pours a nice opaque black in the glass with nice a tan/brown head that has good retention . a perfect picture of a stout .  tasted in at the brewery on a breezy december day in tustin . aroma minimal . just a little bready . pale gold in color , minimal head . some chill haze . light body with a noticeable grain sweetness . a very easy touch of floral hops . an excellent example of a drinkable light ale .
the best part of the pour is the amazing head . the lacing is tremendous really sticking to the glass .  m : a little bit too light for the style but it helps the drinkability .

poured out of a bomber about an inch above the glass gives you a big light tan head that lasts quite a while before fading into a pretty decent lacing above a clear beer with a deep amber caramel hue that reminded me of a thick farm honey color . a very appealing looking beer in the glass .  there 's a strong taste of spices that sets the tone of the drink and towards the end of the mouthfeel it turns slightly bitter although all in all the beer feels fairly balanced .

reviewed 1/17/2007 ( 750ml bottle ) : pours a dark red/brown/black . tannish white head , very fine bubbles , creamy looking . good lacing .  m suitably moderate to big but nothing extreme like an ris .

forming a very foamy 2 inch off white head . very constant carbonation rise . the head takes several minutes to settle , leaving mounds of clumpy foam and plenty of very thick curtains of sticky lace .  the mouthfeel is a little light , but not overly so .
it 's a beautiful rusty brown copper , with a nice foamy off-white head , and exceptional lacing . looks delicious .  m : very normal carbonation .

this is a beautiful beer , it has good color and looks quite appealing , however i thought that the mismatch of its grapefruit aroma and it 's highly tart smell and it 's low citrus draw made it oddly unstable on the palate .  this is a fantastic dark beer . if you are use to the typical light american style of beer this one probably is n't for you . however if you like a dark brewed beer with a strong flavor and finish this is the beer for you . also at $ 20 a case it is a nice money saving change of pace for a guiness drinker .

s- hibiscus flowers , strawberries , a bit of belgian funk , and maybe some honey . very complex and appealing . t- hibiscus flowers , honey , with a sweet malt backing .  4.5 m a bit on the thin side .

smell : first off , i really love dried apricots . the scent is entirely built on dried apricots therefore i enjoyed it quite a bit . taste and mouthfeel : the taste is primarily that of dried apricots only slightly less sweet .  unremarkable mouthfeel , but the drinkability is pretty solid on this one .

zero lacing & head retention s : awesome sour/lactic odors t : an almost sugary sweetness is quickly steamrolled by sourness tartness & dry/wood notes .  the lack of flavor is the most important part , it 's more like a watery , sour drink with a bit of beer added . i guess that is malt , but it 's ... light . on the bright side , it 's refreshing at first and there is no really offensive `` off '' flavor 's , i 'm not picking up any metal and it 's rather clean .

aroma is exquisite - spices , yeast , malt , fruit , herbs , in an exotic blend that is beguiling . flavor 's not as intriguing as the nose , but still pretty good . reminds me of a good saison .  the taste was strong sour vinegar with some cherry and alcohol flavors . this one upset my stomach and i think this 2005 vintage was past its prime . god only knows what it was like fresh . this beer was not good and i happen to like sour beers .
a-dark ruby brown with a nice thick tan head s-syrup and salted caramel ... and soy sauce..strong aroma .  m : a little out of style ... pretty light bodied with good carbonation .

i thought this was a great beer and gave the smell a 5 for the style for the amazing chocolate smell . a - dark small foam head really brown s - rated as exceptional because it nails the style it is going for a deep dark chocolate . it really does nail it too . t - great if you like chocolate not so great if not it is sweet but well blended and tasty . m - again chocolate , smokey , nice .  mouthfeel : full-bodied , low carbonation . there 's an odd chalkiness .
appearance- dark mahogany brown with a huge billowy head .  aggressive fizzy carbonation .

aroma is wonderfully full of sweet malt , dark fruits , light fruits and spices . aroma may be the most balanced combination i 've ever had the pleasure of enjoying . not so shabby ... kind of nice .  tastes almost like graham crackers with spicy hops m - medium everything d - very drinkable , probably the best session beer

i loved the color . the head is nice and big , white , creamy , fluffy , and beautiful .  poured into a traditional english mug , typically reserved for a cream ale at my favorite pub in downtown minneapolis , lyon 's pub . after removing the orange slice that i did n't think to ask without , the taste is of wheaty malt and orange rind . this beer goes down quite easy . a great summer drink and heads and shoulders above blue moon . not being from the midwest , it is n't available to me or it would become my new summer session beer .

the aroma is heavenly ! ..think sweet , dark hazelnut coffee , maple syrup and vanilla . really amazing aroma . taste is initially brisk flavor hops , dark sweet malt , some burnt sugar , giving way to a chocolate and coffee finish .  the color was the only thing remotely impressive about the beer i thought , it was a fine dark reddish color with a medium body , there was almost no head ( maybe a half inch ) . this beer has a very weird taste , almost like bubble gum mixed with some fruit and spices . for me this is typical of magic hat , i only really enjoy the heart of darkness . the after taste was even funkier than the initial flavor , i doubt i 'd drink this again .
smell is very smokey with roasted malt , the smoke really takes hold of this beer .  the feel is a little to light , almost watery .
appearance : is dark amber maybe even reddish ; it 's very clear and the head is super frothy with a long lasting tan foam .  m : medium but complex body with minimal carbonation .

sweet jesus this is an aromatic beer . had a pint of cask conditioned last night , and halfway through it my saliva glands had gone dry . this beer has a wonderful fresh hop aroma . aroma might even be too subtle a word for it . it was a powerful smell , obviously it had been dry hopped .  this beer drinks very easily ; it is actually pretty light on the mouthfeel , a little creamy smooth , but mostly just light .
one of the best heads i 've ever seen . very thicka and frothy .  very mild flavor and mouthfeel , but very lively and well carbonated .
excellent head retention and a whole lot of sticky lacing . a mouth watering beautiful ipa , probably the best looking i 've seen .  a bit light bodied with ample carbonation .

pours hazy orange body with a tornado of dark yeast swirling around . head is big and frumpy , extremely long lasting and clingy .  mouthfeel was fine . a little thin - i think that a big , thick mouthfeel would accentuate the pumpkin pie-like characteristic that i think they 're going for .

bottle crystal clear mahogany , with lots of ruby highlights . large , creamy , light brown colored head .  very easy to drink ! it has the feel of any other wheat beer , but the watermelon taste is so unique that it simply floored me . initially , i thought the color seemed very artificial which made me expect an artificial flavor . there is little up front beyond a generic wheat beer , but in the aftertaste lies a brilliant watermelon flavor ! it is easy to drink and not very filling . it is slightly more alcoholic than your run of the mill macrobrews making it possible to drink a great many of these at any given time . it 's a good beer to give to new beer drinkers . it 's an excellent example of how diverse craft beers can be !

s- bomber with the best seasonal label i 've ever seen a- much , much better looking than i expected . a bright golden orange . amazing color .  body seems to lighten a little on the swallow , maybe just the ease of consumption but takes away on the mouthfeel score for me .

very clean and very aromatic . taste : the tropical fruit hop flavor really is the main note in the flavor profile . overall , a nice , aromatic ipa with good tropical fruit notes .  slightly watery with a dry finish , a la guinness . medium effervescence . nice warming alcohol bloom . relatively rich for a weak body .

like most , if not all , moonlight beers , this is beautiful , being dark amber with a big , creamy light tan head that lasts forever and leaves thick lacing .  a bit thin in the mouthfeel but nothing off-putting .

smells *intensely* of grapefruits , with a hint of pine trees and cloves . i could smell this all night ! taste is just a *hint* of golden brown sugar and rum , before a barrage of hops obliterates everything else . this stuff is bitter !  it had a medium feel to it in my mouth with ok carbonation .

pours a clear yellowish gold , thick white head forms , slowly drops to a thick layer leaving some nice chunks of lace on the glass , good retention .  m - medium-bodied , but a bit too hoppy on the finish to be as refreshing as it should be .
a - golden hazy yellow , with a beautiful white fluffy head s - lemon , some coriander and spices ( cinnamon ? ) , and wheat .  great finish , though a little thin .
huge sour aroma of lemons and green apples taht really leaps out at you .  m : thin , fizzy and cutting .
a : a blackish-brown body with a creamy tan head . nice head retention and lacing .  lighter bodied , thinner carbonation .

the aroma is one of the best from a wit i 've ever had . the taste disappointment after the great aromatics . it 's pretty bland , and it misses all of the citrus and spice found in the nose . slight spice , and a lot of the strange , off flavors i find in a lot of adjunct lagers .  finishes dry with light floral hoppiness m : light bodied and medium carbonated .
nutty , peanut butter aromas , with hints of caramel and toffee , doughy yeast and a light hint of banana and clove . not very good , but wow , what an aroma .  m : yeah , i guess .

superior lacing & head retention s : bready notes , some lemony notes , not as much as i hoped for ... t : grassy & lemony hops , plus sweet grainy notes , slight grapefruit hop smack as well & some honey notes up front .  mf : thin for a baltic porter , the big flavor makes up for this , medium carbonation d : this beer has a ton of things going on and i must say it is well executed .
it is a beautiful looking beverage .  m - light to medium body , medium carbonation . very slight harsh bitterness lingers on the back of the tongue .

real juicy malt aroma . caramel and toffee wrapped around fig and spices .  appearance - horseblanket smell - horseblanket taste - horseblanket mouthfeel - horseblanket just kidding about the appearance and mouthfeel ( kinda ) .

intense tropical fruit salad aroma of passionfruit , orange , mango , lime . distinctive nz hop aroma . gorgeous . sweet white wine and sorbet also . very hop forward , full flavours yet for a double/imperial ipa - extremely low on bitterness . o - beautiful beer . extremely tasty and seriously drinkable , absolutely no indication of the 7.3 % abv . but i just love it . more !  a little grassy , little grainy and a bit watery . slight softness to feel from carbonation , otherwise not that soft and too thin .

whiffs of cotton candy and sweet cinamon bread come to mind . sweet cookie dough and biscuity malts . great aroma . the mouthfeel seems a little empty . the taste does not follow through to the extent that i 'd like with the aroma , but some nice qualities to exist . sweet candied tones and the `` menage a trois '' of figs , raisins and dates .  m- not a bad mouthfeel i just felt it to be average . light on the tongue , a little too dry and yet somewhat of a lingering aftertaste .

the head on this makes the appearance , a awesome tope head with great retention and lacing that coats the glass the whole drinking experience top to bottom ... the aroma is like a malty ipa , lots of caramel , with grass wet hops , its really appetizing ... taste is grass hops that have a fresh bite which is nice , maybe that bite is the rye .  it was a little over carbonated for my likes but still had a great feel to it in my mouth .

damn fine looking beer- translucent brown with rusty orange highlights and a kick-ass tan head .  i poured this guinness into my tumbler at 45 degrees . the beer was very black and bore out a big tan head . the beer smells like a guinness as it should . the taste was big molasses but the brew had a bit of a dry finish . i like the beer and will buy again .

for a beer that could almost fool some people into thinking they are drinking sparkling wine , this beer almost filled my room with apple . the most intense fruit beer ive ver tried , ive had it in growler and bottle , growler was alittle better , but for being a apple beer it wasnt as easy to drink as id think . had a little bit of a weird aftertaste , but im looking forward to trying the other ephemere styles like cherry , grape , etc .  m - nice light carbonation and creaminess , but the body is a little light and watered down .

very interesting . taste in line with the nose , with the licorice even more asseritve upfront in the palate .  light in body , but crisp and sufficiently dextrinous in mouthfeel to help lend excellent drinkability . lightly carbonated . perhaps a bit thin , but otherwise outstanding .
the beer pours a dark maroon color with a full head . it really is a beautiful pour with a great rich hue .  very little carbonation , the beer feels light but also dense .

it pours to a dark golden amber color with a few continuous jetstreams of bubbles rising to the top to support the delicate off-white head .  m : very medium-light body and a slightly bitter but almost watery finish .

aroma - awesome aroma of malt and hops . probably too hoppy a beer just from the aroma for me .  appearance : high carbonation , 1/4 inch head , cloudy , yellowish-green smell : wheat , and melon taste : very watermelon -- almost like a watermelon jolly rancher , bready wheat , with some small hops near the end mouthfeel : sweet , light/smooth body , high carbonation , slight bitter taste in the end .

absolutely love the smell . super piny/citrusy hops , maybe a little orange or grapefruit type smell in there t - the taste really catches you off guard . intensely bitter and dry , super hoppy as one would imagine m - nice carbonation , a little less than i expected , dry and a strong lingering in the back of the mouth d - although i love just about every aspect of this beer , i couldnt see my self drinking it all night or sessioning more than a couple .  carbonation is too high , but it tastes pretty clean and fresh .

out of a nitro can this is a classic and beautiful beer . black , even when held up to the light and a creamy smooth head . one of my favorites before i really knew anything about beer .  m : very carbonated .

i had this beer poured from a bottle into a pint glass ... a : the beer is an orange hued golden with a small white head which quickly fades away to nothing ... s : the smell is nice . tart citric fruit and a sweet artificial apricot smell ... t : the taste is the same as the smell just a little muted .  thanks kplynch for the bottle . color is orange amber with a variety of floral hops hitting the aroma . it 's on the lighter side , but tasty . just not really living up to the imperial in ipa . i 'd call it a well balanced , smooth ipa with notes of citrus and floral hops ...

a : pours a fantastic golden-orange . slightly opaque , with a voluminous yellow head . nice retention , and great lacing . phenomenal .  mouthfeel : light for darker beer . nothing special . but as in mouthfeel , nothing here will blow your brains out .
smell was amazing . lots of bananas and some spicy notes . very nice .  m - not bad , but a little thinner than i was hoping for .

cork and caged , no visible date information thick white head , golden orange hue , thick lacing aroma is very citrusy , tart , peppery on the finish .  m : very light carbonation but there is just a bit to give the beer some levity .

a - crisp and translucent copper body topped by a somewhat frothy eggshell colored head standing over an inch tall .  m - nothing really too exciting here . the bottle i got was not really crisp , not really flat , not thick or thin , a little silky do to the alcohol , but nothing to write home about ... d - i just noticed that i 'm killing off a bottle of this stuff by myself ... thank god it 's a cool night , this will warm me right up .

a 2 '' tall , creamy , fluffy , almost edible off-white head forms . the brew is a nice golden color .  speaking purely from personal preferance , this beer looks about as close to perfect as any i 've had . spice and hops stand out in the nose . nice balance of malt , hops , and spices . a little thin-bodied -- this beer 's only flaw .

the pour begins with an ever-expanding head that forms quickly and sorta takes over . very mousse-like and very sturdy in formaiton and retention . the color is the standard copper-golden and with typical dry-hopped haze . an outstanding look .  the body is light and the carbonation is very high .

mikkeller beer geek breakfast is an opaque black beer with a dark muscovado colored head that gets blotchy and has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel is slightly thin , with lower carbonation , not bad .

the beer appears dark ruby colored with a thick tan head . lasting retention and plenty of lacing coats the tulip glass .  body is a little thin for an oatmeal stout , but it still has the smoothness . carbonation feels a little too heavy for this style i think .

pours a very clear light copper color with a large and impressive cap of off-white head . retention is very good , as is the lacing . an exceptional looking beer .  felt a little weak in the mouth , not much texture .

s - chipotle comes out immediately along side semi sweet chocolate , coffee grinds , hints of anise , light hickory smoke , and chocolate liqueur .  medium to thin in the body . i thought the carbonation seemed a bit to high and lessened my enjoyment of this brew .

a- this beer poured a gorgous amberish orange color with a huge fluffy white cream colored head . the body is slightly hazy and there are some gigantic horizontal mountains of lacing from the head that cling to the glass .  this beer contains the same yeasty , yummy taste as other delirium beers . as a series , their three beers do n't go out of their way to be different from the others . in my opinion , tastes just like tremens with more color ( it looks like carbonated jack daniels ) and more seasonal flavor ( smells of strong caramel and tastes much more tart and spicy than other deliriums ) . had this a month or so ago in a 750ml bottle from a local pub , and it was labelled `` noel '' . to me , it tasted slightly different , or maybe because that night it was my first beer .

probably the most beautiful pour i 've seen . sizable chocolate colored head almost `` rolled '' up the pint glass and stuck around for a long while . black as night , a little deep coffee color at the edges .  and a bit thin d-easy and enjoyable , drinks almost like a session ale .

367th review on ba bottle to tulip 750 ml cap & cork 086/477044 app- sunshine yellow with a gigantic three finger bell filling head . very good looking saison .  mouthfeel is a little thin , but the taste more than makes up for it .

the nose is a sweet and sour explosion of tropical fruit , pineapple , fresh garden herbs , bright juniper pine , and bubblegum . the slightest breath of alcohol , caramel backbone , and some spice seeps through as it warms . a joyous aroma , i 'd like it in a body wash . the flavor is a tropical and herbal hop jungle . the malt bill is caramel and a bit buttery .  the mouthfeel is clean and crisp , with less body than i 'd hoped for .
smells really really good . beer is medium bodied and has a good hop character to it .  m : for a stout the mouthfeel is awfully simple , though the sweet notes add some much needed depth .

s : smells amazing ! hops immediately hit the nose and give you a first-hand experience of why it is called `` hopslam '' .  it does leave with bit of a skunky after-taste but its a small aspect of this otherwise delicious beer , m-medium carbonation with a slight watery finish d-the taste seems to lose its quality but it does n't seem to take too much of a dive . its a very thick beer so it does seem to go down slowly .
light brown to off-white head . great retention .  i felt this beer was too carbonated and hence it was too slick and creamy in my mouth .
smell is quite strong . i could smell it after the pour from an arm 's length . very bitter and hoppy , slight sweet malt aroma .  well balanced m : a little coppery and bitter .

a : a honey yellow - orangish hue , slightly hazy , with a soft and creamy foam head . head caught in the top of the weizen glass as it should - the got it pretty much right on this .  the body seems a bit watery , but matches well with the rest of the beer and makes this highly drinkable .
appearance : a gorgeously intense brown/amber color with a tremendously dense tan head that lasts and lasts and lasts .  mouthfeel is very syrupy and cloying with a potent kick of alcohol .

appearance : this is a dark , dark beer , with a thick and creamy head , that you can cut with a knife . very decent lacing .  mouthfeel : does n't feel bad , just tastes bad . decent body and texture .

beautiful clear mahogany . fine tight beige head settles to a thin complete cap . just a beautiful beer .  m - my only complaint about this beer , wish it would thicken up a bit . approriate carbonation .

life & limb is a lively , dim , reddish brown ale with a dense , waxy , khaki head that has outstanding retention and lacing .  mouthfeel was pretty average drinkability was pretty good i could see myself having another one .

12 oz bottle app : great amber with a lasting cap and lacing smell : honey and caramel apple malt dominate .  very thin body and i could easily put away six of these . i feel it is a little thin overall and that would be something i would like to see changed .

the aroma of this one is pretty intense . rich dark malty odor but also some sweet hints in there as well .  m : smooth , full-bodied , but the lack of carbonation makes it a bit watery , the booze can stand out at times . d : this is certainly a tasty beer , but it is very expensive , and at the end of the day i prefer regular old viscosity more , especially with it 's nicer carbonation , body , and the fact that it is considerably cheaper .

dumped in to a footed glass . brilliantly clarity , tawny amber .  m -- maybe i should n't have drank this after sipping on a j.w . its not quite what i would call `` watery , '' but it could use a little more body . carbonation levels are fine .

extraordinarily enjoyable , i 've had double ipa 's that do n't smell this good . not nearly as complex as the smell would indicate .  definitely lacking in mouthfeel - expected something fuller and creamier .
a - thick , light brown head that stays forever . opaque black except for a tint of dark ruby on the edges .  the feel is a little too thin .
pours out to a thick opaque black , forming a nice whipped dark espresso crema head with amazing retention and one sticky sheet of lace .  medium body , but maybe a bit thin , moderate carbonation .

that 's 90 % of what 's there , and it 's beautiful . taste : this shows more of the alcohol than is perceptible in the nose , as well as a nice firm hop bitterness and bite . this is a bit simplistic , but good . mouthfeel : big and smooth drinkability : pretty high conclusion : the aromas are so much more pungent on-tap than out of the bottle , and are some of the best i 've ever smelled on a dipa .  sampled this beer at founders own tap room . the beer was way too sweet . the malts from the stout style could not overcome the maple and and sweetness from the high gravity . that rarely happens , i almost never orphan a beer . founders has many beers that are excellent , this was not one of them .

s : rich , smooth , and amazing . the smoky intensity of the base beer lends serious character , but is beautifully mellowed out by vanilla + toffee sweetness , as well as some oak and smooth bourbon . just a lovely ba stout . t : follows the nose perfectly , with both powerful and finesse . fabulous balance of booze and malt , sweetness and richness .  mouthfeel : very light/somewhat watery with a high degree of carbonation .

as dark as a moonless desert night , the head is quite modest in size , the texture spumescent , light chocolate in color and as it degrades leaves behind a fine coating of lace upon the glass .  the only place i would knock it down is in the mouthfeel .

a- i do n't like to give 5 's , but out of a bottle this had a gorgeous orange , rust color , opaque with excellent head and lace . it 's a good looking beer .  the mouthfeel is medium and slightly watery with some sharp carbonation .

a : moderate pour down the center of the glass leads to 5 finger head ! wow this head is not going anywhere , sticks around forever . lots of carbonation in this one . looks like it could be unfiltered .  lacks a good bite . it 's dry and nibbles , but i want a good bite in my iipa . not that this is bad , just a bit short . easy drinking , though .

pours a good dark black with a caramel head . good head , receeds quickly but leaves good lacing .  m - somewhat thin to medium bodied but with just the right hoppy aftertaste to leave my mouth tingling for another drink .
smells of brown sugar and sweet and musky molasses , straw and dried leaves .  mouthfeel is a bit dry , but that does n't really take away from it 's drinkability .
pours a deep amber/copper color with a huge fluffy white head that shows great retention and lace .  m : well , that 's where i 'm a bit disappointed . medium body , with mid carbonation .

crystal clear gold color with an off white head . the foam is 2 fingers high and leaves a surprisingly thick coat of lacing on the glass . great retention too , none of the fizziness of the typical crappy pale lager .  first sip reveals a mild smooth body and fine rolling carbonation . the body gets a little watery on the finish , but it is a mild and the brew goes down very easy and would be an excellent session beer .

a : big , bright white 3 finger head with a swirling tempest of carbonation feeding it . head is very stable and creamy not breaking up much to smell .  aside from the dry end this is an easy to drink beer with an average mouth .

pours a beautiful red-pink with some fizzy head that lasts for about a second and recededs to a glass that looks more like wine than anything , carbonation rising on the sides of the glass looks great .  m - i tried not to destroy by palate by keeping this beer in my mouth for an extended time , so i really ca n't comment on this .

lots of leather and clove in the aroma . mothballs . honey flavours but not very sweet . lovely dry finish . brett is the showcase here , along with some noble dry-hop . very nice and worth trying .  i saw this on the top of a shelf in the back of a local beer store and it was not priced but i decided to buy it and give it a try seeing who i never hear of it , i think i bought it for a quarter . i was very suprised when i poured it out , it was a nice pale ale and it was full of hops aroma and flavor . when i drank it i just sat back and sipped it tring to enjoy every drop . well done .

a : golden appearance that pours 50/50 liquid and foam . i rated this 5 on appearance because this beer has the best head on a beer that i 've seen . it is rocky and tightly beaded , leaving a lace as it slowly recedes .  good flavors , with excellent roasted grains and a huge creaminess ; very little detectable hops , which was fine ; perhaps just a bit too much on the creamy , sugary side . a little rough , going down , but not too bad ; it just would n't be an all-the-time beer because of this .

coming from my hometown , i was psyched to try this one , and it looks like my excitement was justified . pours dark as night with a wondeful nutty coffee aroma .  complex . looks like an ale , drinks like an ale , finishes like an apricot wheat . the first time i had this was in burlington vt with a plate of mussels . i could n't get over the intrigue of this brew . i totally forgot about the mussels until my second glass .

think a pretty v rod cycle of beers . frothy white head that lasts the whole delicious beer , the gorgeous copper rust color is also very attractive , in all honesty i have n't seen something not to like so it survives round one s : then it falls flat .  m : smooth but it has a ton of carbonation which i 'm not a huge fan of .
a deep rustic orange in color with a gigantic , sticky and awkwardly shaped head of foam .  m : the body is medium and the carbonation is low to medium i suppose .

watching the cascading effect is truly one of the pleasures of a beer drinker .  my sister always goes on vaction to mexico and says this is her favorite beer . i collect 40oz bottles have about 150 in my collection , so when i saw this in a mexican resturant i was happy to say the least . i got my chance to drink this beer and add a new bottle to my collection . beer was smooth and pretty good for being on 4 % alch , was suprised that it was dark in color . taste was like other mexican beers , but i liked this more , due to it being `` rare '' only problem is the price i paid $ 15.00 for this 40oz bottle .

this harvest moon beer poured a solid coal black color . i held it up to the light and it was truly a solid black color . this head had decent retention that left behind foamy tan rings and a small amount of tan blots of lace .  m/d - a little thin , though probably appropriate for a session beer .

nice robust smell for this style : light cappuccino notes , with burnt sugar and whole-grain bread notes in there . the sugar and bread flavors that were promised by the smell are there , but they play a background role .  mouthfeel was slightly on the thin side , not quite watery , but close .

aroma brings bright layers of pink grapefruit , lemon zest , mj , apricot , tangerine , etc ... this is one great smelling beer . this ipa has nice balance between bitter and flavor in regards to the hops . not quite as bright and juicy as the aroma led me to believe , but rather , a little rough around the edges , which is n't all bad in an ipa .  m : medium body that could use more carbonation .
a : tar black with tan , creamy head .  overall , a bit thin .

a two finger head is pale biege in color and holds very well leaving marvelous spiderweb lacing .  palate was medium to light bodied , lively carbonated , watery onto a dry finish , some slight metallic feel .

smelled of a warming sweetish malt , caramel but not really , cherry-like , with some shades of thick maple sugar . some milk chocolate scents as well - overall , somewhat similar to a good scottish beer , and a complex one at that .  m : medium body is dry and chalky , with a bit too much fizz .
a- pours just a shade darker than the average ipa with a thick , long lasting , white head .  taste is creamy , though the mouthfeel is a tad on the thin side but no so much it hurts the experience .

pours a cloudy brown with a three-finger off white head . great lacing and retention throughout .  it starts out thin with the wheat malt taking center stage then gets spicier as it goes . it finishes with a lot of banana and touch of yeast that lingers a fair amount for a lighter beer . the rest : a solid , tasty wit ; it checks all of the boxes of the style , and does it pretty well .
pour was a beautiful deep amber with a one finger off whiite ring for a head .  i found the mouth feel a little thin , not as think and syrupy , as i would expect , but it 's a minor complaint .

pours a dark but brilliant red with a tannish 1 finger head .  taste is malty sweet goodness with a light hop finish . this is a nice session beer very drinkable . it has the malty sweetness i have been craving lately mmm .
a - this beer looked great , poured well , nice tan head and dark as night .  m : higher carbonation than expected , medium-full bodied .

a : pours a hazy bright yellow , looking like a hay field . provides a nice 2 finger foam head with superb retention . there is a thick layer of lacing as well .  this is a bit over carbed to be true to style i think but still very drinkable .
smell = nice ... very stong malt and hop scents .  body though is a bit thin and watery which is a little disappointing .
it 's kent goldings aroma , however , is outstanding ! it 's bright and clear , and obviously goldings .  m : thick , creamy , almost sticky . a bit too heavy for me .
smell is delicious . pure honey , reminiscent of sam adams honey porter . ends up being pretty tame .  m - bubbly and medium on the tongue .

s- strong citrus , grapefruit and lemon . pine and floral notes also come through . this is an amazingly hoppy beer with just enough sweet malt to give it a nice depth and complexity .  some balancing earthy hops mix with the spiciness of the rye to finish this with a satisfying dry ending . the mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a slightly astringent creaminess . there is just enough of a light sharpness to the carbonation to keep this crisp in the mouth .
a : pours dull black with two fingers of pillowy khaki head , leaving behind incredible lacing . good retention .  quite thin and watery at first , yet it seems to improve in time .

sweet aroma , slightly raspberry with mocha tones .  this is miles better than early versions when moo brew was just getting off the ground . nose is very expressive and lifted with intense oranges and tropical fruit . the flavours are much more serious and show genuine pale ale chracter ; firm , bitter hops , some piney notes , but surprsingly the fruit offered on the nose is a bit hard to find . doesnt harm the beer though . well worth its percentile rating .

the nose was outstanding , orange peel was perfectly balanced with the malt and just a hint of hops to keep it rounded . there is no body to this wit . it drinks like a cheap lager leaving very little for the finish .  appearance : very cloudy , much more so than an average wheat beer . smell : smells faintly of hops and strongly of yeast and fermentation . it tasted a lot like a bad experiment of mine where i mixed some peach cider with some yuengling because i was sick of drinking yuengling . the only difference was that instead of having a peach flavor , the flavor was more like mixing apple juice and a wheat beer . very difficult to drink since i resented every swig .

poured black with a bit of ruby on the edges and a tan 3 finger head that left quickly , but hey this is an is .  this one strikes me as kind of flat . needs a tad more carbonation and i think it would be leaps better than it is . nice creamy smooth mouthfeel though .

-very black body with a tall , fluffy brown head with a nitro look to it . good lacing as well -at first it is mostly bourbon ... as it warms , chocolate comes through as well as some roast , vanilla and some warmth -milk chocolate throughout the taste .  m : a little weak for my tastes , but it probably degraded a bit over the past year , still quite oily and resiny , medium-bodied .

big aroma of red ripe fruitcake like smells ... nuts , raisins , caramel and chocolate ... lots of yeasty esters , with a candy like nougat nose . smells absolutely delicious . the taste is quagmire of flavours ... yeast and peppery alcohol ... a good deal of hops peak in and out ... all loosely held together by a milky way candy bar like malt flavour that quickly dives down to a back end alcohol burn . it 's hot and hoppy without any real discerning character . an interesting , complex , and unique concoction .  thin feel , but not too thin .

a - crystal clear , nice carbonation , solid/lasting head with significant lacing down a clean glass , medium brown in color with a red tint when held to light . nice looking beer .  m- thin to medium body- highly attenuated- with a coarse carbonation which delivers a slightly bloating feeling . could stand to have some softer carbonation .

aroma is outstanding , filled with sweet oranges and caramel , not caramel malt , but candied caramel . mouthfeel is a bit cloying , maybe a bit too heavy on the malt , but it coats extremely well .  surprisingly light in the mouth , and very drinkable , but as i have been rereading some of my reviews lately , i think everything is drinkable , it seems that i would almost always take another .

smelled of brown sugar and ginger like scent , plenty of spice , and some sweet malt presence in the back .  '' the nutmeg overpowers the beer and completely destroys any other tastes that might have been present . if there were hops in the beer they were negligible and added most likely as an afterthought . leave this one on the shelf this christmas and go find out what uncle al spiked the eggnog with .

appearance : pours into my hennepin chalice a crystal clear pale gold color with a huge , loose-bubbled , white head . the becomes very rocky as it drops leaving tons of lacing down the side of the glass . this looks perfect .  m- near dead flat . it seems to be a bit on the thin side as well . d- despite the feel this beer still drinks deadly smooth .
) a : pours dark yellow/orange color with a very thick white bubbly head . very nice .  tastes great , but the mouthfeel is a lot thinner than i 'd like for the style .
it looks beautiful in the glass , kind of a smoked ruby color .  mouthfeel - very average .

a - pours a deep copper , forming a good three fingers of off-white head . heavy lacing on the glass .  slick and little bit flat , the mouthfeel is a disappointment considering the other solid qualities of this beer .

s : smells like maple bars and bbq smoke , an intriguing mix which i quite liked . t : tastes a lot like american amber , has that typical rogue pacman yeast with crystal malt base .  mouthfeel is flimsy and light , but the carbonation is mellow , so that 's not too bad .

soapy white head that dissipates quickly . s : i expected the grapefruit greeting of the ipa , but my nose was met with citrus combined with tropical fruit , almost a pineapple or mango and hint of floral . t : same blast of citrus and tropicals ; finishes a little bit quickly , without a lot of bitterness or drying , which i missed . a really fantastic beer and a lucky find since i understand hill farmstead is not found much outside of vermont .  medium body with low carbonation . a bit more carbonation would be good too .

appearance- given to me with a sturdy tan head that started at two and a half fingers , and eventually receded to a one and a half finger head that stayed the whole enjoyment of beer . color is a deep brown when held to the light , but other than that its a translucent black . smell- pretty subdued in every way .  no offense ... er..ahem ... gentlemen , however your review of this all time worst pisswater excuse for even a macro beer is to say the least , culpable , at best , dubious , but in truth , how can you live with yourself ? t-non-existent m-ok , not too harsh , but goes flat quickly . good carb up front .

s : bright tart raspberries , chocolate , caramel and sweet sugars . dessert wine-like . incredibly inviting with layers of all things sweet and desserty . very rich , too rich in fact even for the pairing with the chocolate brownie .  this is way to watered down for me . mouthfeel and drinkability : finishes somewhat dry . this brew also has a super light body with higher levels of carbonation-okay , these are appropriate for the style .
the nose is marvellous - strong and sweet of caramel and hazelnut . definitely disappointing .  the mouthfeel is a bit astringent and finishes extremely dry .
for as strong as these aromas are , they do n't smell at all artificial -- good work .  m - even , with a slight bitter aftertaste .
i poured this into a glass and it was so dark and rich looking .  mouthfeel : medium bodied and a bit undercarbonated imho .

2010 bigfoot ... a : pours with a typical sierra nevada perfectness ... gorgeous deep amber color and has an off white head . the head is rocky with large bubbles and amazing retention/lacing .  the hops are n't super astringent and they finish well . mouthfeel : medium-bodied .

this brew has a great smell - dark roasted grains , coffee , and hints of licorice .  m- smooth , medium-high carbonation , clean , with a hint of dryness in the finish . d- of course . it 's cheap , available everywhere , and quite good .

the pour is pitch-black in color ; head is immoderate in size , light chocolate in color , and the lace thick clinging sheets that last till the bottom of the glass .  the appearance and mouthfeel were n't too great but i could n't get over the great taste .

this is one of the most attractive brews i have ever seen . a light ruby color with creamy light head that has a finger and a half upon pour and settles to a ring . no lacing , but good legs .  m : thin to medium viscosity , resinous and sticky on the palate but lacking the heft of the other qualities , with moderate carbonation . the bitterness demands a little too much attention here , constraining its smoothness .

a - wow a pitch black liquid and with an aggressive pour i saw at least an inch of coco head .  smell : wheat , alcohol , wierd hops , tangy smell , maybe some wine alcohol smell in there too taste : hints of grass , toasted wheat , nice and smooth , mellow , nice malt aftertaste and a bit tangy mouthfeel : a little tart , this one is pretty highly carbonated .
a : solid bock appearance with a crisp , clear brown color with amber hues . a soft white head and not too much carbonation .  mouthfeel is pretty thin as well .
a - a huge frothy eternal mocha brown head .  low carbonation .

served in a nonic , the 75 min ipa appears with 2 fingers worth of silky , creamy white head . displays a solid amount of retaining power that lasts with a full finger 's worth until the last sip . the lacing on the glassware appears as a webbing just about everywhere it was in contact . the brew itself is a hazed golden orange color .  i 'm just back from a trip to the bahamas and the place i stayed at offered heineken , kalik and miller lite . i 've had both heineken and miller lite so i thought i 'd try the local brew , kalik . boy was i impressed . i drank quite a bit of this brew while sitting by the pool and each one tasted as good as the last . i sure got a good buzz but even better , no headache ! if you ever get to the bahamas be sure to try kalik .

the color of this beer is a beautiful , rich , reddish , amber .  taste was bland . not much to write about . normally , i 've been very happy with everything i 've had from them up until now . hopefully this was an experimental beer that taught from it 's mistakes .
pine tree , but somehow a more pure pine scent then a standard ipa . t - started really unique but eventually all i was tasting was this overpowering pine taste .  mouthfeel is thin and crisp .

the aroma is incredible . all of the dried , dark fruits i 've ever tried at one time . this was really nice . the other barleywines i 've tried have been far too hoppy but this was a wonderful , sweet , thick treat .  m : disappointing . suffers from lack of body .

great retention with a ton of lace .  its got a light alcohol content and indeed a long haul session beer . this is a very tasty beer considering how light it really is . this pared real well with a cheddar burger .

smell-like a slice of pumpkin pie as soon as i opened the bottle the aroma of nutmeg , cinnamon and of course pumpkin , exactly what a pumpkin ale should smell like .  the body is a little light for me which just adds to how drinkable it is .
it is really a nice looking beverage .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , slightly syrupy , and carbonation is low which produces a somewhat still feel .
dark dark dark brown .  mouthfeel : good carbonation , otherwise nothing special .

prunes , prunes , prunes and a hint of burnt chocolate espresso/coffee with a huge amount of hop-less goodness ! one of the best smells i 've ever had out of an american stout . you can taste the burnt coffee and well , that 's kind of it . there 's really no huge taste that i expected out of a beer with such a huge nose . feels pretty good like going down with a carbonated and light thickness oil like liquid . quiet drinkable but i 'm disappointed in the flavor . still not a bad pick up .  after my first taste i really was able to feel how refreshing this beer truly is , and i enjoyed ever sip . not your normal fall seasonal , due to the lack of heavy sweet notes , but none the less one of the better seasonal beer i have had .

poured form a bomber bottle and into a tulip glass it pours a pretty , dark coffee color with a nice bubbling , mostly dense tan head at the surface . nice cascading in the glass as i poured .  carbonation is a little bit higher than i prefer .

hoppy , approachable , and ( like most southern tier beers ) a highly attractive appearance . most southern tier beers have a clear body and brilliant color , and this beer is no exception .  smells like apples , tastes like hops . very tasty . the fragrance certainly did not match the taste , which is a good thing . the apple/apricot scent is strong but would be overpowering to the tongue , the muted apple notes balanced well . i would definitely order this again .

golden colored topped with a thick foamy off-white head and lots of lacing on the glass .  brewed in celebration of the liar 's club 7th anniversary . aromas are amber malts and simple hops ... very clean and fresh . only a little grapefruit peel in the taste . very little about the sweet malts in this brew ... only enough to cover and blend with the hops to keep them from being obnoxious . good for several pints ... too bad they ran dry .

now that i 'm over my cold , i can pick up a whiff of cherry and some alcohol . still , the aroma is a big part of this beer , so i 'm glad i waited to review it at a time i could savor it .  mouthfeel needs a bit of work . medium body , carbonation is low . needs more carbonation .

the smell was great , high notes of carmel and a nice sized head made this a quick favorite of mine . this is the first oktoberfest beer i have ever had and i would def .  the roast flavors give way to a hop bitterness in the finish with virtually no malt backbone in between . hints of licorice and coffee give this nice complexity for a lager . m- a little fuller than your typical schwarzbier . d- it drinks like a big beer , much more so than it 's 4.9 % abv would lend you to expect . overall : this is a very flavorful schwarzbier . my personal criticisms are that i would like it to have a little more malt in the middle while toning down the roast malts just a little . still , not a bad beer by any means .
burgundy color , with a full and creamy foam that lasts .  the body is a bit lean and draws somewhat thin in the finish .

appearance this one poured a bright yellow in color with a huge , foamy head that left clumps all over the inside of my glass .  mouthfeel is a little thin ( but then again , what do you want from a wheat beer ) with tangy carbonation .

very little lacing . absolutely beautiful s-malty , roasted coffee smell t-coffee is definately at the forefront with a very faint hint of chocolate .  mouthfeel is surprisingly light for the style . very little carbonation makes this one almost too easy to go down .
a - deep amber gold , with a low white head , and very nice lacing .  a little thin in the body for my taste , and a bit low in carbonation .
a - brilliant muted yellow color .  carbonation scrubs the tongue with perky bubbles ( almost too much , but not quite ) and has a medium-light body .

the beer malt character shows off with lots of chocolate ... the taste is not dominated by the bourbon sadly as even though it was strong i was excited . the malts show through here in a creamy fashion , cream , vanilla and some chocolate ... the beer is to light on the palate but pretty easy to drink . one of the better beers of the night .  the initial taste is medium in body , and the malt flavors are similar to those in the aroma , with enough hop bitterness to balance it . all sweetness disappears approaching the finish , and you 're left with a mild trinity of tartness , hop spice , and roasty character , combining to leave an overt dryness on the palate . so it has a warm place in my heart , and i feel validated to say that i can honestly still enjoy it for the same reasons i used to , even after having learned a great deal more about beer since that time .

i got this little guy in a recent trade ( thanks to jwale76 ) pours a rich dark brown , almost black , has an abundance of head . easily three finger that is a rich mocha brown . the head turns into a mass of larger bubbles in the brew and leaves a nice amount of lacing on the glass .  the mouthfeel is a little weak .
black in hue with a tan head .  the only disappointing part is the mouthfeel , which was more thin than i would have liked .

pours a cloudy dark amber color with some golden orange hues when held to a light source and a frothy two finger head that slowly settles into a lasting cap that leaves sporadic chunks of lacing .  this is a good bridge beer for those who often find themselves at a party that are n't as fond of typical domestics . perhaps an unrealistic setting for beer in general , but i like them cold ! pleasant aroma and flavor for what it is . it 's a very drinkable , hot summer 's day , beer . it 's not a bad tangent from the original bud light .

reviewed from notes taken 4-02-2010 served on nitro at the left hand tasting room a - black with red highlights and a thick , dense off-white head that lasts the whole glass .  it 's very easy to drink , crips , and light , but it 's a bit thin in character & feel .

taste- sweet , tropical fruits as in the nose , hop bitterness . feel- medium carbonation.. creamy ... yummy overall this is a really good ipa ... kind of reminds me of union jack .  hellooo hops ! this is a nice beer that hits you with hops right off the bat . nice hops with a touch of malt , and a lingering hop influenced aftertaste . i ca n't help but pick the slightest metallic twinge in the flavor and aftertaste , not sure where that could be coming from . not a bad strong ale at all , definitely worth revisiting but probably not distinguishable enough to stand in the upper echelon of style .

it was a dark black with a red stained glass type aura that made me feel that this would be quite a special beer .  as a williamsburg native , and dark beer fan , i was severly disappointed with this porter . it could have been that the six pack was skunky , i guess . nonetheless , a big disappointment . if one could imagine a porter that is too sweet , this would fit into that category . baltika is also a sweeter porter , but only has a hint . this beer is blatantly sweet .
has an absolutely wonderful fruity smell ... . some nice head on the pour ... .  the mouthfeel was much lighter than expected with a slight buttery feel .
the first smell brings pine , oranges , more citrus and puts a smile on my face .  the mouthfeel is average , medium-bodied , watery ( even slightly oily ) in texture , with soft carbonation .

color : pours very dark brown , almost black . sits midnight with a very small dark brown rim . big , rich , creamy mocha head with great retention smell : over-ripened bananas upon approach . wierd .  it finishes very clean with a hint of carbonation lingering on the palate .
appearance - looks great , black as night with a nice caramel tan head that hangs on the whole time .  a very nice balance of flavors m : average mouth feel .

smells absolutely delicious . not sure it smells like a brown , but it smells great . tastes watery .  grapefruit rinds , m : maybe a little more structure would be good- everything but the pine tends to fade on the finish .

the beer pours a blackish red color its very attractive and pours a thick head that disaperas in a couple of minutes but leaves lacing till the end of your beer .  m : medium-bodied , but i feel like there 's something missing .

outstanding . t/m : not as legendary as the aroma , but still very nice . the sweet milk chocolate still dominates , but this beer is far more bitter than i 'd expect .  look : black as night with a 1/2 inch head and good retention smell : the nose carries some nice licorice and dark fruits taste : plums and figs that a tad sweet present themselves right away the back end has a nice roasted malt character and a hint of chocolate mouthfeel : is a bit thin and over carbonated for the style overall : the beer is ok right now but i think that this one will do well with some age .

12 oz bottle poured into a mug a : pours a very deep amber/copper with about two fingers of light tan head . lots of lacing and good head retention .  mouthfeel is a touch light for my liking , but i 've come to expect that .
