smell deep , rich coffee aroma with mild chocolate scents . the heavily toasted malt smell came out as well in this nose .  body was a smidgen thin , but it held the 8 % back quite well , i knew it was more that 5 % , but thats what i perceived from this great brew .
slightly hazy dark amber with a big very-light-brown head with great r & l .  a little less than medium bodied , with lowish carbonation .

sundance is the best looking amber ale i 've ever seen . true to its name , it looks like a setting sun . the body is a deep , translucent amber with a pillowy , stable head sticky like melted marshmallow .  had this side by side with weihenstephaner 's dunkel . i think the comparison made this beer seem pretty awful . the beer is a ruddy , red , muddy river looking beer with a sizable , reddish head . super sweet and caramelly . it reminded me of michelob amber bock but stronger and richer . it seemed like there was caramel and toffee syrup added . taste is like the nose , syrupy sweet like artificial caramel . i did not like this beer . i think i would be able to drink it easier if it werent side by side with the quintessential dunkel but still i dont think i would like it very much more .

this beer has a dark brown , almost black colour and a great head that really lasts .  crisp malts , light fruits and near indiscernible hops all float to the nose . a bit dry going down with some malts , a surprising hoppiness , and a good , somewhat delayed fruit hit at the end . light-bodied and highly drinkable , but still tasty , which is what i look for in a good summer sessioner .

a= pours a caramelly brownish color similar to coca cola looking . the head is a nice two fingers and appears to be a just off white color . nice retention and lacing on this one as well .  the only real complaint i have with this beer is that it is just too thin ... i do n't buy that this is an ris ... if this was just an american stout , the thinner body would be suitable , but it 's just not on an imperial stout .

absolutely stunning pour .  very much like the herbs for a fish of sorts . m/o : not the crispest carbonation that i was expecting but the beer has a great complex flavor with some great sweetness and bitter hop flavor .

very nice ubbling in a clear , yet dark copper color . two fingers of beige head , that recedes to a thick foam and leaves some nice lacing on the glass aftter each sip .  there 's a slight bready quality to the mid mouth impact , but the flavor is balanced and lessens evenly as its swallowed . i do n't look for a lot of bite or chewy mouthfeel in vienna lagers , so i 'm pretty happy with firebrick .
aroma is a good yeasty breadiness , some citric and spicy notes as well .  mouth is over-carbonated indefinitely .

big thanks to tayner for this great little brew.. into the dfh pint glass goes this pitch black brew , forming a very impressive khaki head and some of the best lacing i 've seen in a while.. terrific aroma of dark roasted malts , perhaps some cocoa and coffee , and what i 'm guessing is the brewers licorice talked about on the bottle .  medium to light body .

s : great aromas of hazelnuts , cocoa , and sweet caramel . t : the taste is very malty with lots of sweet caramel and a bit of toasted malt flavor and a touch of hops bitterness in the finish .  mouthfeel is thin , but typical for brown ales ( i always expect a fuller beer based on the smell ) .
beautiful amber/red color and nice thick white head . impressive retention and lacing .  the mouthfeel is a little thin for the style but its still a fairly minor flaw .

s : what a wonderful dessert smell ; a combination of vanilla , caramel and coffee ice cream . t : taste is super sweet roasted toffee malts with a generous helping of vanilla and some powdered cocoa , even . it tastes sort of spot on as a creme brulee , but i think i might have liked the aroma better than the taste here .  too carbonated , average m/f .

wonderful aroma . mix of bright , citrusy , fresh hop aromas and a cookie-like malt sweetness . malty sweet presence comes on surprisingly strong and overwhelms some of the hop complexity . still , a very drinkable , flavorful ipa .  mouthfeel is tough .

cinnamon , clove and a natural `` pumpkin '' aroma that does n't smell faked or overdone . light ginger is a good accent to the smell . nutmeg is n't overdone which is key in my opinion . amazing complex yet not overdone spice presence . nicely balanced , nicely spiced .  the mouthfeel is also unexpectedly thin - for a beer this dark i was anticipating something more viscous .

| 5.8 % abv | 2011 brewer : birrificio del ducato style : saison / farmhouse ale glass : crystal mug appearance : honey-gold with a righteous plume of angelic white .  m : a bit light and quite fizzy for the style .

the smell is very nice and very much in line with what you 'd expect from a solid hefe : sweet citrus fruit , a bit of spice and wheat are all prevelent and seemingly well balanced thusfar . while bold yet standard scents were detected , the flavour is less aggressive while remaining very basic for the style . good nontheless though .  it goes down smooth and is nice and wet on the tongue but is just a tad thin .

s : big smell of molasses , caramel , and pancake syrup . t : much like the smell , although more subtle and subdued .  mouth feel : reasonably full , not unpleasant , a little carbonation at the opening .

this pale ale pours with a nice , clear deep amber body topped by a medium thick to thick , off white head with lots of lacing .  m - well , this is honestly a step down from the better macros . it has a decent body , but the hops detract a bit from refreshment the beer provides .

a clear but dark garnet color at first , it clouds up considerably , chunks up actually , with the bottom pour . the head is three to four fingers , and fades to a thin covering with a dark cinnamon-like corona about a third of the way inside the rim .  mouthfeel is average , thin and just a bit too carbonated for my taste .

the aroma is excellent : dark cherry or currant with slight carob .  a slightly over-caramelized ( read : burnt ) sweetness resurfaces on the finish , somewhat diminishing the overall enjoyability of the brew . the beers ' only weakness , a touch thin and yet over-carbonated at the same time . still , this is a winner from a rather uneven stable of beers from new holland . my only concern is how this came to be listed as a red ale ; it 's fucking brown ! ? !

bottle courtesy of kryptic : poured a hazy brown color ale with a bug light brown color head with great retention and great lacing .  it was a light to moderate mouthfeel . good balance of carbonation .

s - big juicy citrus hop aroma . i love ipa 's that smell like this ... big fruity nose with almost nothing else to it . a very easy drinking and tasty ipa , just like every other hop project of theirs i have tried .  fairly dry with ample carbonation and a lighter body . a bit coarse in texture .
black color . very thick full cascading type head .  light body , wish it were bigger and more creamy .

lots of good hop went into this beer ! i have no reason to hate on this brewery , i loved pliny a lot more , though .  mouthfeel - the only downside imo is that it has a dry finish and leaves the pallet thirsty .

s - what an orgasmic aroma ! i have n't had my socks knocked off like this in a while ! rich milk chocolate , dusty cocoa , notes of cold coffee , and a roasted barley aroma flourish with the brilliantly blended bourbon barrel aroma . not hot at all . no hops at all . while it 's still good , a lot of the subtle nuances and richness do n't make it through . very nice dry finish with just a small hint of warming . a good beer regardless , i like the subtleties of tyranena 's barrel-aging .  ( m ) medium bodied and a medium mouthfeel .

the nose had a lot going on , big juicy orange fruit and dried apricots . you could also pick up the big caramel and buttescotch scent . the finish had a nice hint of vannila and soft caramel .  m - thin , lo-carbonation , smooth and easy on the palette .
pours a very dark , almost black amber with some reddish tones to it . a very sticky map covers the glass as you drink .  feels like champagne .

very nice looking beer , 2 finger head that stayed around for a while , almost clear at the bottom of the glass more cloudy as it builds towards the top .  mouthfeel was unremarkable , which is as much as can be expected of any pilsener .

aroma is lovely and near perfect for style : brown sugar , burnt sugar , prunes , cloves , stonefruit . taste is much of the same notes as the aroma , but more muted , and less pronounced on the fruit and burnt sugar that makes the aroma so nice .  the carbonaton is a bit high and detracts a bit from the quality of this beer , but overall an excellent , potent stout that is sweet without being too sweet .
looks incredible . the smell was a bit disappointing .  m- medium body , slightly carbonated , has a bit of creaminess to it .

s- dark malty aroma with a very sweet smell . roasted malt , cocoa , and vanilla all come through . a warm alcohol smell also hits the nose . t- very big and malty . well-balanced and very roasty . i alway aim my lost abbey corks into an empty corner , because i expect the cork to blow off , but with this batch , there was barely a puff when the cork came out .  the nitro can has both its positive and negative effects on this very english strong ale , the look of the beer with it creamy head and cascading pour is the closest you can get at home to an `` authentic '' pub pour unless you have a beer engine and sparkler in your bar . nonetheless , the aroma is english hops ( most likely east kent goldings ) on top of a mild caramel malt sweetness . the taste is lacking the true depth a real ale should have , but it is well-balanced and mild . for those expecting the assertiveness of an american pale ale this beer will be a dissapointment , but for those searching for a closer approximation to a british session beer served in a suffolk pub , this is a nice try .
drinking it out of a frosted pint glass the appearance is a very appealing light caramel color that is very clear .  m - overcarbonated , light bodied for the style , but really good .

huge malty and floral aroma with sweet citrus reminding me of grapefruit and pineapple - smells great ! mouth-feel is rather thin with plenty of carbonation . unfortunately the nose was better than the taste of this one .  lighter in body than i anticipated .

one of the prettiest beers i have ever seen : a deep ruby red color with lots of carbonation , a creamy , foamy , rocky head , light brown head and some nice sticky lace . the head diminished , but settled down to a fine creamy layer that lasted throughout .  mouth feel is a little thin at first with too much carbonation for an english style brown .
poured into a tulip a- copper very pretty beer s- oak and almost a tea smell no hops what so ever .  mouthfeel is thin and a little overcarbonated .

neon white head radiates brightly from its position atop my beverage . clear , crisp gold straw colored brew .  m : sticky and fairly thick , dry , slightly dry , prickly carbonation , hint of warm alcohol , just a little too syrupy for my taste .
appearance : pours a dark brown into an opaque black beer . a generous chocolate head that settles into a thin tan film .  m - uberchewy , sweet . med-light carbonation .

appearance : gorgeous amber brown ale with tan bubbly head atop . clarity is slightly cloudy . head lasts and lasts but does n't pour so big as to dominate the glass . flawless appearance as allagash beers typically are .  m/d : sweet and full-bodied , just the right carbonation for the style .

served in its own urthel glass from draught , on to the beer : beautiful ! shimmering golden color with a huge , billowy head on top with excellent retention and lots of creamy lacing sticking to the glass .  a little grittiness in the texture . m - a little weird and overcarbonated for a porter . it would be better off less carbonated and as creamy as it appears .

the smell is predominantly toasted chocolate malt . overall i was disappointed in the taste which did not measure up to the wonderful color and aroma . i would drink this again if someone gave it to me , but i 'm not sure i would fork over another $ 10 for another bottle .  other than the slightly thin body , this is a superior porter .
s : it redeems itself . great hop aroma . nice citrus notes .  the mouthfeel is a decent medium , a little too much carbonation results in a thinner feel than i would like .
extrememly frothy and creamy . leaves large chunks and patches behind . a nice lightly clouded golden colored pour .  cloying . full-bodied , slick and thick . an odd astrigency lingers .

aroma of honey and lavender . very complex and almost reminiscent of a west coast barley wine . aroma is dominated by pineapple with hints of peach , vanilla , and a little raspberry . definitely the fruitiest non-citrus aroma i 've ever smelled from an ipa . taste is just mild sweetness , then a huge clean bitterness , with a feeling of a bitter tea finish .  m : pretty thin and not too lively .

yellow-orange pour with a huge rocky head . one of the best heads i 've ever coaxed out of an ipa , and it stuck around and left tons of lace as it slid down the glass .  mainly a flattish mouthfeel .

fuller 's esb is a crystal-clear solid amber ale , atop which sits a rich , frothy , cream-colored head that leaves excellent lacing .  m : it doesnt give the mouth a longlasting tingle that some ipa 's give but gives a tasty coat on your mouth that lasts and gives the chocolate taste as well .

s - very complex ! grape , sherry and port wine-type aromas are dominant , with hints of raisin , nuts and esters . alcohol is apparent , too . very sweet altogether . m/d - hardly any carbonation . i look forward to trying another one a year from now !  wow ! really liked this beer . i did n't think i would . looked like it could have been any pils when i poured it . smelled like a nice lady 's perfume ... with hops ! : ) nice hops balance with some maltiness too . i am not a pilsner fan but i think i am now . way to go victory !

appearance : deep , clear red color with a very excited , very foamy white head that lasts forever . once in the glass this is a very impressive looking beer .  a touch too much carbonation for my liking .

poured with a tan thick pillowy head witha deep amber color with some excellent clarity .  after several sips i finished the taster and got a bottle of water to cleanse the palate . the body was average for a wit , but the hops made this sloppy mess nearly undrinkable .
a- pours a deep brownish hue with a nice big , 2.5 finger head .  feel is a bit thin , probably because the alcohol presence is a bit pronounced .
smells wonderful . t : unfortunately , the taste suffers and does n't deliver what the nose promises .  m - nice carbonation , but it could be much bigger bodied .

12oz bottle into a snifter a : pours a hazy amber with a big light tan head that lasts for a while and leaves ton of lacing on the glass .  sweet tasting ... m : a little on the acidic and sour side to me .

a- this is the funnest beer to watch while it settles , as it morphs from a caramel colored , bubbly state to a completely dark brown/black brew with an amazing tan head that has an incredible retention from start to finish s- deep roasted aromas ... cocoa , coffee beans , black tea , kind of earthy .  body is a bit thin , with the malt slipping quickly away under the bittering hops that dominate the finish .
overall a very nice effort . smell is really great . taste is up there , just needs a little more substance in the body  mf - medium body , very creamy , light carb .

bottle into tulip . pours deep brown to black , with a beautiful , creamy , dense tan half-inch head on top with amazing , solid walls of lacing . beautiful from top to bottom .  found it medium bodied for the style considering the rich taste .

smell : the smell is incredibly complex , with crisp notes ginger , spices , coriander , orange peel , and floral hops . weak . smells phenomenal , but the greatness stops there . but still , it 's unique , and i always have to give props to dfh for being original and daring . worth a try .  m= body is medium/average but probably a little too thin . i was hoping for a little thicker in the body as well as taste department .

it 's a beautiful beer to look at . really great looking .  makes it look like a blue moon ... i dont know just dont see the drinkability and mouthfeel to be good at all ... it was one and done for me ... .
pours black with a big , thick , firm and pillowy off-white/tan head . nice looking .  mouthfeel is very cloying with a firm body and medium carbonation .
a- a very hazy orange/ brown liquid with a massive light brown head that has astounding retention .  the feel is alright but it does n't matter at this point .

quite unique , but i 'm very impressed . the taste is a lot lighter and less robust compared to the aroma .  should you drink this warm or cold ? when it 's cold the flavors are : dark chocolate , coffee , heavily roasted to burnt malt , and bitter hops . when it 's warm the flavors are more like : sweet chocolate , maybe some sort of fruit , coffee , heavily roasted malt , and not so bitter hops . i perfer the sweeter chocolate , not burnt malt , and less bitter hops flavor when it 's warm .

served in a pint glass this beer pours a motor oil black . it may be categorized here as a smoked beer , but this has the rich sexy dark brown foam and black body of an amazing stout .  a bit of a thin mouthfeel , for a porter .

smell - intense . can smell the malts with a hint of hops and definitely the bourbon . a bit dry and the oak lingered over everything .  the carbonation is medium strong ; the few medium sized bubbles are fresh . the liquid is semi-smooth . a lager with lots of off flavours .
pretty good , light tan head and foam for a barleywine .  the mouthfeel is light also and thin .
a huge , tan/mocha colored head forms on top and is quite dense and rocky .  little bit of fizziness and a lingering cottonmouth aftertaste i could have done without .

this beer , in a tulip , was exceptional . gold color , thick white head , lots of lacing .  m : medium mouthfeel , slightly thinner than what i was expecting , especially once the carbonation is gone .

smell : the aroma of the beer is a cleaver blending of caramel , vanilla , suggestions of hot fudge , brown sugar , melons , berries , banana , dark toasted and roasted aromas , spicey earthyness , its boozey but in the way that a nice single malt is boozey . taste : this beer taste good but not nearly as good as its smell . the beers flavors bring an undefinable fruityness to my mouth . sweet honey brown sugar , vanilla , the alcohol comes across as boozey .  mouthfeel is a little bit lacking as the beer is a little bit thin , although it is still okay .
dark golden , sorta amber , about a finger of frothy white head . lacing and retention are both great .  m : a tad overcarbonated , a bit watery , medium-light body . a bit astringent .

pours a very nice burgandy with a tan head that is thick and rocky . in certain lights this brew appears to be brown , but i like it better as a burgandy .  a little bit of sweetness also from the yeast taste : there is a very interesting dark fruit flavor profile going on here with raisin definately standing out as the main flavor mouthfeel : medium body with really high amounts of carbonation typical of lost abbey beers overall : i really dont care for lost abbey and their high levels of carbonation in their beers .

appearance- wonderful semi-cloudy off orange , slightly golden colored pour . full one inch head on pour which form a ultra creamy milkshake-like head . actually , more like cool whip . leaves behind great trails and patches of lace .  m - good mouthfeel . a bit low on the carbonation .

excellent . the beer is the color of honey , and since this is a honey ale , it succeeds in this area as well . the taste and mouthfeel are light , pleasant , and ultimately forgettable .  just ok . this is a very sweet beer . it 's a good beer to drink when you are plowed . drink it very cold . when it warms up , it tastes like butt .

it looks incredibly inviting , well done .  i 'm so sorry , but i do n't see what everyone else does in this beer . the malt flavor is too aggressive and tastes over-toasted . in this case , both flavors are too aggressive . still , in all departments i find it profoundly below average , except maybe appearance and mouthfeel , which are standard ( gold with a tinge of brown and not too oily , respectively ) . this is just one of those beers i ca n't get into .

poured with a healthy 3f of foamy , white head , atop of a fairly opaque orange-tea colored body . plenty of lacing .  aroma of allspice , nutmeg , figs , apples , leathery yeast , and pepper . flavor of dark fruits including plums and cassis . slightly sour . palate lacks expected richness . good but not great like the previews ( appearance and aroma ) lead you to believe .

s - as soon as i cracked the bottle i could smell all the hops . extremely powerful aroma though .  mouthfeel : a slight cloy in the finish makes this a less-than-refreshing ipa . drinkability : this is a nice , simple beer with a delectable hop profile and light body .
pours a nice dark chestnut . nice foamy head with good retention and lace .  m : on the thin side , and carbonation is on the low side .

a bit of an orange copper color , little haze , with a fantastic looking head .  mouthfeel is a letdown - it may just be this bottle but the carbonation is too weak . only have one of these 750ml bottles as it 's imported and a special occasion but i 'd be keen to have another one , if only to compare the carbonation .
nice fluffy white head . good retention .  the body seems a bit lighter than i would have expected .

it 's very deep purple red with a big , dense , pink head that lasts forever and leaves pretty good lacing .  a nice toasted nut element , good smokey , roasted flavors , but the body is thin and watery to me .

a beautiful cloudy-golden color with an explosive 2.5 inch head that lasted for a few minutes .  this 'beer ' is weak . this 'beer ' is flavourless . no wait , i can taste some corn syrup , and what 's that ... pickle juice ? honestly , i think i taste hints of pickle juice !

head dissipates at a quick pace , and lacing is nonexistent ... s - lots of sweet notes come through . caramel , vanilla , oak , and toffee . very smooth and well balanced ( especially considering the abv ) .nothing is over the top or out of place ... m - goes down extremely smooth . medium bodied with a medium/moderate amount of carbonation ... o - one of the better american barleywines i have tasted to date . definitely something that i am looking foward to trying again in the near future .  mouthfeel is very light , a little watery , with a somewhat crisp feel to it .

thanks to the crew at drakes for makin a hoppy beer i could enjoy and drive home after 4 of them . lots of citra hops in the aroma which sets you up for an ipa but surprise this great tastin beer is under 4 % really great session beer , if you like west coast ipa's try this one , just dont expect finishing kick .  mouthfeel is a touch watery .

s : classic sculpin nose , mango and apricots , very tropical and distinct . there is some heat on the back end from the chiles , but nothing that grabbed me , nothing that screamed habanero . still a solid effort .  mouth : very light for the style , heavy on carbonation .
a long-lasting head and lots of lacing down the glass make for a pleasing visual experience .  it feels a bit thin and overly carbonated for a strong english ale .
very good . t : has a sort of sharp , dry toffee flavor up-front that goes away fairly quickly .  mouthfeel is a bit thin .

the appearance is as good as they come .  it seems to say , above , that it 's cask ... it was certainly carbonated when we tried it - just not highly carbed . a bit light in the mouthfeel like all of the brutopia beers we tried .

the smell is very nice with hints of wine , fresh fruits , smokey alcohol hints . very solid olafactor .  only criticism : powerful aggressive carbonation , would it ease if i left it a while - just too fresh ?

appearance : it poured out a light brown color that quickly turned into a beautiful black color that you have no chance of seeing through . it poured with a beautiful thick finger and a half of darker tan head that just will not die down . there is also some really nice lacing . i mean this is just a beauty of a beer .  mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish .

poured to a pale golden color , with foamy white head that lasted the entire bottle , with high carbonation and excellent lacing .  m - two words : over-carbonated . it 's just too crisp for my liking for an imperial stout .
this is the first time i had a foreign hefeweizen and i am very impressed . i love it .  m : medium-bodied in the style , not the smoothest imperial stout for me .
poured a light amber hue with a two finger creamy white head . there was very good retention and lacing .  m : medium bodied , but the carbonation is lacking .

it opens up with a beautiful floral hop aroma that is sweet and begs you to take a sip .  on tap the the brewery . all american hops . pungant and resiny . big hop flavor with rye spicyness . caramel , and good bitterness . quite dry and refreshing . my first founders beer every . pretty happy so far .

beer is amber and clear with an exterior cascading head of nitrogen bubbles that forms a soft head of tiny bubble , with ultimately moderate to low aeration and minimal lacing on the glass . looks fine .  m : the body is on the slicker , thinner side of medium , with sharp yet low carbonation .
a really beautiful beer to look at .  in the mouth , it 's a touch thin and gritty .

smell : upfront is a nutty note that seems to be a nut brown mixed with a stout so it creates a unique nuttiness . there is some roast to the beer as well and of course some chocolate notes smells exactly what a black n tan should smell like taste : the taste for me kind of falls short and kills this beer for me .  the mouthfeel is atypical for a saison . it 's a little heavier and not as carbonated as is typical of the style .

a : this brew presents a perfect appearance , with a massive , rocky head , great retention , crystal clarity , and a light copper tint .  not sure what 's going on with this one . smells and tastes like a bucket of water with household cleaner thats been laying around for a couple of days . try for yourself , but i guarantee you wont want to try it again . also , ive read about people paying upwards of $ 9 for a 22 oz . bottle . i paid $ 6.49 . pay no more ...

dark chocolate with a reddish tint , the head is big and mocha colored and leaves some wonderful lacing .  m_moutheel was actually ok except that it felt like sugar was coating teeth . other than that it was thick and full bodied .

leaves one finger of a foamy white head that eventually recedes to surface skim , and leaves some good lacing . appearance will be this ale 's high point .  the mouthfeel is nothing exceptional but it is also not bad . it is a bit fizzy but this does n't offset the flavors .
a nice looking ruby color body topped by a very thick off white head fills the tulip glass .  that being said , it feels a bit too thin . qutie unfortunate .
pours a deep orange with a very large foamy head on top . perfect lacing/webbing .  mouthfeel : thin to reference the entire continuum of beers , but average for a pilsner .

a : chocolate syrup brown with dense , oatmeal-colored 1-finger head that retains well and sheets the glass .  on the palate , this one is fairly light bodied with flavors of tart cherries , prunes , raisins and lightly roasted malt .
smells great . a whole lot of spices , mostly nutmeg and brown sugar . i wish it tasted as good as it smelled .  mouth feel : frouthy and a bit slimly , carbonation is good .

s - caramel-ly bourbon is huge , with dark malt , bitter chocolate , vanilla and oak . mmm . definitely a bit of heat from the bourbon , but i 'm a huge fan so i 'm loving it . m - thick and chewy with medium-low carbonation . it definitely lives up to the name , this is a bourbon-bomb , no doubt , which is absolutely fine by me . yet another great gi beer .  m : mouthfeel is average . nothing special , medium to low carbonation and bone dry .

taken into my notebook large brown bomber style bottle with nice looking label . like their northern hemisphere ipa , the head and lace are unbelievable . very luscious in appearance .  m - heavy , almost cough-syrup consistency with light carbonation .

the aroma is breathtaking . a beautiful balance of oak , sweet malt , and dark fruit with a layer of very clean smelling whisky gently overlaying the rest of the aromas . just marvelous . unfortunately , the taste fell a good deal short of the ethereal aromas .  mouthfeel is a little thicker than i thought it would be , and it 's drinkable if it 's cold enough to mask its most interesting characteristic : this beer tastes like bananas .

aroma is very nice and hoppy .  this beer seriously surprised me . it pours a pretty nonexistent head . look like a deep mahogany in bottle and glass . taste is subtle but gets better after finish . it is a good brown ale . not mind-blowing but rather enjoyable to say the least . better than i expected .

s- amazing , like dark roasted coffee + stout beer t- good , although i did n't like the bottom end . overall- as much as it was talked up , i was pretty disappointed as a stout lover .  mouthfeel is quite a bit thinner than i would have licked it to be , but the carbonation level is nice .

first pumpkin beer this year with a good head . the smell on this beer is intense . it smells like a very aromatic crumbled pie crust with light cinnamon with a whipped cream aroma .  my first `` f '' rating here on ba .
this poured a very clear light golden with a nice light head that lasted longer than i expected and left a nice lace on the side of the glass .  medium and a little grainy with prickly carbonation .

s : aroma is exquisite : sweet dark chocolate , hints of caramel and bourbon , bits of coffee and molasses , lots of scent and very welcoming . t/m : has a low to medium amount of carbonation with the bourbon very well balanced between caramel , chocolate , and coffee notes .  nice taste , extremely easy to drink and light bodied . the only problem is that it is a little gassy and over carbonated . very nice .
poured a cloudy yellow with a huge head that displayed pretty good retention .  mouthfeel was deceptively thin because of the high carbonation , but was n't that bad if given a chance .

attractive red-amber with a thick , off-white head . beautiful lacing -- lovely and meticulously detailed . a in presentation , for sure !  for such a lively beer , it falls a bit flat in the mouth - not terrible , i just expected a bit more .

looks great though but that does n't make it easier to drink .  the flavor and mouthfeel is where i miss the original bender or some of the bigger coffee stout beers . the most disappointing part of the beer is the finish which has a nutty , dry bender like flavor , but is overall rather thin and has a watery character .

light amber with a dense white head with exceptional retention and lacing , this looks every bit as good as the regular ruination .  this is an epl through and through . do n't be persuaded by the pilsener title . i had it after a holsen which is a real grain bomb . neither beer is that great but this one seemed inferior . and compared to holsten permium that is n't saying much . i you like stella artois or heineken or something like that in a can then go or it , but it is n't too good .
pitch , midnight black colour with a creamy , foamy , long lasting tan head . great lacing . pretty much as good as a stout looks .  m - high carbonation , but a little watery .

the aroma is unbelievably complex . i love the cheesy/cherry taste !  an overall fantastic drink a- poured a rusty orange/brown color . kept a nice white head the whole drink s- like nothing you 've ever smelled before as far as im concerned . had a pleasant wheat aroma t- detected not only a creamy wheat flavor , but also a hint of blueberry m- thick d- i highly suggest it . not usually a fan of beer of this nature ( wheats ) , but would try another make of this

the scents are amazing ! i notice a woodsy , kind of floral or piney smell , with a great hoppy undertone . man this smells good . mouthfeel is definitely better than average for an ipa -- balanced , yet light , intricate nonetheless .  mouthfeel - kinda effervescent . nothing exceptional .

a - pours a rich , reddish-amber color with two fingers of creamy , pale golden head . outstanding head retention and nice lacing .  mouthfeel is a bit sticky and the flavors stick around for a bit after swallowing .

i thought it delicious . aroma is tons of pineapple , and is totally delicious . flavor is also quite good although not quite as good as the aroma .  the mouthfeel is low carbonated almost syrupy , not what i expected .

a : bright , clear golden color topped by a perfectly white head of big bubbles . a lot of visible carbonation supporting the head .  tightly packed carbonation which makes the body feel more medium , feels just a bit too foamy for my tastes .

first of all , consider the deep toffee and caramel aroma ... it 's impressive . also , the yeast strain they use has a nice balance of dry crispness with fruity esters .  thin in the mouth , which leads to great drinkability . would make a good session beer .

black oily pour with a medium dark brown head .  kombucha is usually very vinegary , but this was more in line with a reserved lambic . carbonated to the tongue , but low head retention . m+d- it is a touch watery .

) with other hop nuances and malt to balance it out , very nice . taste-spicy hop at the beginning and then balanced out by some caramel malt finish , huge hop hits on the end of the toungue , very nice .  it smells and tastes like a cheap beer . it is not worth the money that a premium beer can ask . i ca n't think of anything good to say about this beer other than i 'm hoping it will be gone soon . i 've tried pawning the beer off on people and they did n't want to drink it either .

classy nitro appearance - huge smooth white head sat atop a radiant gold body .  i think that it is a bit overcarbonated and that the body is a bit thin , but the smell and taste are absolutely wonderful , and i could drink this all night .

nice head and great retention .  good , predictable macro carbonation , not too fizzy , and a softly crisp , dry , thin , light bodied mouthfeel , average , to be expected , nothing to really complain about here , again , predictable , you know what you getting before you pop open the can .
lots of malt and alcohol in the aroma , like an old ale , no hops like an american-style barley wine .  m - syrapy with a decent carbonation .

appearance- a light clear golden color about a fingers worth of white head and good lacing smell- the aromas of this beer is just exceptional , the noble hops aroma is just perfectly balanced , it is everything i would look for in a pils in terms of aroma taste- the taste of this beer is clean bittersweet that is well balanced it is clean and refreshing on so many levels mouthfeel- this beer has good body and good carbonation balance drinkability- this is one of the best beers ive had and is a perfect spring/early summer seasonal beer it is very refreshing a must try !  it feels just a bit watery .

pour is very dark , but a deep red , garnet up to a light . the head is full , off-white with decent retention , very light lace .  in fact the beer this most reminded me of was the dixie blackened voodoo i reviewed which had the look and taste along stout lines but a much lighter body .

poured like pitch - wonderfully black .  taste : thin malt levels , corn , honey , green grapes , grass , and no bitterness . mouthfeel : lightly crisp to start , dry and smooth at the finish . light in body , thin in flavor . clean aftertaste .
as good as the three finger ivory crown looks , it laces even better .  lighter with some fizzy carbonation and a dry finish .

12 oz bottle poured into a tulip - best by 12/3/2007 appearance : pours a deep , dark brown that still shows a little bit of light through it . the head is tan with a height of one inch.the head is cakey and has deep craters . plenty of lace clings to the glass .  m - carbonation is more muted than i thought .

appearance : an almost crystal clear dark yellow/ light gold beer with nice fluffy white head that has some staying power and great lacing .  the moutfeel is medium , thicker than a lager , but about average for this style .

served in a tulip glass . a - hazy deep gold pour with a generous frothy white head . medium retention , nice surface memory and very rich lacing .  m : mouthfeel is thin and light . thin in an offputting way .

huge inch or more very creamy white head . one of the best lacing jobs i have ever seen from an ipa .  hahahahahaha bourbon my as- . this beer tastes like the worst cake frosting i 've ever had . body 's not bad either if you can get by the taste .

the aroma is incredible on this beer . coffee , chocolate , vanilla , and wood almost completely manage to mask the alcohol which lingers nicely in the background . carbonation is very low but that 's not really a huge problem for me in this style . wish the body was a bit fuller but i 'm not going to sweat the details too much as this is a very enjoyable beer . what 's this ? a bourbon barrel aged stout that allows the barrel influence to do it 's work without drowning out the base beer ?  on the tongue , everything that was on the nose is amplified , bigger , bolder , stronger , more . the body was a bit different than typical , a touch more syrupy and thicker . still nice but not what i 'm really looking for in a wit .

s : traditional witbier smell , but perhaps on the strong side , richer and going deeper . quite floral , like a magnolia . t : promising smell but the flavor does n't deliver . mediocre  they float the lemon in the beer , so you do n't have a chance to yank it out before it imparts flavor . great example of the heffeweizen style , with banana and clove aroma and flavors . a light beer that can be quaffed in copious amounts .

a - this is one seriously dark , sludgy thick beer . tall and frothy dark tan head that hangs around for awhile . pure black and highly viscous .  smell has ton of spice upfront , with belgian yeast and banana . lots of pepper in the taste , which is great because i love pepper . nice bready malts with the belgian yeast flavour . a bit overcarbonated for my preference . this was n't hard at all to get through the bomber by myself .

smell is malty , wheat , banana , citrus ( sweet like tangerine ) and vanilla . complex and very well balanced . taste is tangy , not the malty sweetness i expected . still complex but out of balance . not the smooth wheat beer i thought , more the initial bite of a lager , kind of like a hybrid brew .  this brings us to mouthfeel and i 'm once again taken back to the question of carbonation . in the mouth there is a degree of weight and intensity , however this is beset on both sides by an intense carbonation that strongly effects the overall weight of the beer . the carbonation issue is really just a thing of personal taste but it needs to be put out there , but , overall ; this is a fantastic beer .

from the second i cracked open the cap , the room filled with the sent of vanilla , as far as smell goes this the best smeling beer ever ! the tast is good but not as good as i had hoped this one is sweet with a fair vanilla kiss and a carmalised malt flavor . i think it might be the hop aftertaste on this one , i would rather have this one finish sweet .  spices are clearly evident in the flavor ... some cloves and cardamom both come through with a lot of caramel malts , and an unfamiliar flavor , that i am , in my mind , linking with the yeast used . the beer is pretty light for such a dark color . i expected more carbonation , and i was a little bit disappointed at the smoothness .
appearance : it pours a dark ruby brown practically black with a huge tan head leaves behind nice even lacing as it dwindles .  watery feel for a stout but with just enough body to get you through .
the head is truly fantastic , and the lace clings tenaciously to the glass all the way to the bottom .  m - light bodied , thin with a bit of a sticky feel .
i poured this one in a pint glass and was impressed by the large head .  beautiful mouthfeel : needs more carbonation .

it has a deep amber color with a thick tan head . very attractive . very bland and just slightly `` off '' the taste was somewhat better than was indicated by the smell . it is drinkable but disappointing considering it 's wonderful appearance .  enjoyable to be sure , but it seems like maybe , just maybe , it could have a slightly higher carbonation level .

holy cherry wood campfire smoke !  source/serving : draft smell : coriander , orange flavors , belgian yeastiness , and some brown sugar . overall fairly deep , dark flavors . taste : quite sweet up front with pronounced coriander . the middle does n't really go anywhere , just sustained - or even more - coriander . perhaps there is a ephemeral note of some ripe fruits and alcohol . disappointing . finish is oddly bitter , noticeable alcohol and has a slightly off spiciness .
orange-amber color , quite carbonated . white foam , creamy and abundant , with a good perlage .  m - the feel is sharp initially with a chalky and sublime salty finish on the palate .

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 '' beige head over the clear brown brew . dense head lasts and lasts , with thick lacing .  m : carbonation comes on unexpectedly crisp , but it drinks smoothly .
solid three finger off white head .  the mouthfeel is a bit lighter than expected but doesnt detract , and drinkability is excellent for the abv .

smell is fantastic , pure belgian .  this colored water pours with a pale golden body topped by a thin head with no laciong at all . the aroma is barely detectable with some malty notes . the flavor is almost non existent , however some malty sweetness is evident . no wonder everyone puts a lime in these , it 's to add some flavor .

appearance this one came out a very dark brown in color with a nice , big , lacing brown head .  taste : this is a fairly thin-bodied brew , and the carbonation seems a little much . it has a nice malty taste in the middle , but it 's dominated by strong , orange-tasting hops . this is certainly a hoppy beer , but the hops are n't that intense or asskicking .
a - poured a beautiful and clear copper - i wish i could brew my homebrew to be this gorgeous a color and sheen .  mouthfeel : extremely light feel considering the alcohol and massive aroma .

born on date : june 14 , 2006 ... .aged two years before i drank it and wrote this review ... pours a negro color with a decent brown tinted head .  the mouth is actually a little heavy and chalky for what should be , and mostly is , refreshing .

from a nitro filled pint size can ... pours honey golden yellow with typical nitro-style can head . the head is very dense , creamy and leaves belgian lacing all the way down to the end .  feels a bit thin , low-medium body and medium carbonation .

this is a really nice stout obviously rich with strong coffee aroma and flavor . the aromas are huge . like a big piece of double chocolate cake and an esppresso . a very drinkable stout . too bad it 's just a seasonal .  m - medium bodied and somewhat oily , but the carbonation is a little too lively and prickly for the style , which in turn really thins out the body .
the smell is like chocolate and fresh ground coffee beans.what a great taste .  overall : very light bodied for the style , but very drinkable .
appearance- beautiful clear , dark , golden color . pretty much the color of apple juice . nice loose but creamy one head with lots of staying power .  the mouthfeel is kind of bland .

the apricot smell is huge , very aromatic , and sweet . the taste follows , like drinking juice with hints of beer , but still a good beer .  looking at it you 'd expect a stout , smelling it you 'd expect it to be sweet - it 's neither - and it feels thinner than expected as well !

a : mohogany red brown with a fluffy tan head that lingered for a few minutes . very pretty in the snifter looking glass .  i gave the mouthfeel a lower score due to the extremely bitter after-taste and the thin-ness of the body .

there are so many wonderful west coast , hoppy ipa characteristics in this one , love it . taste was not as equally robust as the smell , however it was solid . juicy oranges and never harsh citrus pith bitterness .  some bitter to this as well there is still some hops to it a little syrupy but there is some carbonation to it so it is bearable .

a : exceptional , should be the example of perfect lacing ! it pours a golden hue topped with a frothy white head that leaves you feeling the beer wants you to drink it .  mouthfeel is thin and becomes slightly tannic at the finish .

the smell is amazing . not sure if i poured a beer , or the sweetest can of ruby grapefruit juice i have ever smelled . a little hop bitterness and toffee scented malts at the very end . nice !  poured into my maudite snifter and produces a caramel color with a finger and a half of off-white foam . light carbonation . banana , pear and floral aromas . a rather tart , spicy taste with some alcohol taste present . while this is highly drinkable , the experience is more enjoyable as it warms .

overall- this beer smells like ... heaven ... i mean the delicate balance of malt , sugar and creamy chocolate is incredible . however , the taste of the beer is comparatively average in my opinion . the hazelnut brown nectar is the exact opposite , not as rich or full of a smell , but a much smoother finish .  f & t : crisp , firm moderate body , more rounded feeling than a lot of macro lagers .
appearance : gorgeous frosted lemon body with a luciously frothy 2 finger white crown . seriously sexy !  mouthfeel is thin with just moderate carbonation .
this is a beatiful beer with a rick cloudy ruby topped off with a thick , dense , off-white head .  it 's slightly watery , but refreshing and finishes a little dry mouthfeel is pretty average .
the nose is amazing . i have to say , i just kept going back to smell this one before every sip..and sometimes just to smell it .  the mouthfeel is light to moderate .

smell imo gets better with its temp . great in the smell category taste is weaker then the smell . i can still get the chocolate and coffee tastes but it is really subdued .  almost feels a bit thin and watery . the mouthfeel throws me a little because it 's a bit thin , but on the whole , it 's a tasty and quite drinkable bruin .
love it when a beer looks imposing enough to quell dreams .  m - medium to light body .

whoo ! an intense whiskey aroma is noticeable as soon as the glass is set in front of you . a malt monster offsetby the alcohol presence . very little subtlety , and there 's nothing wrong with that .  not a big wit guy , but it is summer in san diego and i just got done playing some b ball and was thirsty . i always see it at places and not big on most japanese breweries . very refreshing and complex at the same time . over all i am glad i tried it and i am actually going to buy a pack down the street right now .
smell is definitely that of hops , very nice hoppy smell .  mouthfeel i liked the fullness of the body here , but the carbonation was quite annoying . otherwise , this felt good .

went down to spuyten duyvil and figured i would have a gueuze during the night . the aroma was the big prize here . i could have kept smelling it all night , but i really wanted to taste it as well . i got a big whiff of apricot tartness in the smell and a large amount of barnyard funk . flavorwise this was quite nice , sweeter than i figured it would be , but it also had a sour quality that was much appreciated . this was the fruitiest gueuze i have ever tasted .  m : the mouthfeel is average .
s : very hoppy - i also smell pineapple and citrus . very inviting ! t : great taste .  m : very light , slightly watery , lower carbonation .

a : the beer pours a rich dark color with a huge foamy caramel/parchment colored head .  ok , born and raised in st.louis.. i may be a bit biased . but last summer , i had my heart stole by this beer . i didnt want it to happen.. it just sorta did . its bright a little rich , and nice bitter finish . citrus and maybe honey , i think in these hot humid summers , it cant get any better than a nice summer kolsh at about 35 degrees . ahhhh
a : extremely hazy orangish-yellow with a fluffy white head . it really is an attractive looking beer .  body is thinner than expected on the palate , and the uppity carbonation level does n't help .
the color is nice and dark and has a good tan head ( good name ) yet the aroma seems to be weak .  m : it was thin with moderate carbonation .

blue moons on top of thier seasonals . the beer poured unexpectedly well . it looked great in the glass . slightly hazed amber do to nice active carbonation .  i understand it may the fruit flavor comes from apricots . as expected the taste did n't improve the experience . i gave the rest of the six pack away and got similar reviews from all who tried it .

full frothy tan head , very sticky , not enough of a sample to see lacing , dark stained mahogany color , slight rust colored edges .  appearance : like beer smell : beery taste : like pils in germany mouthfeel : beer-like drinkability : i did n't see jane stop until they stopped bringing it i 'd say its an excellent example of the style .

rich bacon fat . rich and lively . more like eating a brisket than drinking a beer . very smooth . a bit of alcohol warmth at the tail end .  this is not a beer for holding onto and chatting this is a beer for downing quick . when it heats up , the taste gets worse . there are alot better australian beers than this .

50 degrees pours black . beautiful . massive dense head that looks like frothed coffee . a steady hand can pour this so that the head rises in a column right out of the glass .  poured on tap . big thanks to sean for this ! pours a deep cloudy golden color with almost no head at all . smell is nice and sweet with a great maple aroma . taste is nice and sweet , maply but sweet enough to even it all out , easy drinking and super excellent , very awesome !
why not ? appearance : golden orange , with a pearly white head with gorgeous honey-comb bubbles that were perfectly aligned one next to the other .  slightly thin body but just a great flavor .
beautiful looking beer .  the feel was slick , medium-bodied and mildy carbonated , the best aspect of this otherwise horrid brew .
the aroma is amazing with strong fruity hops and maybe even a hint of coffee ... although i may be crazy .  it had a light mouthfeel and slightly carbonated .

smells fantastic . sweet and juicy tart cherries . nice . smells a lot like ng wisconsin belgian red .  feel is light and refreshing , but very active , carb is felt and a bit distracting , it 's not a sleeper .

pineapple , mango , wheat , yeast , flowers , toasted grains , very sweet smelling , lots of resin , alcohol is n't very high but you can smell it t - the taste is a more pungent form of the smell . there is a toastedness at the end as well m - sticky , coats the mouth in sweet , bitter fruit flowers that last for a while , so does the resin d - for being 8 % it 's pretty nice and balanced . there is tons of hops and tons of malt . despite that , it is still very balanced final thought - $ 9.49 is way to much . but it is excellent !  roasted aroma with hints of dark ( bittersweet ) chocolate and coffee . could be fuller bodied , a little less on the tounge then expected . different flavors hint you on the first sip , roasted malt , coffee , dark chocolate , hop citrusness . finishes dry with some hop bitterness and a nice aftertaste . another quality brew from the boys and rogue !

s - lemon , orange , coriander ... pretty standard wit smells . it 's a very very highly dominated by lemon type wit .  i thought the mouthfeel may have been a tad dry and thin for all that malt , but that just adds to the drinkability , which is very good for the strength of this beer .
cherry is very present and smells amazing . slight grain smell .  mouthfeel/drinkability- mouthfeel was at best average for the style .
poured motor oil black , produced a thick impressive tan head , featured excellent head retention and produced very nice lacing .  m - medium carbonation with a rather watery texture .
hazy , with a massive head of white foam kept alive by abundant streams of carbonation erupting like strings of xmas lights . a very beautiful appearance .  smooth but lifeless .
split with airohead2001 a : dark brown with a 3 finger tan colored head that has excellent retention and lacing .  medium-bodied rather than thick .
pours a beautiful ruby color with some haze . i was totally caught off guard with the color ... .a truly beautiful presentation .  the mouthfeel seems a tad too watery as well .
a fine , steady stream of carbo rises within , making its way towards the healthy , billowy , white , mousse-like head . lacing is top-shelf !  mouthfeel : it was a very light beer .

the look is just outstanding . full orange unfiltered goodness with a clingy head . beautiful beer .  taste is clean and very hoppy in a sweet and earthy way . not as much citrus/pine note in taste , lots of hearty hops and almost fruit like malt backgrounds . very easy drinking double . highly enjoyable but not something completely unexpectant from the style .
slight fruity strawberry , smells quite delicious ! t : fresh malt .  the taste is really well balanced but the beer feels a little thin and watery which is surprising given it 's alcohol content .

it 's a combination that works incredibly well . at first the chardonnay does n't come through so well , it 's more of a vinous acidity that blends with the funk .  pours black but with some deep red highlights with a slight off-white head that is gone in a flash leaving nothing behind , milk chocolate is very prevelant in the aroma with a little smokiness and a roasted coffee hint.nice deeply roasted flavor with big doses of cocoa and smoke , alot of flavor melding going on but seemed a little light in the mouthfeel department otheriwise a top notch brew.a easy drinker with alot of flavor needs a little tweaking to be great in my opinion .
aroma is huge coffee with some vodka and vanilla , overall very strong and wonderful . flavor is again coffee , alcohol , and vanilla .  m - very light and crisp .

pours a slightly hazed honeyed orange in colour with lots of visible carbonation . the head is absolutely massive , taking up almost half the glass and leaving a patchwork web of lace on the walls of my glass as it slowly recedes .  m- carbonation is high , and initial mouthfeel is good , but somewhat thin .

s : wow , that is the greenest nose i have ever smelled . huge fresh/wet hop aroma ... i ca n't stop smelling this beer . i have put my nose to the glass at least 20 times before tasting this one . t : wonderful crystal malts lay down a biscuity flavor which is very nice . very `` green '' hop flavor .  a bit too thin , and a tad over-carbonated . the body was n't quite there , but still a winner .
surprisingly good retention and spider web lacing .  the mouthfeel is crisp and refreshing , although almost too light and dry .
dark auburn with ruby hues . thick tan head , 2 fingers tall , great retention and lots of creamy lacing .  medium bodied slick mouthfeel , slightly cloying .

pours like it 's worth the mad duckets . inky , opaque black with a full brownie colored soapy stout head that absolutely will not die no matter who tries to kill it .  lightly bodied with a lean , but passably dextrinous mouthfeel .
d - the flavors are good , the aroma great , and the alcohol is n't too high .  m : light to mid bodied , little watery at first bit smooths out as it warms up .
a pretty balanced aroma . very nice . t- roasted malts upfront followed by a earthy/spicy hop bitterness that carries through to the finish .  mouthfeel is the only real weakness for this beer .

the aroma is huge ! full of yeast and sour citrus ; this has all the classic characteristics of a wit except bigger and bolder . could stand a little sharper carbonation , it 's a little too creamy and makes the beer feel slicker and heavier than it out to be .  so , i guess it 's got an average mouthfeel .

pours pretty damned opaque black , slight red tinge when really held up to the light , very decent head - ochre in colour - sticks around at about half a cm thick , leaving some gorgeous clingy lace , really sticky webs of beige foam . very nice stout appearance .  mouthfell was ok , but it is a stout , it better have a decent feel to it .

a : pours black with two fingers of khaki head that recedes into a creamy cap with good lacing .  the looks are not deceiving , in that this beer goes down very easy . the finish is semi-clean with a hint of flavor left on the tongue . p.s . i like this beer better on tap than from the bottle !
real nice looking beer .  almost a medicine-y mouthfeel .

the head has pretty amazing retention , lasting even after i have consumed half the beer .  m- a solid amount of carbonation coupled with a lighter body makes this drink overall a little too light for my personal tastes .
dark brown thick viscous liquid with a brown head .  it had a medium body but was kind of rough along the palate as it went down .

pours a hazy pale golden yellow with sky-high , frothy white head with great retention and generous lacing . beautiful beer !  veeeery smooth taste , could drink a few of these . not sure how true to the style this one is , almost like a stout lite . i like it quite a bit though , hides a 6.3 % well . malts are dominant in the flavor , but balanced excellently ... i dig it , dawg . would buy again , but not a super deal at $ 4.88 a bomber

some dark fruits even this out and make for one wonderful scent . taste is strong on roasted malts and coffee beans with some dark fruits and a bit of water .  mouthfeel is ok. not too thick or too thin , but carbonation could be a little weaker .

easily the most impressive appearance of any single ipa ive had . perfectly clear deep amber in color . an average pour yields a 1 1/2 head that hangs around for a minute leaving lace on nearly every area it touched .  this beer pours a hazy orange/amber has a 1/2 finger head with very little retention and spotty lacing . the aroma is a strong citrus at first but as the beer warms there is a earthy bread odor . the taste is a spicy citrus with bitter grapefruit in the finish . this beer is smooth and very drinkable , i plan on having this one again .
appearance the beer is a perfectly clear , fiery copper . insane walls of lace are left from the dense , but narrow head .  m- a very fine carbonation .
black as the night , exquisite head .  m : this is crisp and refreshing early but the carbonation goes quickly and turns watery .
this looked exceptionally wonderful .  it is medium-light bodied ; bubbly , with a dry , slightly gritty finish , almost like it was dry hopped . this is a pretty solid dubbel .

pours clear copper with a towering , dense 2-finger off-white head and tons of effervescence . fantastic stickage and lacing .  mouthfeel : feels slightly carbonated and thicker than water on the tongue .
very nice .  it was lite bodied , almost watery .

the nose was really quite amazing . banana , spice , phenols and wheat . quite an amazing non-german weis beer smell . the taste on the other hand was quite a bit different . light and very smooth . so the smell is amazing . like fresh german weis , or a belgian like leffe .  the beer did suffer a bit on the palette from the high hopping rates , as this did not glide down in a soft manner , and presented a bit of an edgy mouthfeel .

very sweet . t - sweet slightly toasted brown sugar with alcohol being noticeable . taste like it smells but more robust .  the mouthfeel was kinda thin and fizzy , but did n't really detract from the wonderful flavors .

out of a bottle this beer was a chestnut brown color with a huge three finger head . the khaki foam died back slowly , displayed good retention and excellent lacing .  i 'm sorry guys but another swing and a miss . beer aggressively foamed out the bottle immediately on opening , after sitting in the refigerator for two days , so no mistakes on my part there . the sourness overwhelms any good qualities which are there , lying underneath but truly irrelevent . cigar city is a great brewery with great potential but lets get it together guys . do not put these beers on the shelf when they are clearly sub-par . cheers everybody- it 's only beer . i expect great things from this brewery but let 's please enact some quality control .

hazy orange with a yellow hue at the edges . massive , creamy white head that fades very slowly . good lacing .  flavor is nice and smooth with the sweet nutty flavor followed by a cocoa sweetness . watery mouthfeeling makes this one a smooth brown ale .
just an awesome and complex aroma ! all of the same on the taste buds but there is also a hint of cherry syrup .  m : fairly light , slick body with a low amount of spiky carbonation . mediocre .

minimal head retention & lacing s : apples , candi sugar & apricot t : apples , candi sugar , & leafy hops . dryness , leafy hops , & candi sugar , jammyness , dirt , plus lemon hops are all there as this warms . finishes fruitty & dry , plus some grapefruitty hops mf : medium bodied with low carbonation drinks pretty slow , due to the dryness , the brett did n't really help or hurt this one  the mouthfeel is not a complex one and is rather unbalanced and nondescript .
really kinda sexy .  the mouth feel is a little thin , unlike some higher-end ales , but the drinkability is very good .

old blarney is warm oaken brown with a glowing fruity aroma hinting at melon .  lager quality with a lighter cleaner body and feel . my one `` complaint '' is the bite of the carbonation that holds a particularly sharp feel .

appearance is exceptional due to the huge creamy , rocky , tan head .  pours a deep red with an inch or so of head and reduces quickly down to a nice lacing.. no much of a hoppy nose more of a malty raspberry preserves.. mouth feel quite light with a tinge of pucker.. i would have to say there is a very clean bittering hop flavor masked in the fruitiness .

bomber at mad mex in pittsburgh ... a- deep golden color with a nicely carbonated head but not much lace left in the glass s- big , fresh hop aroma ! mf- lots of carbonation and slightly oily d- the bomber was plenty . i was n't big on the bitter finish - if you like earthy hop flavors , this is your beer .  the taste is of roasted malts , toffee , and to some degree , molasses . the smell is good and the taste is incredible ... but letting this porter get warm isnt such a good idea since it significantly reduces its drinkability . i will definitely pick up another case of this becauce it is probably the best porter i 've ever had . if you like this then definitely give brooklyn black chocolate stout a shot because thats damn good too .
strong smell of fresh hops and tea .  mouthfeel : body is a bit thin , but it is a brown ale .

a : the head and coloring on this is flawless . beautiful thick rich creamy head that has staying power . color is not far off from an ipa .  more of the same in the finish , kept triggering my gag reflex medium bodied , slick with moderate carbonation , skewed way to sweet , needs some alcohol burn to mitigate this horrible drinkability .

aroma is bright with citrus and syrupy with alpha acid promise . this is without a doubt the most unique and hardest nose to describe that i have ever come across .  the mouth feel is a bit light for such a porter .
stellar head retention & lacing s : has a bit of off/brett smell to it , phenols , the main shortcoming of this beer .  it had a medium to light body .

see thru light orange with a swirl of vigorous visual carbonation feeding the thick and fluffy cap of foam on top .  carbonation is medium to medium-heavy , and mouthfeel is slightly viscous , landing just north of water .

a : a beautiful beer with golden very clear hue topped by massive 3-4 finger white head with pyramid of bubbles -- large at the bottom , small at the top -- with a whipped cream , frothy top with good retention and spots of lace .  mouthfeel is a little thick a little syrupy .
poured into a new belgium snifter a - transparent blood red , half finger head , off white almost tan/brown and some serious lacing s - sweet .  f - medium body but carbonation is very weak .
bomber a : beautiful two finger fluffy white head .  mouthfeel : surprisingly thin , but not too watery .
pours a nice looking copper color with an impressive head and scads of lace .  m - the mouth feel is lush and oily but a tad too soft by the end .

appearance : 3/4 of the bomber was moderately poured into the tulip , leaving a full 3 fingers of fluffy bubbly white head . this is probably the nicest looking head i 've ever seen in this glass besides the beer it was intended for . absolutely fantastic lacing .  ( m ) - a very high carbonation level .
a - nice dark mahogany color , very thick , ca n't see through it . excellent character and all that i expected coming from stone in a porter .  sharp and light bodied .

i had this on tap at ashleys , a bartender recommendation ... it pours nice and black with a full creamy head that has really nice lacing , my hopes are high ... the aroma is really dead , hard to pull anything out but a little roast coffee , my hopes start to fade ... the taste is better than the aroma , it has a light flavor but not much here and its super thin to drink .  light body and mouthfeel .
bottle courtesy of thebeercellar2 : poured a slightly hazy blonde color ale with a huge foamy white head with great retention .  mouthfeel : pretty light in the body department .

pours beautifully , golden , with the head of a root beer float , great lacing , plenty of activity . the beer will pour clear until you add the yeast from the bottom , then a haze .  wow ! what a pleasant surprise ! i tried this beer on-tap at a new restaurant near my apartment called `` kushi . '' i was in the mood for a light , white ale - and this beer definitely delivered . it was crisp and refreshing . taste was tart and light , a little sour , but well balanced . i 'd have this beer again , and again , and again..

great aroma . coffee , roasted malt , brown sugar , rumlike molasses . decent .  m - high carbonation , chalky , tannic , medium balance , some sweetness and high bitterness for a stout . i would love to see this oak aged as it would help to refine the bitterness and carbonation that hurts it .

the smell is fantastic , with an aroma of fresh strawberries .  no real cascade , but a full , rich tan head with plenty of texture over a nearly black and opaque body . heavy lacing clings to the glass . delicious aroma of black bread . espresso and chocolate flavors . labels soak off easily and make an excellent decoration for plain garage walls .
awesome looking brown .  mouthfeel -- medium-light in body with prickly carbonation . slightly gentler carbonation would have been preferable , but a twirl or two dozen remedies the issue .
pours a four finger off-white head that fades slowly to a thin layer leaving some lace . nice crystal clear amber color .  medium-full bodied with smooth , lower carbonation .

pour : 12oz pour to tulip glass . looks amazing . nose : somewhat light as far as this style beers go .  weakest aspect of this beer is the body , which is a bit on the thin side , with light carbonation .

bomber poured into a gruss aus munchen mug ... both received from zorro in the beerfest bif a- deep orange with red highlights ... big pillowy off-white head that leaves great lacing on the way down and takes a while to subside ... looks delicious s- intense and complex with some elements atypical of the style ... big sweet fruits ... caramel malty goodness ... spices ... clove ... raisin ... and big earthy grassy hops ... smells like a great oktoberfest but bigger and hoppier t- similar to the smell ... but everything is soaked in booze a little too much for my taste ... finishes with a hint of toffee and chocolate ... burns a bit on the way down ... still tastes like an oktoberfest though m- tiny carbonation bubbles feels good on the tongue ... despite the heavy sweetness it does n't feel syrupy ... medium bodied d- limited by the booze and the burn on the back of the throat this is an interesting take on the style ... and one i 'd love to try a different version of  the amount of flavor packed into something this thin and `` refined '' is unusual and noteworthy . it feels a little creamy on the swirl , but i do n't really like where it stimulates the tongue . however , the mouthfeel leaves something to be desired , so how many will you want to down consecutively ?

this is a very nice hefeweizen . at first , it smelled of ripe pears and cloves ; as the beer warmed , ripe banana notes became more prominent . the taste was a complex blend of the fruits and spices from the nose and the strong yeasty backbone i expect from this style .  rich caramely malts , maple syrup and toffee with a hint of bitterness to balance , but definitely very sweet . finishes with ripe fruits . mild carbonation . notes : very pleasant and surprisingly delicious to pair with just about any food .

nose is classic stone yeast with a great floral hop kick . overalll , it was damn good . i thought it was almost an ab light with some added pine and less citrus , and no hop double kick to the palate , which works well .  mouthfeel is rather full but not heavy , and it is certainly not full-bodied but moderate .

aroma is quite fruit forward with pineapple , pine , grapefruit , malt still comes through though with hints at caramel and biscuits . taste is an amalgamation of flavors and aromas coming together to form one badass beer . all aroma 's transferred into taste , pineapple and mango coming through swinging in a sweet nectar . awsome as always .  mouthfeel is average , not much to say one way or the other , except , i guess it was smooth .

pours a very black with a beautiful 2 finger milk chocolate colored head that leaves sticky mapping on the glass as you drain it .  the only thing i do not like about this beer is that it is a little lacking in body - seems a bit thin .

pours a bright amber color , with an awesome head . great looking ipa .  mouthfeel : i 've never been a big fan of the body of almost all american porters as they just seem thin , a tad watery , and big on carbonation , and this one does n't break that trend .

a - a dark brown color with a thick head with the carbonation cascading down the sides continuously in some convextion like action . lacing clings all over the sides after the monsterous head dissipates to a managable level .  mouthfeel is kind of thin , and a little watery .

thick , black beer pours with a beautiful , fluffy head that is the color of light caramel . it shows staying power that would make a porn star proud . a very well distributed lace is left behind .  crisp and dry with soft to moderate carbonation . kind of metallic . the flavor was pretty good , but the mouthfeel was lacking .

the beer poured into a chalice clear medium orange/amber with a tall and white frothy and spirited head that fell slowly and then lasted to lace the glass .  mouthfeel is a bit lean , and watered down .

smell : this beer has a very sweet and fruity aroma . you can also smell some of the malts .  m : light smooth and refreshing , im serious . its a run of the mill average beer in the mix with huge macro beers that ussually will run marketing circles around it .

appearance : pours a crystal clear pale gold with a fluffy white head on top . the head settles to a full cap with tons of spider web lacing covering the entire glass .  very suprised . i am a fan of lighter beers and this one provided a very unique grapefruit aftertast . i have yet to have any other beer that i can even compare to this one . it 's appearance and mouthfeel are typical of a lighter wheat or white beer .

nice ! maybe this one suffers from where i am in my own personal `` beer journey , '' but i 'm getting a little tired of ipa that smell great & fragrant & then assault you with aggressive , tongue-battering bitterness .  a beer haiku for you : '' norwegian beer ? yes ! a great ipa option , seek out and find one ! '' my first norwegian [ that 's what she said ] . nice citrus overtones , not too 'hoppish ' , and very drinkable . a rare find , but well worth the money to have another option .
hazy straw yellow in color with a strong , dense white head .  if this beer has anything going for it , it 's a decent body which lends itself to an okay drinkability rating .

appearance this was black and thick like engine oil with a giant head that showed great retention . the foam was like lumpy shaving cream and covered the inside of my glass as it went down . awesome !  m : medium body and carbonation . it is a little sticky . some sharpness on my tongue as i swallow .

12 oz bottle poured into mad elf tulip . pours reddish amber very clear with a nice fluffy white head .  surprising amount of carbination gets you with the first sip , it foams up in your mouth . but the body is alot less than i was expecting ... not think , just mostly carbination on top of a thin to medium body.. ? the flavors linger on your tongue , mainly at the back sides .

copper to gold ... lots of light flickering through and a rocky 3/4 '' bright white head ... aroma is awesome ... truly great . some spicy cinnamon and grassy hops ... herbaceous in a very cool herbaceous way with a a hint of basil and nosefull of dill . peppery and delicious . awesome .  unfortunately this seems a bit thin but very tastey though . well for a sawbuck per growler it is real nice .
a - pours a cloudy , orange-tinted , medium-brown color with a 2-inch , off-white head . truly a beautiful color .  m : fairly light bodied and the only part that 's halfway decent .

a - dark black and viscous with oily stains that recede into the glass as you drink it . the pour produced a 1/2 inch dark tan head that dissipated fairly quickly .  mf : pretty thin , good carbonation .
liquid dark bread .  mouthfeel : on the light side of medium with a crisp finish . it is a touch too thin imho . with the malt being so delicous , i want a bit more body to compliment it .

whoa ... i can smell this one from about 3 feet away ! milk chocolate , cocoa and latte coffee aromas . roasty , toasty malty goodness with a healthy dose of grassy hops . 4 words that best describe the flavor : fresh , roasty , malty and hoppy . i only have 2 minor complaints with this one , the noticeable astringency and it is a bit pricey . aftertaste is long lingering and slightly bitter . for me , this is a good stout , but not quite great . easily quaffable and certainly will drink again , but the price tag limits this one to just a bomber or two per year for me .  m- on the lighter side with lots of carbonation .

poured a dark walnut color . as the beer hit my glass , it came alive producing a nicely controlled enduring head that laced the walls of my glass .  mouthfeel is dry and light bodied , but it 's sorely lacking spritz .
pours a nice cloudy , straw color with a great head .  mouthfeel is flat feeling and a little thin .
a- pours a cherry color with a thick off white head and sparce lacing .  mouthfeel is ok , very watery , lacking hop oil and that `` slickness '' that many other ipa 's have .
huge vanilla , wafer , and lemon custard aroma .  somewhat thin and watery mouthfeel .

the chocolate/vanilla combo is lovely . t - woody and earthy with some cola . the aroma is top notch . i just do n't taste any of the aroma in the beer .  this was probably just average on the mouthfeel , imo - whether you consider this a wild ale or bsda .

a - this looked absolutely beautiful .  the taste is even worse , at first it taste like a regular lager and then an overwhelming amount of chilli flavor hits with a spiciness in the back of your throat after you swallow . i really do not like this beer at all but they do do a good job of making it very jalapeo-y . if you 're into novelty items and spicy food then this the beer for you .

pours a dark , black coffee color with three fingers width of mocha colored head . reduced to a fingers width over consumption . great head retention and the lacing was so thick it just caked the sides of the glass .  m : 3 day old ginger ale type carbonation ... o : not a great beer .

s : this beer has a overwhelming aroma . it 's extremely rich , yet smooth . one of the sweetest beers i 've ever drank , but it is still well balance and taste exactly how it smells . definately a sipping beer .  the mouthfeel is light bodied , but a little thicker than i would expect from a beer with such little taste and aroma .

looks beautiful . fluffy white head compliments the golden body .  the ringwood yeast just tore this up and gave it a slab of butter on top ... m : crisp , but just tastes pretty bad ... d : a pretty bad beer , the ringwood yeast dominates this brew so much that i had to drain pour the rest , too bad .
bottle : poured hazy brown reddish color ale with a super huge off-white head with excellent retention .  starts creamy , but finishes surprisingly thin , which is more noticeable as the beer warms .

bottle purchased at julio 's liquors , westboro , ma poured a somewhat hazy , light straw with a huge , five-finger bubbly head . the resulting chunks of froth eventually faded to a dollop of foam in the middle of the glass , which lasted for most of the drink . tons of bubbly , sticking lacing throughout .  super easy to drink ... just a little thin on the mouthfeel .

a - crisp , brilliant clarity . bright orange with hints of red . head is initially thick then fades to a persistent thin layer with gobs of lacing on the glass .  elements of pine , citrus , resinous elements too -- slightly oily but in a very pleasant manner . the biggest flaw i can find with this beer is that it wastes too much of the carbonation in the beginning when it is first poured . it is slightly flat in the mouthfeel although i have tasted some other ipas recently that were far worse in this department .

pours like a yeti , oil black , black on black no light thru this baby with a beautiful coco colored head that laces well man this brew looks goood .  the beer 's mouthfeel is smooth , if a bit watery ; this may be the same problem as the vanishing head .
