a - beautiful and clear dark red/amber with a lacing that lasted through the entire glass .  m- medium body , slightly watery d- very drinkable . watery , but enjoyable .

absolutely fantastic ! taste : very mild in the taste , but with a strong , strong oatmeal component - stronger than many oatmeal stouts . every other `` stout '' aspect is pretty subdued : there 's milk chocolate chips , some simple sweetness , a regular malty note , and a little bit of coffee , but the coffee definitely is n't too prominent .  light and effervescent , with a hint of caramel malty sweetness . i bought a six pack of this , and after drinking the first beer , immediately grabbed another six . definitely the best 5.99 beer in the store . do n't pick this up if you 're looking for a complex thought-provoking brew . but if you want a session beer that 's a good alternative to macro-swill and are n't into over-hopped domestics like sam adams and goose island , this is a great seasonal . similar to a leinenkugel brew . a friend said that this was what you 'd get if newcastle brewed an amber . drink straight from the bottle - not really enough nuance to bother with a glass .

the pils is a beautiful , vibrant , absolutely clear bright gold . very nice sticky lace .  a smoked lager from fort collins brewery . 1.0 liter bottle for $ 8.29 . i was somewhat skeptical about this beer especially because i thought there two other beers edgar and doktor were an abomination , but i opted for it and was it ever worth it ! a slight smokinness stimulates the nose as well as some alcohol , caramel and citrus hops . the palate was dominated with notes of butterschotch , smoked malts , cedar , citrus notes , light fruits and the flavor was very lingering on the palate . i did polish off a 1.0 so obviously this brew was pretty damn drinkable !

after a really good pour from the tap , i 'm served this very pretty beer . golden amber color with a perfect head and lacing .  i remember when this beer hit the streets - people loved that cute little orange slice they served it with . it really introduced the variety of beer to many of my friends . my girlfriend once had me call coors over the july 4th holiday because she did n't like the looks of the white sediment on the bottom of the bottle . coors gave us the thumbs up to drink . appearance is quite hearty . for me this is a beer to compare other witbiers to . not the best , nor the worst . the irony here is i drank this beer given to me by my friend `` porter ''

pours a clear orangish red color with a heavy thick wite head that stays around for ever , the smell of hops in all ther floral glory take my nose on a rush of excitement .  medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .

the strong aroma of fresh strawberries is uncanny , and overpowers any other scents .  m : slightly acrid which is a bit off putting . it really is not as creamy as i would have liked but there is a good amount of body .
black body with a big off white light tan head , lots of sticky lacing .  m : medium-light body with medium carbonation , this beer is a bit on the heavy side for the style .

( a ) - pours a clear amber color that produces a large 2+ finger off-white head that has superb retention ; thick fluffy stuff that is sticking to all the sides of the glass .  magic hat wacko 12oz into tasting glass this beer is wacko . expected a fruity aroma , but instead got some beefiness . not much in the way of taste either , maybe some citrus from the hops . this beer did not do well in my new england beer tasting .
amber pour with an effusive white head that left great lacing and never dipped below a substantial film .  m- kinda thin , but full of great flavors that wrap around your tongue .
s : it smells great ! very citrusy/fruity and somewhat spicey .  m - smooth and medium/light body . a slightly dry aftertaste .
pours a nice orangish amber topped by a fresh , bubbly , thick head .  mouthfeel is strange .

poured into a rapscallion glass , formed a 1 1/4 '' tan head over the clear burgundy brew . head fades sedately , with heavy sticking froth lace .  i 'm almost halfway through the pint and still impressed with the carbonation . i 'm also surprised at the body ; it seems a bit thin and makes the beer rather perilously drinkable at nearly 7 percent alcohol . this long , bitter and dry finish is perhaps the most enjoyable quality of this beer , that and i suppose it 's dangerous drinkability .

tried leffe blonde for the first time and it poured as a lovely golden color with an amazing head . probably the best appearing beer that i 've ever had , especially when it was n't even poured into its signature chalice .  m - moderate beer body , strong carbonation bite .

intoxicating , rich and sweet hot cocoa aroma . i ca n't say that it smells like anything i 'd call beer , but i love it nevertheless . fantastic . although i love the aroma , i find myself glad that it does n't taste like it smells - something this sweet and chocolatey would be better suited to one of my wife 's sickly sweet nightcaps .  the mouthfeel was a lacking but i just may start picking these up as a session beer .

the pour was a spectacular deep red , like the color of sunset with an almost yellow head .  smell : piney hops and malts are slightly toasty , tickles the nose readily easily . taste : hop sensation is immediate , blending with the mild toasty-earthy malt taste , progressing to a light , tangy-hop bitterness in the finish , surprisingly balanced . drinkability : darker than a typical ipa , the character of the malts successfully complements the well-hopped taste , very drinkable .

beautiful pour on this ... nice brown amber body with minimal bubbles popping from the floor of the glass , but the head is rich and creamy . beautiful look to it .  got this in the secret santa 2008 - from dmeadows , thanks again ! a bit of a funky musty aroma mixed with the spicy nutmeg , quaff is a boatload of allspice , nutmeg , fig , plum and an underlying hint of alcohol booze - even after 2 years in the cellar . and the elderberries add quite a different take on the solid offering . sweet initial start , boozy and hoppy finish . a true winter sipper , tasty and enjoyable with the football game .

s : some banana right at the front , chocolate and roasted barley notes . caramel and a yeasty fruit scent are present . ca n't wait to see what develops as it warms .  the aroma has a touch of stale coffee that then moves to a better defined roasted malt in lager form . the dark malts are great , minus ther adjunt must to it . i ca n't really explain why , but this is one of my , `` right after a hard day of work while you wait for dinner to cook beer . '' easy on the palate and tastes good from the bottle and the glass .
a unique , well balanced , clean smelling brew . the taste brings on a more smoky malt profile .  m - this one goes down extremely smooth , but it is a tad watery .
a : a vibrant goldlen ale with a strong haze . towering snow white head ... frothy and creamy . looks like scoops of whipped cream .  it 's a bit thin in the mouth .

aroma is spot-on for the style , full of ripe banana , yeasty sweetbread , clove , and a touch of vanilla . pretty good mouthfeel on this one too , although it felt a bit watery at times .  if you 've ever drank the milk after eating a bowl of fruity pebbles ... spot on i guess maybe add a little carbonation .

the bottled version pours dark brown , almost black , revealing deep crimson highlights when held to the light . an awesomely creamy tight head the color of chocolate milk shows no signs of stopping even at the bottom of my glass .  m : where it falls the shortest with a light-for-style body and overcarbonated .
a really great looking beer .  this brew can feel a little thin , although it 's so tasty that it hardly bothered me .

pours a slightly hazy dark gold with a big frothy white head that retains well and laces the glass .  served on tap in the black angus restaurant at the stoudt 's brewery . body is a dark copper color . thick head with excellent lace . the scent is a bit fruity and has elements of apples and hops . a nice balance of sweet malts and bitter hops make up the flavor . alcohol peeks through , which is surprising as this is a relitively low abv ale .
appearance : the pour is golden with a massive white foamy head .  m : sticky , slight aftertaste .

the nose offers up a large puff of coacoa and some nice roasted malts smothered beneath it all with just a pinch of coffee beans in the mix as well . taste wise this beer took a step down from it 's wonderful nose . some bitter chocolate was obvious as well as bitter coffee notes but the roasted malts seemed to fade away and the finish offered up an odd tangy quality . overall this beer started out very promising but i think the overall taste failed to live up to the appearance & nose of this beer .  m - little watery , but lots of carbonation .
delicious aroma ! the taste is fairly roasty upfront , with hints of cocoa in the backing .  taste-taste 's like water . mouthfeel-very light , crisp .

appearance - wow at first it looked like a coffee milk shake , but after it settled it was a pitch black color with a creamy tan head .  tastes like ... well , the bottle says , `` english style amber ale '' ( _not_ american amber , eh ? rich and sweet and malty , mild hop flavors . maybe a bit of a blend of an esb and an english brown , you know ? very pleasant . easy to drink . very easy to drink ( ahem ) . hmm .
poured a deep and clear amber color with a huge off white rocky head which remained for the duration . a beautiful beer .  very simple , but i simply like it . lots of carbonation .

a - i love the colour . pale , bright cloudy and with a great distinctive glass .  this is one of my favorite beers . had it at a fall rennaisaunce festival locally . hate that it 's seasonal . it was light , and very refreshing on a hot autumn day in the south , and yet warm and comforting on the cool ones .

i always look forward to the fall and winter season beers that boston beer puts out ; winter lager is my favorite . pours a beautiful dark copper color , with a nice head that retains throughout .  m - not as much carbonation as i expected after how it poured .
s- one of the best smelling beers i 've come across .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , but the carbonation is pleasant .

poured from a bottle into a pint glass , the beer is jet black , with a half-inch milk chocolate colored head that is dense , small bubbled , and has great staying power .  taste : sweet and funky but so refreshing . mouthfeel : lingering taste .
very fresh and well balanced . 5/5 t : again , very fresh . very nice balance and complexity .  the mouthfeel is just a pinch thinner than i would have liked .
great cascade . black as night . lacing . less impressive flavors than appearance and aroma . nice creamy feel in the head and body .  mouthfeel and carbonation are both slightly low .
aroma - delicious nutty with a hint of yeast appearance - golden amber yellow with plenty of carbonation .  it was very astringent .
pours nicely , light golden color not quite straw , making a lovely 1-inch high rocky , stark white head that left excellent lacing .  m- good carbonation . a little watery for an imperial stout .

inviting and complex . this ale is a sniffer . no odors . a good , complex aroma . taste- this ale tastes like it could be the base for the belgian red , except without any of the cherry , sweetness is well balanced by sour and bitter .  m - moderate to thin body - the backbone appears to be driven by its hefty carbonation .
smells : sweet but spicy smells protrude though a spectacular wave of citrus and floral hop characteristics .  medium mouthfeel and no carbonation .

pours a slightly cloudy reddish brown with a gorgeous light tan head with amazing , photographic-quality lacing along the sides of my cab glass .  medium bodied , but has too much carbonation for my liking .

pours deep , rich mahogany with a one-inch head that descends to half-size and stays ( very impressive for abv level ! ) . some lacing sticks to glass .  i usually really enjoy drinking founder 's brews . it is missing much of the character that founder 's usually has from its selection of hops and malts . i could n't finish this , as it reminded me of raspberry pucker . somewhere someone probably really likes this brew , but it was way too sweet for me . sorry founder 's , but this seems like you tried too hard and failed . i 'll still have other founder 's brews because of there fairly good track record with me .
smells wonderful . hops , and some hints of malt .  mouthfeel is thick and flat , with a slight prickle that could come from carbonation or just from the alcohol .

amber bottle offering from cooperstown poured a spectacular inky blackness with a noisy , rocky and frothy tan-colored head that eventually settled down to a finger-thin level . very nice patchy lacing of the glass .  the mouthfeel is light-to-medium-bodied with a mild amount of carbonation . my only complaint is that i expected a heavier mouthfeel .

bottle into a pint glass , this is one good looking beer . based on looks alone , it looks like a great marzen , just deep , deep copper that almost glows from the middle of the glass . impressive .  average body for a stout not too viscous but the carbonation is a little low , makes you work to get the flavors out from the alcohol background .

the head is four or five fingers tall , light tan in color , huge sized bubbles , wonderful retention and thick sticky lacing .  a dark , dark brown beer shows reddish highlights . it 's mostly clear and sports a big , 3-finger head : pale beige , caf-au-lait , dense , thick . roasted chocolate nuttiness in the nose . dark cocoa up front turns thinnish through the top . some nice chocolate malt goes tangy for the roasty , nutty , bitter chocolate , toffee finish . it 's just a nice , tasty , roasty , chocolatey brown .

auburn with a suspended cloudy of silty and plenty of rising carbonation . a flocculent head of ivory nearly tops the glass , cresting at about 3-fingers . excellent lace hangs in frothy curtains .  mouthfeel suffers from lack of carbonation , but flavors are all right up my alley .

tried this one in a tripel karmeliet glass , which really did it justice , gleaming burnt-orange body , clear with a huge head of off-white foam that left an opaque lace on the glass . it was litereally impossible to see through the lace .  mouthfeel - refreshing but a little sour-ish on the tongue .

2006 vintage batch 2 16.03 % abv poured black as the background of ba into a southern tier imperial glass , tan fluffy fine bubbled head rose quickly and fell jest as fast leaving a nice topping of bubble . not exactly sessionable but it makes you marvel at stouts like black albert with nearly as much alcohol that can hide it as well as they do .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , but seems a bit flat .

special thanks to vapodge for sharing poured into a dogfish head goblet a- dark brown with a small white head s- vanilla , fruity and some alcohol/rum t- caramel , spiced in the end , there 's a nice sequence , one after another with a nutty flavor after the end when you breathe ! m- creamy and smooth with good carbonation d- great brown and easy going !  this , i hate to say , really is n't very good . the spice is entirely too powerful , it 's cloyingly sweet ... everything is out of whack and the concept of balance seems to have been lost on harpoon 's brewmaster on this one . very glad i had the sense to grab a single instead of springing for a sixer . a real shame , as i quite like several other beers brewed by harpoon .

| 5.5 % abv | 2011 brewer : moa brewing company style : euro dark lager glass : pint appearance : burgundy body with an incredible trail of lacing and a not-too-shabby head .  m : this is where this beer turns a bit down for me . to me this tastes a bit undercarbonated , making the mouthfeel a bit watery for me .
one of the better smelling beers i 've come across .  m : a little thin and prickly , but not bad .
almost looks like a stout , even smells alot like a stout with roasted chocolate malts in the scent . very good lacing all the way down the glass .  m- feels `` sticky '' to my mouth .
pours dark , very dark , brown color with light , light , brown frothy 2 finger head .  this beer is exceptionally thin in the mouth however .

the color is a beautiful deep rich ruby with hues of copper infused with rust around the edges . the head is about a half-finger thick , and there is a slight amount of lacing , as well as some spotty gobs that stick to the edges of the glass upon a swirl .  aromas of grapefruit , malt , herbs , melon , chocolate and espresso . taste was an all-out battle royale between the toast malt and the grapefruit hops . tart and tangy , this full-bodied brew was not for the faint-of-taste . no fruity sweetness here , just a hint of molasses and brown sugar way in the background . a paean to malt and hops .
poured into a pilsner glass . a - beautiful , deep mahogany brown .  mouthfeel is pretty fairly light with decent carbination .

appearence : pours a very attractive hazy dark reddish brown with a creamy , foamy beige head that leaves nice lacing , and has decent retention .  i would have expected a little more body in this beer . a little skinny for my tastes .
beautiful ruby amber color with nice tracings of bubbles around the glass .  m : not particularly laudable .

a : has a roasted red appearence that is very inviting .  the mouthfeel is like nothing i 've tasted before ... kinda an awkward feel . '' not necessarily bad , but just very different and weird feeling .

s - cinnamon , vanilla , wood , bourbon , chocolate , custard and i swear a bit of curry spice in this sweet and fun aroma . i 'm picking up some minerals , cherries , and prunes too . d - after the really attractive nose , this beer was a huge letdown . underwhelming , and not worth the money spent .  the mouthfeel is a little more carbonated than i like in a brown & not as thick .
aroma was a blast of fresh hops . very fresh and nice . pretty nice balance for such a hop bomb .  mouthfeel is on the light side , but there is too much carbonation in this .

this is a super dark porter with a tan , tight head with excellent retention and nice lacing .  light-medium carbonation and medium bodied . piney hops and paint thinner nose . flavor starts with sweet malt but quickly goes to hop and finishes with a paint thinner aftertaste . overpriced at $ 1.50 for a 12oz bottle from manchester wine and liquors manchester , ct .
great looking beer .  feels thin for such a high abv barrel aged beer but it is easy to drink and the alcohol heat is mild considering .
the brew pours to a deep red color with a nice inch high head that will not break down ! the brew has left nice heavy off white lacing on the sides of the glass .  a little watery at the end .

the aroma is fantastic . it 's a boquet of floral hops .  m - thin to medium body , but not watery . the carbonation is at a moderate level . the mouthfeel overall is at the appropriate levels , but nothing jumps out as distinct or mind blowing .

this beer looks great , feels great , and smells great . it tastes awful . a beautiful , rich cherry smell is most noticeable in the nose , backed up by chocolate espresso .  served in a bottle i picked this up during the christmas season just to try one of the many seasonal types of beer that were available . the smell reminded me more of a vinegar- esque flavor and once i took a sip my mouth was taken on a journey that i never want to recreate again . now do n't get me wrong , this is n't that bad of a beer , the flavor just was not something that i myself could truly enjoy . for those looking for an interesting take on a beer i would suggest this particular brew but i just did not like the feel of the pickle taste in my mouth after awhile .
pours a blood orange color , mildly translucent , with a whitish amber head 3 fingers in length .  light bodied and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

the aroma is great ! it has a nice malty scent that boasts of pale and crystal malts along with a solid spice content . it has a solid malt flavor , but the spices really take away from the overall enjoyment . it 's just got too much spice .  mouth feel actually makes me think of watery , unlike several other fff beers i 've had .

pours pale amber with a large lasting head and lots of lacing .  thin even for this style , i 'd like to see just a little more intensity in the backbone . mouthfeel : as you 'd imagine as you watch it pour , this is very much light-bodied . good carbonation and a clean finish .

this beer brings me to the rare occasion where it smells better than it tastes . the smell had me anxious to take the first sip , but i was slightly disappointed by the taste .  m : moderate body , mild carbonation .

this is probably the most intense , thick , beautiful looking nitro pour i 've ever had the pleasure of gazing at . dark blackness with effervescence of the gods fueling a truly never-ending frosting-like cap . the curtains of lacing are epic .  carbonation was ok , but with the heavier than expected mouthfeel , i think the hops were lost on the palate more than others textures .
crazy lacing .  the only place that is lacking is the body is a little watery .

served on nitrogen , it looked very much like guinness drraught with the cascading waterfall of tiny bubbles .  m : medium body with hardly any carbonation d : drinks good all the way thru that makes it seem like winter in the summer .
hop aroma galore ! ! this beer has a nice copperish color a decent size head . the aroma is amazingly floral and zesty hop bitterness .  not very full in the mouth , a bit thin in my opinion .

poured into a new belgium globe , this saison is golden honey topped by a three fingers of peaked off-white froth , bubbles vary in size . the head tappers off to a manageable quarter inch and sticks all the way down the glass , nearly a solid sheet .  moving back it develops a bigger bready malt profile and the spice really picks up , finishing the hops take over leaving a big earthy peppery bitter hit . m-after the very exciting show with the cork and having the bottle almost overflow i was really surprised at how low the carb was . slightly slick , i would like it to finish a little drier . d-very nice , i would even venture to say that its better than dupont . i was really interested by how well they work in the high abv , i did detect a little heat but it only helped to bring out the spice and citrus flavors .

appearance- pours a 1 finger head that has awesome retention . head stays the entire time and remains a dark off-white color . the beer has a deep brown color with no visible clarity . ties many other brews in the best appearance contest !  pours a nice orange/ruby color with a thin head . it has a nice bitter `` bite '' to it but it 's not overwhelming . some citrus fruit with a hint of some darker fruit , maybe plum ? weird , i know . i could n't defiantly drink a few of these over the course of a night .
( a ) - pours a pitch dark black color that produced a fluffy head . good retention . bits of bread in there , but this is crazy .  mouthfeel is oe 's strongpoint .
appearance : this beer looks incredibly promising when it is poured .  the body has a little chalky hard-water feel to it -- like mineraly .
a - dark , dark brown with red-brown edges . big creamy looking head with good retention and lacing .  mildly thin body , but not alarmingly so .
pours a light copper/gold with a big creamy off-white head .  mouthfeel is a hint to the watery side , would have liked it a little chewier .
s - really impressive aroma , oak and alcohol , also fruity and caramel-like notes .  mouthfeel was alright but nothing to write home about .

it pours a lovely midnight black , with an ample head of whipped chocolate . the aroma is probably the brew 's best feature , with a roasted chocolatey flavor mixed in with malts and fruits . it 's a delight on the nose , and had the mouth watering before even taking a sip . it 's surprising that it 's only 5 % alcohol , because it really tastes like more . there is definitely a sweetness to the beer that really gives way to the hoppy bitterness .  on draft at brewery , 11/19/07 . light golden-yellow with reasonable carbonation . aroma is of artifical strawberry flavoring , like a breakfast cereal or strawberry soda . flavor is likewise dominated by artificial fruit flavor , although there are oxidized , corny off-notes as well . i suspect this is just their blonde ale with strawberry flavored syrup added . aftertaste is mainly lingering , unpleasing mild astringency and some nasty bitterness . blecch . will never drink again .

pours a beautiful amber with a frothy foam head with nice lacing from a 12 ounce bottle .  light to medium carbonation , with a creamy mouthfeel on the tongue and in the mouth which leans towards crisp and almost watery in the overall feel to it .
not a huge imperial stout fan , but i enjoy one now and then . this beer is night black , and no light through it . solid  m : somewhat thin , especially for the style i hoped for something richer .

my overly aggressive pour not only caused a wee bit of spill-over , but also netted me two fingers ' worth of light-tan head with good retention . color was a solid copper ( no amber at all ) with ne-quality clarity . beautiful !  m - medium to light bodied . it 's just thinner than i expected .

i love hops , and you get strong nostril stinging hop aroma up front . actually smells similar to a hop flower . t- surprisingly sweet , very strong . clearly much stronger than your average beer but still very drinkable .  m - the feel is lively and refreshing for something so big , could still stand a bit more oatmeal feel .

looks delicious . whats amazing is how dark the head is .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with high carbonation . not sure if this is a weird bottle but the carbonation is much too high for the style , better once it had some time to dissipate .

this pours pure black and thick . nice head .  this is one of those beers that drinks more like a wine than a beer . aged in wine barrels and carrying the flavors over into the finished product with a unique character added to the tartness of this beer . all the rr products are made to the highest of standards by one of craft beers true master brewers ! i recommend trying all their brews if you can get your hands on them..

pours a clear amber with orange hues in the light ; blood red in poor light . lazy bubbles rise up to two fingers of light khaki head that last awhile before falling . there is all kinds of lacing sticking to my glass .  m : smooth . nothing too impressive here .

great look - booming 4f frothy cream-colored head , with tons of sticky lacing ; golden amber in color , 50 % opaque , and plenty of visible carbonation .  '' - phish my girlfriend picked this up despite the owner of the beer store saying it 's one of the worst beers he ever had .

s - pretty nice , like a tripel-lite . this was nice to try , but i 'll stick with other wits i have preferred .  s. rich brown sugar , molasses and smoke t. quite complex with molasses , roasted malt , smoke , brown sugar , cinnamon and clove in the front with a touch of hops in the back m. surprisingly clean , with lingering malt behind medium carbonation d. very drinkable for anyone who likes malt i first tried this beer at a local liquor store 's beer tasting . this is a great example of a fall seasonal for the relaxed craft drinker .
a - pitch black . huge , solid brown foam with fantastic lace .  mouthfeel : it 's ok but it could use more carbonation with the associated bite .

by blackberry so this will be short . beautiful pitch black with dark tan head . lots of hops in this dark intense beer .  mouthfeel is light , a little on the thin side , with a mouthcoating bitterness . good level of carbonation .
smells really enticing . i kept wanting to smell this one .  mouthfeel seems a little watery .
pretty good retention with tall clouds of lacing on the sides .  short , dry finish which makes this eminently drinkable . light bodied and perhaps a little under-carbonated .
quite nice . carbonation is moderate .  sharp carbonation in the mouth feel . not a very friendly mouth feel but it is very drinkable .

s : wonderful , i could really pick out the chocolate and coffee notes .  wow , i enjoyed the flavor of this beer , the hops are more present in the aroma than the taste , maybe showing up in the extremely dry mouthfeel though . not exactly full bodied , a little light compared to the dark lords we were drinking prior to this , but still it matches the flavors in an appealing way .

a : this is one of the nicer pours i have had in a while ... deeper in colour than they will often be , it 's almost copper but has a gold hue to it , as well . head is frothy , creamy , and has something of an orange hue to it , and it loves to hang around . retention is great , with a nice wall of lace left all around the glass and about a quarter finger of head remaining as it is consumed .  maybe this is a touch thinner than i like , but it definitely works on a hot day like today .
overall a nice stout with a great nose .  the mouthfeel is thin with a watery texture , and lively carbonation .

pours pitch black with a huge huge tan head , fades incredibly slow , if i was in a rush to drink it i 'd be kinda peeved it took so long to settle down , leaves a good amount of sticky lacing .  light carbonation and light-medium bodied . starts almost sweet but hops dominate , boring , finish is dry and slightly bitter . brewed aug 12 , 2005 . $ 1.79 for a 330ml bottle from lina 's beverages painesville , oh .

pours a one-finger nearly white head over a crystal clear light orange rust liquid .  an astoundingly good dark beer for the price : 10 bucks for a 12-pack at wegmans in state college , pa . it brings some of the unique flavors found in yuengling porter to a slightly lighter beer , but make no mistake ; the stuff is not weak . it might not be the most delicious beer on the planet , but the combination of good flavor and low price are unbeatable for me as a beer-enthusiast college student ( not a drunkard ! ) everyone else has described the taste well enough . my review is mainly economic .

wonderful appearance . fluffy off-white head . a lot of belgian lace .  a good pale and pretty cheap . $ 4.99 a six and 5 buck pitcher specials are easily had . full flavored and nicely hopped w/goldings .

on the nose i get alot of tropical notes , mango , papaya etc . a lovely nose , but a kinda boring taste .  creamy head and taste . drier than i expected yet not too hoppy ; which makes me happy ! the color is the dark murky chocolate you expect from a good stout , but lacks the `` fall effect '' one sees in guinness for example . overall a nice drinkable and easy on the palate brew !

this brew came out looking quite nice . there was a good amount of off-white head , and very cream looking .  it 's rare that i ca n't even stomach a beer long enough to get a few sips down . this beer gave me one of those rare moments . the smell was a sour , and the taste was dirty and skunky . i did n't want to waste the pack , so i made a couple of michelada cocktails . they were actully quite tasty.. nothing like worcestershire and tabasco to make something taste better !

it pours a lightly hazy , yet radient honey amber orange color . three inches of off-white head explode towards space , settling about a half inch above the rim of my pint glass . this is one of the most impressive heads i 've seen in all my years of beerdom , earning it a 5 in appearance .  the mouth feel is very dense and viscous that is entirely too syrupy . a little too thick to be enjoyed , but if you can separate the mouth feel from the flavor , youre in for a treat .

pours a very nice clear deep dark amber-reddish-brown with an inch of beige foam that lasts .  kinda liked this one , the guy at the beer store said the bottle was sitting there for awhile but it held up great.real hazy-orange color with a good head , smelled fresh and citriusy , body was a little thin to me for the style.refreshing taste with some citrius-yeast note very easy to drink.i also think this would be a good warm weather ale .

pours a beautiful crystal clear gold with hints of amber and amazing active bubbles . nice bright white 1 finger head . this is what a pilsener should look like , a beauty . this beer glistens .  m : light to moderate body ; moderate carbonation ( a little much for the style ) ; hints of chalk & acidity .

malty , yeasty , and a hint of pine hops , this just seems to have it all ! appearance : frothy finger of creamed coffee head settles to a finger of creamy head on an opaque black mug that only shows a few carbonation streams . the head left some clumpy lace that thinned out to a trace before i finished the mug .  i 'm 90 % sure this is the same beer as their `` gretchen 's gold '' , which is really what i 'll be reviewing . the bottled version leaves much to be desired vs. on draught . i 've not tasted such a difference between tap and bottle in any other beer . extremely refreshing and drinkable , pleasant sweet malt w/ barely discernable hops for structure . scant head . overall a great beer in its style , with no real flaws . if you can get it on tap , it 's well worth it .

a picturesque color of orange rust with a large , frothy and lasting head of white foam .  consequently , the body was found to be light , yet the beer was flavorful , with a nice , almost malty , finish . the mouthfeel was similar to what one would find in most of the american large brew beers .
a nice looking beer .  the finish is fairly dry and woody , but the body is a little flaccid without much supporting carbonation .
12.3 % pours a crimson lavender with a huge pink tinged white head .  mouthfeel is unfortunately overly carbonated , it leaves it very bloating .

this beer has a beautiful pour ; two fingers of head that slowly deflate , leaving thick lacing on the glass .  it basically boils down to personal preference . a crisp mild bitterness lingers in the back of the tongue , accenting the overall characteristic of the beer . while thin on the head , it does have a nice nose of lemon and yeast . that musky , spicy smell that makes my mouth water .

a : poured a deep dark brown with a thick creamy head , but that was the highlight of this beer .  the texture is smooth and a little oily . the favor is a nice mix of sweet orange peel , coriander and wheat malts . the finish is wheaty and a little dry . blue moon is very refreshing and drinkable . [ orange slice was not used for review ]

this pours a great copper color with a creamy white head .  it has a sharp astringency i can only assume is the fruitiness . the finish is chemical and most unpleasant . the finish was crisp , for what it 's worth . i like saranac 's pale ale , their adirondack lager is ok , and even their winter wassail is drinkable and interesting , but i had to sacrifice all of my remaining saranac belgian white beers to the drain gods .
pours thick and dark brown which settles to an opaque black with a huge mocha colored head that retains well and laces very , very well .  somewhat thinner bodied than some of my favorite pas .

poured from 12oz brown bottle into clear pint glass a : beautiful copper color with clumpy white head but scant lacing s : citrus and piney hops aromas with a bit of biscuity malt t : well-balanced with prominent hops profile with a pleasant sweet malt finish that is a bit drier than i expected .  the mouthfeel is ok - just slightly under carbonated .
appearance - probably the best looking beers i 've seen in a glass .  of course . a little high in the effervescence .

the smell is quite nice , its a bit yeasty , and smells like raspberries and oranges .  m : sticky , almost syrupy and resinous to the extreme . kinda unpleasant but not terrible . o : not a bad double ipa , mouthfeel is really detracting though i think .

very nice smelling beer . currants are the first flavor i notice , following that comes a punch of coffee and dark malt . cherry is the most pronounced flavor here , and overall it is an interesting , rather good stout .  the mouthfeel is ... well ... ok ... a little bit of an after taste and the alcohol is apparent ... the beer is absolutely worth a try ...

silky chocolate aroma with a touch of smokey malt , vanilla , earthy oak , bourbon , toffee and lactic cream . there is a perfect amount of barrel presence in the nose providing earthy oak , subtle vanilla and coconut balancing out the roasted malt , burnt toast and coffee bean notes . the complex balance suggested in the nose is missing here with an overwhelming bourbon presence . this beer improves as it warms but overall the bourbon is too strong , overpowering the other flavors .  m- a thin body- highly attenuated with a nice spritzy non-bloating carbonation .
love the aromas . sweet tropical fruits and florals . a little malt as well .  m- a little thin and watery for a stout but goes down smooth .

a- while i was looking for a bottle date i noticed a lot of chunky sludge at the bottom of the bottle . this is perfect looking .  presented much carbonation when poured.a thick beige head with spotty traces of sticky lace.a strong malt and coffee aroma.very nutty , molasses , and chocolate smell also.the color looks to be a very dark red to almost black.the smell and appearance are above average for most sam adams beers.the mouthfeel is a bit weak and watery.no carbonation bite to it.a very dry finish with a touch of a hop bitterness that stays in your throat.a drinkable stout and goes down smooth but is average .

this black beer lets a little red through when held to the light . it has a creamy , frothy tan head that fades and leaves excellent lacing .  mouthfeel is thinner than expected , with a slightly higher-than-expected carbonation . rather drinkable , but i 've had better oatmeal stouts .
very strong fruity aroma ... possibly bananas , from the onset throughout the entire bottle .  mouthfeel is medium-light .

a- wow , what a great looking pour . nice one finger pink/cream head s- the smell really through me off on this .  m : sharp at first , fizzy , but lights up as you hold it . still , a bit strong and that cuts down on how much you can have . d : i had 10oz with no problems , but a second might have gotten bothersome due to the fizz .
pours a dark brown color with a really large tan head with quite the retention time and a ton of sticky lacing as it falls down my glass .  mouthfeel - a bit of a strange after taste but very crisp .

the aroma however is a little more impressive , smokey , burnt toffee , mocha , and roasted grain were pretty strong , definetely got my mouth watering .  m : the only real cavet of the brew is the feel . but it 's generally a bit thin .
poured deep black as midnight with a huge creamy head the would not fade till the end .  the feel is really light and crisp , almost how i wish many lagers and pilsners could feel .
aroma is probably my favorite thing . fruity and tart aroma .  m - mouthfeel was alright ... carbonation was high and body was light .
a - brilliant clear orange-amber body with a frothy 1 finger head .  medium carbonation and thin mouthfeel makes this brew very drinkable .

a light brown very fluffy head with a dark brown body with mahogany light coming through . good lace left on the inside of the glass . interesting , inviting . i really appreciated the look of this beer but the smell , taste , feel and drinkability were like many other more readily available beers in this area from great lakes brewing company .  full bodied with low carbonation that made it feel a bit flat and dull , mild astringency and a bit of warmth . the texture was pretty good even with the low carbonation .

the nose is huge . heavenly hops aromas of pine , citrus and resin and backed up by a malt backbone that miraculously isnt completely shut out by the monster hops . fabulous . the taste follows suit with more of the same balance between the two heavyweights . however it almost met up to my expectations , i think mostly because of its fantastic aroma and great balance . im not sure if id consider this one of the best dipas in the world , but it certainly was an enjoyable experience that brought a smile to my face .  m - interesting flavors dance around but actual feel is pretty standard light ale d - fun , interesting , pairs well with peppery steak or cheese , not too strong .

we evaluated every stout we could get out hands on here in the western us . we did the same with the non-us stouts we could find . obsidian stout had a robust roasted flavor but a very strong , bitter late bite that ruined it for us .  m : pretty low carbonation , which is definitely not a problem for the style . the body 's a little thinner than i 'd prefer , though . a nice , smooth mouthfeel to the beer .

it 's hard for a high original gravity beer too look great.. smelled of tons of maris otter malts , syrup , brandy , grapefruit , roses , and tiny hop leaves . lots going , but mostly toward the sweet side . had some strange creamy but earthy notes too , and also some strange alcohol and hops flavor in the finish .  m : a little too light in body , i know this is a brown ale , but i feel it was lacking something .

appearance : pours a good lucking translucent to clear amber with a moderate head and quick dissipation .  it drinks a little like carbonated white wine . the finish is somewhat dry . an interesting and refreshing brew .

12oz bottle poured into a pilsner - fridge - 2009 appearance : a somewhat cloudy golden orange beer with a 2.5 '' off-white head . good carbonation and a relentless cake of a head .  had my fifth sn pale ale tonight thought id have another for reviewing purposes and same as always it goes down very smooth very clean light hops aroma with a piney finish taste . even though i love this beer i do think its an extremely drinkable all around beer just a bit hyped maybe ?

pours a pitch black color with a dense , solid , foamy head with excellent retention and lacing .  mouthfeel : others have pointed out that nuova mattina falls short delivering a creamy mouthfeel . it is highly carbonated and too harsh .

the daunting image , 16.03 abv content and the word `` stout '' all together had me mesmerized as i added it to the cart . appearance - black gold ... texas tea ... could-not-see-light-pass-through-black . pours thick as oil . nutty brown color head that gets darker to the bottom of the foam . it left a syrup like film in the mouth and peppery feel at the back of the throat .  mouthfeel : a little high on the carbonation and not as thick as i 'd prefer with a stout .

a : deep gold color . very good clarity . fades to the classic belgian lacing .  not exactly a esb by definition but a good beer by my standards . a dark beer in color , with a fruity hint on the nose , of apple and a strawberry sort of smell . the taste is smooth fruity and a bit hoppy all at once . my only complaint was a bit of a bitter after taste , but hey it is a esb

great looking beer , with a clouded glowing yellow body and a large fluffy white head , but asides from this promising appearance its all a bit of a letdown .  m - the feel is cold and mildly coarse .

pours an ominous black with dark brown head that is thick & creamy . simply amazing appearance .  this beer is very balanced m : little bit of body but still water and plenty of carbination but it complements this beer extremely well d : give me a twelve pack of these and i would be glad to finish them any time .
a bit one dimensional , but damn does it smell nice . good , but just good . 3.5 m : lighter medium body .  really seems watery . carbonation is nice .
smells great . many people have stressed the coffee part .  mouthfeel is a bit thin , carbonation high .
a - clear golden orange colored brew , nice head , great retention and some bubbly lace .  the mouthfeel was really lacking for me in this otherwise uni ( brou ) que brew .

nose : a nice rich pine , grapefruit , and floral is the initial aroma . the nose is better than the flavor .  mouthfeel is okay , but needs to be either thicker or creamier to work with the taste -- as is , it 's just a tad watery .
pours a beautiful red/brown with a creamy tan head .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied and slightly syrupy . minimal carbonation .

not quite perfectly clear light honey amber . a couple solid rings of lacing .  split with the wife at the eccentric cafe in kalamazoo , michigan . looks like a wheat beer with absolutely no odor coming off the brew . very , very wheaty , to the point of being a bit of a turn off . more cherry & less wheat would have been a better combo , methinks . this got actively unpleasant as it warmed - the aftertaste was a killer .

this stout is a deep brown/black with a good-sized , frothy red/brown head with good longevity that leaves great lacing .  mouthfeel great carbonation . perhaps a little thin , but not a detraction . a bit sticky on the aftertaste .

it smells exactly like wisconsin belgian red , no stout scent whatsoever . it is a nice sweet cherry pie scent with a hint of oak . interesting . i like it better than bell 's take of the style .  medium-light body with moderately-high carbonation . good but a bit astringent and tannic .

this elixir pours into the glass with a beautiful clear amber body topped by a thick off white creamy head with a good amount of lace left behind .  nice scent , very bitter with some nice citrus and floral american hops , but with little of the nice sweet , clean red ale scent i expected to go with it . nice hoppy , pale-ale-type flavor , nice american hops , with enough malt to keep it near to balanced ; much hoppier than a regular red ale , but that was what they were going for . goes down fine , if a little rough from the slight unbalanced aspect . pretty darn hoppy for such a low abv red ale .
this beer had a beautiful apearance . i thought that the sedimentation was amazing as it slowly fell to the bottom of the glass .  palate : medium body and higher end carbonation .
strong pour results in a creamy head , a bit soapy until it settles . dark as night in hell . beautiful .  overall feel is good enough , but was a bit thin .

a : deep red and cloudy with a nice reddish 2-finger head , dissipates slowly with beautiful lacing .  m- a little on the thin side and a little under carbonated . overall i thought this was a good octoberfest beer , spot on for its style , besides its mouthfeel .

the beer pours a dark black color with a thick , creamy , cocoa looking head . retention is very good in this beer and there is plenty of sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel is less than exciting . fairly thick , though not as thick as it could be , and hardly any carbonation to speak of .

poured an extremely murky cider color with a great , 2-fingered head of frothy , beige foam that loved to just hang out and leave terrific lacing behind on the glassware . beautiful looking beer ... like an apple cider with a frothy head on top .  mouthfeel is medium bodied with some carbonation on the tongue .

appearance is a clear orange to amber hue , head is a huge mass of effervescent foam that mostly sustains , great lacing all over smell is moderate caramel and toasted malts intermixed with fruits , toffee , and light sugar sweetness taste is mostly toast and roast malts , the toffee comes in midway as does slight caramel and bittering hops , finishes dry and malty with a hint of alcohol mouthfeel is light-to-medium bodied , thin and watery texture , mild carbonation drinkability is high , this is an amazing beer and what i would hold to be an exemplar of the esb style , alcohol is well-masked and this is well in the the session range , big props to the guys from the craft beer radio podcast for hyping this beer !  mouthfeel is highly carbonated and drying , as it should be .

pours a ruby light brown with a medium creamy off white head that retains well and laces the glass a little .  body is a little thin and the carbonation is a little high for the sweetness of the beer .

big hoppy nose , with fresh oranges , and a bit of cut grass . sweet and hoppy , playing less off the flavors of the nose and adding new ones like grapefruit and pine , with a sharp pepper bite to close .  mouthfeel is decent and light , but not as noteworthy as the aroma and taste .

this beer had a great color .  the taste is nice , the coffee does n't seem overbearing or anything , but i 'd prefer more a thicker body and maybe more sweetness . very tasty but more body would be nice for a fit with the flavor .

s- wow , lots of spices . gingerbread and pumpkin are huge in this beer . nice for someone who is concerned about spices dominating , but i think i would prefer them to be a little more noticeable . the taste was unexpected compared to the smell , but i guess that is the beauty of beer .  m : a bit thin , but still decent .
pours to a brilliantly clear straw color with a thick white head .  m - very light for a stout .
the smoke is not overwhelming , in fact it 's well balanced . d : a very interesting beer . not for everyone , but i enjoyed it .  mf is a bit lacking , thin , though creamy .

on tap at the stuffed sandwich a : peach/golden hazy color . head is solid , 1/4 inch layer of whipped cream on top of the body s : lots of funk .  bready malts and a faint aftertaste of alcohol is also present beer is way over carbonated . only thing that got to me was the over carbonated .
the look is decidedly porter-like , with a magnificent head of darker froth that would make that style proud .  mouthfeel : highly carbonated for the style .

candy like and distinctly phenolic aroma . taste is phenolic and candy-like . warming on the palate yet hot with alcohol.. musty and earthy with undertones of blood and iron . mouthfeel is very distinct , light to medium bodied with an aspect of wine to it , ca n't quite find the word to describe it , other then winy .  smells of sweet malt , grains , hops , toasted bread and honey . very weak nose overall . tastes of roasted malt , grains , lemon , citrus hops , caramel , bread and yeast ... a toasty flavor that is not typical for an ipa and more like a lager than an ipa . it 's a bad ipa , not hoppy or like an ipa at all ... a drain pour , as it was tough to finish this beer . bordered on terrible .
pours a pitch black with a nice creamy head .  m - i 'm finding myself rather indifferent towards the mouthfeel .

huge ripe fruit aroma . very juicy with lots of grapes and apples . great nose on this one . solid flavor .  mouthfeel : carbonation is average . body is unfortunately a little thin , contrary to what your taste buds are telling you .
pours a beautiful dark red , bordering on mahogany . the lush light brown head leaves plenty of lacing .  smooth and sweet , this is pretty nice . carbonation is a bit low , even for my liking .
smell is good ; roasted malts and heavy with chocolate , but with a nice hop aroma in the background .  the disappointing : wow , what a highly carbonated brew , almost champaign in the fizziness .
impressive by sight and color only .  sort of thin . the hops seem a little tired , though .

s- bright , citrusy , floral hop aroma with lemons of course , orange , pineapple , apple and mango followed by some alcohol fumes . very pleasant . t- whoa .  had on tap at the brewery . pours nice golden color , clear and crisp . true to style in every way except maybe not as malty . but this makes it nice and crisp . brewer does a good job on the lagers . light grassy hop aroma blends nice with the earthy malt flavors . recommended .

on-tap at beachwood bbq , a : pours a murky orange with a full white head , excellent head retention and lacing .  im sure this loses ratings for its thin palate , but taste wise this is spot on . more roasted coffee flavors and a touch of smokiness . an imminently sippable brew . nicely done .

pours a lightly hazy blonde with very strong orange and copper tones . huge , super-creamy head , white to off-white in color ; lasts a good while and leaves thick lacing .  the mouthfeel is probably a little bit too carbonated and thick for how this beer tastes - the delicate floral aspects make me long for something a little more mellowed out .

pours a lovely burned clear copper in color with very , very thick and sticky white head that not only lasted the entire pint ( s ) , but also left thick lacing on the glass .  m : medium mouthfeel , with medium carbonation . leaves the mouth semi-dry .
s - smells quite fruity . very light and refreshing smelling . t - with such a crisp nose , i was taken aback by the taste of this one .  m : very light . a bit over carbonated but not overwhelming .

appearance- golden honey , beautiful color in the pils glass . no unattractive , excessive bubbling . a nice head formed during the pour and lasted the duration of my drink . there was a significant amount of lacing on the sides of the glass .  the feel was unremarkable .
beautiful in this glass . truly , a sight to behold . ok - on to the beer ... opaque - dark as night - the darkest night .  the mouthfeel is a bit thin .

blonde bock/mai bock is my favorite lager style and in the spring i look forward to trying new ones.this poured into a .5 liter stein a full rich golden ( not blonde ) with a fluffy very well defined white head thaat turned into a creamy mass after settling slowly.aromas were not pleasant , like wet grain with some sort of spoiled corn element , just not good.the flavors didnt show many of the nasty attributes of the smell wich is good , big buttery , caramel sweetness with some sweet alcohol and and toasty grain in a lingering finish.if you take away the bad smell this is a pretty good blond bock , just needs some tweekin .  very nice hoppy taste , crisp and clean with a nice malt balance and a great bitter aftertaste . goes down fine , perhaps a bit rough from overcarbonation , but a very well down ipa .

smells deliciously smokey . lots of rich , dark campfire smoke and bitter black malts .  t & m - lighter body and rather refreshing in it 's character ; if anything , feels a little too light ... almost a hair watery . clove character is lighter , but present with a hint of bubblegum .

color is ominously close to budweiser , but dark enough to tell the difference . s-faint undertones of a normal ipa , then the hops gloriously hit your nose like a freight train . t-quite bitter as it should be , but there seems to be an odd or off flavor that does not belong , but dissipates after a few swigs .  mouthfeel was far more watery than i expected .
pours a nice honey golden color with voluminous , thick , white head . beautiful lacing/head . great retention into a little cap .  pretty good carbonation with a little creaminess to it as well .

bottle enjoy before month notched-sep served in a pint glass like the other beers in the latitude 48 deconstructed ipa series , this one poured a glowing , orangey-amber color with a near three-finger tall head of khaki colored froth . outstanding retention .  mouthfeel is avera- man , this beer is actually giving me a headache .

very nice looking beer .  m - my only complaint with this beer is that it is a little thin . i may be just really enjoying everything else about this beer which makes we want to forgive it for being thin .

it had a nice amber colour with a thick foamy head and a fruity aroma .  a light to medium body , with prickly , active carbonation . the carbonation was just a tad bit higher then i would have liked , but was still enjoyable .

arroma : what a bouquet ! this is one of the freshest , hoppiest noses ever to come out of the bottle . if i could drink this through my nose i would . taste : this is basically a stronger , more full bodied version of arrogant bastard ... which is already pretty damn strong and full bodied .  very good beer but does lack with a thin somwhat over carbonated mouthfeel for a stout .
short , sustainable head with a creamy looking dollop of foam clinging to the glass . extremely enticing .  mouthfeel was average -- no bad bite , but not much body either .
really good staying power and pretty heavy lacing .  m : less smooth than the iv ; it has a rubbery booze component that i do n't care for . otherwise fine .

this poured out a very beautiful orange-gold with a very hefty snow-white head . the lacing on this was pretty impressive to say the least .  really interesting for a christmas seasonal . a good amount of spice and hops as it poured into a nice dark orange , with a little bit of lacing and head . i did n't really feel the `` festive ale '' as much as some of the other beers i 've had around this time , but it did have some good spices and taste .

presentation : it was poured from a 14.9oz/440ml nitro or widget can into an imperial ( nonic ) pint glass . appearance : it pours slowly and extremely foamy with an abundance of tiny tan bubbles . after a minute or so , the bubbles settle on top of the beer which is a lovely honey amber colored liquid . the head that forms is supper creamy , slightly oily and light tan in color . the lacing slides down the sides of the glass just above the head .  somewhat substantial body , nothing too heavy . if any hit , a little too much carbonation but that is stretching it .
very complex and enjoyable smell . the taste is very interesting .  mf : there could be a bit more of a body to back up the full flavor of this beer .

the pour produced a thick , dense head nearly 2 inches thick . head lingered for a long time and left good lacing . surprisingly few bubble streams .  it kind of explodes in the mouth and the carbonation is a bit on the sharp side .
bottled feb. 12 , 2010 - dark black viscous stout with a thick frothy dark mocha head ... wonderful looking stout .  m - mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side for my liking .

i 'm usually not much for appearance ratings to begin with , but this thing looked gorgeous - thick , ruddy brown head that stood 1 '' tall on a 3 '' pour in my tulip glass .  body was a bit thin/watery with average carbonation .

a - slightly cloudy amber with an amazing , globular , dense styrofoam , duvel-like whipped head and tons of lace . impressive by any standard ; beautiful . s - pine , malt and ( believe it or not ) sweet cucumber .  aroma is assertively malty and a little bready . well-balanced on the palate , hops are subtle ( that figures - the use of east kent goldings is revealed from the label ) . malty and a littly nutty , with a clean finish after the malt notes dissipate . a good session beer ( again , as suggested from the label ) , and a very close cousin to a true british mild ale .

the foam stopped exactly at the top of my perfect pour glass , nice trick . it 's a pretty ruby red color with moderate carbonation .  mf- lower carbonation than i was expecting right out of the gate . mouthfeel was the only slight flaw .

barnyardy , old gym sock , malt vinegar , champagne like aromas . astringent with each sip . beautiful beer , i 'd expected some carbonation , but i coped with it .  the only odd thing i noticed was sort of low carbonation , odd because there was a lot of foam on pouring . but it was n't really stale feeling , it just could have had more mouth presence .

12 oz bottle poured into a nonic 2008 vintage a - the usual ris color with a 2.5cm tan/brown head that would have been larger had the glass been taller . d - the beer itself looked beautiful , but its flavor and aroma were really weak .  tiny bits of lemon or orange come in from the hops , but there is not a huge fruitiness . finishes dry too . this is an interesting beer .

no lacing at all s - sweet dark fruit and rich spices come through the nose that produce great pleasure and a sense of holiday .  it is a bit thin and has a low abv , but this makes the beer a great summer refresher , when you do n't want a heavy beer .
pours beautiful , medium-large head with huge retention .  m : medium-little body , ok carbonation .

pretty looking beer here with a nice ruby red body with some lighter amber hues when held to the light . creamy light shade of tan and about 2 fingers of semi-sticky viscosity make for a nice looking head .  about half-way down the glass , the mouthfeel seem smoother and slicker as well .
a - black color , dark brown head . one of the darkest heads i 've seen in a beer .  bit of texture on the feel but still pretty thin .

a- pours a splendid bronze with a frothy white head that lasts and leaves plenty of lacing .  `` bottled in 2009 '' pours a nice red in color , a hue i have n't seen in beer before , with no head , though it is carbonated . there are also weird vegetable flavors that are not that pleasant . noticeable alcohol flavors and dryness . the more i drink of this the worse it tastes , actually . this beer just does n't do it for me , and it hurts me to give a bad review to a beer from such a great brewery . this is the least distinguished ( a polite way to say `` worst '' ) dogfish head beer .

a - a big thick three finger head of densely packed tiny bubbles distributes a huge amount of creamy lace on the glass , and shows outstanding retention . the lace on the glass looks like icy frost on a window in the wintertime . this looks outstanding , and gets a rare five for appearance in my book .  mouthfeel is a bit on the thin side .

never thought i 'd get a chance to try this one ... xpimptastikx is a hero amongst men for sharing this bottle with me , himself , and two others at a recent tasting . blauw sports a creamy , light custard head that is superbly retained atop a hazy caramel-colored body . this gueuze embodies the definition of barnyard funk . soily , hippy funk . a bit of funk , but blauw has more of that lactic bite i 've come to expect from a good belgian gueuze .  palate is a little cloying from the fruity sugars , but ends dry . finishes with a parching pinesness and slick fruit punch .
a : hazy orange with a massive , rocky head with everlasting sustain .  the mouthfeel is a little on the thin side , but drinkability is excellent .
a - looks great ! black with ring of tan foam , brew desperately clings to side of glass s - smokey , not my speed .  finishes pretty dry , perhaps a little too carbonated for the style .

appearance - pours very dark with a faint redish brown and a creamy brown head .  medium bodied but a bit thinner than expected with a prominent roasted coffee presence that lingers over the dark malts and subtle barrel character into a dry finish .

this looks beautiful in my tulip glass .  cask at the cricketeers arm . served by a big dude named red . it is indeed chock full of coffee , toffee and roasty notes . very dry finish and as i can readily attest highly drinkable . great stuff .

deep coffee beans , chocolate and licorise on the nose , very pleasant . surprisingly thin up front , coffee flavors subdued , oily , slick charcoal to be noted in the body .  to me smelled like wheat/grain , nuts . t : taste just like you would expect , after smelling . d : pretty good beer , surpassed my expectations . could drink this one all night and be satisfied !
poured a oily and thick blackish brew , with a great topping of tan whipping cream .  mouthfeel is pretty thin , nice a smooth carbonation , but just feels weak .
looks great . moderately clear , dark amber color and reddish hue .  it 's pretty light bodied with a low level of carbonation .

the color is nice , a pretty translucent golden , and the bottle is on the sexier end of the spectrum . pours nicely , smells decent ( very fruity , especially banana ) and has a good sticky head .  the aroma is hoppy and earthy with some fruity notes , reminds me a bit of orval in this sense . the flavor has a nice character of fruity hopes and a mild malt sweetness , but the beer is dominantly dry . there is a very mild tartness here but generally the beer is dominated by a blend between some spicy yeast notes and pleasant hop bitterness .
pours a dark , hazy mahogany with a giant off-white head . lacing is just about perfect .  if only the texture was less paper thin and more like cardboard .

this brew poured a medium head of fine to large brown bubbles and an opaque black body . it has a very mild malt aroma to weak for a good stout and a strong coffee flavor . i did not taste the typical chocolate or roasted notes that are typical of most good stouts , only coffee .  the taste is thick and interesting . its just a tad lacking , leaving this beer to taste like eating hershey 's special dark chocolate powder . this beer coats the tongue well , but the taste is over-powering . i 'm really impressed with the idea here and think this is a good beer .

pours a pale amber color ; hazy with just a hint of bubbles . putting my nose into the glass , i was rewarded with a huge blast of lovely , citrusy hops . the hops carried beautifully to the palate , which was very hoppy , which led nicely to a bracingly bitter finish .  m : a little thinner than i expected but still coats the palate , probably why it 's a porter .
smells pretty good ; slightly sweet , with mild malts and citrussy hops making up the aroma .  mouthfeel is excellent . it 's creamy and almost chewy .

solid , spot on aroma of strong nutmeg , vanilla and clove , lovely fruit scents of deep orange , tangerine and banana . oddly enough , this is slightly sour especially on the mid-palate and in terms of flavor , this reminds of hitachino nest weizen and that is a good thing . an odd beer for sure but quite tasty .  creamy and chewy . pretty yeasty for an apa , although this is leaning towards english ipa i believe .

a- hazy golden color , strong head s- intense pine and citrus . this one wafts up from the pour . t- very much a west coast hop bomb . d- for me , i can only handle one beer a week with this level of hop intensity .  mouthfeel is very rich , smooth carbonation .

aromas of honey and flowers . there 's a bit of a sake-ish sour tinge to the aroma , and you can certainly smell the minerality and fruit of the muscat grapes used to make this . this is an interesting beer , very cool to try , but i do n't find it to be particularly tasty .  mouthfeel 5/5 medium bodied , appropriately crisp , and clean finishing , the mouthfeel of this beer is spot on .

definitely one of the top 5 hop aroma beers i have ever consumed . it is so so so inviting from the aroma . i totally love beers with this full citrus hop aroma . the taste is totally different than the nose . it makes you think initially that it will be bitter and hop centric but then the malt character makes a huge stand and controls the main flavors your tongue perceives . it is quite pale malt dominated and i really appreciate this because overly resiny beers make me gag . i could pound this to no end which is dangerous considering the abv , lucky it is quite high in $ $ $ so this will limit my consumption . this is a very tasty and simple straightforward dipa .  a- very murky , tan head , and faint hints of a red hue on the outer-most parts of the glass s- muted nose , that such of chocolate pop tarts t- marshmellow , chocolate , cocoa , raisen , over ripe cherry and a nice little chunk of bitter bight m- creamy and gorgeous . this beer is awesome .

i would drink this with a spicy sausage covered in peppers and onions at tony 's and it was just about as close to beer pairing heaven as it gets . love this beer 's heavy pine nose and taste along with its more citrusy side .  the mouthfeel on this beer is superb . very creamy with subdued carbonation and a medium body .

the aroma is sweet fruits ( peaches ) and some vanilla / wood with some vinous floral notes . overall , an interesting fruit wheat . the barrel definitely makes it more interesting .  mouthfeel is surprisingly smooth and creamy for such a sweet beverage . very nice .

s- fruity and phenolic , with alcohol aromas complementing the yeast . very fragrant and nice . t- tart fruity and sweet , again very much like a weakened tripel .  the body is medium with one of the finest , creamiest , super fuzzifyingly , silky-slippery-zippery carbonations i have ever encountered .

strong complex aroma that waifs out of the glass that is rich heavy fruits , burnt caramels , and maybe a little oaky , earthiness .  good with food , good standing alone , and a wonderful , creamy mouthfeel when on tap .
the smell was very complex , many different things happening and really reminded me of hoegaarden which i have really taken a liking to lately .  very well rounded .
a very delightful smell . some traces of malt in the background , but this is all about the hops .  awesome mouth feel . thick and creamy with the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

smell : the wood from the cask conditioning is very prominent and melds well with the pronounced coffee and more mild dark chocolate notes . a little molasses and no hop aroma at all . taste : very bitter , burnt coffee ... . i think that without conditioning the beer would have been a little bland , but when cask conditioned it was delicious .  taste is very smooth with a great mouthfeel .

smell : vanilla & oak ; awesome taste : malty , some caramel , some vanilla . excellent `` sipping ' beer , but unless paired with hearty food , 2 pintseasy to drink , but will drink better older ...  the texture was excellent , not too thick or thin .

the smell was very nice , piney spicy hops with a sweet buttery biscuit note .  for a supposed potent*ipa* i expected a huge blast , but it is light refreshing yet surprising t. sweeter ipa , nothing too extreme , dry finish on the tongue with an exceptional mouth feel .
s- this beer smells of tart cherries and a hint of musty basement and a soft oak note .  great mouth feel it 's carbonated perfectly making this a great beer .

the aroma was really nice . dark fruits , brown sugar , tart cherries , red wine , oak , leather , and a little bit of brett . very complex and interesting . the taste was perfectly in line with all the aromas but a little off .  this beer is full bodied and velvety smooth . it is a little high in alcohol , but the smooth mouthfeel and nice flavor would go a long way .

bottled oct 3rd , 2011 - consumed oct 19th , 2011 a : nice clear light golden amber with a thick creamy white head that laces the glass very nicely and stays around throughout the beer s : wonderful citrus and grass hop aroma coming off the top . very clean hop aroma .  very well balanced , nice full mouthfeel seals the deal .

has a nice sweet brown sugar nose that fills the air like the falling leaves before they totally dry up .  mouthfeel is perfect , medium bodied with a champagne silkiness that is delectable when swirled .

it hits you hard with the cinnamon upfront , and some ginger , nutmeg , and malt ... it smells like a gingerbread cookie ... also boozy especially when it warms and then maybe some citrus peel and some brown sugar t- lots of flavor ... cinnamon , pretty boozy , and bready ... again like a cinnamon/gingerbread cookie ... a tiny bit of dark berries on the finish ... the cinnamon sticks with you throughout ( like their pumpkin ale ) m- more carbonated than i anticipated ( a good thing ) ... creamy but also crip enough to keep me sipping d- would n't be able to drink too many of these because of the richness but then again you can never complain about too much flavor right ?  body is rich , creamy , smooth , and damn near perfect . another excellent offering from d'achouffe .

s : the nose is great . it is almost reminiscent of the cantillon funk smell , which is great . smells very tart and sour . overall : it is a solid gueuze , smells better than it tastes , but it is still good .  mouthfeel is creamy and smooth , and the taste is complex with more dark fruit and caramel with almost port-like flavours .
s - amazing aroma of oak , wood and vanilla notes . o - this is a fabulous brew . outstanding aroma and flavor . really great beer .  perfect body with great carbonation .

smell - absolutely wonderful hops smell . its best qualities are appearance and wonderful aroma . taste and drinkability are a little challenging but tolerable .  mouthfeel is nearly perfect , with a refreshingly light and crisp body .
very drinkable , light and flowery . amazingly complex hop smell and flavor without being over-powering or too bitter .  very creamy and full bodied , perfect carbonation to keep it moving .

a beautiful copper colour , with hints of candied pear in the nose and some peach . nice , full mouthfeel but the taste lacked the wholesome maltiness that i expect in a bitter .  nice mouthfeel of solid carbonation .

2010 vintage aroma : a big toffee-like maltiness , some chocolate cake batter , a bit of vanilla , and some floral hops . definitely a brew that kept me smelling for a while before tasting ! very strong , well-carmelized brown sugar supported by an extremely hoppy foundation . i also noted a bit of bubble gum-like phenol , more smokiness , and some alcohol toward the finish . overall : definitely worthy of its reputation . i think i learned with this one , though , that i definitely prefer the fruitiness and complexity of a british barleywine more that the american style .  mouthfeel is perfect for a porter , chewable but not too much , this is a meal in a bottle .
i really enjoy the smell of this one .  there is the perfect amount of carbonation for the style .

the smell of this beer is excellent . nice rich coffee and dark chocolate notes that seriously raised my expectations for the taste of my half-glass . this brew smells much better than it tastes . i tried to like it because it smells so great , but i ended up dumping out my portion and moving on to the next bottle .  fairly soft but noticeable carbonation , thick creamy mouthfeel just like chocolate milk .
the nose is quite excellent . the grapes are quite noticeable with a ripe , fruity , berry-like bouquet .  feels wonderful on the palate . excellent carbonation as well .

aroma is berries , vanilla , and alcohol . taste is really follows the nose , with fruity maltiness upfront , creamy vanilla and barrel notes in the middle , and a warming alcohol close .  mouthfeel is silky and full with a dry finish that reminds me of a light red wine .

this is the best smelling beer i have ever had , ever in my life . it smells like fresh brownies just pulled from the oven , so good ! soon though the carbonation naturally dies down and it 's a very pleasant taste , quite sweet though not too much .  perfect carbonation .

smell is fantastic ... filled w/ piney hops w/ a whiff of cotton candy .  thick and silky with a medium body . velvety smoothness characteristic of only a handful of the best belgians . clean finish keeps me wanting to drink more .

the aroma is awesome . a great mix of spices , mainly cinnamon and nutmeg . the actual scent of pumpkin plays only an ancillary role , but that 's fine given how appealing the overall aroma is . pumpkin comes through in the mid-palate , but it 's quite subtle . pretty remarkable that this is an 8 % abv beer . it 's maybe a touch too thin , but still pretty decadent given the sweetness and minimal carb .  a : jet black , no head s : traditional russian imperial stout , dense , licorice , oxidation , great t : dense , true russian imperial stout , cloying , deep burnt caramel taste , great beer , tastes like it has been aged for several years d : very good m : excellent

a bit too one-sided in my opinion ... hazed golden color with a nice juicy citrus/pine/leafy hop aroma on the nose ... .but the taste is too one-sided for an apa ... .big bitterness on the flavor ... hop tea like ... .needs more malt ( some malt ?  t/m : mouthfeel is perfect to me .

s - the smell is delicious . malt , biscuits , dark fruit like plums and raisins , and alcohol . this is clearly more of a british barley wine than american .  medium body with a wonderful rich texture that is soothing in the mouth . just enough carbonation to keep things lively .

the smell is also quite pleasant . hoppy , but not too hoppy .  love the body on this one . on lighter side of moderate , but the oiliness from the hops makes it somewhat slick and the softest carbonation fills it our gloriously .

lots of yeast character in the aroma . apricots and esters and honey . pale gold , no head , little carbonation bubbles .  mouth is silky smooth with a full body a great carbonation , did n't go flat like alot of darker brews have .

a great smelling ipa . smooth , almost fruity flavor , high hop bitterness in the back , some sweetness up front , nice palate connectivity .  m : completely smooth and wonderful . d : very easy to drink .
the aroma is quite pleasant - fresh citrus and hops are very noticeable .  m - almost syrupy . i love the mouth feel .

nose shows a rich mix of hops and malt . big piney , resinous , earthy and minty notes from the hops , while the malt adds prominent caramel , nutty and toasty characters . very nice !  absolutely wonderful . drinkability : pretty decent for the high alcohol levels .

smells glorious . definately a unique mixture of piney citrus and floral hops . very enjoyable . mouthfeel : a tad tart and carbony with a big soda style bite followed by big hop oilyness .  a great , thick mouthfeel makes this beer very satisfying and drinkable .

earthy oaky aroma with a lot of oaky tannis , vanilla and a huge b ourbon presence . this beer has an amazing nose resulting from the time spent in the barrel . lots of chocolate malt underneath the sweet bourbon character . i took in the aroma of this beer for several minutes before even taking a sip . slightly watered down but still a complex , quaffale blend .  this beer is incredibly silky smooth and boasts a clean , light carbonation . big on the bitters , but great taste and mouthfeel .

the smell is extremely aromatic and floral . a very pleasing taste , you can definitely tast crisp apple as well as the hint of wine . this beer tastes exactly like it smells , crisp and clean . easy to drink .  split this among a few friends last night in celebration of the hockeytown boys winning lord stanley 's cup.poured a jet black with a thinner creamy dark tan colored head , aromas obviously had deep dark roast coffee tones mixed with dark fruit and a hint of bitter chocolate.mas what a silky smooth mouthfeel this is what make a very good beer a great beer no faults to its mouthfeel whatsoever.flavors are rich but not overly so , smooth dark coffee and dark chocolate like a mocha espresso with a hint of spiced rum in the finish.a fantastic brew to end a fantastic night .
s : fresh herbs . amazing . nothing like it .  absolutely fantastic mouthfeel , creamy and oily without being cloying .
aroma is fantastic . best smelling ipa ever ( believe it or not ) !  mouthfeel is wonderful . creamy with smooth carbonation .

hard to beat this aroma : perfect balance of toffee and caramel malts combining with resinous , citrus hops . the body could use a touch more hops , but the greenery soon makes itself known , delivering a sticky , piny finish . overall , a solid ipa that ranks up there with some of the best .  mouthfeel is wonderful . dry as chocolate coyotes thirsty mouth in the chocolate atacama .
