s : huge hoppy smell . really fresh smelling , i thought it was pretty floral , although most other people seem to be picking up on citrusy flavors . m : really lively , although it settles down somewhat quickly .  mouth is silky smooth .

s - wow -- fantastic aroma . a sweet , malty scent with fresh fruit characteristics . a definite oaky scent here . t - when that oaky scent turns into a flavor it makes a beautifully round beer .  has good slight citrus notes with a full hop oil and hoppy feel and body , a good finish mouthfeel- very very smooth , it has an extremely soft and smooth body that really helps it going down , the mouthfeel is a real strong point of this beer drinkability- a very good beer that i would definitely want to try few more times and see how it matches up with some other ipa s certainly worth another look .

although it smells amazing , fresh , and hoppy , there is little to no initial flavor ... wait for the lingering hoppy finish ! appearance : clear , golden , light foamy head smell : incredible . piney , earthy , hops .  the other reviews cover pretty much everything , but i have to add that this is possibly the creamiest beer to ever touch my lips . it was so wonderfully smooth i damn near shat my pants .

the first thing i notice is that this beer reminds me of white wine - the nose is remarkably similar to a chardonnay , with undertones of orange/apricot and other citrus .  before i can say anything about the taste , the mouthfeel is perfect . thick and smooth , with light carbonation that just seems so right .

aroma- incredible tropical scent . pineapple most notable . taste- disappointing considering the aroma . maybe i set my expectations too high.the flavor is as intense as the aroma , and that 's not necessarily a good thing . overall a beer that smells so good that the taste sort of disappoints .  decadent creamy texture , very smooth despite the high carbonation .

the aroma was what i will describe as `` fun '' , candy-like sweetness , fruity yeast , lemon and green apples similar to a jolly rancher candy . tart , tart , tart but refreshing . the acidity was very high which made sense given the flavors but definitely took away from its drinkability . the mouthfeel was ok but slick no doubt due to the varieties of citrus-inducing hops , the body medium and the carbonation the same .  m - this is what really sets this beer apart for me . incredibly creamy and thick mouth feel .
superb .  mouthfeel : chewy , full bodied . low carbonation , which suited the beer nicely .

a - lots of sediment , light gold s - amazing aroma . sweet hops , honey , orange water . for such a delicious bouquet , and great name breweries , i was hoping for something more .  the carbonation is medium and perfect . mouthfeel is great .

head was a finger+ and a yellow/brown color ( grey poupon dijon mustard ? ) . smell- hickory wood smell and a hint of coffee . very good !  mouthfeel - smooth and graceful . this beer has great texture and flow .
a great combination of nutty and bready aromas ; exactly as it should be .  smooth and full mouthfeel .

s - hop aroma is wood , not necessarily pine as some others are . exceptional smell . t - just as it smells the hops and malt blend perfectly .  absolutely perfect . drinkability is very high as well . even , balanced flavors with that great mouthfeel make for a nice combination .

smell is a lovely hoppy bouquet , a lot of candied citrus rind , some florals , a bit of pineapple . good well-rounded hop but too astringent , the body is way too thin .  4.0 m great syrupy sweet bigness , absolutely love the feel .
smell is smokey burnt wood and malt -- exceptional . the taste is a little dry but its quite pleasant .  mouth is very nice , damn perfect .

great belgian smell.. dark fruits , sweet raisin paste and brown sugar delights waft gently into my nostrils . tastes very sweet.. very sweet.. fruit is there , but it 's overripe and accented by a slightly metallic disintegrated hop character .  the mouthfeel is superb : sticky and chewy but also very creamy , with fluffy carbonation .

smell is pine sap , citrus , floral , grassy , and resinous hops , touch of lemon , raspberries , cedar needles , toast , fruity esters , and liquor . taste does not live up to the aroma - i get sweet caramel , orange peel , pine , ethanol , spicy and citric hop bitterness , a bit of alcoholic burn on the tongue with a cloyingly malty aftertaste . way too malt-forward for my liking , seems like the dry-hopping comes through in the nose but does n't add much to the flavour .  very smooth , almost velvety mouthfeel . excellent brew , but the 8.4 oz bottle is entirely too small .
the smell is really interesting . sweet , malty , with a bit of vanilla and maybe some cinnamon . really pleasant , interesting nose .  i love it .

smells amazing ! big on citrus and grapefruit , smells like sugar in your nose.. really great.. taste follows well and tickles the tongue in all the right ways without feeling boozy especially for a 10 % beer .  great smooth mouthfeel..creamy .

the aroma is of roasted malt , graham cracker , cream , hints of blueberry , and only a faint gesture of hops . it reminds me of tres blueberry stout , but a lot lighter on the blueberries .  m : eminently smooth with a light but firm body and some fine , velvety carbonation . perfect for the style .

absolutely beautiful aroma that reminds me of the finer czech pilsners , not that that is surprising . in short , a superb smell . the taste is harshly bitter with almost a hot pepper bite .  the mouthfeel is astounding . with all the charged up carbonation , i was expecting a soda like fizzy mouthfeel , but i am pleased at the silky smooth , well rounded and succulent body of this ale .

no sharpnes of a dryhop but still nice carracter . furter the sweetness of best munich & carramelic malts in litle sournes bathing of the wheat malt .  the body of this beer was exceptional , thick , clean , and enjoyable .

smell : an intoxicating citrusy sweetness bursts forth when i open the bottle . floral notes abound , west coast hoppiness all the way here . i could smell this all day long . taste : pronounced hop bitterness , pretty damn close to pure hop nectar .  an exquisite mouthfeel for a baltic porter .

taste isnt as good as the aroma but still nice . more roastiness but not overly roasty , figs , chocolate , caramel , some weak hops ... tad thin .  nice , full , creamy mouthfeel , as good as it gets .

smell : sweet and chocolately with a hint of roasted malts . taste : like it smells , sweet and chocolately , with a bit more roasted malt in the flavor than smell , some coffee undertones .  mouthfeel : super thick , creamy , sticky with medium-low carbonation overall : great smell , but the pure , burning ethanol is too much present for me in the taste .

a very nice aroma . low carbonation , slick and buttery in the mouth .  this is definitely the best oatmeal i 've had . the mouthfeel is so luscious it 's insane . sweet and slighty bitter roasted malts mix with coffee , chocoloate , oats , smoke ; all in a sublime smoothness . you have to try to find the alcohol , but it 's there , warming the palate ever so slightly . on tap this was the smoothest beer i think i 've ever had .
smell is citrus and piney hops .  mouthfeel : extremely smooth and crisp .

maybe the best beer smell ever to wander up my nostrils . this stout sit below a thick vapor that is sweet and boozy with anise , chocolate and coconut . smells a little grapey , like a heavy red wine . goodbye , beer , down the drain .  mouthfeel is just superb . satisfying .

the nose is beyond sweet , smelling of candied raspberries , followed by light roast , then a vinous smell . spicy alcohol joins the olfactory chorus as it warms .  m = heavy , heavy body , luscious creamy feel , great mouthcoating . one of the best mouthfeels i 've ever experienced in a beer .

the aroma is musty and lemony with a distinct dry oaky backbone . some nutty earthiness as well . the flavor is muddled and oaky ... very unique . as a huge fan of gueuze and all things lambic , i really love to get a chance to sample the building blocks . i probably would n't buy it again other than as an experiment in long term aging , but nonetheless i highly recommend this to anyone even if it is merely a way to learn to appreciate the sheer beauty and art of gueuze blending .  coats the tongue just right , insulating it from the alcohol .

smells good ... real good . sweet chocolate , touch of roast , lactose and some definite oatmeal . one of the best smelling oatmeal stouts i have smelled , hits all the right notes . taste does not quite live up to the nose , but still a decent offering .  wonderful mouthfeel .

great aroma . lots of whisky character when the bottle was opened , more of a refined alcohol that you get from a good scotch rather than a boozy nose . nice texture .  medium bodied and oily . simply exceptional .

pours reddish light brown , appearance is closest to a belgian dubbel in my opinion , which may be a consistent characteristic . nose is strong on the bourbon which is a definite plus in my book - so often these bourbon aged beers dont carry as much of the characteristic .  mouthfeel is great with a very filling quality about it .

minimal head retention 7 lacing s : apple & pear blossoms , plus bubble gum t : green bananas , bready notes yeast bite & peppery spiceyness up front . green apple peels , dryness , a bit of pear , faint lemon , cloves & juicy fruit once warm . finishes a touch dry with more juicy-fruit & a bit of lemony hops mf : medium bodied , low carbonation & nicely balanced drinks really easy , a nice hefe that quenches the thirst  incredibly smooth and goes down easy .

s - good lord , this reminds me of my grand 's lemon tree in florida . the citrus characteristics are colossal , this smells freakin great . smells of fresh squeezed lemon , a bit of lime , orange , mango and tangerine with a bit of fresh cut grass . to reiterate , this is an amazing bouquet of citrus with a hint of sweetness and biscuit/caramel in the background . the malt profile is really subdued , i 'm wishing there was a little more to it . this finishes very light and clean , with hardly any bittering at all , some of that juicy lemon and grass lingers into the finish , super refreshing . m - body is medium and spot on , the carbonation is on the high side , but i 'm enjoying it the carbonation feels like it 's scrubbing my taste buds . d - so drinkable , so clean , so light .  outstanding mouthfeel ! d - drinks like a champ for a ris at almost 10 % abv !

the aroma is wonderful , truly like strawberries . ( sometimes the beer looks a bit murky , like a weizenbock .  m : the feel is super creamy which makes it near full bodied . this is the biggest difference between this bottled version and the on-tap version i had last year . the mouthfeel was a huge step up .
smell : this is one of the best smelling beers i have had .  mouthfeel was very thick and rich . i almost wanted to chew it .

that 's not a problem though , because the nose is great . it 's a lovely mix of lemon , coriandor , and orange .  m - very rich and full , reminds me of double bastard . dry with a nice low carbonation d - very well rounded , a little dry but bery easy to drink overall a great beer .

lots of molasses , cherry and plum as it warms , making me think it might be english first sip is very sweet caramel and toffee , with a nice balanced bitter finish . overall , this is a fantastic beer and quite complex . definitely goes down easier than what i think the abv is .  the mouthfeel on this is quite decadent and smooth with a wonderful lingering finish .

s : this is one of the best smelling brews i 've come across in the summer ale category . i 'm not sure what kind of hops they added in the aroma portion of the brew , but it 's outstanding . unfortunately , it 's the best thing about this brew . t : really good . for a summer ale , it 's great .  velvety and soft-spoken , yet deeply sexy . more to the traditional side .

hints of earthiness , brown pear , lemon peel , dark wine , wood , green apple peel , some sweet and sourness , with that wildness of the yeast , an amazing array , quite a scent . it is like a saison on steroids without the barnyard scent , more refined instead . this is unlike any sour i have had , it is pretty sour put it does n't make you cringe , it makes you pucker the mouthfeel and flavor delivery is incredibly smooth . overall an incredibly unique beer that i could only imagine coming out of belgium , it has characteristics of a wheat beer and a sour but takes the fruit level to new heights and is n't too sour .  very smooth . mouthfeel is full and round .

a- orange light amber with a huge offwhite head that fades fairly quickly and good overall clarity s- malt ! and lots of it . a sweet fruitiness with mild spice that bowls you over and makes you want to grab some wurst . i kid you not ... this one made me salivate .  m. perfect for style in all aspects .

i do not find the beer to be as tasty as the nose indicates , but it is still a damn fine pumpkin ale .  super smooth and creamy body that glides down your throat like butter . so smooth and delicious that i had finished 3 pints in less than a half hour .
s- reminded of a floral bouquet mixed with piney aromas .  the mouthfeel was awesome . very heavy and smooth feel .

s - unbelievably good . sat there and just savored the aroma for a while . it steps in and distracts and overwhelms the wonderful aromas . m - medium bodied , flat .  the beer looks thick and chewy , but the texture is perfect for a brown ale .
smell - delicious citrus high notes with an almost overpowering burst of hops .  body is perfect for the style , rich and semi-thick with restrained carbonation .

aroma is like a beer desert , sweet with candy like aroma , some mild cotton candy , caramel , plenty of malt kick , a touch of fermented dark cherries and a touch of alcohol .  carbonation is perfect , mouthfeel is perfect .

amazing if i could turn this into a scented candle i would burn it all the time , pumpkin nutmeg cinnamon and allspice flood the nostrils reminds me of new england in the autumn medium bodied malts and allspice are strong throughout well balanced with hoppes to finish pumpkin rind also has a strong presence nice effervescent carbonation which keeps keeps the brew extremely interesting however , overall i would say the beer lacks body i really liked this beer i will surely enjoy it for the rest of the fall the light body and delicious flavor makes this beer easy going down  wonderful body .
wow this is a wonderfully floral blend of citrus hops that warns of hop balanced sweetness and really gets the mouth watering .  palate is sticky and smooth . wondrous ...

aroma is amazing ( it was perfect when it started but as the beer warmed it fell off , still giving it a 5 ) . it is so hoppy , piny and wonderful overall . no harshness , the level is strong but not overpowering . its great . beer is medium to light in a body with a creamy mouthfeel .  chewy , and creamy , a perfect mild carbonation level for this style.. a lil warmth on the finish just to let you know , as chris rock would say `` slow down !

quite a unique and pleasing odor . tastes very hoppy , with strong floral hops that give off a spicy taste , piney hops , sweet malt , caramel , grass , flowers , orange peel , grapefruit , apple , brown sugar , pepper and spices .  excellent mouthfeel .

definitely some nice , big bourbon on the nose , with rich dark chocolate , tobacco , plums , and figs . good nose . flavor is big , rich , and decadent .  m - carbonation cleans the palate nicely , the tartness and funk does n't linger long . the carbonation is just spot on , love it .
thought it would be too sweet from the smell , but the malt and hops definetly bittered the vanilla bean aroma .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel .

this beer is one of the more complex beers i have ever smelled ! it takes awhile to discern specific aromas . mildly tart and funky . nice . o - very enjoyable beer . i had had this beer many years ago and did n't remember it being so amazing .  although it has a coating , luscious feel , it is not thick or syrupy .

s : very fruity nose . some dark fruits mixed with candi sugar and sugared candy fruits . strawberries , raspberries , pineapple , tart white mango . grape juice .  truly velvety on the tongue . the mouthfeel is second to none , it 's that good . this is a very good stout .
strong tropical fruit scent even from a great distance . pine pineapple and spice are the first things i notice .  very smooth and full mouthfeel .
strong roasted pecan smell with coffee tones . overall malty and enjoyable . mouthfeel : pretty heavy for a porter but very drinkable even in the heat .  the richness and weight is perfect for me .

absolutely excellent scent . t : dry cocoa powder , dark chocolate , and some fresh oak . o : one of the best smelling imperial stouts i 've ever had , and the taste was good too , but just not quite as good as it smelled .  massive body , and silky smooth . fruity , creamy , wine-y , and then comes a stiff roast/coffee crack of the whip .

smells like a beautiful bouquet of chinook and cenntenial hops . i love the taste of this brew as much as the smell . it is the perfect example of a west coast ipa with the nose and bittering hops ringing through . it quickly turns to bitterness form the columbus and chinook hops that is extremely potent but yet still tolerable .  coffee laden roastiness fights off beany vanilla sweetness and those accurate flavors remain held tightly together thanks to a round , well carbonated , cleansing malty full body .
smells great but fake .  mouthfeel is exceptional and there is nothing objectionable here .

smell- clean buttery and citrusy hop aroma . the finishing hops are delightful . taste-this beer comes off with a clean , crisp taste that exudes a slight hint of diacetyl .  '' the mouthfeel was silky , the body full and the carbonation perfectly soft . enjoyable , but it 's really an american stout contrary to the label at the bar .

smell was exceptional - vanilla , wood , almonds , caramel ... very , very nice and remniscent of a cognac or similar nice sipping liquor ( w/o any strong alcohol smell ) .  it was medium bodied and the carbonation was perfect . it was very enjoyable to just hold it in the mouth .

n- massive fruity hops , big fresh centennial and cascade pellets , fresh grapefruit , pineapple , fresh pine , caramel . really just a super dank hop nose . t- astringent , dry , resinous , loads of nutty bitterness piling on . sort of one dimensional .  carbonation is spot on and really helps lighten the mouthfeel .

what a nose ... huge espresso , black currant , dark chocolate ... and that special , unique character that brings to mind the dark lord itself . a beast of an aroma . taste- bittersweet chocolate and the roastiest of malts , with a robust backbone that carries all the flavor throughout the mouth ... the finishing hop blast lingers on for days . mouthfeel/drinkability- thin and easy like a true ids , but not nearly as impressive as compared with the massive head , nose , and taste . it would be easier drinkin ' if the ingredients were downplayed , but then where 's the fun ? this was a real treat to sample , and at 5.25 % i ca n't believe this lasted for 2 years in the cellar . another sheer pleasure from three floyds that deserves praise for its incredible character .  simpler flavor and wonderful mouthfeel enhance the drinkability ; but it is slightly boring .

lovely . a bit of grassiness as well . it 's like they have left a shadow but the hops totally overwhelm everything .  mouthfeel was outstanding . the lush , creamy and full body was absolutely amazing .

the aroma is a stand-out , a very complex mixture of ripe fruit , tobacco with a hint of smoke , chocolate , molasses , vanilla , brown sugar and various spices . a very nice scottish strong ale and another bottle may give it a better score .  just phenomenally satiny . in the mouth : satin , silk , creamy , smoothness embodied in liquid .
smell is excellent on this imperial ipa .  body and carbonation are perfect for the style .

orange and grapefruit burst through immediately ... sniff more and get the graham cracker of the malts , trying desperately yo catch up . i was hoping the taste would copy the smell , but it does n't ... still nice . excellent hop combination going on here and a great example of an american dipa .  m : quite thick and mouth-filling for an ipa , with enough smooth carbonation to keep things fairly clean . just lovely .

smell : the aromas are sweet caramel and hint of toffee malts with a surprisingly light hop character . very alcoholic throughout and leaves a dry hop and floral film inside my mouth .  the mouthfeel is full , warming and fabulous . flavor is full with lots of yummy esters holding hands with the sweetness and the fininsh is where i get the coriander .

nice reddish amber color that had huge aroma of berries . awesome tart raspberry flavor accompanied with the burn from the alcohol .  its thick and syrupy and full of body and character . the alcohol warmth is soothing as it makes its way to the back of the tongue , leaving a sweet resin .

the citrusy hops smell delicious , however , and for me the nose is the real strength of this beer . taste starts off very citrusy , orange and grapefruit but mostly orange , but bittering hops soon take over and overpower everything else .  the body is perfect . honestly .

wonderful menagerie of hops . citrus fruits with pineapple being the one i notice most . pine and earthy . while the taste does n't match the strength of complexity of the aroma it 's still a very good beer . imo it 's too hoppy to be a eipa but too balanced to be a aipa . regardless of style it 's a good beer .  m : lovely viscous feel . perfect .

t : the taste is n't as amazing as the smell , but it 's still very good . the citrus , floral flavor carry over from the smell , and there 's also a slightly caramel , but more biscuit-like flavor in the malt . o : this is a very solid standard ipa .  medium/full body with an extremely creamy texture , assisted by the fine carbonation from the bottle conditioning .

aroma was a beautiful array of fruits , just the right amount of sweet caramel , and floral hints for good measure .  m : the carbonation is so perfectly tied to the spicyness making the mouthfeel very special . amazing mouthfeel .

mahogany red , crystal clear , big foamy thick head . smell is heavy hops wafting out as soon as the cap is cracked .  the mouthfeel is incredibly smooth and coating , leading to an extended finish that eventually coaxes out some espresso and a final touch of nuttiness .

s : very interesting caramelized scents , strong roast smell is very appealing . t : taste does n't quite deliver what the scent promises , but it 's still a strong porter .  mouthfeel is oh-so smooth , and drinkability is superb .

smell - i really enjoyed the smell of this beer .  thick and chewy in the mouth - one can definitely understand the allusions to barley wines in previous reviews . hops tingle as you swallow . is it an old ale ? compared to other old ales that i have seen reviewed , i 'm tempted to say old ale ... but a marvelous cold weather beer in any event .
it also smells fantastic . tons of chocolate and sweet , roasted malts .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer , very creamy .

smells like a lemonade/orangeade mixture but in a really inviting way . not sweet or sugary like the aroma would suggest but that just must be from extreme dry-hopping and the oak somehow . bitterness is perfect , no traditional hop aromas , no earthiness , pine , woody , flowers , just fruitiness . crazy .  mouthfeel - this beer i have to say is one of the most pleasant on the mouth , perfect carbonation , little foam action , and little breakthrough of warmth from the alcohol .
different , but good . ( t ) - heavy on the spices up front .  the feel is smooth , full , creamy and rich ( without being overly thick ) . nice texture , coating .

s : nice hop aroma . very pleasant . much hoppier than i had anticipated .  mouthfeel - smooth , silky , lower carbonation ... in a word ... perfect . drinkability - so smooth and tasty , they would go down easy .

granted , i was stoned at the time ... smell ? pumpkin pie . cinnamon , nutmeg , pumpkins , awesome . taste ? damn this was a good beer .  m- super creamy and smooth . the carbonation level is perfect . a nice clean and crisp aftertaste .

( s ) - a good blend of spice ( nutmeg & cinnamon ) with some creamy pumpkin . simple , but great for the style ; not overpowering with spice .  mouthfeel is fantastic , super thick and syrupy , perfect for the style .

the smell abounds with fresh cherries . something medicinal in the taste has the unfortunate effect of drawing comparisons to children 's cherry flavored cough syrup .  thick smooth mouthfeel , very silky .

this is what you would expect of a drink based on cherries . it is a good session drink . however , as it warms up , the aftertaste and mouth feel is degraded by the sourness of the brew . but , i would recommend this beer .  stellar mouthfeel .

aromas of sour fruity esters and spicy yeast , and a light caramel malty , actually quite tasty smelling . good carbonation and a crisp , dry and smooth lightish bodied mouthfeel .  m - great mouthfeel on this one , very light and easy drinking , alcohol is well hidden .

aroma : massive floral , pine and spruce aromas . taste : this beer is so incredibly resiny it is impossible to tell what else is going on .  very soft carbonation that makes it feel creamy and silky smooth one of , if not , the thickest beers i 've had . love it .

s : loads of hops . piney , somewhat resinous , lots of pungent lemon . very spicy as well , helped along by the yeast . funky but hard to describe .  thanks to ba greggy for this one . the beer is very thick and smooth . not overpowering but just the right feel . the only thing that i have a problem with is the fact that this beer is so thick and rich , there is no way i would be able to drink more than 2 of these in one sitting .

weihenstephaner vitus | 500 ml . appearance : hazed , glowing , straw-colored concoction . the massive , wintery head and abundance of fine lace warms the cockles of my heart . aroma : big banana/plantain aroma , peppered with clove , on bready background . taste : nutty , lightly toasted bread , spicy alcohol , fruity banana and asian pear . mouthfeel : sticky , chewy , slick , prickly , sharp . good carbonation . harmony : you 're doused in flavor towards the end of the sip , though the beginning is a bit lackluster . i actually found the taste to be the least endearing aspect . i was blown away by the nose . it works cohesively , though i sense a strong and unfavorable imbalance of flavor towards the end of the sip . the bros. are absolutely right : this is fine on its own but would go oh so well with some fine bread and cheese ( i 'd call for some aged gouda or edam ) .  thick and chewy with all the perfect elements . the real stand out for me was the mouthfeel .

very rich aroma . quite sweet - lots of dextrins in the finished beer . still , interesting and somewhat complex flavor and aroma .  supremely smooth . it 's just silky smooth across the tongue , the carbonation working to prevent it from becoming syrupy .
looks great , smells even better , but tastes just about as fake as a spontaneously fermented beer can get .  insanely smooth , creamy , and slick body with light-medium carbonation .

wonderful aroma ! reminds me of moosehead . this has a pretty good flavor , but not as good as the smell , at least not in my opinion .  amazing balance in this beer . mouthfeel is full , and this is very drinkable .

s- smells of natural raspberry over a tart wheat base . i 'd say they did a really good job here by keeping that `` artificial '' raspberry and cloying sweetness out of the nose . for what it is ( a raspberry wheat ale ) , this is a technically good nose . t- underwhelming flavor ; surprisingly mild .  mouthfeel is awesome . full , luscious , and smooth .

nose is fantastic : huge and sweet , dried fruit , cotton candy , maybe some aprioct and kiwi in there too . surprisngly light alcohol , given the abv . overall , a delicious and really unique saison . maybe not one i 'd go for every day , but an excellent beer nonetheless .  m - refreshingly tingly , with a slow and steady rise in volume , ultimately becoming quite creamy and dense . very appealing .
i 'm most impressed by the incredible aroma but i 'd buy this regularly if it was available in my market .  m. thick and heavy , strong and chewy , with plenty of carbonation .

the aroma is a surprisingly accurate facsimile of creme brulee with caramel and vanilla and creme and a mild coco and roastiness underneath . most of the aromas are replicated on the palate with caramel vanilla cream with more roast and less sweet than the aroma . the mouthfeel , while pretty heavy , might have been a little bit better if it were more so .  light-medium in body .

s- smell is very hoppy , deep piney notes , resiny , sweet light fruit notes . t- resiny hops all the way through , an unbalanced grainy maltiness followed by a raw alcohol character .  m- full bodied with medium carbonation . thick and almost chewy in the mouth .
s : has an interesting smoked aroma with some roasted nut in the back .  mouthfeel is great .

the smell of this beer is excelent , smells like coffe flavored chocolate and caramel , but the taste is quite dissapointing , the carbonation hides most of it , i only got a little bit of caramel there .  m - perfection , i love the way this feels .

i was blown away by the nose of this beer . it took over the room with perfumes of chocolate , vanilla and other holiday spices . it had a nice head and offered a pretty good mouth feel that lasted for well over 10 seconds .  nice , thick and just the right level of carbonation in my book .

smell : the nose is juicy and firm with a very hoppy smell . strong and potent , but a balanced smell . taste and mouthfeel : for a beer that is `` blessed with hops '' - it almost too balanced .  feel is thick and creamy , with a light carbonation of fine bubbles that help give it a velvety character to it . this is a damn fine beer .

s : huge hop aroma . big citrus hops and inviting sweetness . smells as good as any dipa i 've had yet .  tight but low carbonation with a light to medium body . the mouthfeel is perfect ! very elegant flavors and seems to have great balance with the flavors .

what a complex smell ! t - lots of lemon/lime citrus flavors with a light malty sweetness that finishes very light and refreshing ! d - due to its incredibly strange flavor profile , for me , this beer 's drinkability is not as high as it could be .  mf : silky and smooth but without compromising its thickness , which is needed as a foundation for the abundance of flavour . not too wet or dry , but the perfect balance between . not a unique mouthfeel , but an expressive suitable one .
smells like a fireplace w/ hints of roasted chocolate .  mouthfeel - full-bodied , velvety smooth , and creamy with a semi-dry finish and moderate carbonation .
the smell is fantastic . super complex with vanilla , bourbon , toffee , caramel , brown sugar , and sweet dark fruit .  very creamy , highly carbonated mouthfeel .

smells like bacon ! only one things smells like bacon and that 's bacon ! many smoked beers smell like liquid smoke or a burnt-down house or a campfire , but this one smells like ... say it with me ... bacon ! yeah i overdid that a bit . the smell is also sweet , not as `` sweeeet , it smells like bacon '' or `` well , is n't she sweet '' but in the `` sugar is sweet '' usage of that word . all those smells and yet it works . awesome ! if you do n't like rauschbiers than you wo n't like this one .  m - perfect mouthfeel .

smell was intense and amazing . woody with dried fruits and burnt caramel . the taste unfortunately was not nearly as complex . somewhat sweet and malty rich up front with some noticeable hops on the back of the palate .  huge taste and mouthfeel . lots of bitter hot chocolate taste and viscous almost chewy feel to it .

the malt is there at the first sip , but then the hops take over from there . smooth and just the right amount of bitterness to go along with the hoppy character of the beer .  mouthfeel is exceptional . big , small foam mouth , which smooths down , edgy all the way -- but never sharp .
s : lovely perfume-like odor .  ( m ) - really smooth and creamy . the carbonation has subdued to a really nice level that balances it out to a totally silky beverage .

the smell is deeply fruity and reminds me of a fruity burgundy wine . fairly sweet smelling this has a little bubblegum scent to it .  it is the mouthfeel ! nice and viscous without being too soupy . this enhances the creamy taste and makes it really feel like a true winter ale .
earthy rustic notes thick cut wheat bread and big dirty hop compounds .  carbonation is comfortable and helps the round mouthfeel to build an authentically belgian mouthfeel .
looks good , smells good , no taste !  mouthfeel is perfect , goose island is the best of the best in this regard .

smells very inviting ; i could smell this one while the glass was sitting on the table . a pleasantly sweet , hop aroma ... herbal , almost like honey or clover . very fragrant and very appealing to the nose . sierra nevada fans will dig this one but i do not like the kind of hop bitterness found in here ... that sharp citrus rind bitterness that takes too much attention to itself and shouts down other flavors that might speak up .  first sip reveals light carbonation that rolls across my tongue and a creamy , silky textured brew .

a bit of lacing & minimal head retention s : bubblegum , cloves & white pepper t : cloves , grainyness , juicyfruit & grassy up front . crackery notes along with lemony hops as this warms .  mouthfeel is the star of this show -- thick , rich , round , full , all very slurpalicious .

huge hop aroma . smells like an ipa . tastes of hop bitterness and malty crystal sweetness . in general i really like over hopped red ales , they 're much more interesting than the usual malty , sweet and boring brewpub reds . i had low expectations for this beer and was pleasantly surprised .  m - thick , heavy , sticky ... in short , decadent . as a straight up style exemplar , its feel is darn near perfect .

smell is of hoppy juice , orange , grapefruit , and pine . taste is of the aromas with an over-abundance of hoppiness outweighing the malt .  rich , creamy , and smooth mouthfeel . a bit of alcohol bite , and an excellent overall russian imperial stout .

the aroma is robust and full . leather and rich dark chocolate come to mind . everything i would expect from the aroma is here ; rich dark chocolate with a little bit of dark fruits in the background but this one is hot .  mouthfeel is really silky , solid , and smooth in the carbonation .

the aroma was delicious , orange and grapefruit , apricots and floral hops , amazingly inviting . the flavors were also spot-on for the style , huge hoppy kick heavy on the oil and pine , followed by the solid malt backbone and a bitter finish .  m - perfect carbonation in a perfect medium body , godly smooth .

heavy pour and still poor head retention atop this golden wheat colored brew , though the nose is potent and pretty nice - heapings of wheat malt , bubblegum and clove , all of which follow suit in the flavor , though not nearly with the same complexity , possibly because of the oxidation .  mouthfeel is soft and creamy smooth . just a hint of carbonation to cut through the abv .
s : clover , orange , balsamic vinegar , raisins , molasses . lots going on here , and pretty much all of it is good . overall smells sweet w/ a hint of tangy / acidic .  just about perfect for me .

nose of ginger and honey , with hints of sweet apple .  with thick molasses and velvety feel to balance a bold and alcoholic content , this one hits me with a lingering hoppy bitterness on the finish of strong malt presence . seriously strong , often incapacitating ... but ever deliciously so !

s - smells a lot like a winter warmer should ! the finish is a bit confusing , a wheat-oat malt flavor comes in that is would be a perfect finish to it if it were not for the strong alcohol and cherry flavor in there again .  also was surprised by how creamy this went down . this is a pleasure on the tongue .

aroma is great and not your typical apa/ipa . elegant . very balanced , ending just a tad bitter .  nice creamy mouthfeel , thick and pleasant and well balanced flavors of sherry , burnt carmel , toffee , roasted bananas and ripe stone fruit with hints of walnuts .
quite impressive . t : starts tart and fruity , but instantly dies into a nothing sweetness .  the mouthfeel i think is perfect for the style .

s : belgian yeast , touch of brett , pears and apples . a little spicy floral hops on the back but funk dominates .  the brew is incredibly creamy , and really coats your entire mouth . it 's fluffy to the point that it feels exotic .

smell is really nice . toasty nutty malts and a blast of cascadey hops .  i do n't find much to be said really , excellent balance , medium body shows a perfect carbonation to my liking , quite creamy lager , pretty crisp dry herbal hops finish .
nice complexity . i know this is a tripel , but the alcohol is the primary piece present , and it almost gets in the way .  mouthfeel is very soft and smooth on this medium-heavy brew .

getting the rich toasty and sweet malt with the huge bourbon and vanilla scents as well . rich and delicious . all of the richness that is described above . with some age , this one would be perfection . full bodied , hot and dry finish with soft and smooth carbonation . this stuff is so deliciously tasty and flavorful that i have to keep drinking it .  touches of carbonation throughout , the mild breakups of tingling yield a remarkably smooth bevvy .

smell : wow , this one is extra funky ! it 's like he shook the cobwebs a little more , kicked up the dust from the attic and pressed the juice out of the wet blanket a little harder !  the mouthfeel is medium-full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture .
a wonderful hop aroma greets the nose . a decent double ipa .  the texture is creamy and silky .

nose is incredibly sweet , with a thick chocolatey aroma , but also a sour edge , with a big smokey and meaty hit , a large bacon aroma with tart hints of fig , chlorine ( ? ultimately , very chocolatey , and slightly disconcerting from that meatiness , but an interesting and very pleasant nose . taste is ultimately dark , with a great burnt , ashy bitterness underlying it .  this is crazy , super tart and sour with a crisp carbonation bite .

very nicely hoppy aroma . piney and bright with a background of grapefruit rinds and peaches .  it 's smooth in the mouth , but still lets up the high abv that 's lurking in the depths of this monster . it 's damn good . so smooth and creamy .

by far one of the most unique and sweetest smelling beers i 've had the pleasure to whiff . very little floral aroma for this style it seems , but i love that . glug glug glug taste contains a sticky sweetness that first reminds me of a kind of tart grapefruit juice with notes of floral hops that did n't come through in the smell as much .  mouthfeel is the highlight of this ipa ; it 's velvety smooth and saves a bite for the back and sides of the palate . quite the juicy beer , very refreshing .
s : like orange tang . really nice natural orange flavor .  very velvety , creamy lactic mouthfeel . the aftertaste lingers big time w/ yeasty stickiness .

the lagavulin ( scotch ) aroma is very good . the aroma is only of scotch and slight malt .  appearance clear , dark orange ; off-white head that is about 1/4 '' tall - 4 smell banana , sweetish malts ; not overly complex , but pronounced and invivting taste & mouthfeel the mouthfeel on this beer is outstanding , further convincing me north coast knows how to give a beer a good feel ; full flavor from front to back , but with hard to describe flavors ( due to my limited experience with belgian style beers ) ... banana , malt , a little sour , slightly medicinal , caramel overall pretty darn good .

nice bready and hoppy aroma . the nose is very balanced . on the palate this beer screams american ipa .  '' m : really very exceptional . it has a nicely balanced carbonation and bitterness which make this one deceptively smooth for all its alcohol content . d : the mouthfeel is essential to me here since the taste is good but this one otherwise is below average .

had this beer tasted like its aroma , it would have really knocked my socks off . the aroma profile was fantastic ! i just wish it had the body/texture of an oatmeal stout ...  m : thick , syrupy viscosity with light carbonation -- exactly as a beer of this style should be .
wow this is the best smelling beer i think i 've had to date . it took me several minutes before i tasted this beer , because it smelled so good . very clean .  perfect carbonation for the style .
pretty good .  mouthfeel - velvety smooth . ca n't think of better adjectives to describe the mouthfeel . wonderful . soft .

this smells delicious . t-sweet bananas followed some mild cloves .  body is refreshing yet almost full in its thickness and rich , creamy carbonation . overall it 's damn delicious and a great collaboration ; no surprise that there 's yet another beer with the dogfish head logo on it that i love .
smell : a tropical sweet fruitiness . a mix of flowers and grapefruit .  full bodied and lightly carbonated .

the smell is fresh and inviting as well - orange peel , pine , hints of honey and bitter hops . this is a good beer , but the hops are a little over the top for my tastes .  mouthfeel is on the dry side with effervescent carbonation that contributes to the crisp clean finish . its a fascinating brew that manages to be both crisp and refreshing yet still rich and satisfying .

minimal head retention & lacing , some oily sheen to this s : apple skins & white grapes & pears once warm t : follows the nose , also getting candi sugar & chipotle pepper spicyness ( ? this one is a bit different , nice change of pace , not really a `` go to '' saison imo .  first sip reveals a big creamy brew ... darkly sweet hoppiness upfront with fruity alcohol and rye in the second half . rich , creamy smooth body - big and coating . plenty satisfying overall .

a- beautiful crystal clear honey color with mild white lace . s- honey , raisins , toast , biscuits , almonds , barley , alcohol , cane sugar , vanilla , fruit . very spicy , very alcoholic .  very nice mouthfeel .
the spelt brings a bit more musty earthiness than the average wheat .  smooth , medium body and carbonation , slightly chewy , with an astringent finish .

the nose was heavily laden with cherries , like opening a jar of cherry preserves . the finish was very tart , extremely dry , and entirely refreshing . this would be a great beer on a hot summer 's day .  mouthfeel is chewy and creamy .

nothing too unique in the aroma , but it was fantastic . smelled like it was fresh out of the conditioning tanks flavor was sublime . overall an incredibly impressive ipa and glad i landed this .  creamy and luscious body and wonderful layered complex flavors . pale malts , lead into corainder and tropical fruits with a yeasty belgian spice induced finish that lasts into a tingly carbonation with some hop bitterness . very nice .

smell - holy shit , honestly probably the best smelling ipa 's / dipa 's i 've ever smelled . as soon as the bottle was opened it came screaming at me , i was amazed . big orange peel , lemon peel , touches of mango and pineapple in this . very sweet rather than tropical , bitter and bready . oh i love it . please make this all year round . overall - really was impressed by this , at 11 bucks a 6 pack here in ma you ca n't go wrong , it smells and tastes absolutely amazing which i value more than appearance and mouthfeel .  mouthfeel is exceptional , is medium to heavy in body .

this beer looks really good and smells really good , but it is a tad disappointing in the taste department . its a very enticing nose on the beer .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really , really shines .

the beer is quite fruity and complex . this is one that must be served in the right glass at the right temperature .  m : very well balanced and sophisticated lambic , feels great in mouth , mouth puckers an enjoyable pucker d : it 's a sipper , but each sip invites another that 's for sure .

unbelieveable aroma . straight hops ! nice aroma ! seems to be lacking flavor up front but finishes great . grapefruit , pine and some unusual flavors that i enjoyed but simply could not identify .  m - dry and quite bitter . perfect carbonation .

s : primarily malt notes , with a good deal of chocolate as well . smells delicious ... t : i wish i could say it tastes like it smells , but that 's where this beer falls short for me .  spices are well balanced by the soft sweetness , mouthfeel is outstanding .
smells really nice and inviting .  very creamy mouthfeel . again , marvelous mouthfeel , probably one of the best i 've ever enjoyed in that regard .

bottle says brewed both with vanilla beans and flavoring , which is disappointing but economical . aroma is a great mix of almost smokey brown malt , pure vanilla , and coffee . i think the coffee does it for me in terms of appeal and adds a great amount of complexity to the aroma . like smelling a cappucino . taste is just a bit watery at first and too dextrinous .  it almost tastes like an ipa , but with a darker malts and a more complex sweetness . the citrusy hops balance it out nicely . the beer is quite heavy , i guess it is following its `` scottish ale '' description here . it is so creamy and goes down nicely . almost perfect drinker .

pours a crystal clear light orange with a thin white head . the nose is an all out assault of juicy tangerine and bubble gum . the flavor does n't live up to the expectations set my the aroma , but still its very good with some piny and citrus hops .  m- i do love the creamy soft mouthfeel of the brew . carb is soft , but the beer is full . d- this beer perplexes me ... i would never had guessed this was a wit ... .more like a dubbel ... i guess that 's the pinot/oak flavors .

the smell is wonderful . coffee and chocolate with a grainy almost nutty flavor . i like my imp stouts to have more of a hop backbone which this one seems to lack .  this did not effect the mouthfeel at all it was perfect as is .

the aroma is rife with vanilla bean and a fresh , sharp rye spiciness . caramel sugar daddies and liquefied raisinettes make for a sweet touch that plays well off the rye bill . overall , this is delicious stuff .  m - the mouthfeel is amazing . really smooth and creamy .

no hop aroma . very nice taste : alcohol dominates what otherwise would be a nice beer .  its mouthfeel is incredible ; obviously this is enhanced by the nirto-tap . the positive was creating an amazing mouthfeel that fits perfectly with the style .

nose is a conglomeration of aromas , sweet malt , bread dough , port wine , cotton candy , caramel , and spices , clove i think . start has a deep malt sweetness , some alcohol bitterness at the back with the top moderate in feel . magnificent beer , as belgian strong ( s ) are my favorite style , this was a most enjoyable beer .  m - very luxurious mouthfeel to it .

s : piney with hints of citrus and some herbal notes with just a hint of sweetness . this smells like an ipa should t : flavors kick off with some nice herbal notes and a dash of caramel sweetness from the malt .  the beer didnt quite taste as good as it looked , but it was still quite pleasently sweet and i highly enjoyed the creamy mouthfeel it had .

predominant smells are cocoa and vanilla . starts out with a nice roasted malt profile . i 'm not a huge fan of the sweetness in the aftertaste and i wish a bit more vanilla came through on the flavor , but still glad i tried it .  m : this has a great body for the beer . it has the consistency of motor oil which suits it nicely .
i love the smell of a good , dry-hopped ale ... very attractive , hence the reason i rate the aroma as a 5 .  m - very dry with perfect carbonation !

the aroma was easily the best part of this beer . i 've summed up the aroma like this ... .imagine a freshly baked fruit cake with sweet white icing glazed all over the top , sliced apples dipped halfway through the cake and sprinkled with cinnamon . tons of pears , apples , cinnamon , sweet malts , yeast , caramel , dried orange peels and alcohol . i really enjoyed this !  this exhibited a creamy mouthfeel .
beautifully strong citrusy hop aroma . very well balanced taste , with grapefruit hops , then resiny pine needle taste and then a superb malt finish .  mouthfeel is incredibly full .. almost chewy .

the aroma is strong . there is a lot of dark fruit , caramel , flowers , oak , and the right amount of bourbon . once i get used to that i can detect caramel , more bourbon than there is in the aroma , not as many floral notes , more oak , no fruit . i like this taste , but it is nowhere near as harmonious as the aroma . the mouthfeel is full bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky texture . very nice feel . unfortunately , whereas the aroma is a harmonious blend of strong smells , the taste is a bunch of in-your-face flavors that work together but have no real grace .  mf : masterfully fizzy but light and balanced .

s- i love the aroma , this one is packing a lot of hops . overall , i think this is a very good dipa that i 'm glad i tried .  the texture , in its sublime perfection , is creamy like a milkshake ... unbelievable .

smell : delicious floral aromas hit the nose along with various fruits ( i 'm picking up grapefruit ) , along with other hoppy scents . still pretty good though -- a mess of hops ( with enough of a malt backbone presence to help the beer ) with a dry , bitter finish . overall : a pretty decent beer , but i was a little disappointed that the taste lacked so much that the aroma captured .  the first sip reveals a velvety smooth body with mild gentle carbonation rolling right along through the swallow .
nice .  m : incredible mouthfeel .

there is a great pumkin/cinnamin/ginger smell to this beer .  mouthfeel is awesome and is what makes this beer for me , this is a good tasting beer that is enhanced by a perfect creamy smooth feeling as it passes over my palate .
the smell was amazing and what i liked most about this beer . every aspect of this beer works together great and it was worth buying .  full bodied . perfect . the oats add some awesome smoothness .

overall , this beer has a very nice smell . t - the hop bitterness is right up front .  the mouthfeel on this brew was amazing . i ca n't imagine a brew being more full-bodied . mouthfeel is thick , chewy , almost syrupy and definitely absurd .
amazing complex aroma , very exciting . taste doesnt quite live up to the great smell . still tasty but missing the fruitiness .  medium body with perfect amount of carbonation .

very balanced . really great . most pumpkin ales smell like pumpkin and spice , this one spells like a baked pie . a more than solid representation of the style , though the taste was a slight light down after the amazing aroma .  exceptionally smooth mouthfeel and medium/full bodied .

the aroma is nearly perfect , capturing the belgian pale ale style very well , with honey , clove , ginger , and lemon-pepper mingling with subtle earthy yeast .  this really has the acidity and fermentation of kombucha tea , giving it a great , crisp mouthfeel .

but , geeeez , what a wonderful aroma lurks underneath the mess . tangerine and grapefruit along with rock candy and toffee . pears and apples , raisinbread , and a meadow of wildflowers add to the divine nose . mouthfeel lacks carbonation ( it must be on top ) , but is medium bodied and has a unique fruity apple hops bite . taste is well balanced and very complex . much of the aroma is reflected in the taste , so i will simply say that this is one unique pale ale .  it 's pretty full bodied and very smooth .

nice savoury aroma of smoked cheddar comes off this one.taste is also of smoked cheddar or meat , with some chocolate malt .  mouthfeel is the best part about the rasputin - just the right amount of chewiness and the malt and alcohol linger heavily on the sides of your tongue .

tart funky aroma with a nice oak vanilla presence from the barrel aging .  the body of this beer is incredible , and the alcohol content makes itself well known throughout the pint . very silky smooth and quite viscous for the style .

aroma is a ton of citrus , grapefruit and sweet acidic fumes . smells fantastic . taste is very nice , hops up front , dry , floral and citrus notes as expected . the aroma of this beer was the best part . the taste was good , but the smell was the tops for any dipa i 've tasted .  velvety smooth creamy mouthfeel , moderate level of carbonation , medium to thick body .

smell : the smell is wonderfully complex and full of fruit and nut notes . truly a treat to enjoy , and i enjoyed it heartily . quite taste , and quite drinkable .  very dark with no light coming through and light head n : nose has lots of chocolate and sweet malts and a touch of hops t : starts with lots of chocolate and coffee , some sweet malts but very slight , a touch of hops are prevelant , some oatmeal taste as well , it 's got a sweet earthiness to it which is somewhat unique , a slight bitterness shines through m : it has a velvet feel in the mouth as it slides around , very thick and smooth f : a touch bitterness comes out in the end with the nice stout and oatmeal taste , coffee lingers on the back of the tongue , it has a sweet quality to start but gets drier as it fades and finishes really dry , its got a great smooth feeling in the mouth to go along with the great taste final thoughts : a great stout , it would be great if it was labelled as oatmeal or irish stout since it seems to have qualities of both , but listed as imperial it makes me wonder since its lacking a lot in the hop category .

the aroma is exceptional , and the bourbon notes are packed with vanilla , dark fruits ( raisin , fig , orange peel ) , and a touch of chocolate . i would have liked there to be a touch more chocolate n this one , too , but its still a fantastic beer . in my book schlafly is 2-for-2 with big , bourbon-aged beers , as their barleywine reserve was equally as impressive .  wonderful feel .

smell : smells unbelievably hoppy . smells very hoppy and promising . taste : meh , i really was expecting a big bold aperican ipa from this .  perfect carbonation , which i am growing to expect from oskar blues .

a wonderful nose bursting from the nice off white head . nose of citrus perfection that blends into something quite nice .  this coats the palate with a burbon goodness . just the right amount of carbonation .
s - pine tree . big piney hop presense , and a little floral and grassy . very good stuff .  mouthfeel : a perfect amount of carbonation .
wonderful hoppy aromas . very resiny and green , herbal , with some earthiness , and pine as well .  amazing . 4.5 d - over the top , how much can you really have ?
beautiful flowery-perfume aroma with pinnapple and apricot .  mouthfeel is medium and very smooth with the perfect level of carbonation .

smell - strong smell of lemon zest and citrus . coriander , banana , and orange as well.. taste - strong flavor of coriander and orange .  it was lush , creamy , smooth , rich , decadant and full . a very full bodied stout with a low carbonation .

the best part about this beer though is its aroma . just plain hoppy goodness . citrus with some pineapple , maybe a touch grassy .  it possesses the best mouthfeel i 've yet to come across , rich and velvety , it just rolls over the palate and tongue , and goes down incredibly smooth .
( s ) it smells great . a ton of light and citric fruits .  mouthfeel - 5.0 silky smooth , with very fine , lively , almost creamy carbonation .
smell - best smelling beer i have had yet ! the coriander mixed in really boost the smell of this beer .  the body is surprisingly thick and coating with a rich slick mouth feel .
solid caramel malt in this as well , this smells magnificent . hints of alcohol detected as well . d - very drinkable , great stuff here .  incredibly smooth and creamy in the mouth .

smell is excellent . orange , berries , bitter , big sweet tropical and mango scents and slight pine and slight wheat scents but very full . almost frothy mouthfeel it is so light and creamy but still has a good body but extremely bitter .  mouthfeel - great mouthfeel .
this is the best beer ive erver smelled . period .  m : absolutely the best part of the beer .

first thing i notice with the smell of this one is how hoppy it is - wow , the huge blast of citrus makes me think i 'm smelling an ipa or something . awesome . i had a hell of a hard time trying to find anything i did n't love about this one .  carbonation is perfect and really adds to the beer .

nose is wonderful , citrus , melon , pineapple , and piney hops jump out and stay in full force for the entire glass .  m = a truly exceptional mouthfeel , full bodied , great mouthcoating , frothy , luscious , creamy .

s - wow . dark fruitiness up front backed up with some sweet caramel/toffee with a touch of spice . normally if i like the smell i like the taste even better but theres just something hypnotising in that smell . still , it 's great and almost like liquid rum and raisin cake . good on the odd occasion .  the carbonation feels great on the tongue .

s : fantastic floral hop aroma that only dry hopping can produce ! t : the hops have done more than just produce great aroma , they are prevalent in the flavor as well - and not just bittering . i love hoppy beer and this was no exception . a nice smooth base ale , perfectly accented with earthy flavorful hops . great ale !  the mouthfeel is incredible on this beer .

s - smells of vanilla , alcohol , oak , raisins , all spice , chocolate , cherry , and brandy . t - tastes are really good , with chocolate , brandy , raisins , vanilla , coffee , and some fruitiness that is a little off .  mouthfeel : no real aftertaste ( remarkable for a malt-heavy beer ) , carbonation is excellent and it plays well on the palate .

the aroma and flavour are of huge citrus from the cascade hops used in the brew . this was the first british ale to use them this heavily , but it seems that half the brewers in england have now come out with their lager-malt/cascade bitter . a couple of them even do a better job - mighty oak 's maldon gold has an edge on jhb and hopdaemon 's incubus is worth the trip to canterbury in and of itself . now , if the brits would discover centennial or chinook , or even give a better chance to their own challenger hops .  it pours a brilliant gold , and the mouthfeel is very thick and chewy .

nose is hoppy alright , juicy with bubblegum and minty notes . has a nice aroma , but i prefer nn over it . i prefer nugget nectar to this , but it was a fun beer to try .  mouthfeel/drinkability- absolutely sublime texture in the mouth ... it 's medium bodied with a richness matched by the beer 's stunning palate .

smell- sweet , dark , plummy malts abound ... an absolutely delectable nose . i 'm even getting some molasses and sarsaparilla , bringing an old world character to the beer . the finish , long-lasting and quite tasty , is somewhat cloying ; there is an overrriding sweetness that shadows the more subtle , enjoyable flavors .  mouth : excellent mouthfeel is the first thing you notice , tingling all the way through the mouth like tiny pin-pricks that i can actually continue to feel long after swallowing .

has an aroma of citrus , lavender , and spices .  m - nearly full bodied but despite that and the abv , it is extremely smooth and leaves just the right amount of flavor behind leaving you wanting another sip .

grapefruit notes from the hops dominate upfront , followed closely by a bit of sweet malt . yep , this is certainly hoppy .  good , creamy body with a low-medium carbonation is very nice for a ba imperial stout that is not overly sweet .
very fragrant . taste : very clean taste with fruity phenols dominating over any wheaty flavor .  the texture is perfect , though .
clear amber color smell is thick of caramel malts with a pear and apple undertones nice little complexity .  m : outstanding , deliciously creamy , thick , rich for an ipa .

s - aroma is very pungent . smells slightly sweeter than it actually tastes ... in a good way . smells very malty with hints of chocolate and little vanilla .  instead , i got this pefect , autumnal fruit beer , which , though it smells kind of like apple jacks , had an exceptional mouthfeel , and a rich apple kick that coupled nicely with the astringency of the lager .

the smell is the first thing i noticed after opening the bottle . even before pouring the smell of intense hops wafts from the bottle . overall all a great beer , but not one i would session .  the taste is an initial malty sweetness , followed by bitter hoppy alcohol , followed by dry chewiness . this brew has a great thickness and presence , and the carbonation is not too much to interrupt things . excellent .

from tap to maredsous glass pours an opaque apricot-orange , thick sudsy , sea-foam head with lots of lacing s : strong nose , big bouquet carried by ample alcohol volatiles . floral , sweet , citrusy . flavors are big and bold but disjointed . very sweet , almost cloying . d : loses some points here ... interesting brew , lots of flavors and layers , but they 're all over the place . but it 's far from boring .  just perfect . this is one of the better stouts that weyerbacher has done .

this beer had some wonderful aromas of scotches , alcohol , fruits , chocolates , and more and it tasted like more of the same . rogue should start making this stuff again .  a very smooth and creamy cask ale , that goes down very well .

smells of intense grassy pinneapple hops . there is essence of tangerine and a little bit of grapefruit to accompany it . there is some definite centennial and cascade hop character to the nose of this beer . the taste is surprisingly balanced . it 's remarkably smooth and drinkable in spite of the hoppy nose and 9.5 abv .  m - very creamy . just a small sip seems to coat the inside of the mouth very well .

this smells incredibly sweet . if i smelled this blind folded , my instinct would guess that this is an actual dessert placed in front of me . the result is a wonderfully balanced and incredibly unique dessert beer .  palate is perfect , rich and chewy .

smell is brimming with yeast esters , bananna and clove dominate . smell may be the best part of this beer , and are much better on tap than in bottle . balanced , but nothing amazing . drinkability is the biggest weakness , as it becomes a little heavy on the fruit and esters by the end of the pint .  mouthfeel is perfect . smooth and creamy , light carbonation , just absolutly terrific .

very juicy pineapple hops . very sweet with a lot of bitterness in the nose . whew this is strongest i have ever smelt . hate to say it but it makes me think of what a good dfh 120 ipa should taste like .  full bodied for the style , definitely one of the fullest dipa 's that i 've ever had . nice carbonation levels as well .

smell : a wonderful array of hops -- resiny , floral , piney , and spicey . crisp and quite refreshing . tastes better as you drink more . overall : very refreshing beer with pretty decent flavor .  mouthfeel is complex ( and the best part about this brew ! ) - full of variations in feel , thin and fruity , then rich and creamy . carbonation is an afterthought .

anchor 's humming ale looks like a nice thick wheat beer , turbid and dense blond in appearance . the first sniff reveals a rich and fresh bouquet of american citrusy hops .  mouthfeel is luscious and creamy , very well done there ; average carbonation .

s= nice complexity here . there is a real nice roastyness to the malts as well . really a ton of nose to this one . t= the beer starts again with a lot of coffee flavor . there is a pretty decent amount of heat coming from the alcohol in it .  the rest : another solid beer from ommegang ; good balance and a great body .

the aroma was simply amazing . sweet and complex with strong notes of green raisins , dark fruits , figs and molasses . slightly woody and `` old . '' compared to the aroma , the taste was a bit of a letdown initially . brown sugar and molasses notes came through strong . raisins , prunes and dried figs were also quite apparent . this beer drank like a charm .  creamy and full bodied throughout . one of the creamier feeling beers ive had from this style . exceptional .

this smell 's like a messy , dripping , kindergartner 's peanut butter and jelly sandwich : mild breadiness , sticky skippy peanut butter , and sweet strawberry jam ! unique , unusual , and honestly , pretty crazy . this beer is pretty acidic and sharp , somewhat sweet , and there 's a bit of bread and nuttiness left over , but there 's nothing much here to enjoy or appreciate . that being said , the liquid in the glass smelled far better than it tasted .  mf : thick viscous body , creamy mouthfeel , low carbonation d : i have tried many of dfh 's wild experiments when it comes to unique ingredients , and found that some of them fell short and ingredients got lost ( theobroma comes to mind ) .
it feels very uncomfortable .  mouthfeel , on the other hand , is amazing . perfect level of carbonation and great water quality .
full aroma . not overpowering , but nice . taste : hits you hard on the front and back end .  exceptionally creamy mouthfeel , medium body .

aroma is intense : leather , sweet syrup , yeast getting slightly funky . i 'll be honest , it 's a bit too weird for my tastes . i know a lot like this complexity , but i find it disjointed .  the mouthfeel is the ultimate strongpoint on this beer . it is ridiculously creamy and very chewy , complemented with the perfect amount of carbonation .

s - potent smell . incredible amount of citrus power that comes from something like cascade hops . its almost sharp on the nose . earthy and grassy as well . very bitter , but does have some malt notes .  very smooth . just the right amount of carbonation .

s - some light citrusy notes that mix with a sweeter malt to give a caramel aroma that has some ever so slight notes of fig or plum to it . the appearance and aroma both had me expecting a great offering .  mouthfeel is near perfect with carbonation playing second fiddle to the robust malts .

i drink a lot of great coffee , and this beer smells bolder than some of those . the smell is so bold , i even smell a really deep strong smell that i can only relate to leather or rubber ... that may sound weird , but i assure you that it is in a good way t : like the nose , there is an absolute assault of coffee .  the mouthfeel is just amazing , it enters smooth and goes down smooth .

served from the bottle into a tulip glass a- poured black with tight creamy mocha head that leaves some spotty lace s- big sweet citrus and piney hops , dark roasted malt , currants , and molasses t- some citrusy/piney flavors in this beer , big licorice , molasses , some currant , and chocolate like flavors . odd soy sauce like taste developed as i got towards the bottom quarter of my glass .  first sip reveals a rich and firmly textured beer of elegant character . an encore presence by the hops closes out the taste in a long and seamless finish . faultless balance , beautiful complexity both in the nose and on the tongue make this beer , in my opinion , a perfect desert beer or soothing winter warmer .

garlic and citrus fruit are very present . pine also makes an appearance as well as marijuana . i love it ! t : tastes almost like it smells . i do n't get much garlic , not nearly as much as the smell offered up .  like all chimay beers , it feels great on the mouth : foamy and thick .

the aroma is quite pleasing . juicy banana , bread . a very nice smelling hefe .  mouthfeel is really very rich : like a good stout on the palate , smooth and full , thick and chewy , but it 's got that pilsner crispness .
smell is good , dark fruits with a nice maltiness and a hint of bitter hops .  fantastic carbonation persists in mouth-feel .

lots of cinnamon , apple cider and more cinnamon . the taste is n't near the quality of the aroma . again lots of cider , orange peel , cinnamon and clove . this beer tastes like it needs a different fermenting process , different priming sugar or method or that it might just be superb if offered with no carbonation at all like a utopias .  m : medium-bodied with a soft , silky mouthfeel . the thick , creamy head gives a great texture to each sip .
s - awesome . delicate balance of dark fruit .  mouthfeel is incredible , maybe an even better quality than the taste .

s : simply fantastic . i think i literally spent more time smelling this beer than i did drinking it . great stuff .  the mouth feel is outstanding , to the point of being lip smacking and among the best i 've had .

taste is a bit dissapointing after the perfect aroma - sweetish , slightly watery malt , clove , rather fruity and mostly reminds of ripe apples and banana . overall , it was not bad , but after the nice smell and looks i expected much better taste .  well done feel . i so enjoy the heaviness of the feel and how it combines with the fruit flavors .

nice thin layer stays until the end ... aroma - vanilla , very fruity ( tropical fruits ? ) , some citrus hints , honey ... taste sweet , flowery , vanilla notes ... feel - very , very smooth and mellow . extremely drinkable ... overall - an excellent beer , very individual- have n't tasted much else like this before ...  velvet mouthfeel ; tongue coating and heavy .

s : hops right off the back , smells like hot wort when your chilling t : perfect balance of maltiness and hoppiness .  m - the body of this beer with the carbonation is perfect . tiny bubbles , so you have that nice creaminess with a fantastic , medium and not overpowering mouthfeel . d - because there is so much coffee slammed into this beer , it leaves your mouth a little dry and overwhelms the palate , so i 'm good after one bottle .

poured into a tulip glass a deep mahogany brown with a tinge of amber , not any head to speak of really , seemed to be almost uncarbonated .aromas are great , dark fruit , candied sugar , light belgian yeast , even a hint of smoky peat.flavors have a gummy , fruity sweetness with light phenols , its quite alcoholic as it warms.i have had belgian/scotch dark ales before and this doesnt measure up for me , i like the cause and the strory on the label , the beer..eh .  molasses and toffee sweetness m - rich and chewy caramell . low carb form the bottle and slightly dry d - wonderful !
smells like fresh noble hops .  this is really a very good beer : the finish , the mouth feel , the carbonation , the body , are quite exceptional . it 's the taste .

an excellent lambic with an wonderfully pungent black currant aroma . the flavor is full of fresh crushed fruit and herbal notes .  m : very smooth , sticky , and thick . light to medium carbonation .
the smell is sour and tart with a good amount of musty funk .  smooth as velvet , i love what oak-aging does to impy stouts .

the aroma projects bright floral hops very nice really though i initially caught a whiff of something that said , miller high life to me .  mf & d - sticky and delicious . just the right amount of carbonation and alcohol content to keep the porter balanced .

s - really like the smell on this one with lots of green apple . lots of bready wheat in here , but this was a letdown from the nose . m - medium bodied with a lot of carbonation , seems fine .  the mouthfeel is exceptional , big thick viscous and sticky and is amazingly velvety over my palate . really quite incredible .

s : tons of coffee and espresso that reminded me of founder 's breakfast stout off the bat . t : roasted coffee/chocolate malts with a robust coconut sweetness upfront that seems to linger into a nice and subtle finish . syrupy at times , but never to a point where i 'm overwhelmed ... excellent . m : full-body , oily , and zero to mild carbonation . d : a damn good beer ! overall : never been big on stone 's collaboration beers , but this one is a true winner .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy/smooth . excellent feel .

the initial smell is sweet but there is a touch of charred wood which was very unique ( a good unique . the initial taste was very sweet , almost sickening .  i think it 's the mouthfeel that sets this beer apart from the others . silky smooth with some alcohol kick and lively carbonation .
exceptional . taste offers only a hint of sweetness on the aftertaste . it is really quite good .  m. incredibly smooth .

it smells like dusty lemons , sour fruit , really nice . a little light on flavor , not too sour , kinda watery but bubbly at the same time .  mouthfeel is thick and creamy and everything i could ask for . the tartness keeps pulling you in like a siren , and i am totally captivated by her song .

s - big nose of tropical fruit and citrus up front with some pine . definitely a hop-forward ipa with a very robust and inviting nose . t - grapefruit , pine , tangerine , pineapple .  it has an exceptional silky texture to it - similar to a nitro effect . just enough carbonation .
a very nice , model ipa aroma .  fine carbonation bubbles and a full body give an excellant texture . coats the palate beautifully . more of a bourbon lovers beer than a stout lovers beer .

nose is strong , intense , dark fruits about to rot which someone spilt port wine upon - wonderful , very interesting . full bodied chewy mouthfeel . i 've no idea what the six herbs and spices are but i applaud the choices , excellent complexity . phenols can be the bane of a belgian , here they are aggressively , exquisitely blended .  the mouthfeel and the drinkability of this beer are the stars for me , it was so smooth and almost milky ( in a good way.. not like gagging thickness or anything.. just very smooth ) .

the smell is intense ; the spiciest smell i 've ever smelled in a pumpkin ale ! nutmeg and spice flavors are very pungent . this beer blew my mind with its complex flavor , but quickly became very cloying . this beer would 've been good with dessert . it is certainly unusual and worth a try if you like pumpkin ales .  mouthfeel is extremely smooth and velvety .

nice complex but balanced smell . t : very complex . overall a very good , complex beer .  this beer feels like it belongs in my mouth and is very delightful . i certainly could drink this beer all night long : d
smells super hoppy , with notes of christmas tree .  the mouthfeel is very much like drinking liquid chocolate or marshmallow fluff . so rich , creamy , and very full in the mouth .

this nose is very fragrant with oily citrus and even noticeable mellon with a backround spike of pickled pine . body is a hazy orange amber wheat gold thing going on . this beer is nicely drinkable , it just lacks some of the attributes of other great ipa 's .  oh , before you even get a dose of those lovely hops , that heavy belting richness makes its presence felt , with a slick , thick , chewy texture coating the mouth . once it 's there it releases its bomb - a phenomenally astringent hop bitterness cascading over the tongue . apart from the thick body , there 's almost no whisper of the malt backing , but that 's ok. that 's what this beer is all about .

nose is excellent ... t- much like the nose in all of the tinges , but finish is very sweet , too sweet . d- quite good , but barely garners an average in the style of tripel , mainly because of it being too sweet .  very creamy , smooth , and full bodied mouthfeel . this is definitely a stout that i could drink quite a lot of given it 's mild but good flavor and fantastic texture .
rum soaked sweet cherries , vinegar . excellent very sour - prevalent sharp acidic vinegar flavor + tart berries .  perfect carbonation , i wish all pale ales were this way .
the smell was impressive with strong piney hops jumping out of the glass followed by a faint hop smell . the beer was well carbonated leaving behind a slick piney feel .  excellent mouthfeel .

creamy head poured loose and frothy and faded almost instantly to wispy covering ... no real lacing to speak about ... lots going on in the aroma ... lots of rich oaky bourbon notes mixed with sweet nuttiness - hints of almond and pistachio , toffee and treacle , very woody , musty , some overripe ( rotten ? ) fruits - apples and bananas , grainy malts , lots of booze , toasted ( burnt ) raisin bread , light smokiness , some chocolate , butterscotch ... taste - very strong ( overpowering ? ) boozy bourbon mixed with lots of belgian yeastiness , bready , very woody , musty , toasted nuts , vanilla , very light toffee sweetness , sweet overripe fruits , some vegetal traces , anise - hint of cough medicine , burnt butter ... m & d - fairly sharp and dry ... medium bodied ... way too boozy to be very drinkable ... overall - a decent enough experiment ... not something i 'd want a lot of but worth trying ... definitely a sipper..  carbonation is perfect ; sharp , but not biting .

s : huge hop aroma . smells awesome . t : earthy hop oil , ripe ruby red grapefruit , lemon zest and fresh orange .  medium bodied with low carbonation . amazing mouthfeel with one of the most balanced , robust , and pleasantly malty flavor profiles of any barleywine .
smell : smells of chocolate , caramel , and coffee .  the mouthfeel , on the other hand , is wonderful : creamy , smooth , full-bodied , with moderate yet lively carbonation .
superb aroma , inviting and heavy . no brew has ever smelled this good then tasted bad : ) nice prickly mouthfeel .  the lack of carbonation really helps the mouthfeel of this .
the bouqet is very pleasing with fruit and hops each hitting a high note with nice balance .  it has a velvety mouthfeel .
s : like pumpkin pie filling . spicy . wish it lived up to the smell . i 'll be sticking with punkin if i feel like a pumpkin beer .  it 's full bodied and smooth with a very clean finish .

it smells great . there isnt much head on this one sadly , but the color and smell make up for it . its good but not very balanced . it 's not the most drinkable but its still enjoyable . maybe a little time would balance this puppy out . overall , a good brew .  m : mouthfeel is great . full-bodied , yet not too thick .

aroma of toasted bread and roasting chestnuts with a strong coppery head . strong roast nuts , toasted almonds , caramel and hints of apricot and cherry pull together to give a beer that is a little different with each sip as the palate becomes accustomed .  very refreshing .
