the orange peel and candied sugar aroma was quite intriguing . the flavors were dominated by the sugar sweetness , hints of the alcohol , and that crisp glbc house flavor ( pilsner malts ?  i love the mouthfeel of this beer . i love that thick , syrupy feel .

s- smells exclusively like apples and cinnamon . a blend of apples , both tart and sweet with a slight hint of cinnamon at the end . t- it tastes like a cider more than a beer .  creamy , full bodied feel to it . really outstanding .

stupendous nose . i found the taste to be not quite as amazing as the smell , but this is a really great and enjoyable quad . perhaps a little too much for my taste , but still really good .  feel is a nice creamy smooth medium-full with an excellent soft tickling carbonation .
a very good autumn smell .  mouthfeel : best mouthfeel of any wit i 've ever had ; this has the milkshake-thick , smooth mouthfeels i 've heard described as ideal for the style .

smell - wow , nice strong hop smell , also quite fruity , hints of orange and grapes are present . really great smell . taste - pretty darn good , starts out with a hoppy citrus taste that makes way for a powerful hop bitterness that sticks with ya .  m : leaves a nice stickiness that is not overpoweing .

complex sour with tropical aromas . nice lacy appearance in the chalice with good carbonation in the mouth . what is that suddenly familiar aroma ? i flashed on cutting a passion fruit in half and smelling it . more nose of pineapple guava . one of the best and most interesting beers i 've tried this year .  perfect balance of sweet and bitter with a creamy smooth mouthfeel .

s : the smell is rich and full of sweet caramel , molasses , toffee , and vanilla . the brandy blends in seamlessly with the base old ale and the dark fruits such as raisins , plums , and some others that i ca n't quite pick out . t : the flavor is rich and sweet , featuring brown sugar , caramel , toffee , and vanilla . m : the carbonation is non-existent , but the body is quite full and rich . d : sure , you ca n't sit down and enjoy the full 750 ml bottle of this beer , but you could certainly get yourself in some trouble .  medium body with a thick and creamy yet mineralic texture . perfect combination of lively and fizzy effervescence . finish is dry and tart with just enough lactic sourness .

nice smell , reminding me of the red rose amber ale by baird : red fruits , a nice sweetness and a deep but not harsh chocolaty character . not that much to say about it ; it is just far from being as exciting as the smell and the appearance .  mouthfeel was incredibly creamy .

very pleasant aromas on the nose . like the nose , the traditional pumpkin pie flavors come thru immediately . like the aroma , i get decent doses of graham cracker malts and hints of roasted nuts , and sweet baking spices , perhaps some light brown sugar .  incredibly creamy and light .

very , very nice . the taste is surprising .  mouthfeel : creamy smooth medium body with superb carbonation . swallow is velvet . tasty and the mouthfeel is truely a dream . goes down easy when you enjoy slowly .

this sucker smells like freshly brewed coffee ! fresh ground coffee beans , dark bakers chocolate and the slightest hints of marshmallow and whipped cream . screw it , this is a coffee stout .  this probably has the best mouth feel i have experienced to date .

smell- this one has a really nice scent . some very sweet chocolaty caramel toasted or roasted malt .  awesome thickness , yet not throat-closing thickness -- more like smooth milkshake thickness , where carbonation does n't feel like bubbles , but simply a collective , chilled push down the throat .

nose is still incredible - just exploding with tart fruit ( currants but could easily be mistaken for raspberry ) and some hints of his wheat origin . this is an excellent summer beer and would be great with spicy food .  mouthfeel/drinkability- just when i thought the perfect mouthfeel of a belgian ale was locked up with tripel karmeliet , this beer dazzles with a sublime , gentle texture that lasts throughout the entire duration in the mouth . absolute perfection , it further emphasizes the already impressive quality of the beer .

laces magnificantly ; elegant and 2-toned . nose is powerful and intense , coffee , oak , and cocoa , just as it should be . pretty much spot-on . some oak on the finish , and a lot of robust roasty malt in the middle . quite bitter , but not from hops , mostly bitter cocoa ... cellaring would probably do wonders for this . edit : read the label mention of cayenne and it completely clicked . mouthfeel is very , very , very fine carbonation . overall bitter , but not dry nor particularly rich .  t - bananas , caramel , and mild dates swim around sour-yeastiness and vanilla , concealing well the alcohol that lies beneath ... m - very , very smooth , medium body massages the palate and dries the cheeks . d - nice , very nice , do n't know if i 'd get it again , but very nice .

a : pours a deep golden brown with a decent head that very much clings to the glass s : obviously coffee shines through in this one . also a sweet malty punch at the end . very nice , especially if you 're a coffee drinker t : a classic brown ale with a mellow coffee layer that lingers throughout m : bitter , dry , slightly acidic d : all day , all night . i second the idea of victory putting this one into a bottle .  the texture of this stout is incredibly smooth , possibly the smoothest , creamiest stout i 've had .

winter 2011 : an improvement over the summer 2010 batch . already enjoyable aroma/flavor was even more spot-on . assertive , balanced aroma of grapefruit , floral honey , and a touch of minty pine . despite the lackluster mouthfeel , this brew had some outstanding elements , particularly the aroma and the subtle rye spice . nicely complex beer to which i 'd gladly return .  very full mouthfeel even feels a bit oily on the tongue . super smooth in the mouth . truly excellent drinkability here .

s : incredible hop aroma . spicy/citrus tones at a tolerable level for i 'd imagine just about anyone . t : from such an amazing smell , a bit of a disappointment .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . silky smooth .

wonderful nose , i am expecting a great belgian-style beer . the nose of this brew is so promising that the failures of its flavors are all the more disappointing .  mouthfeel is smooth and velvety with carbonation perceivable at the very end of the swill .
s - very strong . sweet alcohol , cognac , liquorish , chocolate liquor , rasins , t - whoa ... .  the mouthfeel was the best part of this beer .

big aroma of resinous , citrusy hops sting your brain . taste does not try to hide the alcohol - in fact it showcases it . brown sugar taste in more present than i expected from this brew . hops prickly on the tongue . although i would not mind the alcohol and bittering hops knocked down a notch , this is still a wonderful brew .  had on tap at the blind tiger in nyc , pint glass appearance : mild haze to it , light amber color , great head poured smell : citrus , piney hop , sweetness from the malt taste & mouthfeel : brilliantly smooth within the medium body .
s : smells pretty damn fantastic . citrus fruit shows up all over the place .  the body is perfect .

what a fantastic smell to this one . a bit lost there ... it 's a good ipa but it 's not quite as well rounded as i 'd prefer .  ever so rich and creamy in the mouth with soft and forgiving carbonation . medium-full in body .

big nose , filled with charleston chew chocolaty filling and some dark plum pudding . nice ... very nice . has a light , airy feel when drinking it , very creamily meringue like . i dont get a whole bunch of rich , yeasty esters but it still maintains a nice complex profile .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , extremely smooth , and lip smacking .
i downright love this style , which is hard to find but sooo good . this is one of the better !  very enjoyable , with a medium body and creamy carbonation that is perfect for this beer .

this one went off like a loaded gun - did n't even have the cage off the cork before the cork shot out , bouncing off the ceiling , spraying a fizzy brown liquid all over my kitchen . s : complex . fruity malts and belgian yeasts . t : sweet blend of deep malts , light belgian yeasts , apple , spices , and raisins .  simply luxurious on the tongue . the drinkability is also very good .
this smells wonderful . i 'm in a field - no ! fantastic . taste is a balance of the citrus , resiny hops , and a malty sweetness .  the mouthfeel is perfect for a stout .
smell is a nice sweet citrus scent .  mouthfeel is superb , very rich and creamy , gently coating the palate and then closes with a clean , dry finish .
aroma is surprisingly rich and full . great aroma . i would pick this one up again .  m- oh so crisp and so damn smooth over the medium body .

smell : a metric boatload of hops . loads of juicy citrus - orange and grapefruit dominate , and sweet fruit hop notes.the hop aroma is backed by some caramel notes . this is a rock solid dipa aroma . taste : loads of hops with a drying quality wash over my tongue . behind all the hops is a nice caramel/biscuit backbone . nonetheless this a tasty dipa .  really excellent creamy mouthfeel .

rose petals , mangos . lot 's of floral and tropical aromas ( not citrus though ) . this is not the beer that i 've come to expect as a double ipa . with that said it 's a very good beer that exemplifies the uniques of dogfish head . this is not a hop bomb , but is a very flavorful and complex beer . brown sugar , vanilla , and biscuity flavors lead to a very pleasant fruity finish . mango .  excellent mouthfeel for the style .

this is about as good as it gets aroma wise for a hoppy beer . raw resiny pure hops . this has a good hoppy flavor , but it 's not quite as full as the nose promised . still good , no doubt , just not top shelf in my opinion .  m ) rich , almost slick . rich , long mouth coating .
very interesting and really makes you want to taste it .  mouthfeel is very good and creamy with good carbonation levels .

... pours a brown dark brown colour ... has oak , chocolate , cherries , tar and other grab bag candies ... tastes like cherries a bit ... bold yet still quite balanced , a great brew indeed ... quality and crazy mixed in a 750 bottle..  mouthfeel : medium body with colossal carbonation make this an incredibly creamy beer . de dolle gets this perfect for me yet again .

this smells incredible from the moment i pop the cap until i stick the bottle in the recycle bin . dark fruits , caramel , licorice , chocolate , hints of smoke , its all in here . little to no hop presence in the aroma . this is drinking beautifully right now , too bad its the only one i 've ever seen .  the mouthfeel is exceptional -- thick , chewy , syrupy , andincredibly smooth .

the smell is absolutely unique . it has a very herbal nose , after sniffing for a bit , it seemed like a great flavor for a potpourri . one of the best smelling beers i have ever tried .  perfect mouthfeel , actually .
this has a very nice nose , vanilla and cocoa with a little sweet malt . unfortunately the taste is n't quite so good .  mouthfeel is like silk with slight carbination .
very nice aroma all around .  m - fantastic . perfect amount of carbonation , just enough to tingle the palate , complementing the sour flavor .

s : this smells right one the balance of the bourbon , chocolate , and vanilla bean are perfect . the nose on this is really inviting , there 's trace of any off aromas you sometimes get that overpower what trying to be represented . the bourbon is really tame in this one , its lending a nice charred backbone that helps to really life the vanilla to the front .  very thick and full with a near perfect carbonation . a bit dry in the finish .

excellent , grassy smell ; very strong and awesome . taste follows the aromas , but it is surprisingly well-balanced with a bittersweet aftertaste mixed in with the supreme amount of hops . excellent .  m : for some reason , the mouthfeel is great ! perfect balance of body and drinkability .

s - beautiful light tartness , pronounced blue cheesy funk . really great nose t - nice light tartness , some cherry .  the mouthfeel is creamy and frothy very smooth for a beer with so much flavor and strength .

s - quite a powerful hop aroma . beautiful citrusy , bright character . d - i like it . great example of how a beer should be built for a hop lover .  the mouthfeel is gorgeously creamy and full , one of the best beers i 've had for feel .

i pour this chilled sample into my pint glass and the hop aroma hits me immediately . but back to the appearance first . the aroma is dominated by hops , floral scents first then i pick up hiints of pine and some sour citrus notes too . i get a quick hint of sweetness coming through and then the hops take over .  m- very creamy , milky texture .

it looks a little lighter than i remember maduro . it smells like big sound , of all things , mixed with a shot of espresso . it gives aromas of chocolate , sweet malt , cream , with a light coffee bitterness . overall it 's a solid beer , but maduro is far superior in my opinion .  whoa was it thick ! an outstanding beer , i was extremely excited to be able to say i 've tasted it . as it warms in the glass , the bite grows stronger . maybe this brew would be better appreciated by some experienced brewmasters , i thought it was a good beer but i ca n't justify rating it an a+ or 5 , because i would n't buy a bottle again . the two beers that ultimately create this beast are exquisite , but this monster was n't for me .

aroma is a blast of hoppy sweetness -- it 's like a handful of fresh fruit . a very nice and inviting aroma if you ask me .  the mouthfeel is some kind of amazing . this brew is thick , chewy , ultra creamy smooth and goes down like heavy cream . if you like your imperial stouts with an unapologetically brash , bold , slightly raw taste , but with a refined , well-mannered mouthfeel , then you 'll enjoy expedition stout immensely .

absolute incredible , unique-looking brew . nose is a rich , delectable bouquet of sweets . sweet toffee , dates , maybe some cranberries at the back , and just the right amount of an earthy acidity to counterbalance the really rather pungent sweetness . smells sweet , sticky , delicious and slightly fruity . again sensational . while it definitely lacks the toffee sweetness of the nose , there is definitely evidence of a very potent , prominent malt base , very thick and rich . most of the palate is very bitter and tastes like it 's been bombarded with hops , very astringent with a slightly phenolic character that comes around the mid and hangs well over the finish .  there is nothing very `` complex '' about it , just a bitter hops taste and perfect mouthfeel . as mentioned , the mouthfeel for pale ale is perfect ... . perfect amount of carbonation and easy to pour .

sweet in the nose , with some spicy hops . very complex ; i ca n't begin to do all the flavours justice . all i know is i could smell this beer all evening and be happy . spices ( i get some coriander ) with malts in the taste and a gentle hint of lemony gueuze-like sourness . lovely and complex . still ca n't get over the nose .  m : nice medium body with a light carbonation , perfect for a geuze .
great smell , but the taste was a little lacking for me .  mouthfeel is where this beer delights ! so smooth and round , you want to swirl it around in your mouth ! mmmm .

served from the bottle into a nonic glass a- poured a very clear lighter amber color with a two finger soapy head s- huge aroma of cinnamon , ginger , citrus , and floral notes . this smells like christmas at home t- big on the cinnamon , ginger , citrus and honey notes , great balance among those flavors . a beer i look forward to every winter . very good out of the bottle , even better on tap .  exceptional body .

s - freshly cut strawberries , rye , malts and hops . very balanced . t - at first the malt is there and rye hops in but is then the first part of the taste is finished off with the malts .  i love the creamy texture and the suprising full body .

the smell is rich and malty , almost boozy even , with warm notes of caramel and roasted malts . smells like it 's on the verge of being a doppelbock really . the taste is less complex ... the roasted malts dominate big time . a little disappointing after the look and smell of it .  excellent texture with refined carbonation that leads to a pleasant creaminess .

among the best coffee scents i 've ever experienced . an incredibly appealing aroma . pretty strong as well . a lovely coffee porter all around . not as tailored to it as it could be , but all around very complementary .  m-this is full bodied , extremely smooth , very inviting on the palate , it is quite creamy and carbonated just right .

a-orange/amber ... leaves a nice lace on glass as i drink s-great aroma ... tons of toasted malts ... also some candied toffee ... i guess that is what toffee is : ) ... some caramel notes too ... very sweet aroma and a fresh hoppiness complements perfectly ... great smelling beer . t-where the nose is malt forward , the taste is more balanced ... some good hopping to this ... a citrus like grapefruit rind bitterness is evident..but it mingles nicely with the great malt backbone.. m-medium bodied ... .seems sessionable but still loaded with flavor .  m - creamy mouthfeel ; very smooth and full d - this was a pretty solid brew from schlafly .
smells nicely of coffee and cream in the first sniff .  mouthfeel is crazy ! amazing .
smell is domainated by a tart raspberry balanced by a sweet mocha coffee bitterness . very bold aromas linger in the back of the nose .  mouthfeel is full , thick , smooth , perfectly carbonated .

aromatic nose of concentrated orange juice and cloves . more orange notes , soft mouthfeel , taste fades in the finish , worth a try , but nothing great , there are better and more interesting christmas brews and saisons out there  m : you tell this is a big beer just by the feel , it 's almost like i 'm chewing it with each sip . the carbonation is right on as well and finish has a touch of dryness ... perfect for a dipa .

delicious ! raisins and coffee ... apparently i poured this waay too cold ... first sip is a slap of roasted bitterness and nothing else , almost astringently ... just ... never mind . much better as she warms . yeah , as it warms some chocolate notes start showing up in the nose , and the flavor mellows out and gets a bit of a mocha hint to it ... but it 's not big enough , the bitterness is still sharp , not as smooth or well-rounded as i would like .  perfect carbonation .

smell : wow . loads of anise , port , dark chocolate , espresso , cabernet sauvignon , and raisins . awesome . taste : alas , my nose seems to have misled my tongue . overall , fairly acrid and not very good . mouthfeel : flat carbonation and surprisingly thin body . but from this experience ... i can not recommend it , no matter how pleasant the aroma .  mouthfeel - super smooth and silky . low carbonation and a big body .

very strong hoppy aroma , fresh smelling .  m & d : perfect carbonation make the mouthfeel nice , but the alcohol limits the drinkability of this beer ... not that i could n't easily drink a few of these in one session ( if only ! ) reccomended !

lovely . a hint of sweet fruity esters finishes the nose . i like this . d - the beer is pleasing , inviting , and tasty , but that alcohol , ohan that alcohol in the finish ... please go away .  light , non-overwhelming aftertaste which i like , combined with a perfect amount of carbonation .
sweet nose of gingerbread , with faint roasted tones as well .  the mouth feel is beautiful . covers every square inch with a silky sheet and balances it out with a good dose of carbonation .

the color is a yellowish orange with a deep orange heart smell : very strong hop aroma punches you in the fast . its satisfyingly violent enough to a hop-head , but there is a delicate mixture of malty-sweetness .  perfect creamy texture and good body and carbonation .

s - hops , hops , hops , citrus , grapefruit , sweet orange , and a hint of pine . some slight caramel sweetness might be coming through , though that could just be the vast amount of hops playing tricks on me . malt is well balanced . sweet caramel malts balance out the bitter middle .  the mouthfeel is stupendous . rinsing this around the mouth gives a great tingling sensation that beckons more swishing about each swollow .

aromas are malty and almost burnt , with some graham cracker and chocolate in the nose . a very complex bouquet , with each sniff yielding new aromas and smells .  taste : very smooth , lemon must , dried grass , herbal , mild barnyard funk , slightly tart , earthy , bone dry . very drinkable as the tartness does not overstep the rest of the beer . bottle conditioning proves to give the brew ample smoothness . funk is modest and unfolds a bit more when the liquid warms up . a great geuze that wo n't kill you palate , a remarkable beer .

s - `` floral hops a ' go-go '' = big hope presence complemented by nice floral overtones and a touch of lemon t - hops with a breaded malt fullness .  mouthfeel is rich , smooth , and silky . soft carbonation .

aroma positively bursts with tropical fruit : pineapple , mango , papaya , sugarcane , apricot . it 's a hophead 's delight , and i am reveling in it . the flavor announces that the hops have taken over , and my tastebuds welcome the coming apocalypse . big , juicy hop cones spray sap and resin across the palate , palpable in their greenery but not overwhelmingly bitter . the fruitiness is not lost either , as it accentuates a slick backdrop of caramel & toffee malts . this may well be one of my new favorite double ipa 's .  m : surprisingly light and smooth . excellent for style .

it 's actually an amazing nose ... difficult to place , but it is delicious and entices good feelings of things to come .  indulgent , creamy mouthfeel . and i really ca n't get over how pleasurable the mouthfeel is .

seriously , filter your beer guys ... s : the nose is the best part of this beer . loads of floral/citrusy hops that is very reminicent of nugget nectar . if they would reduce the bittering hops and increase either the malt or citrus hops this would be great . m : the feel is nice and creamy with great carbonation . pretty good if you like your ambers hoppy .  mouthfeel is perfection , smooth , crisp , with just the right amount of carbonation ... and the tartness in the finish leaves you wanting to pour more of that big bottle .
smell - very fruity and sweet . raisins , cherries , and honey . delicious ... smells like dessert .  marvelous mouthfeel , so smooth , full bodied and mouth coating .

appearance : mahogany red with a thick beige head smell : fresh wet hop aroma abounds while red malts provide a great smelling basis . flavor : very hoppy and bittersweet , without the complexity provided by floral hop flavors .  mouthfeel : very smooth body , easy to drink . nicely carbonated .

very nice clean , fresh aroma of freh blackberries , yeast , and crisp wheat as well as a touch of orange peel . the taste is n't nearly so clean and fresh and vibrant as the aroma , but still , better than expected and not at all artificial tasting . probably lighter in flavor than it should be , and heavy on coriander and a bit seedy .  mouthfeel is superb , creamy , velvety , perhaps the best i 've had for this style .

very powerful and interesting . taste : a lot like bourbon at first , but a quarter of the way through it started to develop some grape-like flavors which made it more like brandy , or like it was aged in a red wine barrel .  mouthfeel medium-full body with creamy carbonation . i am really impressed with the body on this beer .

a- red brown body with an airy off-white head s- spices and fruit , very inviting ! sweet delicate fruit t- spices , bready malts , more sweet spices , alcohol warming m- medium-bodied , good carbonation and alcohol warming d- that nose is great ! a nice beer and the high abv makes it a sipping beer  very creamy mouthfeel for a hefe , which i enjoy .

the brew was only half way to my nose when i caught a big whiff of pungent and fruity centennial hops reminiscent of apricots . like spotting a beautiful girl from behind , only to have the fantasy ruined as she turns around to reveal her ugly face , the taste of the centennial ipa was a huge disappointment .  m- full bodied , creamy , thick luscious mouthfeel .
s - wonderful citrus hops .  rich , full , thick , round mouthfeel , with a soft carbonation that is really terrific .

aromas of tangerine , grapefruit , melon , tropical fruit , some floral aromatics , a bit of bready malt , and some belgian yeastiness .  good moderate carbonation and a crisp , dryish , oily slick , chewy , creamy smooth full bodied mouthfeel .

it had a great malty , smoky aroma . with a hint of fruit , apples plum , dates .  smells great , coffee and chocolate notes right up front chocolate & coffee flavors , dry and bittering at the end mouthfeel is very smooth . much smoother than i remember when i had it last .

appearance : pitch black with low head retention smell : hughmugus creamy caramel aroma . amazing ... roasted malt , subtle coffee/chocolate , taste : tastes liek it smells and reaslly does capture creme brulee .  taste is also quite yeasty , lemon zest as well , the carbonation is bubbly and soft , not harsh , incredibly creamy and smooth for a hefeweizen .
aroma is delicious , dark fruits , caramel , bread , a mild grassy hoppiness .  mouthfeel is exactly what it should be for this style .
d - after the really nice aroma , i expected more from this one .  m : great silky smooth feel . definitely a creamy feel .

s : w ... .t ... .f. this does not smell like beer , and nor does it smell like creme brulee exactly , but it does smell amazing . gigantic aromas of vanilla , butterscotch , and candy corn absolutely radiate from the glass , providing the most incredibly sweet and candied smell i 've ever experienced from a liquid , much less a beer . this is insane , and i 'm pretty sure that 's what they were going for . t : it 's still insane , but less in a fun willy wonka way than a terrifying clown sort of way : horrifically sweet , to the point of being heart-stopping .  fantastic ! d - i could easily reach for another .
enticing aroma , with fresh fruit and piny hops dominating . overall , a decent pale ale by an up-and-coming austin brewery .  m : a perfect 5 in mouthfeel ... and i feel strongly about that !

nice malty aroma with a healthy dose of roastiness - chocolate , espresso , and caramel . simple , straightforward , and tasty . light in body - silky smooth , crisp and a bit thin .  m - super smooth and creamy . i rate this exceptional compared to some of the other tripels i have had - it is surely the strongest aspect of this beer .
4.0 s : the nose on this beer is really nice . its a great looking and great smelling beer . however , the taste and mouthfeel come up short .  mouthfeel is very nice , i enjoyed it a lot .

s - one of the few beers that i think smells better than it actually tastes , haha . huge sweet flavors of raisins , sweet esters , plums , candied dates , and a faint alcohol aroma in the background .  m/d - full bodied and very creamy . lively carbonation carries the beer through your mouth .

s - smooth bourbon , with loads of vanilla and oak . t - malty and sweet , with just a little too much bourbon for my tastes . m - very nice on the tongue , with just the right amount of carbonation ( after it was all released on opening ) . d - it 's a great , well put together , complex beer , but it almost seems futile to rate the drinkability of such a rare beer .  mickey 's ice has an amazing mouthfeel to it , one of the best in my opinion . the carbonation comes on strong then fades to a creaminess .

it looked very appetizing . it even smelled very hoppy and full of citrus .  mf - this it where this beer shines the most to me . very nice carbonation that tickles your mouth as you savor it . also reminds me in some ways of an eisbock albeit less vinuous and more carbonated and roasty .
really nice intense aroma with piney hops , citrus , sweet malts , and brown sugar .  m : close to perfect : rich , thick and creamy .

pleasantly fragrant . slightly bready with some fruitiness and hop bitterness in the afteraste . taste does n't quite live up to the aroma , but it 's very drinkable .  body is creamy and rich , with mild carbonation , pretty strong abv , but alcohol is not dominant in the taste i enjoyed this beer the more i drank , very impressed .

estimated at 200 c purchased at : super saver pennington , nj for $ 3.00 aroma : amazing , chocolate , syrup , heather . visuals : beautiful design , deep brown , mostly opaque , thin white head , little lace . overall : a real disappointment , more of a brown ale than an imperial stout , not a repeat , not a favorite , little value , medium craft .  perfect mouthfeel for an ipa.. substatial , chewy but not syrupy.. drinkable but nowhere near being called 'light ' .

an explosive aroma , soft fruity notes ( the likes of peach , apricot ) coated with light funky notes ( as result of the wild yeast ) that blends for an almost cider like complex . steady streams of bubbles rise . i fell in love with the aroma . the taste is n't as effervescent ( or impressive for that matter ) . fairly void of spice and not as `` fresh '' as the aroma would have you assume . a little flat and really quite dependent on a boring malt bill .  a nice , balanced beer with a clean taste and a smooth , exceptional mouthfeel .
the aroma is delightful - by far the best part about this beer . i love dfh products so i finished it for them .  the mouthfeel is fantastic if you sip and swish ever so gently .

smell is incredible , bright and pungent , resiny , sweet citrusy cascades , yummy ! taste is a bit of a letdown after the incredible smell , still hoppy , but not as pungent , much rounder , with a hefty dose of toasted malt . still , a huge improvement over regular mirror pond for sure ! drinkability is good , much better then regular mirror pond , but if the taste kept up with the smell , it would have been great . of the three deschutes fresh hop ales i 've had this year , i 'd rank this second , behind goshie 's and ahead of harvest moon .  mouthfeel - superbly smooth and creamy , especially due to the carbonation . overall drinkability - this beer is all about the smoothness of the mouthfeel , and inoffensive characters .
s - smokey , mesquite , coffee . it is one of the most unique beers i 've been lucky enought to sample .  palate : full bodied and medium carbonation . great feel . full bodied and enjoyable .

it has a great smell of banana , clove , and dark/caramel in the background . overall a nice beer , but nothing like many small brewery belgians . it 's nice you can find it most places and a great alternative for any occasion .  mouthfeel is dead perfect for the style , full and solid .
an interesting smell for sure .  thick , syrupy and silky smooth with just enough carbonation to tickle the tongue . goes down so easily - incredibly smooth .
sense of some bitterness , but this smells really good and inviting .  : ) silkly smooth mouthfeel ! awesome .
overall , this is a very good beer with an unbelievable chocolate smell and taste .  the mouthfeel is unbeatable . it is almost chewy and just enough carbonation .

the aroma is really fantastic . i love the floral sweetness , the citrus , all so bright and fresh , with out being heavy-handed .  mouthfeel : this is where it shines . smooth and heavy and very warming .
fabulous , fruity , bready , almost hefeweizen nose . great stuff . pour is equally good , up there with the best tripels . yuck .  mouth is light-medium bodied excellent carbonation .

the smell is fantastic , berries , flowers , a little bit of grass , very sweet .  the beer sits in your mouth with a crisp , well-rounded feel and swallows with a tingly freshness that is quite delightful . the taste is a tad leathery ( this is a positive thing ) and the crisp dryness is not overbearing .

aroma is smokey malts with a beechwood or bologna smell to it . slight hops are found in there as well with a slight sugary caramel ; pretty complex ! taste is rather smokey and sweet ; it reminds me of deer jerky or sweet bologna really .  the mouthfeel was exceptional , heavy bodied with a warming alcohol presence .
nose is amazing and if i didnt know better i would have thought it was a barrel aged beer . i was really excited by the nose .  mouthfeel is so silky .

very good head retention & above average lacing s : dark chocolate , faint smokeyness , raisins & plums t : dark chocolate , charred malt , some leafy hops & a bit of coffee tinged booze up front .  mouthfeel is also top notch . low carbonation that goes down very smooth .

strangely enough the combination works to produce a pleasing aroma that is lactic with sour grape notes through the back . this brew smelled awesome but fell a bit short in the flavor .  m- exceptional swirl inside your mouth , allows the flavor to be enjoyed even more .

awesome aroma . pours a cloudy dark orange color , some nice head with decent retention . very smooth- from the smell , i was actually expecting a more pronounced hop flavor here , but regardless , this is an excellent ipa . mouthfeel- appropriate carbonation , buttery , clean . drinkability- i could drink this one all day .  m : mouthfeel is fantastic . very creamy with just the right amount of carbonation .
it has a strong aroma of roasted malts , coffee and lots of semi-sweet chocolate . the hops are very bold , but not quite over the top .  mouthfeel was exceedingly smooth .

as a proponent of doug fir tips , spruce tips , etc . on tap at the midnight sun house , it is a deep dark brown , nearly black , with plenty of roast and spruce tips blazing through . it is definitely a bit astringent , and i ca n't be sure if that is from the roast or from the spruce , but nonetheless , a very tasty brew .  the medium - heavy mouthfeel is perfect for this type of beer .
fantastic overwhelming aroma .  overall = exceptional mouthfeel but the taste is just average .

perky roast and a mega bar of milk chocolate make a creamy , full nose . subtle fresh brewed coffee and tootsie roll are also nice . that milk chocolate stays up front with an immediate hit of diner coffee .  m : full bodied with an awesome carbonation feel .

beautiful nose t - great complex flavor comprising smoked meats , dark fruits and apples and various barrels .  mouth feel was exceptional , with a naturally carbonated soft bubble feel on the tongue . not to strong on the hop flavor department but the mouth feel is exceptional .

smell is rich with sweet sugary notes , vanilla , coffee , roasted malt , chocolate , burnt sugar , very nice to smell . taste is malty and roasted , lightly astringent , light sour lactic like notes , some bitterness comes out , mild vanilla and chocolate , some coffee , this was pleasant at times and at times a little on the bad side .  the carbonation is spot on , it carries the beer extremely well on the palette . this drinks like a slightly hopped up brit but not so much to kill you with hops .

this stout pours a dark black with a light tan head ... not as frothy as most stouts i have had . the smells are definitely different as aside from the coffee and chocolate one can sense a bit of vanilla and banana .  silky smooth and creamy mouth feel . such body without being cloying .
aroma is a very nice mix of scents . sweet pears , apples and plums mix perfectly with citrusy and piney hops . quite a nice brew that i recommend to all barleywine fans out there .  superb feel .

smells phenomenal . funk and very tart cherries . still , a nice beer and i 'd have to imagine it would be much better with any semblance of carbonation .  the piney hops dominate the flavor , but a snappy finish makes it 's hard to gripe too much . exceptionally well balanced . in spite of the bold hops , it drinks with amazing ease .

nose is a wonderful candied smell , combining apricot and rose in what is the best smelling ipa to date for me .  exceptionally viscous and savory body starts creamy and full on the tongue , developing a wheaty wetness and light carbonation , ends dry .

pretty good stuff .  pours a rich crimson color with a creamy off white head that stays put thru out the duration of drinking it , deep caramel aromas along with some milk chocolate quite sweet.absolutely sublime creamy mouthfeel just glides down smooth , flavors of caramel and brown suger hit ya up front but there is a decent dryness midway keeping it from getting to sweet.i wouldnt say earthy maybey more herbal in the finish , its quite heavy a one or two and done for me.this is a doozy a great winter beer , it would real warm ya up , not that i need that down here in nc .
d - nice appearance and great smells led to a slightly disappointing taste .  m - the feel is surprisingly rich for the genre , smooth and oh so drinkable , nicely done !

outstanding . t : really a letdown after such an intense aroma . coming out of the bottle this looks and smells great , it just does n't deliver on the flavor .  first thing i notice when drinking it is the fabulous mouthfeel - so soft and creamy yet a rather thin body .
again , wow . fantastic .  perfect carbonation , sits in the mouth just right , a touch of oiliness , slightly drying in the end , and all around wonderful .
very unique nose . slightly bready as well .  mouthfeel is wonderfully thick .

smell is of dark fruits , raisin , sweetness , a little bit of coffee .  mouthfeel is perfect , thick and creamy but not too syrupy , and with none of that trub you sometimes get in the bottle , maybe im just not used to drinking from a tap .

rich aromas of burnt sugar , curacao orange and raisins , but a thinner body , less malt and hop bitterness than it should have had .  the mouthfeel fits this beauty of a beer - it is thick and pleasingly rich . the full amount of suggested aging did this beauty wonders .

this one smells amazing , there are hints of lemon lime , apple peel , sourness , a hint of woodsy pine , fruity , yeast twang , and a nice blast of sage . the sage smells very fragrant and perfumey . the body is smooth but well-carbonated , in fact some pretty exceptional mouthfeel overall .  perfect carbonation .
smell is fragrant and wonderful like fragrant burnt sugar with hints of orange . mouthfeel is pretty smooth , very nice .  mouthfeel is perfect .
the smell is fruity . i notice cherries , apples , plums , maybe oranges .  perfect bitterness and carbonation . exceptional .

s-smells like very fresh and grassy hops . the grassiness is more fresh and spicy than stale like some hops tend to be .  m - perfect texture , it seems somewhat oily and it slides over your tongue like a sweet hop blanket .

big , woody , bourbon notes come off this thing . it 's a big aroma , but it 's not offensive . it 's medium , but with the great aroma and solid taste , it really would have rounded this out nicely with a more chewy feel .  mouthfeel : nice creamy thick body drinks exceptionally well ! drinkability : the abv and the flavor profile holds this one back for me but the mouthfeel helps in the drinkability department .

interesting . mouthfeel is light-medium bodied , silky-slick with a fair amount of soft carbonation . overall a fantastic looking and smelling ale . i ca n't remember a beer with so much to offer in the color and scent , and then practically bottoming-out when it hits your tongue . the flavor is there and gone in an instant , very strange .  the mouthfeel on this beer is really creamy and smooth ( it has this milk-shake texture to it ) with medium to high carbonation and moderate to heavy body . although it lacks a little complexity of the usual coffee , oak and vanilla notes , it makes up in mouthfeel and drinkability .

nose is full of spices - pepper , clove and corriander , wheats , and nice softer orange hint .  carbonation is moderate with a medium-full body yet still decent drinkability . the one thing that really stands out with this fest is its remarkable smoothness , definitely the smoothest octoberfest ive had .

one of the best smelling beers i can remember . those citra hops really bring it on the nose . tons of tropical fruits . just great stuff . taste- follows the nose . it 's downright tart . however , it gets a little muddled . i had one and really wanted another . this is a very good beer .  much lighter body than the bottle of extra stout i just had ; also a little more tart which was what i was looking for . roasted malts and hard water . mouthfeel is where it really shines . smooth like silk . goes down like water .

very nice , actually ... my mouth is watering . the very beginning of the taste is good , but that first sweetroastiness is eclipsed by a strong bitterness and waxing dryness that detract from the experience such a good smell . man .  m : quite thick moderate carbonation , love it .
very nice . the taste is lighter and more astringent .  body is big and very creamy and smooth . mouthfeel of melted velvet .
the nose actually smells rich . buttery , molasses , melted milk chocolate and roasted malts are all present .  goes down incredibly easy with a silky mouthfeel .

smells like citrus . reminds me of summer and we 're in the middle of a grey november day , so that 's nice . smooth , well-balanced taste , but perhaps a touch too bubbly .  generously carbonated feel . goes down like nothing .

incredibly complex , balanced , and appealing .  head retention is poor , almost non-existent , a little dissapointing smell is not what i was expecting , surpisingly subtle , with a nice malty sweetness taste comes as a wave , roastiness , coffee like , followed by mellow sweet malt , bitterness like dark chocolate lingers in the mouth , pleasant after taste wonderfully full mouthfeel , thick , fits the beer 's complex flavor the alcohol is apparent , but not overpowering , easy to sip , not exactly quaffable , but pleasant

the nose of this beer is all about hops ; lemon-peel , orange pith , grapefruit meat . also has a green after-image , chlorophyll , and just the faintest suggestion of caramel malts . fireball hop belches . the more i drink local and regional ipas the more i realize how good i 've got it . ipa is a difficult style to hit ; make it too malty and you 've upset hopheads , make it too hoppy and you 're drinking acid hop-tea .  m : this is one of the thickest stouts i 've had in a while - very similar to dark lord in it 's heavy , cream like thickness that coats the mouth very well . d : good drinkability , but it 's definitely a sipper .

a - poured into a squatters ipa glass , it had a deep pruney appearance , big nice-looking head for a doppelbock . s - big and raisin-y , cinnamon-sugar , like a pastry at a bakery . t - raisins encrusted with sugar , this was a sweet brew - too sweet to my palate , i could not find anything to dry it out .  m - perfect . perfect for an imperial stout .
s - wow . aging has done it well . some slight sweetness but still with a pretty hefty burn .  mouthfeel- super creamy , lower carbonation and silky smooth .

s - strong , spicy , phenolic aroma with notes of cinnamon , nutmeg , and clove . there is a spicy yeast note in the background that supports the spices nicely . t - lots of malt with toasted notes and a bit of toffee . not surprisingly , the aroma is the strong point ; the yeast and spices compliment each other nicely .  m - perfection - just enough hint of carbonation to tickle the tongue .

very sticky and malty nose , lots of sugar , blueberry , and fig .  m - slick and warm on the palate with an oily texture and chewy mouthfeel . this stuff glides down the throat with ease . d - this brew is exceptionally smooth and creamy , making it extremely easy to drink .

good lacing and below average head retention smell : intense fruitcake/christmas pudding aroma taste : caramel , frutiness , & toasted malt . slight bitterness as it warms . slightly sweet finish mf : good carbonation but oscillates between hints of thin and astringent to me drinkable , but just did n't pull together the way i know this ale can ( on cask ) , i 'm sure the clear bottle ai n't helping the cause ...  f - medium/full bodied beer that 's creamy smooth for sipping .

this brew has a hefty hop character ... maybe even over done , but i happen to like it ; pine more than citrus . the hops are more pronounced in the odor than in the flavor but it is strong all around . the socks may come in somewhere with the malts ... not too sure ... a solid all around ipa , if a bit on the abrasive side .  the mouthfeel is great , perfectly coating .

nose is immediately notable , fruity and , sweet while also reminding me of flemish sours . also reminds me of this brewery 's product , zoetzuur .  magnificent . drinkability is only average , as this is one once in awhile brew , not intended for or enjoyable on a regular basis .

more precisely , it smells like my french press when grounds have been in there for a day or two -- very bittter , very impressive . taste is candy-sweet , and heavily rosted , like ingredients have been roasted repeatedly .  mouthfeel is phenomenal for a regular ipa . thick like a dipa , and very smoothly carbonated .
the smell really got me excited for trying this , but the flavour is lacking a pumpkin finish . the pumpkin and cinnamon fad almost instantly .  one hell of a mouthfeel with this beer .

s : very chocolatey , pleasant nut , cotton-candy esters , dark caramel , herbs & a hint of citrus . d : very good , but a little big to session .  mouthfeel is exceptional . perfect amount of carbonation and such a smooth beer going down .

s - the single best part of this beer an explosion of belgium candies , rich dark fruits , fresh cut lemons , and just a tiny bit of alcohol in the nose . starts off with a bit of bittering lemon , then some raisin and cherries and finish 's off with an extreme bit of belgium candied sugars that is stellar at first but second pour makes it cloying and boring . m - to me it was a medium bodied triple with hardcore abv .  it 's mild to medium body with the really great mouthfeel makes me want to swish the beer around my mouth before swallowing .

the aroma is amazing ! it was hard to pull my nose away from this one . the whole hop gamut fills my olefactory senses . huge hoppy beer . it 's a damn good beer .  the mouthfeel is where this beer really shines and seperates itself from the pack .

s - lots of fresh floral and pine hop notes , with an interesting woody backing .  the mouthfeel is medium bodied with appropriately low carbonation , and a silky , creamy texture . the mouthfeel of this beer is one of the best i have encountered in a beer .
s - nice smell , quite sweet , herbal and perfumy , some notes of chocolate . good point : i can not smell the alcohol !  the mouthfeel was great . very smooth , thick , and rich .

s- incredibly deep and complex nose . i could just sit here and sniff this for hours . absolutely incredible . t- an incredibly sweet replicate of the nose with some substantial ( but unoffensive ) warming booziness midway and through the finish .  the mouthfeel on this beer was truly exceptional . i 've never had a beer with such great viscosity that managed to avoid being sticky .

a - dark cherry red , some light getting through , little head , a few tiny carb streams , loose lacing s - black licorice , chewy root beer candy , unsweetened bubble gum , tart dry cherries , anise , strong alcohol t - dark toasted pumpernickel , raisins , dried figs , dark cherries , almost too-dark toffee , alcohol m - medium to medium heavy in body , lots of alcohol warmth . i have a feeling that a fresh tasting would not even compare to a vintage tasting . i imagine that the strong alcohol aroma , flavors and warmth will mellow over time letting all these earthy fruity aromas and flavors come to the foreground .  throughout , the carbonation is perfect -- not too much , not too little , just right , and the overall mouthfeel is full , creamy , and well rounded .

smells of passionfruit , peaches , apricots and strawberries in no particular order . smooth mouthfeel , very light , this is highly drinkable if you like the sweet stuff .  the feel is right on for the style .
the smell is great - hoppy with a hint of sweetness and grapefruit .  mouthfeel : medium to full bodied and incredibly smooth . just a hint of carbonation tingle .
bananas , cardimon , cinamon , dry ripened plums , maybe some cherries . an outstanding beer . nice lacing down the tulip .  the mouthfeel is incredible for a red ale , just so thick and smooth .
smell is pure smoke . very nice mouthfeel , not thick , but substantial . overall really good if you can get it and love pork .  gorgeous mouthfeel .

aroma - i get at first a strong raspberry scent , some caramel and raisin , toffee , and even some vanilla scents all through and well balanced , and get some oak with some alcohol coming through .  mouthfeel is crazy smooth and thick .
smells wonderfully of grapes . very appealing .  mouthfeel : full-bodied . medium carbonation . very soft and velvety on the tongue , like the texture of melted chocolate ice cream .

the nose of this beer is outstanding ... very sweet pumpkin and spice . nevertheless a decent oktoberfest . good beer good season .  m : i have to say that this was the most impressive aspect of this beer . oftentimes porters end up a little too thin-bodied , but this one had a very full body , and combined with the very nice carbonation made this a pleasure to drink .
absolutely beautiful . t : chocolate flavor is more subdued than the nose , but still a major influence .  creamy , smooth mouthfeel goes excellent with the flavor profile .
i know that is n't in it , but that is the cool smell i 'm getting ... at least tonight .  mouthfeel was silky smooth with a mild bitterness on the tongue .
it has a very inviting aroma . taste : the flavor is more bitter than i was expecting from the aroma .  m : the carbonation is gentle , making for a perfect silky , but thick , body .

aroma : fresh , fruity ( like peaches or apricots ) , and caramel , but a presence of tartness . comments : a very dynamic beer .  mouthfeel is a regal velvet ( likely due to the oatmeal ) , coating the mouth with a smooth creamy layer . so smooth . excellent .

i love the aroma of this beer ! just a hint of diacetyl butteriness , but i really did n't find it objectionable . mouthfeel is surprisingly thin , with some grapeskin-like astringency on the finish . drinkability is very good . a 22 oz .  m - very full bodied , nearly stout full .

nice american hop aromas , some pine and grapefruit some sweetness . this is a little too much for me , i prefer the regular and less bitter arrogant bastard ale .  m - beautiful mouthfeel and impressive balance for such a powerful brew .

sweet citrus , fresh sliced oranges and tangerines hit the nose in the initial blast . later on it becomes more `` green '' and herbal , still extremely resiny and pungent . best belgian ipa i 've ever smelled ... though this one has a decidedly american slant .  mouthfeel is phenomenal , like liquid velvet down the throat , and with a good bit of carbonation to tingle the tongue .

the aroma is relatively strong delivering a ton of vanilla on the nose with a finish that provides some nice depth with oak dominating followed by some distinct bourbon flavor .  the best part . smooth as butter , no alcohol detected . fantastic beer , the barrel aged version i 'm sure is outstanding .
s : slightly roasted , definitely chocolate aromas . after a pleasant start to the nose , this body is a bit disappointing .  m : awesome , aside from the hops , it may be the best part of the beer .

tasted may 18th 2011 ( from notes ) poured into a la chouffe tulip a - pale amber , three finger white head and some serious lacing s - oily , alcohol , hops , hops and more hops ! sweet fruit , earthy flowers , sugar , yeast , sweet malts and awesomeness t - super hoppy !  almost like adding a slice of lemon to water . mouthfeel is rich and luscious . this is really an enjoyable beer .

it 's beautiful . the taste is n't quite as funky , but it 's still good .  m & t - first impression was really just the perfect carbonation , great frothy and fluffy mouthfeel and just all around benefit to the palate . very nice , but the mouthfeel was absolutly pefect .
the aroma is great , and the beer is a decent ipa , however i think their yeast detracts a little from the nice hoppiness expected from a traditional ipa .  mouthfeel is very luxurious and pleasant .
nothing nearly so exotic , though . smell was also similar , sharp and spicy , cloves and nutmeg .  m : the mouthfeel is well balanced .

nice milky caramel nose with hints of roasted malts and vanilla . hoppy , light body does n't feel watery but does n't match atypical barleywine profile .  very nice d - i would drink this all night if i could , but at 11.5 % , that is n't exactly possible .

s- the nose on this brew is reminiscent of orange marmalade . it also exhibits some sweet vinous notes , and some citrus hop aroma . further examination reveals a touch of honey playing-around in the background ... t- wow !  the mouthfeel was amazing , drinking the beer it had the typical bite of aftertaste that normal ipas have , but i took a drink right when we left the pub and i still could taste the hops about twenty minutes later .
a very nice mixture of the woody hop aroma with a sweet malty background .  mild carbonation , super creamy body , smooth .
nice .  superb . d - this is a tasty beer , but the fusel alcohol character and high alcohol in general make me appreciate it less fully .

this beer smells absolutely amazing once the cap is off . it pours a nice dark stout body , with a nice tan head . the first sip of this beer is really overtaken by the aroma . definitely serving it at 42 like described is a good idea .  the mouthfeel is wonderful . thick and almost chewy but with enough smooth , creamy carbonation to keep it from seeming too syrupy .

a - i love pouring stouts and porters . either way , it 's friggin dark . i love the smell of coffee , but besides that , there are smoky notes , and something mellow in there like warm cream . t - love it . definite coffee ( obviously ) , but also a little of a hoppy twang , and a zip of charcoal . d - i loved this beer , but i would n't drink to many .  m - the feel is as smooth as i 've ever had . unbelievably impressive ! the feel of this beer is really what sets it apart from every other dubbel i 've ever sampled .

very hoppy when taking a nice whiff ( cascade mostly ) w/ bright citrussy aromas ( grapefruit ) and a distinct grainy malt that reminded me of dry cheerios . also a slightly sweet sugary maltiness creeps through as well making this seem very interesting . taking the first sip , the hops comes through with a vengence .  m : mouthfeel is awesome ! slick , heavy and chewy . it gets fluffier and chewier as i swirl it in my mouth .

aroma of hops , spice , coriander , lemon , and some grapefruit . although for being a wheat beer this is somewhat of the mark but for an interpretation this is excellent . citrus overtones , with few hints of bread . overall this is great .  and the hops are well placed and enjoyable m- probably the best thing about this beer almost chewy , think , and creamy , with a long lasting bitterness d- very nice balanced easy drinking dipa , a little different than ones ive had lately , not an over the top hop attack that hides some of the flavors .

smell : very strong . alcohol up front with nice raisins and molassas and a bit of sweetness .  gentile mix of flavors , not super complex , but with an incredible silky mouthfeel , and an oragne glow that makes it look great .
beautiful smelling brew , strong hoppy aroma , relatively fresh - considering the journey across half the world .  love the feel in my mouth .

very unique aroma for an amber . extremely sessionable and unique ale but the nose leads you to believe it may be more complex than it ends up being .  mouthfeel : wow is this stuff smooth . very silky and perfect carbonation .
i really like the nose on this .  the mouthfeel is excelent on this one though , very smoothe and crisp and very drinkable .

the smell is excellent : rich barley malt , a bit fruity , honey sweetness , with noticeable alcohol underneath .  mouthfeel is great , really silky and smooth , perfect carbonation , very dry and a nice warming sensation .

laces well very nice pine and citrus hop aroma slight malt very nice the taste is bitter upfront and throughout the carbonation starts upfront and dissipates i would like this more if it was n't just bitter hop flavor there is n't a full hop profile i 've come to like in my ipas .  insane drinkability ; perfect body , perfect bitter/sweet balance , and did n't even seem alcoholic .

the aroma is full of spices and reminds me of a hearty , spicy carrot cake . overall , the spices are tasty and are a nice blend , they just went too far in the quantity they added to the beer .  the mouthfeel really shines here , it 's bright and crisp and creamy . good body .

oh , such a nose - just luscious with huge quantities of the very finest american hops . it genuinely is an absolutely classic american ipa nose . to my mind , you ca n't get better than this . a sharp , but extremely well balanced ipa .  mouthfeel was perfect for me ... .slightly tingly , but at the same time silky smooth and gentle on the palate .

pours dark & amp ; thick , kinda like maple syrup ... had a creamy white head of small bubbles initially , but that dissipated quickly leaving just the black tar behind . the smell is very complex , like coffee one minute but also with strong hints of vanilla coming through . whatever is in there , it smells big , roasted , and dark !  m - thick and creamy , very full bodied . complemented by the right amount of carbonation .

nice enough ale to look at dark amber with a good sized pure white frothy head . beautiful spicy fresh hop aroma. , taste however is a wee bit subdued..but certainlly the hops rule this beer..i detect the 7.8 % alcohol..and theres a curious soapy taste at the back of the throat .  this is a big bodied , chewy brew with medium carbonation , and a full palate .
nice caramel and crystal malt smell with a touch of chocolate malt . nuttiness comes throughout .  m - mild carbonation precludes an incredibly smooth and delectably creamy body d - fantastic .

smell : the wheat creates a pleasant aroma that combines fruit characters with a slight spicy note from the light amount of hops . a lot of complete fruit smells are noticeable .  mouthfeel is smooth and fantastic as is the drinkability .
the aroma is still just about as good , with a nice hazelnut base along with some spices from the rum .  soft and very creamy feel , this is a dream to drink .

aroma of caramel , vanilla , nougat , butterscotch ( i guess this is aged in barrels ? ) and plenty of booze . kinda odd flavor . bit of a let-down from the aroma . again , a bit watery with very little carbonation .  mouthfeel : amazingly prickly carbonation after all this time -- a nice counterpoint to its velvety body .

beautiful aroma . taste is also excellent . bourbon , cherries , dark fruit , caramel sugar - but not overly sweet . not terribly complex , but delicious . mouthfeel is dissapointing .  very earthy and dry . notes : excellent balance , but a very mild smoke beer .

smells very enticing . really a sweet smelling beer , but smells very good . considering how great it smells , the taste can only be surprised as a major let down . it 's very strange .  m - smooth , a delicate sudsing that tickles the palatte , and quite refreshing with a subtle warming effect from the alcohol .

smell : smells of orange rind , a touch of grapefruit and pine as well . very aromatic for a wheat beer ... .much better than most pale ales out there as well .  luciously smooth and creamy in the mouth , soft carbonation across every cubic centimeter .

aroma is fantastic , this all centennail hopped ipa is heaven to wiff in . it does have a little bit of everything wood ; pulp , fresh leaves , green , not as resin filled as the smell leads one to believe , there 's a bit of a strange tang ensueing as it goes in . the smell is wonderful , but beyond that this would n't be one to continue with .  very full , creamy body that 's quite impressive for the abv .
s : great pure nose of lactic acid , direct and full . i also get a lot of lemon and some orange peel .  the mouthfeel is perfect . it is slightly carbed but still rather flat .

where was this aroma when i had this on draft ? tons of vanilla , toasted coconut and bourbon notes meld with lightly roasted/sweet caramel malt notes of maple . t-lusciously sweet maple , bourbon , vanilla and oak are strong up front . touch of wood astringency and lightly spicy hop notes help balance the sweetness out . founders strikes again with another masterful barrel aged brew , this brewery simply knows how to barrel age beer ... .period ! i thought it a dud on draft ( or maybe it was just me that day ) but out of the bottle ... shazaam !  pure velvet mouthfeel here , no better bock .

s : the nose is full of some of the best fruits ive ever smelled . this one smells amazing ! t : never had i have a beer that smelled so good taste so completely different . its good , but a definite letdown compared to the nose . o : fabulous nose , above average taste ( just barely ) , but a disappointing mouth .  mouthfeel/drinkability- the smooth , foaming mouthfeel is perfection for the style ... it swells and quiets to the point of not being able to discern bubbles at all .

strong dominant nose of super-tart raspberry and a mouthfeel and taste that followed suit . a nice beer to try , but it wouldnt be a regular for me .  m : silky and creamy . d : i 've never had more than one chocolate stout at a time , and so i do n't know if i would get sick of a beer if i overdid it .
wonderful smelling . it 's like holding a green apple blow pop up to your nose .  taste and mouthfeel : it 's incredible what the bourbon did to this beer . the mouthfeel is superbly creamy .
s : smells like a mocha latte from starbucks ; chocolate , coffee and a little bit of roast .  mouthfeel : medium body with tingly carbonation and a dry finish .

pour lets out a large , just off-white head head over a clear , tan body . excellent retention and lace . tons of carbonation makes this look like one refreshing , attractive lager .  mouthfeel is honestly fine , medium bodied , good carbonation .

from a 500 ml brown bottle . massive head development on the pour , a solid foamy mocha coloured entity with amazing retentio that settles very slowly . the body is deep pitch opaque black , faint almond nimbus when held to light .  a medium-light body with good carbonation . nice texture .

11.2 ounce bottle poured into pint glass two finger , tan head last thoughout the duration of the drink . mouthfeels is a bit thin and watery for a stout ... .just average . overall , this stout will do in a pinch , but not in my top 10 .  the mouthfeet was soft and light , and the overall beer was close to a cream ale , but without the cooked corn flavors .
a- pours a nice shade of black with a lovely brown head .  medium to full bodied and smooth .

this beer has a really attractive bottle design . it pours a luminescent orange color that isnt as hazy as other unibroue beers . the head is almond color and frothy , leaving massive lace as it recedes down the glass .  has a fairly refreshing clean finish , and nice body .
this light beer poured a clear , golden color with creamy , full , white foam that settled and clung to the glass well .  big mouthfeel .

this brew pours picture perfect with the nitro-style cascading foam as you poor , just like guiness . beer is a perfect amber with a thick creamy white head that does n't change or leave .  mouthfeel : lightly hop-oiled , ample carbonation , slightly chewy .
the smell is fantastic . it is fruity , chocolatey , toffee , tobacco , cocoa , raisin bread , apricot , plum , and pudding . it 's interesting .  the mouth is light and carbonated well .

this is a beautiful looking beer , it pours a dark brown with ruby highlites . 2 fingers of off white-tan colored head that takes forever to settle to a nice creamy looking film on top . gorgeous thick heavy lace left clinging to the glass .  m : medium bodied , relatively light on the carbonation . it feels like a nice fall drink .

smell : this is where this beer really shines in my opinion . loads of spices that dominate the nose . cinnamin , nutmeg , gloves , ginger and oddly pepper . highly disappointed on this one .  m - nice mouthfeel . does n't feel thin .

this beer pours a cloudy orange color , with a thick and fluffy white head , with a light yellow tint to it . the head fades very slowly , leaving a massive lace . this beer has a very grainy aroma to it .  mouthfeel is medium and appropriate .

this beer poured a brown a little deeper than cooper with a very nice stand of thick white head . too bad the rest of the beer was not up to the appearance . as nice as this amber 's appearance was , the mouthfeel was disappointing .  mouthfeel= good mouthfeel drinkability= average .

it 's now one of my favorites from rogue . appearance : pours a crytsal clear ruddy amber that becomes a light brilliant red when held to light . a three-finger high , rocky , off-white head forms on top and shrinks to a scattered arrangement of bubbles all across the surface of the beer .  it does have that nice slightly creamy mouthfeel that bitburger and a few other quality pils have .
the nose is unbelievable ! the best i have ever smelt .  the mouthfeel is nice and smooth and finishes clean .

no lacing but lots of oils and resinous hop juice and malt sludge . huge . very sweet and potent vanilla and oak . stings the nostrils . t/m : massive . simply massive . bourbon is massive . vanilla and woody oak is also massive with just a touch of syrupy cherry juice in the back .  ah well ... mouthfeel is fine - it 's not as heavily carbonated as originally thought ( from the head ) . smooth and even .
heavy cascading action as i watch being drawn off the tap . the head is thick and creamy .  medium , almost creamy mouthfeel with low carbonation .

the aroma is dry and roasty with a good mix of chocolate and coffee . lightly nutty also it smells quite inviting . the taste is a bit of a letdown though .  3.5 m quite beefed up by the hops presence and the malt which is welcomed .
s : perfect ! candy-sugared-bananas-and-pink-bubblegum-yumminess ! very nice .  the body is on par for the style and is nicely carbonated .
the aroma here is all hops . very fragrant . i smell lots of floral and earthy hops .  mouthfeel is pretty good but at this point who cares ?

real nice i must admit . pretty darn disappointing cause the nose is fantastic .  not knowing this was in the `` russian imperial stout '' style category , i was expecting more of an american stout , only with a little more body and alcohol . the texture changes over time as well : in the earliest stage , this one is thick and creamy , but it becomes lean at the finish . this and eel river 's triple exultation would be enough to satisfy the most discerning beer drinker 's palate for some time .

mississippi mud is a super clear deep crimson brown beer with a soft , foamy light khaki head that has outstanding retention and lacing .  the taste is bitter , more of the citrus but it just taste wrong or something , it 's not very pleasant and leaves this as a long , lingering after-effect , mouthfeel is medium and decently carbonated .

it started as sugary sweet , candied apples , a pleasant musty characteristic , and some spicy black pepper in the background .  the funky yeast just does n't quite meld with the hops . its very spicy on the finish as well , and it feels like the hops and the natural spiciness are fighting with each other for control of your palate . light and zesty on the palate in a good way .

there is an off white head , ok retention and lacing ... the aroma is pretty good but subdued ; nice grassy hop , a hint of oranges , light alcohol finish .  mouthfeel : medium-bodied with lots of carbonation and smooth .
s - nice aroma , deep and complex . smells of darkly roasted malts with espresso coffee , chocolate and molasses .  good on the mouthfeel , but rather one dimensional .
aroma characteristics are of orange peel , coriander , and quite peppery .  feel is good - creamy , medium bodied , well carbonated .
the aroma is phenomenal , pure and simple .  the feel is almost chewy and very dry .
on to the beer : it looks just like a duvel . outstanding head retention and lacing .  mouthfeel - light-medium body , well balanced carbonation .

wow , i 've never seen that cascading effect in a light colored beer , pretty neat . this brew was sort of a dark golden color with a thick creamy pure white head .  the palate is smooth . the aftertaste is absolutely repulsive .

i drank this from the bottle into my rochefort glass ... the beer is a cloudy very nice looking peachy orange with a watery head white head that is gone fast ... the aroma is super nice , very matly on the front with lots of orange and peaches and balanced ever so lightly on the finish with some grass and hops ... the taste is also very good , does n't quite live up to the aroma . there is some of sweet on the front not enough to really balance this beer .  it 's the opidomy of light , the smoothness of velvet , and the price of mexican dreams . degrading this beer comes at a great insult to anyone with a ba , mba , phd or techinical certificate for the lessor of us . i swear the old texts , properly translated , would describle jesus actually making water into natty . it 's constant . this beer is the appertif of beers .

12oz bottle poured into my de struise glass ... a dark brown body with a huge dark tan head that rises several fingers . there is incredible lacing and retention ... the aroma is very strong , as i wait for the head to fall fresh blueberries start to waif over rom a few feet away .  mouthfeel pretty good , medium carbonation and mouthfeel .

had on tap at creekhouse served in proper augustijn glass which makes for even more authentic experience ... an explosive floral bouquet candy balloons dropping on your tongue kind of taste experience that i 've never had prior to this . kind 've like a tripple with waaay more careful hop chemistry and fragrance . a very elegant beer that could be drunk like champagne is ... this is elite stuff for sure .  very clean finish and very easy to drink , it goes down very smoothly .
beautiful , light beige head that forms a long lasting peak . solidly four fingers thick .  carb level and mouth feel is actually quite pleasant , though .
poured a nice deep clean copper with a big white head , nice lacing , looks very good , hope its not all down hill from here .  m -- mouthfeel is soft to crisp with a light to light-medium body .

s - very nice smell on this beer . very nice and complex nose that covers a range of notes . i would have enjoyed a little more sour spice to complex it out and help finish the beer .  m : thick and heavy , but not cloying .

smell- nice aroma that strikes an excellent balance between malt and aroma hops . a nice sweet citrus aroma along with a very nice malt sweetness comes through the nose as well . taste- taste is not as nice as the smell , but it is still quite nice . it has a nice maltiness with a powerful jolt of bittering and flavoring hops ... for a belgian pale ale .  interestingly enough , the mouthfeel is rich and creamy -- what i wish so many other hoppy/piney beers could achieve .

smell was really , really nice . very hoppy , sweet , malty , citrus/floral/piney - everything mixed extremely well .  m. mouthfeel is where this brew plays it safe with a nice even carbonation and medium soft body .
the aroma was caramel and chocolate with a nutty component . another fruit present in the complex aroma was pineapple .  smooth and soft , mouthfeel alone is not bad at all .
a - pours nicely with two finger head and settles well .  m - spot on here . medium body , good carbonation .

smell is fantastic ; the brewery truely nailed this one . i could simply drink this beer forever because of its great taste and smell . plus the great flavor that hangs in the mouth afterwards is so pleasant its almost damaging to pouring another one .  it is quite smooth .

the aroma is quite complex and very appealing- grass , a bit of pine and citrus , some hard to identify floral and spice notes , yum yum yum . grass , lemon , and ... watermelon ( ?  mouthfeel was the most notable portion being medium/light , crisp , and coats the mouth nicely .
s - wow ! really surprised here . light chocolate notes , roasted malt , toasted sweet whole wheat bread .  finish is cool and crisp with lots of carbonation .
pours jet black -- held this up to the night sky and they were the same color . nice thin cocoa head with some strong alcohol odor as well as licorice notes .  the palate is smooth .
s - strong hop aroma . citrus , grapefruit , and pine in this one .  m - smooth with a slight carbonation sensation .

) my ba 1 year birthday beer a - absolutely jet black used motor oil color , yielding nothing else no matter how close i held it to the light . dark brown head , one of the darkest i 've seen , fades to a patchy eighth inch . lots of little lacing bubbles .  the fizz lasts the perfect amount .
this smells great . lots of citrus in the nose and the hops hit pretty well .  the beer is light and refreshing with just medium carbonation , so it leans towards the smooth side .
a- a brilliant copper color , this is a very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel is light with good carbonation .

pours verly clear , bright dark orange/amber with a full , firm and thick pure white head . a beautiful pour .  banana , pear , perhaps a citrusy taste as well m : good creamy mouthfeel d : i think what throws people with this beer is the appearance to it , looks like a miller lite .

a : pumpkin s : pumpkin t : really really good pumpkin m : liquid pumpkin d : halloween just got a lot more tipsy seriously this is a great beer .  m - it was crisp , sharp and smooth . a light bodied ale with a dry finish .

aroma : sweet cotton candy/caramel up front , fruity hops follow . i can smell pineapple and roasted malts .  mouthfeel - i actually have no complaints in this department . it 's comparatively crisp and the carbonation is appropriate .
the aroma was sharp , sweet , and strong . it resembled grapefruit with a touch if tea .  medium-light body with a pleasant carbonation and an apparent slickness and oiliness .

the aroma is of a beautiful fresh hop . nice floral hop aroma with tropical fruit .  a light texture at the front , that gains weight as it reaches the back of the palate to become more medium bodied . the comforting look , pleasing aroma and solid feel can not bring this beer up .

outstanding looking beer .  the malty flavor remainded in my mouth minutes after tasting . i had a trappistes rochefort 8 a couple days ago , and i am not certain of the age of this beer , but it tasted like a younger , more crisp belgian beer .

it pours a beautiful cloudy gold with a thick creamy head .  the medium bodied beer , feels pretty good , with a nice creamy quality to it , and a complimentary amount of carbonation but the spices pretty much ruin any redeeming qualities the beer may have .

pour : opaque black with a nice medium-density fluffy off-white head . good head retention and one of the foamiest , stickiest sheets of lacing i 've seen in a while .  mouthfeel - a full body whit lots of carbonation .

s : i hardly ever give a perfect rating in a category so that i can always leave room to rate something higher . just a wonderful whiskey , raisins , sherry , smoky and port aromas from this beer make me just want to sit and smell this beer . t : sweet , smokey , malty with notes of sherry , port , vanilla and oak . very complex flavor with so much going on . m : low carbonation , very full bodied , thick and syrupy . d : i have a couple of bottles at home , but not sure if i 'll ever get to drink from the cask again .  good mouthfeel ; much more lively than the original pour indicates .

its a hefty onyx black with a fine , frothy light tan head . lacing is fairly decent but nothing crazy . the pillowy foam looks soft and inviting . this beer looks creamy and stout like .  m - medium bodied , crisp , good carbonation . this aspect of the beer is fine .

s- malty heaven . i love the sweet malty aroma and will sometimes just sit and enjoy . how cool that a beer smells this strong . t- malty sweetness up front with dark sugar notes . sweet in a very good way ... but hops keep things in check . this is far different . very good !  ehh.. let me start by saying i adore irs 's . the anise , in my humble opinion makes this beer taste absolutely terrible . do n't get me wrong , you still get the nectar like , frothy delicious chocolate experience in the background , which is almost good enough to save this beer for me . theoretically the sweet/bitter flavor of the yeast should play off of and enhance the chocolate and coffee flavorings , but it does not . a change in proportions could make this a great , unique brew .

s : very aromatic . aromas of raspberries , caramel , apple , plum , apple and cherry pie , cheesecake , and sour candy . t : same as aroma . does n't taste like beer at all , tastes like liquid raspberry cobbler . exquisite in every category .  m : solid in this department , full for a brown ale , even a bit creamy , with somewhat heavy carbonation .
the head retention was incredibly long lasting and left light lacing .  the mouthfeel is tasty and slightly creamy for a pilsner , but i am liking it .
this beer smells lovely , very funky and fruity .  mouthfeel is again average . fairly light with a decent amount of carbonation .
huge peppery nose with good hop presence and malty sweetness , one of the most phenomenal smelling brews i 've encounted .  mouthfeel -- medium-bodied with quite mild carbonation . very interesting .
body is ruby and brown with an intense head that looks like silk foam .  body is quite good and so is carbonation .

smells like a boatload of hops with some citrus/fruit undertones , smells absolutely amazing . taste is amazing at first , very hoppy , citrus and piney , some fruit in there too .  m - full and smoothh d - this is a decent stout .
a : pours pitch black , good sized tan head , lots of lacing down the glass s : smell is very stong chocolate and coffee .  felt good , good carbonation , but not very drinkable . raspberry .

smell : powerful coffee bean aroma . luscious milk chocolate compliments the mocha superbly . taste : the flavor is dominated again by roasted coffee . overall : i was pleasantly surprised as i was n't expecting such a good beer . very good blend of a traditional porter and robust black coffee .  the mouthfeel is quite good .
