all supported by a lovely smell of pale malt . superb nose . t : : orange peel and lemon are huge in the foretongue .  the body is light , but this one 's got a pretty decent mouthfeel ; it 's creamy and smooth .
its a guinness , on draught it looks the best but this comes close .  a little astringent . smooth mouthfeel , close to a porter consistency . nose and smooth mouthfeel make up for it .
aroma- very fresh smelling with a nice mellange of different malt sweetnesses , mild hops , bisquits , etc .  all that being said it felt quite nice on the palate with good levels of carbonation .

i 'm assuming its the same thing.the neck label says dark winter wheat seasonale offerring.poured a huge head that slowly shrank to about half an inch .  fruity , yeasty smells are overwhelmed with sourness . there is some sour fruitiness up front , which is quickly overwhelmed by a vinegar-like taste , finishing off with a bit of bitterness . i really wanted to like this beer , liking more saisons , and various sour beers , but there is too much of a vinegar-like taste for me in this beer .

pours a rich and bright amber colored brew with a tight laced and thick white foam head thats healthy , retains very well and clings to the glass and creates a pleasing lacing effect . its a gorgeous looking beer .  not entirely pleasant . mouthfeel - creamy . very nice drinkability - berghoff makes a somewhat uninspiring line of beers .
beer looks substantial . fantastic retention ... a full finger half way through the glass and excellent lace .  mouthfeel is smooth and creamy , however .

in all its a very nice , rich and sweet smelling beer . t- the taste is a bit disappointing based on the nice smell .  feels good in the mouth with average carbonation and the beer coating the mouth without sticking .
it sort of smells like a dark , musty lambic . this smells awesome ! t-comes in with very sweet belgian malts .  mouthfeel : very clean and crisp with a light body .
huge cherry and oak on the nose , followed by an earthy mustiness and barnyard funk . a bit boozy . a damn fine flemish sour ; ranks with the best .  light bodied , smooth and crisp .

first off i did not think the can would pour as well as it did . beautiful rich orange color , with lots of haze , and visible streams of carbonation coming up from the bottom . big white , frothy head slowly faded to leave about a half inch that stayed until the end . big time sticky lace all down the glass .  the body was pleasantly full and round .
looks really nice .  m - full bodied , nice carbonation level , and a pleasant warming effect .
( a ) - pours a fairly thick pitch black color that produced a good tan foamy head with good retention .  crisp and heavy on the palate like fine bourbon .

great color , nice lacing , fair taste and drinkability .  3.0 mouthfeel - nice heavy mouthfeel , smooth like silk . the carbonation level is pretty low , but i drank it warm so that could have cut it down a lot .

has little carbonation and a small whitish head that dissipates into a milk mustache ... a beautiful auburn color that diffracts the light .  mouthfeel is comfortable for this style and it is very drinkable if you are looking for a sweeter ( english & lt ; ? & gt ; ) styled pale ale .

s : fresh spicy belgian-y tripple nose with a slight hint of alcohol . really smells highly drinkable t : spicy taste , some slight maltyness , and some residual bitterness on the tongue . finishes clean m : bubbles in my mouth and finishes pretty clean o : love the pour and the smell of this one .  i had high expectations with this beer but it sorda fell flat.i shared this beer with my buddy john.i drank this from a brandy shifter.burnt orange , just like fall colors.nice off white head that fell to a ring pretty fast.the smell was boozy , hops and some spices.the taste was the same as the smell but with a nice malt backbone.the mouthful is smooth and sorda on the thick side.nice carbonation.i liked this more as it warmed up but this is nothing i would seek out to find again .

it pours a very clean looking golden/ pale yellow with an impressive 3 finger head .  mouthfeel : crisp and clean , it feels more like a pilsner than an ipa , which , in my book isnt necessarily a bad thing , but it is unusual . overall : alaskan made a half-way decent ipa here , but it seems much more suitable for a hot night in georgia than anytime in alaska .

quite nice , a very good aroma for the style ( belgian pale ) . my hopes really got high upon smelling this one , i thought i was in for a very pleasant surprise .  the mouthfeel is well balanced , carbonated well and not sticky at all .
appearance - good thick white head and solid lager yellow color .  mouthfeel is full .

the scent really gets me salivating .  see also my review of the big dipper dipa . i am a cbh fan , but this beer tastes virtually the same as the big dipper dipa which had a bready , yeasty taste that overshadowed the flavor . is there some sort of house yeast that is being used here that is giving off these flavors reminiscent of a belgian yeast strain ? although it finishes with a fairly firm bitterness , the hop flavors are muted , not fresh or tasty and there is a funky and rubbery finish .

sweet citrus hops dominate , i 'm picking up pineapple . the hop smell is also mildly herbal . there is a nice sweetness from the malt , but the flavor is n't as strong as i would like .  i hate that most of beer advocate disagrees with me about this but i do n't get the hype over this beer other that the fact that it seriously looks like motoroil and has a super thick mouthfeel .
smell is strong of bourbon and vanilla with a spiced rum scent at the end .  the mouthfeel has nice carbonation but the smell is bland .

great spicy scent with corriander , orange zest and lemon . t -- lets you down after the wonderful smell . not bad but does not impress , i was hoping for more . d -- a decent example but could use improvment . a nice beer to have on for those wanting something light but has flavor .  mouthfeel is big surpy almost very full but how could it not be considering the malt in this beer .
smell : one of the best hefe smells ever , since i 'm not the biggest banana-hef fan .  carbonation was spirited making for a tingly mouthfeel .
amazing , huge , fluffy , foamy nut colored head is sculpted and precariously teetering well out of the rim of the glass . damn thats sexy . well crap .  very light nicely carbonated .

anticipating a lot of nice infection ... t- surprisingly moderate flavors- relatively low in acidity ... slightly metallic with traces of lacto and adicobacter ... all with a moderate caramel malt and candy sugar backbone .  m : mouthfeel is creamy and slick . let me say would have enjoyed the mouthfeel a lot more had i been consuming , say , a milkshake d : so thick , so chocolatey , that it took a lot of effort to finish this off .

s- lots of juicy hop aromas coming from this . flavors do n't live quite up to the nose , but are well done . love the big hop aroma , wished for a bit more hop flavor .  mouthfeel is good and the drinkability is below average just because of my personal opinion of the taste .

scent is a pleasant combination of spice and citrus with a solid sweet , but not overpowering bready and carmely background . first sip is predominately mild spice and tropical fruits , the spice intensifies as it warms , yet the citrusy hop presence fades slightly , the sweet and bready carmely background does not come through until the beer is almost at room temperature .  head poors thick and has good retention though s - nice hoppy aroma t - strong hop flavor , but i find it unbalanced , i like a good hoppy beer , but the best in my opinion have a good malt balance m - the only aspect of this beer that i truly consider high quality is the mouthfeel ; it is smooth and dry , very good .

s - sweet , brown sugar with dark fruits ( raisins , dates and figs ) plus a definite hint of alcohol . t - much like the nose with lots of thick sweetness reminiscent or molasses and caramelized brown sugar plus a black peppery spiciness .  m- medium bodied with ample carbonation .

the beer had great raspberry , fruity aroma . the first sip hits you in the mouth with a deep dark cherry flavor that subsides into a light acidic grapefruit flavor that hits you in the back of the throat .  m - medium bodied , smooth beer , good carbonation , finish is where all the bitterness is in this beer .

the bouquet is a mix of roasted coffee , unsweetened cocoa , and whiskey ... like a liquid mud cake . enticing ... after such an auspicious start , the taste had high expectations to meet ... and i found it a little more than disappointing . i 'm a huge fan of the beers from fbc ( they claim to be `` the official beer of earth '' and may not be too far off ) , but , for me , this is their most feeble offering .  m - english style carbonation ( soft ) and lighter bodied . appropriate for the style .
brown bomber - no date info . rich strawberry gold colour with a full lacy head . beautiful to look at .  mouthfeel : fine . refreshing . nicely carbonated .

poured into my duvel tulip ... well , as i open this one , i do n't hear a pop , fizz or anything ... uh-oh ... pours a dead black , thick looking ... like used motor oil.. with no head or carbonation at all ... absolutely zilch ... hmm.. hope this is ok ... this may be the loveliest aroma on a brew that i 've ever experienced ... loaded with rich chocolatey malts and coffee and vanilla , this smells world class to me ... maybe this will be ok ... well , i was right , there is no carbonation at all here and you can tell ... this could be ridiculous but you can tell its pretty much flat ... what i do get are some tasty chocolatey malts and coffee and sort of give you an idea of what this could be ... i did n't totally discount the brew but i could n't give it the high scores that it might deserve either ... this is probably the only bottling they will ever do on this so its unlikely i will ever try this again and that 's a shame.. i 'd love to have another shot at this ...  mouthfeel : medium body with smooth carbonation and a dry finish .

extremely perfumy , vibrant , and fruity/citrusy , this beer provides an awakening spicy zest . a classic witbier appearance . the aromas are the high point for the beer with a perfumy nose that is likely the best i 've had . bright orange zest , spicy corriander , lightly peppery , and with a fruity-alcoholic note that resembles tangerine marmalade . all lead to a fleeting spicy finish . with a soft , creamy , fresh upstart , the beer has a smooth fade towards a powdery dry finish with a minty alcoholic evaporative feel .  m : light body with mild carbonation .
extremely solid ipa here . nice dark amber color with a huge head .  m - nice chewy mouthfeel , what i 'd expect for the style .

s - bananas and bubblegum jump out . i 'm missing the hops for lagunitas ( haha ) , but this smells on point for the style . decent overall , but nothing overly impressive . m - body and carbonation are both on the higher end .  i expected so much more , almost like a club soda with flavoring ... m=dry , nice carbonation , feels good d=not really .

smell : cloves ! white wine , lemon peel , allspice . no alcohol bite with the 8 % liquor , but it 's really fucking sweet .  mouth was thick , not much alcohol , but that sour-grape aftertaste took control and finished as if it was champaign . there are a lot of flavors in this beer , but nothing really to rave about .
s - very tasty . the nuttiness comes out right away , and it does definitely smell like candied pecans .  the mouthfeel is well carbonated , light , and smooth .
12oz bottle into pint bright chestnut brew with a really creamy white head that wo n't go away .  medium body and the malts do not linger as much as expected .

poured into a tulip , swirled the last 1/4 bottle . almost a perfect looking hefe . a little more towards brown , though still quite strawlike & cloudy with a perfect 1 cm white head that slowly fell and laced very nicely .  mouthfeel is medium and highly spritzy with tons of champagne-like prickle .
this is an exceptional beer . it is a very dark color with a milky head .  thick , smooth , lightly carbonated .
smells superb . very hoppy , very , very hoppy with a nice maltiness lingering around in the background . pretty good but not great .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with lively carbonation .
fantastic . t - big and flavorful .  the body of the beer 's great , and pretty ideal for the style .

the foam was wheat in color , very thick , foamed alot -kept growin ' . the color a very opaque with amber/cherry red highlights .  the mouthfeel is creamy and the finish has a creaminess to it as well .

s- ahh welcome to the cantillon barn and i will be your tour guide , jean . just a wonderful tart barnyard smell or as someone trying a lambic for the first time ... sweaty socks filled with cheese . excellent . t- deep funk with oak notes .  the flavor has all the same spices with some sweetness and hints of the alcohol . i really do n't enjoy the flavor of this beer and i really expected a lot more from it . the drinkability suffers from the spices , but the alcohol is very well hidden .

pours a black with ruby highlights with a thick and creamy off-white head that retains well and laces the glass . it 's fun watching the nitro bubbles cascade to the top .  while i thought the mouthfeel of this beer was quite good , i was not a huge fan of its sour grape and champagne flavor .

jet black opaque beer with nice creamy tan head .  the smell is malty , with noticeable alcohol and more hops than seem to be present in a sip . there are a lot of flavors in this mix -- fruits , caramel , chocolate -- and these flavors pack a complex punch in the smell and taste , as does the alcohol , which causes sensation up the nose . overall , it was too sweet for me , like figs buried in sugar . i suspect i would have enjoyed the malt flavor greatly if the sweetness and alcohol were taken down a notch . i do n't consider this highly drinkable : 500 ml was far too much for me to finish .

a : pitch black with only a hint of light that passes at the edge of the glass , wispy head , looks like charcoal , minimal carbonation noticeable - 3.50 , s : espresso and bakers chocolate , solid charring and ash aromas , some milk/lactose sweetness in the background - 4.50 , t : the espresso on the nose carries through on the palate , dark fruits , lots of specialty grains including chocolate malts , hint of smoke - 2.75 , m : a little grittiness but on the side of thin especially for an imperial stout - 2.50 , d : i enjoyed this beer but in the ranks of imperial stouts it falls short , worth a taste but probably not worth the cad $ 3.00 .  mouthfeel - 4.0 fine , nearly creamy carbonation is just right for a wheat ale .

very nutty aroma with some surprising chocolate smells . t : caramel malts with some surfacing hops that balance the sweetness nicely . o : very good , i only had a single 19 oz .  i dunno i expected more from this m - medium bodied with a decent amount of carbonation .
a - crystal clear amber wiht a monster head with long retention and copious lacing .  m : full body with little carbonation .

thx kev pale orange and clear , nice and cold . lots of bubbles ascending quickly . creamy and dense head that finds its happy place at a slight but thorough coating . uniform , tight lacing . looks light and crisp .  m- good thick syrupyness , i do enjoy this aspect of this beer . the really only redeeming quality is the good mouthfeel .

aroma has a tone of citrus and tropical fruit notes with big loads of caramel , a really nice brew that i could sit with and smell for the enjoyment . there 's grapefruit , pine , and earthy goodness in the hops here . overall i really enjoyed it the hop oils due coat the palate and carbonation worked well for the style .  medium body with a nice mouthfeel .

alcohol and some sweeter malt in the back but alltogether a very fresh and good nose . taste is imo overdone on many occasions .  mouthfeel is a smidge lighter than medium with a great creamy feel . the mouthfeel was very nice , but the flavor suffered from the sourness .
s- coffee , chocolate , toffee , molasses rotate in the nose . it smells heavy and sweet . very very sweet .  medium body very crisp and a bit creamy .
pretty good beer , not a huge bitter-beer lover but being on the low end it 's pretty enjoyable and wouldnt mind grabbing some in the future .  m : oily mouthfeel , good body to it .

if you expect banana nut bread you 'll get the taste of it but you wont be eating bread . s : this was perfect , it truly smelled exactly like what i expected . i loved the smell considering i love banana nut bread .  light bodied and soft mouthfeel .

s-very interesting aroma . you have both the typicla biscuity aroma of a beer but the way the hops and malt intermingle on the nose is wonderful . grapefruit hops hit the nose at the end after the wonderuflly toasted malt . the taste does not match up with how wonderful this beer smells . it is almost as if the bitterness comes more from the toasted malt than from the hops .  the dry , champagne like finish along with the funky yeast was pleasant , however . mouththfeel was right on with the style , and was my favorite part of this beer .

winsome dark as midnight porter , the head modest and frothy , lace a fine thick covering sheet .  the carbonation of the beer was good , like a pilsner should be . the beer was light , but not watery . an innocent beer that would offend very few .

this definitely looks like the real deal and the aroma is emanating off the beer as it pours from the cask into a brandy snifter . the scents are overwhelming . think sweet candied bourbon , chocolate liqueur , anise , cinnamon and creme brulee . the backend packs a really authentic bourbon burn that warms you like the summer sun and made me salivate like i just took a shot . i 'd hate to sound like a wuss , but the flavor profile seems to focus on the whiskey much more than the beer , making for a liquor-infused , shockingly sweet mixed drink with very little beer character .  body is full and has good carbonation .
lacing and retention are amazing . gorgeous beer !  mouthfeel - somewhat of a thick body with medium carbonation .

s : beautiful , juicy , pungent , and slightly spicy grapefruit oils . nice fruity esters throughout and a fresh floral hop scent . d : the taste was a bit of a let down after enjoying the smell for a few minutes .  it tastes nothing like a real peach . i would compare it too a jolly rancher piece of candy . i do like the fizzieness , and crisp finish , but thats it .

the smell is incredible . after smelling the first time , you ca n't believe what you just smelled coming out of this beer . it 's like you 're 6 years old all over again . gobs of peanut butter , wheat bread , slight hint of strawberry jam .  mouthfeel is silky and lightly carbonated .
smell is intense , the oatmeal and coffee dominate the scent .  m - good thickness and consistency .

this beer looks amazing . the smell reminds me alot of shiner bock , but much richer , ca n't say i am very impressed with how this smells though .  a low level of carbonation with a smooth and creamy mouthfeel .

huge flavor in the nose - as advertised . brew smells great . brew is thin , crisp and very bubbly . the taste is n't as impressive as the smell . decent . pretty good brew , but once the novelty wears off it is not really something i could session .  m : fairly light-bodied and lively . good .
cracking this beer fills the air with fresh hops like you 've never smelled before . unreal . aroma . aroma , aroma , aroma ... .  mouthfeel has a nice medium body and full carbonation .
it looks very nice with nice lacing !  the moutfeel is big and bold , full bodied but again , overpowering on the pallette .
smells quite wonderful . t : i do n't get as much funk as i like in my saisons .  nice mouthfeel , but i need much more than that .
1/4 '' white head ... excellent retention . a very nice beer to look upon .  the mouthfeel is a nice , decently carbonated , finishes a little dry , but overall good .
i was able to enjoy this one , but i really wish the taste had lived up to the aroma .  medium bodied carbonation .

a : two fingers of dense foamy pristinely white head . excellent retention being aided by lazily paced bubbles . very hazy and opaque except when held to light . looks divine in the glass .  the palate is super smooth .
impressive . and the lacing is dusted across the glass in a nice etched fashion of tiny snowflakes and frosting .  m : decently carbonated but morphs into a nice creaminess . pleasant .
lots of citrus hoppy aroma with some nice caramel and toffee notes .  the mouthfeel was surprisingly not too syrupy , but at almost $ 7 a bottle i wo n't go back for seconds .

pours a very attractive bubbling black with a big , dark tan head .  the mouthfeel was balanced enough , but for me the drinkability is very bad , as i struggled to finish one bottle of this ... cheers to beerluvr for the bottle and the experience !

nose was by far the best thing about this beer . tremendous floral and citrus aromas . taste is earthy floral hops with a little citrus , but the floral notes dominate with a twinge of spiciness . citrus peaks out in the finish . unfortunately the flavors are very subdued and i like the flavors in my ipa 's to `` pop '' more . though i do n't think this is a bad ipa , by any means , i feel it is just good , but not great and with so many stellar ipa 's available , i would not go out of my way to drink this again .  the mouthfeel is actually decently creamy and well-carbonated .
the aroma is wonderful flowers and pine very nice . the taste unfortunatly leave the nice bitter bite of its little brother into the taste of pine resin .  feel is smooth and thick .

all kinds of yeasty scents going on , funky and horsey mixes with fruit . very nice . the flavor has the same components as the aroma , but i notice them in the opposite order . i think the flavor was a little bit of a letdown after how amazing and funky the aroma was , but i still liked my first fantome beer quite a bit . i know that this brewery is known for their spices , but i would prefer a little less of a spiced taste so that fantastic yeast profile could shine .  the hops jump right out from the bottle and sting your nose as the beer pours into the glass . do n't get me wrong there are plenty of hops , maybe too much , but i think as an effort to try and dry out this beer , the brewer added a lot of simple sugars which created more alcohol , and then to counter or mask , he added more hops . the finish is dry and clean with very little lingering hoppiness at least for a iipa . i was very excited to see this brewery 's beer being distributed in ohio . we do n't see many style defining west coast iipas in the midwest so it 's a real treat to find something that stretches your palate . even though this beer deserves low marks for drinkability , its intense aroma was worth the eight dollars i paid for the bomber .
smell was huge of hops and citrus .  m : pretty good . some creaminess , enough carbonation to keep it from getting heavy .

s : strong hop aroma that is of strong pine and earthy notes . a touch of alcoholic heat and caramel comes through later ... t/m : wow , what an incredible disappointment .  m - moderate carbonation and smooth . dry finish . refreshing .

bottle , bought at the hi-times wine cellars , in costa mesa , ca , batch 67 , a : jet black , as dark and opaque as the night sky in an arctic winter , with a thick , tan head , which leaves voluminous lacing .  it has a medium body and a smooth mouthfeel , with the sour flavor laying on the tongue slightly . inbetween a medium and high carbonation , but fairly drinkable .
pours a solid black with a frothy rocky beige cap head that takes eons to fall .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

nice looking and very unique color .  emphasis on the hops really drew me in a- a full amber body of a beer . nothing but malt . you need some type of hop flavor when you write six hops on the label though m- creamy and overwhelming taste that attacks your mouth . i do like this aspect of it d- just being honest ... if your battle cry is hops , you need to have some . the unstoppable malt attack makes this not enjoyable .

my aggro pour resulted in just over a finger of thick , deep-tan head with low retention . color was a deep back cherry red with ruby highlights and ne-quality clarity . beautiful !  mouthfeel is a medium - light with good carbonation .

smell , now this is where it gets interesting . honey , apricot , cherry , and grape . this almost seems like a wine , very different . i just do n't know where the 9 % abv is ? i had a tough time just finishing this one , not because it was n't enjoyable , just because it was so sweet .  m : the head adds a nice creaminess to this drink . body feels medium .
a : pours dark brown , close to black with a finger of tan/offwhite head .  the mouthfeel was reather smooth and easy-going .
light , hoppy , refreshing= excellent .  m- medium mouthfeel . good carbonation .

as with all of the beers at the sn brewery , the carbonation is constant and active ; however the column of bubbles is not quite as dense . a big , fluffy , white , foamy head sits on top - looks just like a bubble bath . great head retention and tons of clumpy , foamy lace all the way down .  not quite as malty as i was expecting based on the nose , just some toasty caramel . medium body with moderately low carbonation .
appearance is opaque black with a thin mocha colored head - no complaints here .  the body is fairly good .
pours a deep , opaque black-brown with a fairly thick and fine-bubbled light tan head , quite appealing .  very crisp , no real aftertaste .
smell is lovely chocolate liquer-like maltiness .  the mouthfeel was good .

nose is phenomenal , it 's very fruity and floral , dank and spicy . not sure how he does it with these ipas , but they all smell amazing . wow , this is so creamy and juicy and dank .  mouthfeel is medium to almost thick . creamy . carbonation is big and loopy , coating the mouth , but at the same time this is not characterized as chewy .
looks and smells great . light orange , clearish pour .  mouthfeel is good , decent bodied lager with the slightly herbal hoppy finish to stop it becoming too predictable .
smell is floral and fruity with some grassy notes .  the beer leans towards full bodied but with crisp carbonation so it does n't feel so heavy .

the aroma was the high point for me : very sweet malts , sugary candy , caramel , and mocha coffee . can smell it from a good distance away . small , light brown head that sticks gorgeously to the side of the glass . i highly advise trying this one .  mouthfeel : nice light mouthfeel with a decent amount of carbonation .
above average retention , lots of lace .  mouthfeel is creamy and soft , medium bodied .

on-tap at beachwood bbq , a : pours a cloudy brown with a firm off-white head . real nice belgian lace and very good head retention .  great feel . creamy and heavy , but not in a bad way . the feel is great , but the aromatics and flavor depth are lacking .

appearance - i like the darkish amber color of this beer . in my experience when drinking this on tap it always has a very good head retention and decent lacing as well .  a really nice creamy feel to this which matches the beer , not the style imo .
great lacing and head retention .  mouthfeel is pretty good .

this brew smells awesome . i do n't even want to drink it , the aromatics are so satisfying alone . good stuff .  mouthfeel : the body is on the thick side of medium . the carbonation is tingly with a dry finish .

s - strong spicy , malty , and yeasty aroma bursting fourth from the glass with dark fruit aromas - raisin and plum - with a tiny citrus sharpness to it . d - good but not great in the drinkability department , it has a nice flavor and an outstanding aroma .  clean mouthfeel , good carbonation , crisp , refreshing , and easy drinking .
thick black body , with a tan-coloured nitro head . a wonderful appearance , but the aroma seemed a bit muted .  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .
smell is very inviting . smells like a sweet chocolate milkshake with some coffee thrown in for kicks . roastiness is very subdued .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , with a fairly long , sweet finish .

warm & deep dark chocolate smell , nutty & coffee-like and very thick in aroma . surprisingly light in flavor compared to the smell , so it does a better job decorating your nose than your mouth .  the medium body is smooth and prickly , and leaves an almost medium finish - nice .
the beer looks great . deep red and oranges with a sticky off white head .  mf : medium bodied , with just enough carbonation to keep it a tad crisp and refreshing .

clear copper that reminds me of apple juice , which the bottle stays the ale was brewed with smell : absolutely beautiful ! the apples really take over the smell . i tell that the apple smell comes closer to granny smiths even though the actual taste is closer to a different one . i was expecting the beer to be more tart and sour closer to a kriek than what i actually got . to me the beer tastes like a slightly watered down apple juice made from red delicious with granny smiths added as an afterthought .  the mouthfeel is the strongest point , which is pleasantly carbonated if a tad slick .

this has to be one of the most gorgeous beers i 've ever decanted . the triumverate of obsidian elements that make up a true , potent imperial stout . nose of sweetness and extreme burnt hop intertwine with slight vinous alcohol and a return to chocolate and vanilla .  m - stout . robust .

theres a wonderful aroma of sweet grapefruit . overall , this is an excellent and extremely enjoyable pale ale , with its low hop bitterness and strong citrus hop aroma . i love it . i highly recommend this beer .  mouthfeel was also smooth and lightly carbonated .
clear mahogany with a mat of creamy off-white head that lasts and leaves plenty of lace behind .  the mouthfeel was good with real depth .
beautiful nose , seriously the perfect porter . it smells amazing , but the flavor does n't seem to live up to the smell too well .  the mouthfeel is done well , pretty thick , with low carbonation .

the smell was intoxicating . the nose on this beer was by far the best part of the experience . malts were most present with the taste of coffee and bitter chocolate . all in all it was enjoyable but i have had far better barleywines before .  mouthfeel was nice and light and easy to drink .
nice lacing , pretty good head retention .  very good for the style .

but this beer , the bouquet is fantastic ! and let me set this straight , `` bouquet '' is not a word i use normally but this beer has brought me to a place where `` bouquet '' was the word i needed to use to get my point across .  mouthfeel was the best part of the beer to me . lightly sticky with a good amount of carbonation to make it feel slightly creamy and smooth .

a - get a lot of caramel sweetness , touches of cinnamon , hoppy scents are there and i now i know i let this one sit too long , or maybe the faded hops have really let the malts come through . o - decent brew but the complex aroma led me to high hopes the taste did n't match to my surprise , with that being said i know this isnt the most fresh offering so ill take that into consideration .  m - full bodied with a clean finish .

s : smells ... like blueberry pancakes ! it does n't have that syrupy sweet smell that most fruit beers do , but its actually the combination of grains and fruit that you get from blueberry pancakes . the blueberry taste is muted and does n't taste as fresh as the smell suggested . still not bad .  huge caramel malt aroma is kept in check by an equally huge grapefruit accented aroma ... simplistic , but i if you like those smells ... its ambrosia . finish is citric , grapefruity and wow massively malty . if i liked massive quantities of hops and caramel malt , id love this ... i dont though and it gets boring to me like i imagine big doses of flavors i like would get boring to someone who didnt like then as much as i do .
scent is extremely funky .  mouthfeel is full though and a little creamy .
very sticky head results in fantastic lacing and excellent head retention .  feels good in the mouth , mostly sweet to start , but there is a hint of bitter at the end of the swallow .

sat on my table next to the bottle , the scene looked like the picture you would see on an advertising board . it looks so good , what a pity it does n't live up to the promise its image paints .  stands for `` panty dropper '' . unfiltered , brewed with apricots , 4.5 % abv . it even tastes like mead with a pronounced fruity acidity , but in a blind tasting i could n't tell you that it was apricots . mild bitterness with a wierd off-flavor . not as fruity as i was expecting .

the smell is off the hook ... piney hops that just are incredibly inviting . the taste is more subdued , with a mellow citrusy hoppiness that just begs for another sip .  i dont know if they have sour tarts in va , but this incense of baby and elderly lambic beers has a unique flavor . it has definite lambic feel to it .

s - the smell is right there where you want it : boozy , older , spicy , with notes of grape and caramel . t - it tastes as it smells , plus wood , and a caramel-toffee flavor .  it is very smooth , though , although that 's one of its few positive notes .
a fruity banana and sweet honey aroma adds alot to the enjoyment of this brew .  mouthfeel : very light and crisp .

s - strong aromas of banana bread , rum raisin and cinnamon t - dextrin malt tones , hints of the aromas above , but the 11 % alcohol dominates , especially in the middle , and mutes a lot of the potential this beer has .  carbonation level is high , giving the body fullness but also making it lively on the tongue . flavor profile is a bit exotic , with grapy/berry fruitiness , spice , and molasses . thins out on the smooth and moderately brief finish .

appearance - a few moments after uncapping , a plug of foam starts slowly creeping up the neck in the bottle . the beer has a purplish red cast , but needs a strong backlight to show it .  m : smooth and balanced . body is light-medium .
a - jet black . this is as black a beer as i have seen .  mouthfeel : medium bodied , the carbonation was right on the button as soon as i cracked the bottle .

bottle says best before 01.16.2012 really a beautiful beer - poured a dark caramel color with a nice head .  medium body and syrupy with a good amount of carbonation keep the beer from being too heavy .

wow , a strange sweet fruity mixture of smells . perhaps the most interesting beer i 've smelled . smooth and just a tad heavy . quite stout like . '' i could n't drink a lot of these , although it 's very nice . it 's not as heavy going down as much as the way it sits inside you .  the feel is rather rich , oily and frothy like many other barleywines i 've had . ultimately , the one-note , intense hop bitterness dorwns out everything else .
this beer pours an opaque black with a nice amount of creamy light brown head that lingers around for a while .  good fizziness - not too much or too little .
it just smells sweet and rich . flavor wise it starts out on the bland side but finishes with a bitter kick .  body is good and so is carbonation .
wonderful looking brew .  it has a good mouthfeel , thick but creamy , goes down smooth .

s : more citrusy and tart than expected . lemon up front , but a surprisingly tropical fruit bouquet of pineapple and lychee . an altogether unique smell , particularly in the salt , which is unmistakable and not something i smell in many other beers . still quite good , but sweet for a sour beer .  medium , creamy mouth feel with light to moderate carbonation .

whatever it is , it 's complex and wonderful . t-nice balance of a stout ( i know there 's a trace of that in here ) with subtle sour characteristics : seems to be cherry . very nice finish .  m : medium bodied with some crispy carbonation in the finish .

the aroma was intense . quite sweet overall . chocolate notes dominated . a nice mix of dark chocolate and powdered cocoa . somewhat bourbony and boozy . the lingering finish was very roasty and hoppy , with the hops being leafy , piney and sharp . overall , the beer was rather pithy , dry and bitter on the back end . the mouthfeel was creamy and smooth yet noticeably thin for the style .  ( m ) light to medium body with a creamy feel .

this beer pours a crystal clear pale gold with a huge frothy white head on top . excellent retention and great sticky lacing on the glass .  on the palate , medium-bodied , nicely carbonated , but not an easy drinker .

looks deep bright orange on the pour . oooh this looks nice .  mouthfeel : thin- to medium-bodied and very smooth , especially for a wheat beer . especially not when there are so many great wheat beers out there .

it smells pretty delicious . taste : lots of dark caramel and vanilla come to the forefront on the palate .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel although sticky and overly sweet is not harsh at all in terms of alcohol bite .

enticing aroma . probably the best aroma of any beer i have ever smelled before . vibrant fruit notes ; apple , pear , berries and cherries along with a maltiness of cookies and caramel .  mouthfeel was medium-light and easy to drink .

the moderation of the roastiness of the coffee is perfect . so damn good . taste is nicely roasted as well with a great malt foundation and an immediate iced coffee flavor . so now , bx is my favorite coffee smelling beer , while speedway remains my favorite coffee tasting beer .  mouthfeel is good , medium body and good carbonation .

awesome aroma . pine and citrus , candied orange , grapefruit , resiny , fresh hops . for such a great aroma the taste is very dull . d - very strange combination . everything great about the aroma just disappears .  m- medium body with good carbonation .

bottle poured into a 25 ml pilsner glass ( not all at once ) a : medium copper color with a thin head and subtle lacing that soon disappears s : sweet dark fruit and gentle pine hops mixed with doughy notes t : solid roasted maltiness and hop finish - slightly medicinal and somewhat more bitter than the smell would indicate m : sharp edge with mild carbonation and serious alcohol presence d : i was only planning to have this one , and i do n't regret that decision .  mouthfeel has a nice body , decently cleansing .

smell - delicious smell . caramel and toffee malts with strong dark fruit aromas . not a complex as the smell . the sweetness overwhelms what i can only imagine to be subtlety in the flavors . overall - great smell , slightly disappointing flavor .  m- there is a very slight creamy note to the light body that gives it a nice mouthfeel .

mmmm ... coffee , mmmmm ... . the lace is definitely forming in rings to my glass here , pretty good head retention for something with whole mexican coffee beans . i heard it 's really hard to pull off , the aroma here is primarily in your face eye opener of coffee beans , a whiff of chocolate tones , dark roasts , and a very light hop aroma is hidden in there . the aroma is the best thing this beer 's got going for it .  m- pretty smooth with pretty high carbonation overall this beer reminds of an extreme great laker burning river .
very pleasant . taste : mildly fruity , very unibroue . the smell really overpowered the taste in my beer .  mf= medium bodied with a fairly high carbonation level for a cask ale .
a great looking pour .  does have a nice , smooth mouthfeel , which would make it easy to drink , if i cared for the smell at all .

the distinctive taste and smell that arrives with most belgians is laced in this beer . but what it lacks in appearance and mouthfeel it makes up in its rich flavor and a slightly sour and fruity aftertaste . it hides the alcohol content very well .  has a good body , definitely fuller than most ipas . some creaminess .

avery out of bounds stout is a solid irish dry stout with a moderate flavor and aroma . it pours to a clean black with moderate carbonation . the aroma is that of deep cocoa with heavy coffee highlights . the initial flavor brings to mind dark bitter dutch baking chocolate accompanied by coffee and a malty sweetness .  500ml bottle poured into tulip mar27 2011 a pours out black with some oil like globs towards the bottom of the bottle , thumbs width of mocha head quickly falls to a thin film leaving a partial ring of lace followed by some unorganized patches s worcestershire sauce and soy with a little booze and mint , not what i was hoping for t slightly better with some smoke , woody earth , vanilla , cola and whiskey but that worcestershire is hard to miss after you catch wind of it m fairly thick and creamy with just a little heat that could be better concealed but still feels good o lea & perrins would be proud , that worcestershire smell and flavor is holding this one way back hard to believe that before this hit the barrel it was one of my all time favorite stouts , i love the beer geek breakfast but this one just did n't do it for me , not a bad brew but i 'd rather drink one before the barrel aging edit : after reading some reviews i suspected i got a bad bottle and tried another .

bottled in 2000 drank in 2004 the bottle opened with a big swish and poured a light brownish beer with a huge bubbly head with excellent retention .  oddly , it is drinkable to an extent , probably because of the smooth and semi-creamy mouthfeel .

the aroma is outstanding , with lots of bright fruitiness , citrus rind , floral spice and powdery yeast . a decent tripel with an excellent nose , though a bit too potpourri-spicy and sweet for me in the end .  toasted malts , citrus , some pine , toffee , grainy husk as well m- good body , smooth , creamy smooth , good carbonation d- enjoyable , interesting take on an amber , but not all to desirable .

a beautiful red color next to that head gives this beer an exceptional appearance , with a light malty\fruity smell .  m & d - mouthfeel is nice due to viscosity but the tart twanginess is not attractive .

aroma is sweet with notes of cloves , candy , and overripe pear . it 's a very nice belgian , but it 's certainly not a dark ale . that they grow all the ingredients themselves is very remarkable . it is a very nice effort at a belgian , but the lack of a real hop profile makes this simply too sweet for my palate .  decently carbonated beverage with a mild body .
s- citrus hops , and they are strong and awesome . getting some nice tropical fruits in there as well . fantastic . d- pretty good .  m : very light and crisp , moderate carbonation .
pours dark with a large tane head .  mouthfeel is medium bodied , some effervescence and a lingering bite .
poured from a draft into a pint glass at san diego brewing company at san diego , calif. color was red amber .  md-thick body and mouthfeel . appropriate carbonation .

truly amazing . t : follows the nose .  m : medium bodied and lightly carbonated . rather smooth and appreciably oily in the mouth and goes down silky . appearance is decent and feel is actually very good .

appearance : wow . viscous , opaque , chocolatey black with a luxurious cappuccino head that retains very well .  mouthfeel is great , smooth , mild aftertaste , does not have the pasty roof of your mouthfeel like other shitty macros .

wonderfull beige head and anorangeamber beercollor with fine haze . nose shows mega brettarome , sweety horse in flowery fields and wonderfull balance between the freshness of esters & spices and on the other hand the bretty arome . thinking this brewery just started gives me good hope and wants me to try more of this newcomber .  the mouthfeel is good though with a medium body .

the smell is delicious , sugary and malty , with caramel , strong vanilla , coffee and mild hops somewhere in there . perhaps given the strong smell and beautfiul presentation , i expected something spectacular .  m : medium-bodied , nice smooth and even carbonation for the style - helps deliver the peppery flavors all over the palate .

s - i was very impressed with the smell . you could almost get a hint of each individual berry , yet somehow they all melded together with one sniff .  even though the menu at goose island says that sticke alt is usually a unadvertised `` secret '' beer made by alt brewers in dusseldorf to reward its regulars , it does n't explain that sticke alts are usually made with more malt and hops and brewed to a higher alcohol percentage . and after tasting it , i see why . at 4.5 % abv , its is a little low for a sticke and the hops were nearly non-existent . aromas were rather off putting with a stale malt aroma dominating . this was a very sweet cloying alt with not enough hops to balance and the aftertaste was reminicient of a ringwood brew . they could just take their hex nut brown ale and call it an alt and be closer to the style .

it came out farely thick but really dark . something that also struck me was the three and a half finger head that matured after the pour . the head is really dark with a brown shade .  good and refreshing crispness in the mouth , which provided some balance to the flavor .

stubby . appearance : pours an opaque black but as it 's poured i see some definite brown tinges . insanely thick , frothy head that 's at least 3 fingers thick with a light mocha color .  mouthfeel is good , but drinkability is low due to the creeping sourness and port notes that just do n't work with the underlying flavor profile .

aromas of lemon , lemon zest , spicy , peppery yeast . finish is short , lemony , and a little medicinal , almost minty . overall a good bpa . but the minty and medicinal qualities clash , reducing the overall enjoyment .  nose is a creamy butterscotch sweetness , and palate of creamy sweet butterscotch with a balanced bitter and a touch of gypsum . absolutely one yummy ale and a must try for anyone . bass pale ale has been on my list of beers to buy when the price is right . bass pale ale is a good tasting pale ale that has been around for a very long time . well , i just went through a twelve pack and lo and behold this brew has turned to banta podo , it is nothing at all what it used to be !
the smell is absolutely amazing with strong waves of chocolate fudge.and coffee .  mouthfeel : all is well and good .
the sweetness of the pumpkin is balanced well by the spiciness . o : a pretty good pumpkin ale .  m- good carbonation and quite smooth .
a : pours a nice transparent ruby/amber color with a thick , lasting head .  good feel here , this is a decent body with good carbonation .

s- fruity and malty , no hops whatsoever . slightly sour , and surprisingly plain due to almost perfect balance . m- highly carbonated , almost so much so that it masks the taste .  '' other than that , it 's water . it provides a subtle tartness that 's far more apparent in real belgian belgians . the tart , twangy , dark-sweet mouthfeel is actually a good one , particularly within such a watery-light medium . again , aligned with expectations from a macrobrewery , the carbonation is more than ample . the feel of full moon is its superior attribute .

sweet candy and chocolate . almost cake-like . great dessert nose . the flavor really brings the raspberry fruit flavor to the front of everything , whereas in the nose it was more balanced . less chocolate and caramel than the aroma , but more dark chocolate . i loved the nose , but the rest of the beer did n't really live up to the hype .  light bodied and smooth yet dry .
it was poured leaving about two fingers-worth of head . fine lacing appeared after each drink .  well carbonated .
amazing aroma . like my mother 's herb garden was dumped into this .  very creamy mouthfeel , but i must admit that this brew was far too heavy for my taste .

a-black with a thick tan head that stays with good lacing s-smells very hoppy . i 'd say this is a terrible stout but a very decent beer .  smooth somewhat creamy and drying mouthfeel , i have had much creamier kolsch and want something hoppier as well .
nicely herbal noble hops showcased in the nose . so far i 'm pretty impressed by this .  m - light body and low to moderate carbonation . a nice crisp body .

golden orange body with a super fluffy white cap that make it hard to fill the glass .  smells kind of like dishwashing liquid , very soapy , but distinct of certain hop combos ... or so i 've discovered over the years . there 's an even malty / big dextrin sweetness and medium-mouthfeel , but the depth of flavour is one dimensional . hops come in as a gentle bitter citric tingle on the palate , then turns into a faint tea-like character as it fades into the malty blandness . hops are a bit oily . earth flavours run through the middle . finish has some residual hop and soap-like flavours . or perhaps the way the hops played out , combined with the dull malty flavours , rubbed me the wrong way ?
it pours beautifully , though with little head .  the mouthfeel is good . it is a low bodied beer with good carbonation .
pours two finger loose rocky white head with good stick and decent to low retention .  very true mouthfeel for a lager .
smell is just exceptional . a sweet juicy hop aroma fills the air above the glass .  at the least the mouthfeel is , typical of apas , nice and creamy .

poured into a nonic a deep copper color with a 1/2 finger white head that held pretty well for awhile.subtle is a good word to be used for the aromas , caramel/biscuit malt , iron , and faint leafy hops , even for an english ipa its subtle in my opinion.flavors of biscuit malt , some engrained fruitiness , and again light leafy hops in the finish.i understand and like some of the more subtle english stuff out there , this just was kinda boring ... in my opinion .  good carbonation .

very similar to the nose of breakfast stout or peche mortel ... this is a good thing .  taste-crisp and light , a decent amount of hop and rice flavor does come through , finishes smoothly on the palette , not the best thing i 've ever tasted but at least flavor is there . mouthfeel-nice enough , flavor is there and goes down smoothly , not overbearing and not too light . drinkability-as good as any other lager i 'm sure , you can have as many as you want at only 5 % alcohol .

the smell is absolutely amazing . this is one of the most aromatic , floral hoppy beers i have ever smelled . it practically smells like burying your nose in a couple handsful of hops .  m : medium body . moderate carbonation that finishes with some fizz on the tip of my tongue .

apples , pears , citrus notes . their is also a pleasant malt balance in the nose . t : sweet fruit notes and a bready yeasty flavor , slight spicy notes and balanced malts throughout m : creamy and medium bodied with high carbonation , alcohol balances the body and keeps the tongue entertained d : alchohol and sticky creamy mouthfeel reduce drinkability a tad , none the less , these characteristics are what defines this beers mouthfeel notes : a certainly interesting take on the style that i will definitely order again  m & d- i do like the mouthfeel , it matches the style nicely .
smell is lovely and sweet with a great fresh hoppy edge . very appealing aroma indeed .  taste is good , mouthfeel is quite good .

a : pours a very deep brownish-crimson color with a sizeable off-white head that retains well and lays down a bit of lacing on my snifter . very impressive appearance .  appearance dark for an ipa , like iced tea ; minimum head that drops fast smell very little smell , but i detect candied fruit and caramelized sugar , but very little hops taste & mouthfeel flavor is full , but it has no real character or pronounced hoppiness ; thick , oily mouth feel which is quite nice ; it 's hard to think of this as even a form of an ipa ; it 's more like an old ale/strong ale/ barley wine -- it 's really syrupy sweet and artificially fruit-flavored overall it 's just a bit too much sweetness for me .
one of the most impressive shows of head retention i 've ever seen .  m - mouthfeel is nice and full and goes down nicely d - pretty decent dunkel .

aroma is intense , incredible , overpowering . what 's in that nose ? blueberries , of course , and nothing else , but it 's a very pleasant , tasty flavor .  m : nicely bitter , typical ale feel with alcohol front and center , no foaming action . t : overpowering alcohol made this seem like i was having a shot , the licorace flavor and hops fruitiness were strong but a bit of a can taste and a thin malt flavor ended it .

the smell is intensely fruity , this is a very unique beer . lots of strawberry in the aroma , not much of a malt aroma in the background , just fruit .  there simply is no malt presence here what so ever . sierra makes a few of imo the best ipa/pale ales on the planet . instead the citrus flavors just take an off turn . this one goes down pretty quickly . the alcohol is present and the hops are brutal ( very good thing ) and it goes down well . i like this beer and it is certainly the most enjoyable of the beer camp , but this is one of the weaker double ipas out there .

the aroma is fantastic ; the hop aroma is simply fantastic with the citrus smell that highlights grapefruit . that hop mixes well with the sweet malt aroma , very inviting ! the flavor , while good , does not live up to my expectations based on the nose .  m - it was crisp , sharp and very smooth . a medium bodied beer with a dry finish .

hugely complex , endlessly amazing . t : sweet sweet sweet . brown sugar , caramel , toffee , bourbon , vanilla , and booze . a bit more heft would have made this a truly spectacular dessert beer , easily the equal of a fine port or sherry .  i get tomato , celery , black pepper and then a wave of cedar . the hops were definitely present in it , but i could n't get past the heavy cedar flavors . sorry , but not to my liking .

smell has sharp sweet cherries .  some how the spices dont drown out the actual beer . m- light , prickly , crackly and drying . very crisp despite all the insane herbs and spices . d- not as drinkable as a normal saison . this beer is wildly herbal and spicy .
very pleasant smelling beer . very fruity with citrus and maybe a pear or apricot smell to it as well .  mouthfeel : adequately fizzy .

aromas of roasted malt , cream , dark fruit , and candy ; quite interesting .  yet , fragrance is almost soapy . mouth feel is creamy . this beer has an unusual consistency for an ipa ; it is smooth , almost silky .

smell : quite interesting balance of sweetness and booze at first , as my glass warmed it had an olive oil fragrance , and then morphed again to a oily , sticky hoppiness .  m - nice medium-full body and creamy . low carbonation .

the aroma is impressively complex . t : chocolate-covered espresso beans ( stress on the beans , as in eating coffee grounds ) ; the chocolate creaminess lingers . d : not very ; one is delightful , one-and-a-half is too much .  m- pretty light body , nice carbonation . i am a fan of less carbonated beers and this one is perfect for me as far as carbonation goes .
after a moment of warming up in the glass , the coconut aroma starts to become very powerful . tastes like toasted coconut and vanilla .  mouthfeel is decent , not too thin or thick .
s - big hops initially with some malt noticeable later .  it had a very smooth mouthfeel , surprisingly similar to what i 'd get out of a tap . the taste however was watery to me .

smells great , but that 's it , a fruit beer not worth drinking .  damn this stuff is sweet and syrupy . while the beer is very smooth with a long finish , the sweetness in this beer , coupled with the high alcohol , is just overwhelming . i really think a bit less alcohol and sweetness , and a lot more hops , would do this beer a world of good .
it 's not a natural smell but it is enjoyable . t : plain , dry , bitter grass fruit .  pretty good .

one word , hops . taste.. very hoppy with flowery notes as well as a nice malt flavor .  there is the lemon zest flavor , but i also get apple cider vinegar and just sour , sour , sour . the sour flavors aside , i will say the beer is pretty light on the palate with the abv . very well disguised . shared this bottle with 4 other people thank god , including a guy at the table next to me ( belmont station cafe ) drinking some gueuze . he was quite grateful , noting the beatification was much better then his gueuze .

s - the aroma of oranges , lightly roasted malt and belgian years make for a very inviting scent . t - the smell is telltale of what the beer will taste like .  a sweeter fuller tasting brew than maybe a budweiser m- medium bodied brew , carbonation was pretty good .
smell : the best aroma from a beer i 've ever experienced . still , there is a hint of alcohol and malt but very unorthodox for a beer .  m : well carbonated and it feels full in your mouth .

appearance : looks great , nice straw-yellow milky pour with a huge off-white head .  the smooth palate is really the only thing that stands out about this . i would drink it but not buy it again , i could easily kill a six pack of it because of the smooth mouthfeel .

a : incredibly pungent . like biting into a ruby red grapefruit in a pine forest , or getting smacked in the face with a sock full of pinecones in the middle of a grapefruit orchard . pineapple is intense , as well , as is lemon and orange zest and , sure , a little bit of bready roasted grain . t : pretty consistently bitter , with a few balancing sweet roasty malt notes and enough of the hop flavors hinted at in the aroma to keep it tasty . however , it 's a bit of a letdown after the aroma - everything seems a little muted . m : oily and slick , and fairly even bodied but not perfectly so . pretty good .  milky , filling , decent carbonation and not overly assulting ... pretty decent feel .
the smell is hugely yeasty and bready , which is a great thing for a barleywine , imo . the maltiness is very understated .  it was very much on the thick side .

500 ml bottle poured into a half litre weizen glass , which proved fortunate given the enormous , billowy , white head that almost ran over the top of the glass . slightly hazed , pale yellow body with enormous carbonation on display . lots of clumpy patch lace is left on the glass . a shame that the taste and aroma fail to match the promising appearance .  good smooth mouthful , did a good job on carbonation .
lovely hoppy aroma , with notes of citrus , apricot and pineapple , also notes of flowers .  mouthfeel is heavy , slick , and coating .
really nice hop nose , clean hops , gives me a the chills just sniffing it .  mouthfeel is nice and creamy-thick .

bottle a clear brown with chestnut hues and a creamy foam inch and a half head that reduces to a minimal sheen and clinging lace . it looks marvelous ! if nothing else hook and ladder # 2 makes a very impressive looking beer .  m - light bodied and dry just like a dry irish stout should be . medium carbonation with nice carbonic bite to aid in drying sensation .

great orange/tan color with a fantastically huge head that lasted forever , leaving stupendous lacing .  not bad , but not spectacular either ; one might use the term `` '' average '' '' here . mouthfeel is good , being crisp , clean , and smooth , and finishing a touch dry , which leaves one desiring another sip . overall , a decent witbier that i would n't ever oppose drinking , but it certainly would not be first choice in the style .

the color is a very dark brown , nearly black , but when held to the light , one can see that it 's a very dark and opaque ruby-like color . update : five minutes later , the head is down to 1cm of stiff pillowy tan/light brown foam .  medium bodied and highly carbonated and crisp .
all these flavors and more really hit your nose as well . wow .  one positive is the full bodied presence of the malt , although the carbonation comes across as lighter than expected .
pours a crystal clear light gold with a pillowy 3 finger head .  easily the best part of the beer . refreshing tingly carbonation with the wheat providing nice texture and some length .

poured black with a nice tan head that didnt last long .  mouthfeel - the mouthfeel was pretty good . even tho the head was essentially nil , the carbonation was very active which was noticeable in the mouth .
nose : grapefruit with sugar tones , very tempting and one of the best smelling beers i 've had in a while .  m : average , fine ... . good carbonation , nice density and thickness .

it is eerie how perfect this beer looks.. from that reverse cascade pour comes a perfectly consistent black liquid under a similar khaki head . stain is crazy thick and solid like the lace .  good mouthfeel , and went down well .

the nose is awesome - filled with all sorts of bourbon goodness - especially vanilla & charred oak . very unique idea , that somehow falls short .  there is a definite hop bitterness that tries to balance out any sweetness that is left over , but gets lost in the wash. that being said , it 's bold in the body and has a pleasantly smooth but lively mouthfeel .

as soon as i cracked the cap i got a whiff of strong coffee notes , highly roasted but sweet and floral . once i get all the beer in the glass i can pick up a nice mixture of vanilla , roasted malts , powdered sugar , lactose , condensed milk , sweet hazelnuts , and lots of powdered chocolate and coco . quite nice overall , very sweet but it does n't feel cloying just yet , there is a decent amount of roasted malts to balance out the sweetness . ugh , dammit ... from the moment it touched my lips there is a very acidic sensation and sour cherry finish .  m-has a tart , creamy medium carbonation with a slightly dry finish d-well as much as i do n't like it as a witbier , i do n't think this beer is all that bad and it does seem to go down easily .
pretty pleasing .  mouthfeel : the carbonation of this beer makes it super crisp with a dry finish .

deep mahogany to chestnut colored , still ( not carbonated ) , and smelling of maple syrup , prunes , toffee , and a hint of chocolate . enjoy this novelty `` triple bock '' , think of it more like a brandy and enjoy !  m - medium mody and moderate carbonation .

poured into my duvel tulip . appearance- rust colored appearance , head rises to the top of my duvel ... at least 2 inches..almost overflows on a slow pour . chunks , streaks , pock marks with a vanilla milkshake looking head ... .one of the best head retentions i have seen .  this beer has a full body as would be expected in a slightly sweet beer . the carbonation is low .

fruit , hops , mango , still the same from the first time . it was bitter and hoppy , like an ipa should be , but not in the disgusting way it was the first time . it had a lot of bitterness , along with toasted grains and a little malt . the only flaw was that i feel it was not as balanced , in maltiness , as an ipa should be .  m : lighter side of medium body , medium body , slick feel with a sticky finish .
appearance - big white head with great retention .  body is medium with nice carbonation and a semi dry finish .

spicy pepper overshadows everything with a glorious `` bruery-like '' scent that 's unexpected . the beets add an odd but good vegetal aroma that subtly pokes out between the pepper . it 's far too powerful as it elevates the nice vegetal hint in the nose to astronomical heights . d - this turned disappointing quickly .  mouthfeel is medium to full bodied with low carbonation .
murphy 's irish stout . the appearance was pitch black , but upon holding it into the light , has a ruby tint , large creamy head . a real stout baby !  m - medium body and moderate carbonation .
this beer smells of coffee and sweet chocolate . overall another good beer from ccb .  f - medium bodied with good carbonation , refreshingly smooth .

a rather pretty presentation .  the amount of bitterness is perfect for an american pale ale but the type of hops they used disagrees with my palate 100 % . their website said they used summit , nelson sauvin , and alchemy hops in this beer . i 'm assuming its the summit or the nelson sauvin hops because i like their ipa and it has alchemy hops in it . would be a great beer if they used something like cascade instead . but then i guess it 'd probably just taste like sierra nevada .

it left sudsy trails of lace on the glass . s - it actually smells like christmas , if that 's possible . really an amazing aroma that comes through in taste , too .  m - feel pretty spot on for a wit .

smell : oh wow , lots of fruity/florally hops in this one . literally bursting with hops , this is one of the best smelling beers i have ever run across . taste : a nice blend of the floral/citrusy flavor from flavoring hops and the bitterness from boiling hops .  mouthfeel : thick and creamy with low carbonation . has an element of smoothness to it .

lots of character in this nose . i pull off some roasted malt , dark chocolate , fresh cut wood , caramel , molasses , fig , and a tinge of brown sugar . overall this beer is very good .  the mouthfeel on this beer is very creamy and pleasant , however this beer seriously taste like they made a guinness and then ripped out all the good taste .
very interesting and appealing .  just what i expect from a fantome .

the second thing you notice as you are pouring is the fantastic aroma of coffee and chocolate . especially when the aroma was so promising . the mouth feel is weak bodied with sufficient carbonation .  less then exciting , sub par for an ipa . flavors are more citrus , the carbonation makes it brighter , and the obligatory pine is noted , more balanced then other ipas , i would say this is more balanced then most `` east coast '' ipas , really borders the pale ale territory , which is what i always thought this beer was . i remember liking this beer more when i was just getting into craft , either my palate has matured past c hops as a preferance or i got a lame batch .

smells wonderful ! tastes very malty and roasty up front , with a definite presence of alcohol . the alcohol and unbalanced flavors take away from the wonderful aroma of this brew .  it does go down smooth , nice carbonation .

bold assertive bittering , much like what i picked up in the aroma , with some herbal and floral hopping as well . the hops are really strong here , possibly the hoppiest i 've had .  fine and litle ginger mouthfeel though probably from the other used spices . well balanced & carbonated brew that 's a pleasure to drink if you can catch it in your glas as it is very rapidly out of the botle ... .

from bottle to delirium tulip glass a : dark amber , clear , fluffy , foamy 2-inch head . small but thick patches of lacing .  m - good feel and smooth d - it was worth trying but i wo n't be getting it again tried both the bottled and tap .

incredible , smells like a fresh herb garden without peppery notes , floral and fruity with parsley and thyme really standing out . not much funk but a refreshing and unique . mouthfeel is light and pleasant , ideal body , less carbonated than the appearance would indicate and dries well . complex and refreshing in a great way with herb notes and that guava fruitiness bursting at the seams . saisons can be hit or miss depending on the drinker but i think this is a winner in my book  m. medium bodied with low carbonation .
the aroma is very hoppy .  m : full-bodied , frothy carbonation , pretty smooth , easy drinking for its size .
the aroma is zesty and citrusy . i pick up mostly lemon notes , there is a sweetness to it as well , akin to honey .  m : full body , smooth texture , medium carbonation .

nice big assertive citrus aroma heavy on the orange comes out of the bottle from across the table . delightfully drinkable .  ever since , this has been a complete struggle to drink and one i wont go back to . it 's a good looking beer with good texture , and probably a valiant effort for people who do n't get onions from the hops .

nose has plenty of nice hops , lots of citrus , bit of tropical fruit , light fresh hop resin , grapefruit , pineapple , guava , lots of fresh tropical fruits . taste starts a bit creamy actually , a light malty base starts to come through , bringing a slight sweetness , but that is quickly cut down by the heavy hops , a strong bitterness starts to come through , lots of fresh musty hop resins , some tropical fruits , lots of citrus , light orange rind , hop oils , it even starts to get a little astringent , and the malty base has disappeared really quickly , leaving the hops alittle flat , almost like drinking hop water .  it has a very thick mouthfeel and a kind of grapefruit like flavor .

s : grapefruit juice , orange peel , lemon , cloves . just what you expect from a witbier . t : very tangy , lemon zest , orange juice , coriander at the end . hops are minimal here .  medium body , medium effervescence , good aftertaste where the malt comes out after the hop start .

g : i & g tulip a : dark reddish brown with some light escaping near the bottom of the glass . one inch of creamy lightly tanned head with good retention and leaves thick lacing .  pretty good for style .

s : strong hop aroma with many characteristics- fruity , flowery , grassy , and slightly earthy all at the same time . a mysteriously delicious aroma laden with hops- those tv commercials are n't lying .  mouthfeel is crisp , and somewhat clean , well carbonated and fairly refreshing .

big peat and smoke that many american versions skimp on . excellent . m/d : a big full body that is low on the carbonation . incredibly smooth , creamy , and decadent . this is really exceptional . maybe the best american version of a wee heavy i have come across ( founders backwards bastard is the only other that comes to mind ) .  m : nice and light , rather bubbly .
a : impressive creamy head 2 or 3 fingers deep . brilliant , clear copper coloring .  a buttery mouthfeel which is unique and nice . medium body and medium carbonation .

i believe this is only the second welsh beer i have had to date.poured into a nonic a lighter copper color with a 1/2 finger white head that if it had not been gone so fast would have had a higher appearance rating.fresh green apple in the nose at first , it really was fresh , a bit of iron and biscuit malt as well.pretty thin in the mouth , to me it took away a little from the flavors , some of that green apple tartness and toasted biscuit with almost a sherry vinegar flavor in the finish.not a bad sociable pint , its thin but its `` nice '' .  fairly full in body , awfully fruity for an ipa with distinct apricot flavors .

prunes , leather , light oxidation , and a vinuous aroma join together to suggest a well aged barleywine . esters are potent and complex , and the alcohol serves as a vector rushing the scents into your nose without getting in the way itself . deeply fruity on the palate , backed by a wave of malt . quite unusual , though reading earlier reviews , i think this has benefited from some age ... dial up the hops and dial down the alcohol and i 'd bump the taste score a half-point .  appearance - poured with a thin head that quicly dissipated to a whisper-thin ring around the glass , very dark brown with a hint of crimson when held up to light smell - malts , brown sugar , spices ( sage , juniper , rosemary ) , picking up some slight green apple taste - coffee or dark chocolate like bitterness , getting the same spices in the taste , hint of alcohol , slight hops but are quickly overpowered by the spices mouthfeel - full and creamy drinkability - would only be able to drink one of these at a time a very interesting beer and a great effort from the three brewers .

a massive white foamy head greets me like a beer commercial . great retention and a crazy amount of sticky lacing .  this is my first review on beer advocate and i will try to do my best with reviewing beers . a very sweet taste goes down very smooth .

smell - very clean , brisk , hoppy smell . big plant-like aroma , earthy pine and slight straw . very full-bodied , but still refreshing . overall- rich , big and bold . a bit pricey , but certainly worth the try .  m- medium body with a moderate carbonation .
smell has that strong nice balance of rich malts and floral hops . a nice enjoyable hearty ale .  mouth : milky smoothness . bit frothy .

pours a five finger white head that fades very slowly , leaving a good lace .  -original gravity : 1.052 -final gravity : 1.013 -abv : 5.2 % -abw : 4.06 % -attenuation : 74.2 % -real extract : 5.04 p -calories per 12 oz : 170 -malts : two row harrington , wheat malt , vienna malt -hops : east kent goldings , spalt spalter while i like the fact that bbc ( or anyone for that matter ) makes a kolsch style ale , i dont think this ones that great an interpretation . the fairly delicate , softly carbonated body is subtly malty , but even more subtle so that this lover of subtlety can appreciate . the slightly zippy , almost citric tail is pretty much what ive come to expect from american-style kolsch beers , though not having had a real koln kolsch , i dont know if this particular flavor is present in the classics .

all i could taste was massive alcohol and insane amount of malt richness . on second tasting , a day or two later , the rest of the bottle ( which was recapped and colder this time ) was much better . very smooth . it reminds me of port wine , so incredibly intense . i can pick up raisins , dark roasted grain , and a nice bit of hops in the aftertaste . i recommend gently sloshing the beer around in your mouth to let your palette pick up all of the nuances . a great experiment in excess but for strong dark beers i prefer something around 8-9 % alcohol .  medium mouthfeel .
wow the roasted aromas burst out of the glass as you pour it out .  medium body with moderate carbonation . quite smooth .
this is going to be one hell of an apa ! citric , bright , floral . ipa like hop smell .  nice creamy body as it goes down .

plenty of bubbles are rising to the surface indicating strong carbonation and their is a beautiful bright white colours foamy head that is two-fingers width in size & settles very slowly indeed & leaves some lacing . an excellent looking beer that slightly lets itself down by being too weak on both the nose & flavour .  mouthfeel is pretty nice , i would think this beer was thin , but it is n't .

smell : sweet malt and fruity esters are big , a tartness is present as well , phenolic , very nice , complexed and balanced aroma .  mouthfeel is fine , would n't suggest , there are far better ipa 's out there .

there are some good things going on here ; the aroma is quite nice , but the flavor comes across as a little rough and it just does n't have enough complexity to justify the huge alcohol content .  the texture in the mouth is quite good , remaining effervescent and enjoyable throughout this tasting .

crystal clear honey body with a generous 1 finger medium density just-off-white head that retains beautifully and leaves loads of lace .  in a pinch i 'll take yuengling 's lord chesterfield over this , but both are poseur craft beers with crisp carbonation , appreciable hop bitterness and easy drinkability .
pours a light copper /amber colour , lovely frothy head and lacing throughout .  good tingle all over the tongue and a bit in the throat .
looks very very dark and pretty .  good sensation in the mouth .
vintage 2009 bottle ... a : midnight black with a super thick mocha colored head that stands 2 inches tall . perfect !  full body and medium mouthfeel has some chew to it followed by some cloying .
pours a beautiful ruby hue with a tightly compacted head of medium thickness .  light/medium mouthfeel .
wow ! this beer is extremely clear and light looking . was n't expecting that ! gorgeous white head that laces awesome . beautiful beer for sure .  has a creamy mouthfeel and was mildly complex .
the head is full and thick fading a lingering creme like a great espresso . lacing on the glass is wonderful .  fairly smooth . would n't be able to guess that it weighs in at 6.5 % .

s- big nose of hops mostly pine and grassy . hard to pick much else out through the hops but some roasted malt and caramel is hiding in there . t- big blast of floral hops right away that lasts through to the finish . hops change in character from floral to bitter at the finish . some notes of malt , chocolate , and caramel at the finish as well but hidden behind the bitterness of the hops . finish is astringent , boozy and with the lingering feeling of the hop oil .  m - i really like the mouthfeel of this beer . it is perfectly carbonated and that takes over when it first hits the tongue .
lacing continues nicely down the glass ( ky ale snifter ) very hoppy aroma . nice citric combined with piney , bright and floral aromas .  this beer was quite thick in body but not too smooth .
appearance : black as pitch with coffee-colored head . however , if placed to the light it emits a reddish glow , like blood .  m : medium body , with good carbonation gives a pleasant feel .

wow , what a fantastic looking beer . pours a deep yellowish golden color and is very cloudy like most unfiltered wheat beer . the head on this beer is just absolutely ridiculous .  the mouthfeel is on the heavy side of medium bodied , and it glides down your throat as smooth as hell .

not much head at first , however after setting the glass down the head flows down into the beer for an awesomely presentable beer . color is almost black with a dark head .  m -- -medium bodied with good carbonation .
sprecher 's bottle is short and stout with `` sprecher '' embossed on the bottle ... pretty cool .  mouthfeel is actually pretty good .
when held away from the light it looks completely entirely black . it also pours a nice 2 finger beige head .  mouthfeel is nice , feels full , with good carbonation .

from notes written 12/02/07 : large brown glass bottle , 18.7 oz , gold foil wrapping around the neck . pours a beautiful deep and bright ruby , with a healthy white head .  mouthfeel/drinkability ; the mouthfeel may be the best thing going on with this beer . full bodied , and close to syrupy in feel , with a very low carbonation .
aroma was absolutely perfect . strong vanilla dominates with oak and bourbon intertwined .  mouth feel is smooth and crisp with an average carbonation level .
very nice aroma of hayloft , some barnyard , molasses , dark syrup , coffee and german bakery .  m - very nice feeling , no aftertaste .

s : the most delicious hops aromas that i 've smelled to date are pouring from this brew . this is balanced nicely with a sweet candy/bubblegum aroma and hints of citrus and alcohol . the taste is better than many beers , however , i felt let down after the great aromas . m : full bodied with just the right amount of carbonation .  mouthfeel is lively and crisp but smoothes out . your tongue feels the bitterness at first , but it does n't last long , which makes this a pretty drinkable hop-focused beer .
