s - smells like pumpkin pie , with some anise and roasty character in the background .  the mouth is full . adequately carbonated , the flavor is malty but it 's not matching up to the nose well .

appearance - nice copper red color with a bold head smell - wonderful citrus nose which was really distinctive ; after smelling it i could n't wait to taste it ; in the end , i found this was a beer that i would prefer to smell rather than to taste taste - first the malt hits you and tends to coat your tongue in a very odd way and then the hops kick in and make their presence felt ; for me , the sweet and bitter combination could have been great if it was n't so unbalanced .  nice medium- to full body . smooth .

as far as smell , i get the belgian yeast first and then some decent hop aroma .  mouthfeel : light- to medium-bodied and pretty smooth . good amount of carbonation to go with the stronger parts of the flavor .

nose is very assertive and full belgian candi sugar and super sweet cooked peach/apricot nose . sounds better than it is .  the alcohol is quite heart-burn-a-rific , the mouthfeel is good - `` light/medium '' but the taste is just missing something.. if i knew what..i woudl tell you .

a- choklat imperial stout pours jet black , no highlights with a small dark brown head . s- the aroma is the highlight of this beer i think . it smells unlike any other beer i 've ever had . the first thing i noticed was the huge chocolate presence in the aroma . but its not like a chocolate malt smell , it just smells like a candy bar or freshly baked chocolate dessert . there is a mild nuttiness in the aroma and maybe a little bit of hops hidden somewhere .  good mouthfeel , with just the right amount of carbonation . found the flavors to be very mild , and it took a lot of sips to really get the full feel of this brew .
aroma was citrusy and just a little malt sweetness and a hint of fruit esters ... a ripe peach springs to mind .  m : juicy with just enough carbonation to tingle the tongue .

the smell is amazingly complex . grapes are prominent , fruits , sugars and malts , and lots of other things i ca n't put my finger on .  m : moderate body , moderate to high carbonation . appropriate for style .

this brew looks very enticing . there is a massive amount of milk chocolate looking head , with great retention .  the mouthfeel was decently thick . this beer needed carbonation and some balance to it .

aroma : smells amazing . tons of grapefruit and sweet cotton candy in the aroma . drinkability : this is an amazing ipa , full of great west coast hop aromas and flavors . it 's easy drinking , and quite delightful .  note : this is the review of creamy mcstout , not the cream stout . says on the menu it has a `` special ingredient to make it taste more like bailey 's irish cream . '' that special ingredient tastes like it is vanilla syrup extract , and a lot of it , and it really brings down the beer . in my opinion cream stouts have enough sweetness on their own , but this syrup blunts any of the potential subtleties found in the flavor . it was dark , rich , and smooth , but too sticky-sweet and one dimensional for my liking .

the smell is rich and complex . first thought is wine , raisins and plums , dark fruit . the taste is much like the smell , very vinous , very port like .  mouthfeel was pretty good , it was medium bodied , on the thick side , and quite creamy .

visible carbonation , this is one fizzy looking beer ! pours with a thick creamy and towering white foamy head . heavy and sparkling lacing . wow , perfect example of the style !  mouthfeel is pretty good , though .
smell has some nice malt sweetness but primarily very enticing hops .  mouthfeel was good , as the carbonation made it 's way to the tongue and was well received .
look : deep ruby in color with amber hues with a thick creamy colored and textured head .  light bodied , relatively smooth and dry .

s - wonderful aromas of honey , pears , lemon peel , floral hops . i really like this . t - smooth , controlled sweetness . d - just an awesome beer , i 'm so glad i can get this locally now !  carbonation is right on and adds to the fullness of the beer , however , the `` hop '' factor of the ipa is overpowered by the malty bitter bite at the end of each sip .

citrus fruits , orange and lemon at the front , followed by some grapefruit , a ton of piney resin , and a nice alcoholic note . the aroma of this bad boy is perfect . taste is hops and more hops . big , juicy , and extremely bitter . i sometimes dislike it when a dipa is all hops and no malt .  it has a nice and creamy mouthfeel , like a boddington 's or tetley 's , it just does n't taste that good .
pours black with a very dark and expansive head that had some real nice retention .  m : nice light mouthfeel .

this appeared a slightly hazy yellow with a tall rocky white head . the head breaks down into a hilly surface with clumps of lacing being left around the glass .  the taste really reminds me of a malt liqour , mainly olde english , but not as bad . smooth mouthfeel .

( s ) - a seriously rich raisin and molasses profile with a heavy caramel and brown sugar sweetness . bits of vanilla , wood , and dark cocoa in the far background . i love the smell , but everything else is rather mediocre . this is so thick that it is hard to put down .  taste is ... well , minimal . it 's creamy and smooth going down ( so i suppose a great session beer if you like the taste ) but there 's just not much flavor . i would call it watery if not for the nitro creaminess .

the aroma is awesome : loads of floral citric hops , a whiff of fruity esters and a faint underlying grassiness . what a major letdown .  clean , smooth , and light mouthfeel , and here we go again , light carbonation . everything about this beer screams light .
darker than i 'm used to with a iipa but this looks nice . brilliantly clear .  moderately heavy and smooth mouthfeel .
v.06 grade `` b '' molasses , with a root beer float head . nice lacing .  the mouthfeel was thick , had some good carbonation but just was n't thrilled by it in the long run .
outstanding lacing , even if it is pink foam .  mouthfeel is soft over the tongue , and drinkability is not bad .
bottle , a : pours black with a frothy tan head , gobs of lace , great retention .  pretty good body .

the smell is a magnificent , floral , citrusy hop aroma with a hint of pine . phenomenal . hop flavor is much more woody than anything else . overall it 's strong and `` extreeeme ! a bit disappointing in its extremity .  mouthfeel : it 's just about right .

s - incredible . i 'm a fan of hoppy beers , so this is right up my alley . lots of great , citrus-y hops . based on the smell , i was expecting a pretty powerful hops flavor , but it 's actually pretty nicely balanced . nothing to write home about when compared to the taste and smell , but definitely not a negative here .  mouthfeel : medium carbonation and medium body .
part of an arcadia sampler : pours almost black with a medium but quickly dissipating light brown head . decent lacing .  m- medium body and carbonation .
smells of very very strong pumpkin pie spices and i ca n't pick any other smells out of it even though they may be there .  mouthfeel is good . decent beer .

s- there is a rich perfumed caramel malt flows even during the pour with a cream note and a dark malt hint adds depth to this rich aroma . t- the dry toasted malt has a faint caramel note with a soft bitter hint in the finish with a slight sweetness . d- this amazing aroma is wonderful but the taste just does n't follow through with the same richness and depth .  more like a cider , apple-ish and very sweet , low carbonation . mouthfeel is full and round .

) s : rosy , hoppy , and luscious t : very sharp , bitter hoppiness ; this is a very complex imperial amber ; streaked through with sweet grapefruit ; alcohol and hop content gives the power of a dipa . a very inviting beer , very powerful .  mf- good medium body with the right amount of carbonation .
pours a very dark brown , pretty much black . head was tan , and very frothy . retention was great , and lacing was good .  the mouth is smooth -- light to medium in body .
smells incredibly delicious . taste reflects the smell up front ; vanilla .  fine carbonation , and very dry , tight mouthfeel .

some `` pumpkin beers '' seem to ignore actual pumpkin flavor all together but luckily river horse kept it in the brew . this smells beautiful with a lot of allspice , cinnamon , pumpkin itself , and a little alcohol .  creamy smooth , heavy , and warming . super sweet , lots of whiskey ... not as complex as it should be since the bourbon flavors pretty much mask most of the malt .
head is an incredibly massive head of dark brown foam , easily five-fingers , and far more extensive than the three fingers of body . looks heavy , rich and black .  medium mouthfeel .

12oz bottle into delirium tremens glass . a : pour a golden-peach color with a couple fingers of light bubbly white head that faded into an oily film that left rocky lacing down the glass .  nice and heavy feel . too big and lacking flavors from the malts to balance off the alcohol and bourbon .
good clove and banana aroma ; good spicy kick . it 's a nice aroma , really .  m - the feel was nice and even when i swished and swallowed . probably the best part about this beer .

s : caramel , toffee , and brown sugar up front with a biscuity malt character swirling around . lots of different fruits - figs , plums , raisins , some light citrus , and green apples . t : big fruit presence up front with plums , raisins , figs , citrus , and apricots all playing a part . caramel , toffee , and some toasted graints show up on the mid-palate before giving way to a sweet , fruit filled finish . m : has a very wine like feel , light to medium bodied with the faintest of carbonation ... usually an undercarbed barleywine feels too heavy and syrupy , but this really works .  the mouthfeel was warming and thick .
smells incredible , good enough to eat !  this was best part of this beer .

this little scenario should help illustrate the two basic elements of this beer ... really dark and really strong , or very malty and extremely alcoholic ! loads of hops per bottle provide serious bitterness and complex aromas . yet none of the extraneous elements of this brew fail to mask the overwhelming level of alcohol within .  mouthfeel is medium to full .

the smell produced a wonderful strong malt , with caramel , bourbon , oak and vanilla . unfortunately , while the taste also yielded all of these warm flavours , i found the cigar-smoke sweetness and over-powering alcohol taste to this beer somewhat unbearable and was n't able to finish what i had poured .  very thick and viscous with a fairly light amount of carbonation .
this brew smells fantastic . smells very hoppy , very citrus .  everything tastes kinda dusty , kinda dirty ... the body is a hefty light , with a light moderate carbonation and a dry finish .
the good - the smell on this thing is crazy good . sweet citrus - mostly grapefruit .  the mouthfeel is pretty good anyway .

nice lacing around the glass , pretty good head retention too .  the smell is rather odd , but that 's a lambic for you i suppose . taste is quite sour , which i am not used to in my americanized lambic drinking . an interesting approach to the style .

500ml bottle with batch code 5368. tasted in late april 2009. very dark , brownish amber . lots of thick tan head , which recedes very , very slowly to creamy wisps and a foamy ring . amazing lace for a bock !  mouthfeel - very carbonated , but good smooth texture overall .

perfectly pictured stout pour -- jet black , no light peering through , dark tan everlasting head with perfect lacing -- from this season 's ( 2005-2006 ) version .  full bodied and nicely carbonated .

thick fluffy head that slowly receded into a ring around the glass and left some decent lacing .  i ca n't really appreciate much else in the flavor because of the bitterness . still , it feels good going down after the initial taste and i appreciated it more at about 2/3 full .
interesting that the smell is so complex and the mouth is so intermixed .  crisply carbonated with a moderately light weight on the tongue .

a : pours a slightly hazy golden with a mega-massive , frothy head with a sticky , long sustain .  the mouthfeel is light-medium bodied with lots of creamy carbination ; probably the highlight of the beer .

attractive . s : amazing . rich candied fruits , tangerine sourness , caramel apple , wet hay , vinous grape , bubblegum + smoke ( these last two go together - seriously , smoked bubblegum ) . boozier than i like a sour to be , but still fantastic . m : slick medium-to-full body with light , prickly carbonation . ok. o : i did n't know what to expect with this one , and even when i was finished it still did n't make any sense - i just know that it was awesome . if i ever get the chance to drink this again , i 'll jump at it .  nice carbonation but remains smooth going down ... not bad at all ... this is a stout ... .by nature not all that drinkable .
it 's a nice clean smell with a bit of alcohol as it warms .  good carbonation makes for a crisp and clean mouthfeel .

s - tons of citrus and pine on the nose with an underlying sweetness from the malt . t - awesome citrus hopiness dominates up front with a great piny resin on the finish . tons of great flavors and aromas , but i found 12oz to be more than enough .  the mouthfeel has a nice full body , with active carbonation .

open bottle and pour into glass and immediately catch the great aroma . pours a nice , lightly hazed , dark orange , with a decent head , leaves great lacing on the glass . this beer has an incredible aroma , a great , bright , hops/citrus/grapefruit/floral smell , very strong , but not too much for the style . great hop dominated flavor , with a decent malt backbone to support the hops , very nice . leaves a nice hop aftertaste , not too bitter though .  even so , it was pretty decently textured and carbonated .

lively ( could still see a bit through the red haze ) smell & gt ; caramel , sweet grasses and malt . excellent taste & gt ; true to its style , it started sweet before bursting with barley flavor .  it drank fine , well carbonated and smooth but i would n't drink this one again . it 's too bad because i love goose island .

aroma was great . had a lot of zest and fruit smells . it was no where near how great the smell was . very dried up taste .  i do like the creamy mouthfeel this beer has , but by now , it is too late .

pours very very black . big two and a half finger head . the light brown head dissipates rather quickly leaving a thin layer on top of a black ocean of goodness .  m : nicely carbonated and feels good .

pours with a thick creamy head over a dark black body , beautifully cascading .  mouthfeel has a pleasant sheen to it , but the flavour is either thin or phenolically unpleasant , so it does n't have much to work with .

the smell is amazing , very strong and aromatic , sweet , chocolate , and malty . this is one of the more aromatic stouts i have ever smelled . the taste follows suit , starts somewhat sweet and malty , then moves into a nice chocolate flavor .  it has a medium to full body , with ample carbonation , a prickly middle and dry finish .

aroma is amazing , the best i have felt in hemp beer , it feels like lingering next to coffee shop entrance in the netherlands . overall , the flavour was average , but i enjoyed the aroma immensely .  smell - malt smells dominate , chocolate msotly from what i can detect , not overpowering , in fact it 's very pleasant to the nose . the first thing i thought of was wine , sour and not pleasantly so . frankly i do n't like it . overall - a beer that 's exceptional in every area except the most important one : how it tastes .
pours a beautiful dark red color , huge off white foamy head to it .  texture is quite fizzy and lively .
oh god it smells good . notes of malt and spice and brown sugar and nutmeg and cinnamon , it 's exactly what i 'm looking for in a winter beer .  m- nicely carbonated and puckering o- not too bad
a : pours a smooth black with a good 2-3 fingers of khaki brown colored head .  decent enough mouthfeel .
smells hoppy before i even finish pouring . smells quite potent . the taste is not quite as good as the smell but very solid .  mouthfeel is good . slick and smooth .

aroma is strong and sweet ; brown sugar and dates , raisins and prunes . the surprise was that the finish was very clean for a beer of this heft . flavor : strong and intensely sweet .  a nice slick mouthfeel with a bit heavier heavier viscosity .

big raspberry aroma . drew a `` this smells like lindemans raspberry '' from my wife . it shows hints of some real fruit , but i definitely get a slight nutra-sweet tang toward the end , and the bottle lists sugar and raspberry syrup as ingredients . otherwise , this one belongs on its own as a cheap fruit drink .  mouthfeel - a good mouthfeel . smooth and slightly oily , crisp carbonation , one of the better areas of the beer .

the smell was quite complex . heavy in malt with mixed fruit smells , citrus , dates and various other fruit . an almost nutty undertone in the rear of the nose . the drink started clean and fruity with just a hint of hops in the middle and a lingering dried fruit flavor to finish . clean mouthfeel , heavy in carbonation at the start but this dissapates and leaves just good beer to speak for its self .  mouthfeel is very smooth .
has a nice sweet aroma , some hops , malts , northwest beer aroma .  m : light body with a very well done carbonation feel .
poured from the bottle into a tulip . beautiful to look at .  m : medium bodied with a medium level of carbonation .
a : it poured a thick , black with a massive dark chocolate three finger sticky head .  the interesting thing is that the body did not feel light ... . actually pretty full .

s : this is great . hops and malt are balanced perfectly . a lot is going on in the nose . almost a cloying sweetness .  it 's syrupy and thick with a snappy carbonation , and the combination of the taste and the mouthfeel are not quite cloying .

s - sugary sweet malt is way up front on this one , blended with a heavy dose of caramel , some fruity esters , and citrusy/grapefruity hops . balanced way towards the malty side . very good - probably the best aspect of the beer . almost candy like in its intensity and ends up being somewhat cloying .  light bodied with good carbonation for the style .
smell is very nice . taste was not quite as complex , but still very good . really great stuff .  it had a medium feel in my mouth and good carbonation .

on tap night of a million zillion speedways o'brien 's pub san diego , ca dark as night black with brown edges , thin head but the body of this beer is just spectacular . it 's thick and oily and leaves the glass absolutely covered in sticky lace . unfortunately , the appearance is one of the few fine things about this beer . while there is still a bit of the coffee and roast combination left from the untreated version of speedway , the dry hopping has given this beer an incredibly woody character .  mouthfeel is spot on , carbonation zing .

aroma is deeply of roasty sweet dark malts . taste follows the nose upfront , and closes with ample bitterness , but in the middle we 've got got watery wort to me .  mouthfeel is smooth and warming .

s - huge fresh strawberry nose , with light pepper , spicy yeast , and a bit of stone fruit and citrus as well . i have n't had too many strawberry beers , but this is by far the most impressive and authentic smelling one . t - taste is a little more muted , but still contains a lot of fresh strawberries , with notes of pepper , stone fruits , belgian yeast , honey , and pale malt mixed in to good effect . not particularly musty or funky here - guessing there is n't any wild yeast at work . d - i had multiple pours of this - it 's very good .  the mouthfeel is nice and dry with a good body and carbonation level .

smell is filled with citric fruit , grapefruit and oranges .  mouthfeel : surprisingly clean and dry , especially in the finish . lip-smacking and smooth , with airy carbonation ... but unfortunately , it does n't do much to lighten the heavy sugar load .

s : strong smell of resin and caramel malt , pine dominates . t : pine bitterness whacks you when you first taste the brew , with a strong caramel malt presence as well .  mouthfeel - medium . crisp .

the beer is quite aromatic , with sweet honeysuckle complimented by a tart citrus character ( mostly oranges ) . disappointing , after the overall high caliber of this brewery 's other beers and the awesome aroma . i poured most of it down the drain .  m 4 the best part . medium plus body , creamy carbonation .

it smells of caramel malts , yeast , allspice , cloves , and dark fruits -- perfect smell for a dubbel .  this one has a `` bottled on 8-5-08 om it . i like the dating of beers . taste is warming , alchohol burn warming the inners . malty , raisins , figs and woodiness . i am tasting the mettalic aftertaste in this.good beer if i could get paste the metal .

smells incredible . rich malts , vanilla , amazing nose . tastes malty , a touch of vanilla .  t & # 8211 ; it tastes a lot like a macro lager , and a little like a wheaty spicy belgian-inspired summer beer . blue moon is probably better in some regards , though i guess not on an overall basis ( i have n't had blue moon in a , well , you know ... ) m & # 8211 ; pretty crisp and refreshing .

everything was tasting weird yesterday , all the aromas were strange . this one was like dipping your face into a fresh bag of weed . aside from the juicy marijuana nose on this it 's pretty uninteresting .  m- dry and crisp with good carbonation .

a-really looks the part . deep dark brown bordering on black with a creamy , frothy tan head .  maybe i had chilled mine for too long , do n't know but i found very little going on in my mouth to make me like this . the only positive comment i can make is that the taste did surprise me in that it was far smoother than what i was expecting . m. light , clean and much smoother than i imagined .

s- as soon as i uncorked this beer it smelled like raspberry candy in my kitchen . taste did n't quite live up to the smell , but still very nice and interesting . m- very light and high carbonation that makes this highly drinkable but i believe that the smell was much more what i was looking for , but still good none the less . d- easy to drink and enjoy , awesome nose and a good taste to this beer make it quite enjoyable .  medium bodied with sufficient carbonation .
in the pint it is as black as night with a substantial foamy tan head .  mouthfeel is good as this beer is light on the tongue and not very thick when it goes down .

hop wallop bottle to glass hop wallop looks like a fizzy yellow beer . smells of freshly cut grapefruit and citrus. , pineapples , lemons . nice and rounded .  m - very smooth with good carbonation , well rounded .
this was 11.2 oz of beautiful dark amber .  the body is on the fuller side of medium with a low carbonation level that gives some wateriness . pretty good .
pours a golden nearly copper color , and an enourmous off-white head on top .  m : medium bodied with crisp carbonation .

the aroma is fucking badass . not some insipid , bourgeois , fine-ground and drip-brewed coffee ; more like french pressed boutique beans . very strong and very impressive ; the beer hides underneath with the same quality dark malt character as usual .  feels good in the mouth , but , the taste is ... unfortunately awful .
it started great it was a dusty brown color with an enormous rounded head -- it looked superb .  m - medium to full body , creamy carbonation .
a- pours a hazy gold with a huge 3 finger head that dissipates very slow , leaving an impressive cap . great looking beer .  m - fine . right where it should be . my favorite part of the beer .
delicious aroma of caramelized malts , with some dark fruits , and a hint of alcohol .  m : medium in body with a medium carbonation .
the kbs poured a rich black color .  m : sort of interesting here . i actually like the mouth feel .

the nose is strong plum , figs , prune , dark chocolate , coffee , brown sugar , wheat , just lots of sweetness in the nose . the taste starts mildly bitter with a grapefruit crack of bitterness , this is very interesting ... .it feels like a fruity belgian beer combined with west coast pungent hops finished with a porter 's roasted barley like quality .  the carbonation and mouthfeel were good , however .
this was my first ever cask ale . the nose had notes of vanilla , oak , nuts , chocolate . light bourbon on the finish .  taste/mouthfeel : medium body with nice carbonation .

a - pours a brilliant dark reddish orange with a finger and a half khaki colored light bodied head that dissipates quickly .  it drinks much more harshly when cold . now is all wintertime spice . and cherry , of course . otherwise , it mirrors the nose being the most palatable . whew . quite an experience and one that everyone should have ... once . props to unibroue for coming up with this , but i 'm not so sure it works .
immediately upon popping the cap you can smell the floral hops . the aroma is very strong and entirely hops .  mouthfeel is full and syrupy will sufficient carbonation .
s : wonderful mix of aromas -- grain , stewed cherry , port , wood , and alcohol . light oxidation .  a slightly creamy mouthfeel with moderate to low carbonation is present throughout .

this smells like the perfume isle at dillards . very aromatic . for a pale ale this is a very interesting and different beer .  moderately balanced bittersweetness with a nice mouthfeel and light carbonation , but when its coming from something that smells like cheap melted hersheys , wax and preservatives , who cares ?
appreance huge creamy head on a straight pour . brown clear body that harbors red amber hues when held up to the light . solid head retention .  medium bodied .
smell : strong and hoppy with hints of citrus .  mouthfeel is good . it 's got a decent thickness with nice carbonation .

a very average looking ipa , the selling point is the flavor and aroma , fresh citrus and pine engulf the senses with much pleasure . some super hoppy brews are n't easy drinkers but this is n't one of those .  m : medium carbonation , light body and a nice dry creamy finish .

s ~ a good dose of coco , chocolate syrup , hint of vanilla in there ... t ~ bitter chocolate ... .dry on the back ... lingering flavors of coco that stay behind well after the sip is gone m ~ lighter to medium bodied bock ... i like my chocolate beers thick and rich - s. tier chokolat ... this was a random bottle i picked up.. o ~ not bad ... i remember the hype behind the beer a year or two ago when it was in the bigger bottles for $ 15 per..glad i did n't buy one then and held out for the $ 1 something 12 ozer ... worth a try..but nothing super special..  smooth moderate mouthfeel and not too filling - not a bad beer , too .
insanely sweet . is there even hops in this ? ? ?  mouthfeel : crisp , clean , and refreshing .

bottle- color of golden yellow , with a white head full nose of yeast , spices , orange zest , and lemons taste of orange zest , yeast , cloves , other spices , and mild bitterness - body is slightly acidic , and with high carbonation aftertaste of orange , hops , and slight maltyness  medium-thin body , nice effervescence .
it looks amazing . orange , great firm sticky white head , great lacing .  thin mouthfeel .
pours a ruby color with a 1 finger fluffy pink head . good amount of carbonation rising . just beautiful to look at .  the mouthfeel is too undercarbonated and watery .
reviewed 8/29/2008 ( bottle coded 0188 ) : pours a ruby-brownish body . big creamy off-tan head , lasting .  the mouthfeel is way too light and thin .
on tap at `` flavor '' in santa rosa ... a good pour , the beer arrived with a thick , sticky white head over a clear , deep gold ale .  the palate is thin .

as with mia & pias other lagers , spring lake is clear with a solid , over-the-top head of dense , white duff . the head begins at a full finger and holds well for some time . this is an amber lager and is suitably colored , though in bright light , a ray of yellow shines through .  nothing at all in the middle except an annoying hard carbonation , watery . finish - a bit nutty , astringent and very mild fruit esters overall - this beer is not bad , but very average in taste . i liked most aspects about this mild except for the taste which i felt could have had more roundness and a bit more plump , just too watery .

a : dark chocoalte brown . huge three fingers of very light tan head . decent retention .  mouthfeel- very thin and watery with a brisk , small , tingly carbonation . drinkability- this beer is very different .
attractive ruby body with delicate carbonation and a velvety tan head .  the feel was too thin . what smoothness there was came more from thinness than anything else .

appearance giant , lasting head atop a gorgeous deep brownish-orange body . this was beautiful to stare at .  very little mouth feel or body and not much that reminded me of the beligians i miss so badly .
a very nice looking beer .  m - too much carbonation for my liking .

a : a beautiful , golden butterscotch colour . hazy s : floral , with some phenolic sweetness t : a really nice hop punch !  mouthfeel is really quite thin , with the flavour kind of releasing itself more from an emanating aroma than any substantial body .

yuengling black & tan bottle into a large wine glass , 9/20/08 150 cals p12oz , abv=4.7 a 4.0 deep dark brown , almost black & opaque , very large frothy foamy head , mediocre lacing s 4.0 malt backbone with pronounced toasty chocolate notes t 4.0 chocolate & roasted malts mf 2.5 mouthfeel is a bit strange on the palate , heavy carbonation , and somewhat watery for a black and tan style d 4.0 i am not a huge black and tan fan , but i do like this one for a ready to go version in the bottle .  m : i know this is big , but there just way too much residual sugar here .
reviewed 6/24/2009 ( bottle ) : pours a opaque dark orange colored body , with a huge rocky off-white colored head , very lasting .  rather thin for the style ; almost like soda rather than a stout .
it just looks fantastic in a glass .  mouthfeel : no fizz and kinda thin .

the beer poured a three finger head that i appreciated . lacing covered glass after head dissipated . light orangish-amber in color that is attractive .  m : painfully overcarbonated , even after multiple swirls have created multiple heads .

pours a very dark tawny-tinted deep charcoal brown . a huge billowy tan head rests comfortably on top . this retains wonderfully , leaving behind plenty of sticky webbing and lace globs .  the mouthfeel is thinnish and very watery .

pours pitch black and completely opaque without even the slightest bit of lighter hues when held to a light source and a frothy dark chocolate neige/brown head that slowly fades into a lasting ring . large chunks of soapy lacing are left behind .  chalky astringent mouthfeel .

a - pours a thick jet black with the darkest head that i 've ever seen . the head was about a 2-finger billowy chocolate color and had great retention .  m- horrid ! lacked any body whatsoever . i mind as well have been drinking seltzer water that had no carbonation . d- given the water-like mouthfeel , it went down pretty easy .

after losing an ounce or so ( on the floor and in the sink ) , a very gentle pour still produced a huge light brown 3 '' head - could n't get it all in a pint glass .  mouthfeel is lacking as this beer just feels watered down in all aspects .
lacing is impressive , as well as head formation and retention .  mf ) watery , thin , and lots of carbonation d ) pretty good for this style !

that alluring nitro profile : the cloud of superfine gas racing to the top of the glass to form a creamy , long-lasting head . attractive amber color . nothing else about this beer matches the bodacious pour and appearance .  however it 's not very complex and is lacking body . thin and somewhat lost to where it should be .

had a point at some irish bar in west allis before a recent cubs/brewers game a : thin brownish red with a solid white head , good retention , and great lacing .  m/d : the body is very thin and watery .

appearance : looks alone , this is nice - dark but not as think and luminous as an imperial stout . has a light beige head - just under a finger think that is going no where . very good lacing .  dayton , oh alefest : this beer had a small sized tan head that consisted of mostly lasting fine sized bubbles.the body was cloudy with no carbonation observed.the hue of this beer was brown with a nose of malts and some hops.the flavor was acidic and bitter which had a lingering effect to it.the mouthfeel was very tingly , thin , watery and light bodied.there was good lacing with this beer .

poured a gorgeous oranged amber color with a bubbly off-white head , good slow lace , and a little staining on the glass .  mouthfeel is extremely light and overly carbonated - doing nothing for me at this point .
it really was a beautiful pour ... one of the best i 've ever seen from a nitro can .  the mouthfeel is very gaseous . i 've had 3 of their beers now and they have all felt shitty in the mouth .

as you pour its a light cloudy straw with a huge and lasting white head . the head itself if very attractive as it is very fluffy and creamy .  this one has no body ; very watery , dry finish , and no oomph . mouthfeel of water with cocoa powder . drinks like water . really thin and unremarkable .
pours a deep black color with a perfect , thick beige head .  mouthfeel : very clean but the body is way to light even for the style . feels like water really .

a : pours a somewhat cloudy pale pink with a beautiful pinkish-white head that never goes away and leaves one the nicest , stickiest laces i 've ever seen . gorgeous .  oily mouthfeel . not at all stout of body - thin in fact .

12 oz bottle poured into traditional pint glass a - pours a cloudy light orange color with a huge , billowing head that becomes very rocky with time . lacing is terrific .  the mouthfeel is very thin .

bottle date : oct 07 , 2010 a- this is a beautiful looking beer , dark pitch black color , opaque , really nice lacing , two finger brown head .  pouring out in a sweaty yellow with high carbonation and zippy flavor , lionshead light offers enough personality and taste to get you past its weaker qualities ( gritty mouthfeel , odd aftertaste , general banality ) and is definitely there for you when you need a night of drinking without the cost of high-quality suds .
appearance : beautiful , golden , clear liquid with sparkling , bubbles that rise to a frothy head .  carbonation is stupidly high .

this beer looks better than i expected . instead of the sickly straw hue of most euro macro lagers , this one has a deep gold color . the head is long lasting and leaves an excellent web of lace .  mouthfeel was light to medium , slightly oily , fizzy with light astringency that turns to harsh astringency on the finish .
a very nice looking beer .  as stated , the body is on the watery side of light . a poor showing from a brewing giant .

the outer edges of the head have a pink hue to it , not much lacing to this one only some slightly above the tight cap . bodies color is a beautiful murky reddish amber bordering on a shade of purple .  a very enjoyable coffee tastes swirls on the tongue ... hmmm ... ... then it breaks my heart , and completely fades away into a watery , thin , no hops finish..not even an aftertaste . if they wanted smooth , they got it by neutering this beer on the tongue and letting it fade into a bad memory . too bad .

dragonmead sir william 's esb 12 oz bottle moderate pour in an english pint recent brewing , knighted 04/06 poured a slightly hazy ruddy copper with a huge off white mostly lasting rocky head with fair lacing .  the beer is really quite watery ; not much in the mouthfeel department .

a - a clear golden color , pores a thick head and tons of sticky lace that just never quits s - piny and floral hops and spices , with the yeast providing the earthy aromas that give it that saison style t - light malts and spicy with dry hop notes towards the end .  m - thin .
a - pours a huge puffy white head into a pint glass . the head sticks around forever and leaves some very nice lacing .  it is medium bodied and pretty watery .
a- nice pour ... 5-finger head , nice espresso color and a great deep brown body .  it watery and thin and does n't taste completely crappy therefore i say it 's pretty drinkable .

from the token `` snow '' effect to the jet black body to the creamy firm head , you ca n't beat the visual effect . it leaves nice rings down the entire glass .  mouth feels a lot thinner than it looks , almost watery overall not a bad beer , but almost to overpowering with the nutt flavor and not enough else going on .

pour : not completely black , but dark with garnet highlights under the thickest , frosting like head that i 've ever seen on a porter . lasts to the end with good lacing too .  the mouthfeel is very thin with medium/low carbonation .

poured a light copper with a huge 3 finger high foamy light tan head . great retention and left tons of lacing . this is a really hot looking beer .  a thinner mouthfeel too . feels like carbonated soda on the finish .
poured a gorgeous 2 '' violet pink head .  furthermore , although the aforementioned flavors are strongly present , the body of the beer feels a watery on the tongue .
oil black body with a thick pale tan head and huge amounts of lacing .  felt very thin in the mouth for a stout , with a little bit of carbonation .

highs : appearance , complexity lows : complexity ok , i must admit i was a bit overwhelmed going into my first fabled trappistes offering . bottle , pours caramel brown with a two-finger brown-tan head that fades at a moderate pace leaving a medium to heavy amount of lacing that lasts until the bottom of the glass .  not much of a honey taste and very thin mouthfeel , very carbonated .
a : great looking beer with a one finger head and no lacing on the glass .  m : whoa , way too carbonated , reminiscent of the swill called bud light i used to drink as one of the ignorant unwashed .
pours an opaque brown-black with a thick , tan head -- looks very inviting .  the beer is very thin bodied , so much so that it almost seems to develop a tartness .

appearance : pours into a becker glass completely black in color . a light mocha-colored head forms on top at about a finger 's height . it slowly drops to a full , thick cap .  mouthfeel and carbonation is poor , i could n't even get a head to form with a hard pour .

pours a brown/chestnut with 3+ fingers of rocky sand colored head . outstanding head retention & lacing s : bready , roasty , & nuttyness t : bready , roasty malt , & dryness up front .  in the appearance , is a coppery color , with a poor head of foam , the bottle and the logo are retro ; lot of caramel and sugar in the smell ; some essences of caramel and roasted malts in the taste ; the drinkability is good ; the mouthfeel is watery and fizzy , with a low bitterness .
a big fat foamy off-white bubbly head with great retention and superb lacing .  m : i 've had a few other rogue brews and they have all had the same watery feel .
gorgeous deep candy burgandy . little to no head . vibrant looking .  scarce body , quite watery .
pure , opaque black in color . rocky , pitted deep bister head leaves muddled , tattered lace . beautiful .  next to no beer flavour of any sort , may as well be soda water with a lime wedge .
dark brown body , very clear with a one finger tight head that lasts the whole beer and leaves huge amounts of lacing .  it was overly carbonated and thin to my disapointment .
coloration is a nice ruddy brown with a healthy 1 '' khaki head which is simply beautiful in appearance . huge and uneven and thick .  not much compexity and feel was very thin .

pours out of the dark clad bottle pure black with just a few hints of ruby around the edges . the rocky tan head lasts forever and leaves a lot of lace patches behind .  m : very thin and dry a low carbonation and a bitterness at the end .
combined w/ the copious , lively bubbling and clear , light amber hue , this beer is vibrant and visually appealing .  m- thin , watery with crisp prickly carbonation throughout .

pours amber with a slight haze , even with the high alcohol , a frothy ivory head boils up and leaves a sheet of lace . this one is looking good .  clearly a lawnmower/party beer , but its quite refreshing and a lot more tolerable and most of the other cheap beers , plus it 's the same price ... one of my favorite cheap beers .

poured from a 11.5oz bottle into a cigar city pint glass ... a - pours black with a two finger light brown head . head retention and lacing are excellent ... s - coffee and dark roasted malts dominate here ... t - dark roasted malts , chocolate , and coffee .  ah coors ... pours a honey color with a nice head , and lace . the look is the best part of this beer . smell is of light skunk.mouthfeel is watery and flat . taste is light with a hint of spice . the beer was not awful , but i would not go out of my way to buy this beer .

a nice two finger head with slow retention to a thick , foa , y head . the steady bubbling complimented the slightly hazy amber , maple colored beer .  the mouthfeel is thinnish and watery with little carbonation .
pours black with notes of ruby when held to the light . the head stays very well and leaves pretty nice rocky lacing .  could barely detect any spices , very thin body .
a : looks great , deep red , very vibrant , with a nice off-white head and great head retention . fantastic lacing .  mouthfeel is where this brew suffers : it 's really just pretty thin .

appearance : pours a slightly hazy yellow color with a super thick 3 '' + head .  mouthfeel is without carbonation ; has a big sour character but without any discernable fruit or style and definitely needs more acid for my taste . some carbonation would have assisted this one .
looks spot on in the glass . good stability and lacing .  mouthfeel is pretty lame .

a - pours a large dark brown head with great retention and nice lacing . very dark brown nearly black beer .  m : dry , i think the mouthfeel takes something away from the beer . overall , i like the complexity and smell but the mouthfeel totally ruins this beer for me .

a : pours a huge , frothy off-white head , the cap is persistent and thick , and the lacing is tenacious like a honey badger .  m - too much carbonation , and some unpleasant graininess . the carbonation bloat and mediocre taste make it something i would n't bother ordering again - would rather go with the sierra nevada or rotating bell 's handle .

11.2oz bottle a- pours a dark brown color with a huge light tan head that sticks around forever and leaves a lot of retention along the glass . this is a really pretty pouring beer .  very thin , and very lacklustre . feel is particularly light , and lends nothing to the weakness in the flavour .

pours with a massive creamy four fingers of white head sitting on a slightly dark golden straw colored body . really intense retention on this one , after a few minutes of staring at it this head shows no sign of shrinking .  the flavour is rather thin and feels watered down .

pours a nice cloudy golden amber with a big two finger white fluffy head that slowly fades to about one finger and it 's sticking around with a bit of lacing .  this was a strange one for me - i was only able to try this one bottle and i have thought it might have been infected pours muddy dark amber brown with a huge huge head ( my first thought of infection ) that left lacing all down the glass smells of some apples ( # 2 ) but could be raisins - get some brown sugar and oatmeal taste - has lots of roasted malt and chocolate which surprised me - cinnamon and other flavors that reminded me of xmas - those same raisins/apples that seem a bit off mouthfeel - was lacking - the body thin and was flat ?

very impressive pour -- hearty black body with a hidden clarity that sparks to a cola color in the light . the head is towering , tan , and slooow to recede . with all those german hops , i 'd expect nothing less than excellent lacing , and seventeen succeeds in that aspect , coating the inside of the glass with thick webs of foam .  but the bottle i had was too carbonated which gave it a bad mouthfeel , blocking the tastes .
gorgeous . thin white head does n't stay around very long .  mouthfeel is the most dissappointing part of this beer ; it 's far too watery .

bottle into a midnight sun cervoise , the kodiak is more garnet then dark brown , with an initially very thick frothy head , that slowly subsides to a thick collar , light skim and scattered lace . very appealing , though , darker then i expected .  thin . thinner than their lager . kind of sad , really , as the thin body nearly ruins this otherwise nice stout .

the pour on this is awesome like every nitro can , nice tiger stripes as it slowly settles out , then you get theat signature nitro one finger white head .  but just barely anything there m-very thin and watery almost no carbonation d-no thanks i 'll be lucky to finish the glass

poured into an imperial pint glass , formed a 1 1/2 '' tan head over the slightly cloudy reddish chestnut brew . head holds on with a miser 's grip , leaving incredibly thick layers of sticky froth .  palate is watery , but drinkable . as i commented to the purveyor , for a pale lager in a can from wisconsin , its not bad .
poured dark dark brown with a brown head .  hops are also low played , like lemon juice and water . thin and oily . carbonation is low , though the yeast inside looks pretty done .
modest to light pour called up a massive five finger head with excellent retention and beautiful copious lace .  not what i want from an ipa . mouthfeel - watery . flat .
poured from a bottle to a tulip has a great clear copper orange body . the head is pretty large and chunky and leaves nice lacing .  m : thin and watery .
it 's alive and frothy ! wonderful head , beautiful jet black color .  m : light on the carbonation , thin & watery .
pours a clear amber color with a great , frothy , off-white head .  overly attenuated , skimpy and lean in overall body , with a mouthfeel that lacks any firm viscosity .

super large foamy white head forms and does n't die down but expands after the pour . settles at a 3/4 inch and leaves behind a nice pock marked appearance with chunks of lace clinging everywhere .  m - watery and very light .

poured from 12oz brown bottle into a clear pint glass a : beautiful hazy yellow-copper with a towering , rocky two-to-three finger head and sheets of lace s : hallertauer hops smell great -- tangy and spicy .  felt very flat and rather unpleasant on the palate .
exceptional looking beer .  very little aroma , mouthfeel 's watery .

dark beer , dark , ample head .  thin and watery . it began pretty cold - a bit more than i would have preferred , so i let it warm up , but that did little , if anything , to produce more of a body .

poured into a pioneer stein ( # 42 , 2009 edition ) , formed a 2 1/2 '' frothy tan head over the slightly cloudy caramel hued brew . head falls slowly with an audible sizzle of bubbles bursting , with tons of lasting lace .  this is not a beer for beer drinkers , pseudo-aficionados , poseurs , whoever ... this is a beer for people who want cheap inebriation , but for whaterver reason do n't want malt liquor . lightly hopped , it has the mouthfeel of water that has been lubricated with the syrup of unfermentable sugars .
pours a beautiful cherry-brown hue with a significant cap of creamy , active foam.. gorgeous .  m- one thing that can not be salvaged , of course , is the thin body and high carbonation .

poured into a snifter , the brew appears black in color with the faintest line of clarity and brown around the edges . a dark brown finger of head appears and as it slowly recedes , leaves spots and a webbing pattern of lace . a swirl revives a full finger worth of dark brown head .  mouthfeel is way thin , and drinkability is just not that great for me .

pours clear dark brown color with a huge 3 finger light tan head with fantastic retention , that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts .  mouthfeel - watery , no bubbles , flat . drinkability - obviously not very drinkable for the fact this is 98 % flat .
the appearance is black with a thick tan head . because of the carbonation , it 's easy to pour this beer a little too aggressively .  let down in the mouthfeel however..very sticky and cloying .

pours the obvious trademark guinness look , prefect creamy white head and the opaque black liquid they call beer .  the main favor is water with some bland barley and only the slightest hops . imo , this is not a bad beer , it is a thirst reliever . if one is drinking beer for flavor skip this one but if one is truly thirsty , this is a decent pick . if one is ever in stockholm , grab one of these at the nearest 7-11 after a day of walking about the city and relieve yourself . save the flavorful beer for a special occasion .
pours a really thick head , nothing frothy but thick and luscious . a golden amber red body , thick with nice color .  very very carbonated sort of like your common soda .
this beer poured a clear golden color with a huge rocky head .  mouthfeel is not so good , since the beer is basically flat .

black with a very thick and creamy head that 's sticking a quarter inch out of the top of the glass and is n't going anywhere .  the mouthfeel has way too much carbonation and detracts from the smoothness of the flavor .

a - great looking beer . pale straw light gold color with a huge white head that takes a while to dissipate .  the taste is average with a slightly bitter aftertaste the mouthfeel is lacking . it feels a bit watered down .

appearance - clear , dark amber body . thick off white head with plenty of texture , lacing , and retention .  a surprisingly thin body with a sharp , tangy effervescence on the tip of the tongue . watery .
poured from my home tap with a deep dark chestnut brown color and a luxuriously creamy beige head .  first of all the palate was very thin , with hints of chocolate and a slightly smoke flavour .

golden , it has a big white head slowly shrinking to a smaller but lasting , puffy , somewhat rocky head , and leaving a lot of nice , frothy lace .  mouthfeel - thin , a little oily from the hops , with very strong carbonation that hits you in the palate towards the finish the drinkability of this beer is very high , it is smooth , and makes a much better impression on people than budweiser , a good transition beer , but not too much to write home about .
nitro tap served at crossroads coffee and icecream on southside richmond , va. a : black with three finger superfine nitro head s : booze !  m- extremely thin , too carbonated .

poured from a corked and capped 750ml heavy bottle dated 12-2000 on the cap . vigourous head remains throughout the session with some lacing on the glass . the beer is hazy golden orange with pinpoint bubbles . it is a composite cork that looks poorly made .  m - not much carbonation ; watery d - no reason to drink more than one .

it poured with a two finger high white head that slowly died down and has excellent retention properties ; a thin head consistently covered the surface .  m-2.0 : watery and thin . the above average hops just ca n't compensate for the weak body and thin feel of this brew .

crystal brown `` loverly '' color . quite effervescent - copious amounts of sea-foam looking suds .  m : 2.0 a very watery beer , while the flavors are constantly present there are no real stand out characteristics in the feel . d : 3.0 goes down easy thanks to its thin consistency .

a - very , very dark black beer .  a text book pilsener-which is a positive note but the bready quality is not full . finish is clean but it has the after-taste of the gaterade power water . drinks ok , and i would enjoy this on a hot summer day-just a bit pricey for a miller lite clone in a nicer bottle .
a - orange-amber with a chunky white head . retention is great and there 's soapy lacing left on the glass .  the mouthfeel is way overcarbonated and harsh .

the head holds awesome retention and lacing on the glass is crazy . really a near perfect looking beer .  the drink started with a quick hit of malt sweetness followed by a hint of carbonation . the overall feel of this one was very american macro crap to me .
very nice appearance , golden and crystal clear with a nice fluffy head leaving no lacing .  really thin , like a light beer . best thing from this brewery .

as it sets in the glass a winsome deep brown to black color with a modest creamy light chocolate head , and as it erodes , the residual lace a fine silky sheet to seal off the glass .  mouthfeel : on thin side .

the looks are by far the best part of this beer . it poured a clear gold/amber with great white head and lacing .  the mouth-feel is quite thin and it feels as though each mouth-full never quite materializes .

a - pours to a two finger tan head . body has a rich amber or reddish brown tint . cloudy with no visible particulate . beautiful lacing clings to the glass .  mouthfeel seems remarkably thin here , even for style .
pours a deep dark brown with thick creamy dark khaki head that leaves lots of lacing !  mouthfeel was very light in body and watery in texture with a flat carbonation .
a : looks gorgeous . a pale gold color with a giant head .  however the body of the beer let it down , very watery , no head retention ; this very quickly started to remind me of lager .
) it looks amazing . amazing .  mouthfeel is flat with too little carbonation .

it 's a very dark brown with a thick , creamy head . as i drank the beer , the sides of the glass were almost totally covered in foam . between the color and the great lacing , this glass of guinness is probably the best looking beer i 've had so far .  mouthfeel is very tame , no carbonation in mouthfeel , though overall there is carbonation in the beer .

this brew pours a beautiful small dark brown head with bubbles of all sizes and a pitch black opaque body with some carbonation seen rising up the side of the mug .  the flavor is only surpassed , or should i say , harshened due to the over carbonated mess of a mouthfeel - i 'm left with a harsh boozy almost acidic/sour flavor in my mouth .

pours honey colored with 3 fingers of rocky egg shell white head . insane lacing & head retention s : biscuitty malt & leafy hops t : biscuitty malt , leafy & minty hops up front , plus slight medicinal juniper twang .  carbonation is fizzy .

poured a dark , golden amber into my affligem gold-rimmed goblet . looks beautiful .  smell-fairly clean , i do detect some malt but not much else , no hoppiness , alcohol , or otherwise . taste-fairly tasteless , some malt does come through again but for the most part this tastes like water . drinkability-somewhat malty and low abv , you could pound these that 's for sure . overall-yawn , sorry for the not so detailed review but this is another not so detailed light beer , even from an ok brewery like pocono .
bright amber body topped with a thick creamy head leaving plenty of lace .  f - pretty limp , even more than i remember . like stout-flavored water .

pours a very hazy red-brown with a fluffy , fizzy khaki head that dies down within about a minute . good lacing too - really a nice looking pour .  the beers got a big body , almost too big for its style . its not terrible , the body is really killing this one for me .

watching this beer settle is part of it 's mistique - its a lava lamp for beer geeks ... once settled , a perfect 1-finger head of slightly off-white cream meets a pitch black beer . the commercial ( widget bottle , nitro-can ) are pale shadows compared .  nearly flat and medium-bodied , the mouthfeel becomes slick towards the end and the drinkability suffers .

pours a fairly deep black , letting in only a tiny bit of light , with a dense 2 finger head . great retention leaves behind abundant creamy lacing , and a thick blanket of foam on top of the glass . looks great .  t/m : very thin ... highly carbonated ... gives more of a champagne quality than a sour yeast ... lacks body . just fizzy . lacks body .

a finger of white head , lgiht brown body . good lace .  the taste is pretty much the same , grains . there is a sharp bite of carbonation , and the coldness is getting to me . this is the beer that defines drinkability , they go down like water .
nitro produces a wonderful cascading effect .  it was certainly interesting and different , sadly its mouthfeel did n't do it for me .
very good looking .  the mouthfeel is medium and watery with almost no carbonation ( seems to be common of ep beers ) .
cloudy goldenrod with great creamy pure white head and lacing .  ok mouthfeel is pretty bad . thin and watery .
a - awesome head ! ! ! pours into crazy shapes ... brew is cloudy orange/amber color . lots of great lacing .  m : mouthfeel is oily , almost cloying .
appearance - very nice deep copper/amber color . a solid almost two inches of soapy off-white head . looks great .  very thin and watery .

pours a full black color with a thick , frothy coffee brown head . retains well with plenty of cloudy film and thick coats of lacing on the glass .  a little too grassy , and excess carbonation , not nearly enough hop bite . thin body .

winter version this beer pours deep orange-amber and is very hazy -- no filtration here . the off-white , creamy head lingers for the duration and also features great lacing .  m : mouthfeel ruined it . way too fizzy , drinks like a coke .

from the bottle . poured black with a small tan head with some lacing .  light roast lingers in the finish , not much bitterness , but again a very thin body detracts majorly from this beer and keeps it from being recommendable .

blend 3 bottled 1/18/11 poured into a tulip appearance- pours ruby red , transparent with lots of active carbonation . large fluffy white head , with a touch of pink . great retention and nice lacing .  hops and malts fought each other for control and left the mouthfeel watery and thin .
this beer pours an amber color with a big head and excellent lace .  tastes very watery . low ratings on taste and mouth feel reflect the lack of flavor rather than bad flavor .

lot and lots of foam reminiscent of a soda more than a beer , but once gone , left great lacing . it feels a bit thin for a stout but you would never know it was eight percent .  rather thin . left a grimey feeling in my mouth .
pours a very dark brown with a brown head that rises and stays . lot 's of sticky lacing .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and watery .

hold it up to the light to see something really incredible . an amazing looking beer .  way too much carbonation..and the mouthfeel is too bubbly . even if the carbonation was done well , i do n't think this would be anything better than an `` above-average '' porter .
pours black with a lasting , thick , brown head and nice lasting .  light mouthfeel , overly carbonated . this was n't bad , but it was too thin .

clear , 500ml bottle , bb : ( see neck ) nothing there~~ a : in a straight pint glass it pours a reddish chestnut hue , coming with a thick , very frothy , off-white beer head full of medium and small air cells , sustaining very well and supported by a constant and moderate carbonation .  mouthfeel is equally uninspired , with body on the lifeless , watery side .

poured pitch black , not rigerous , but not gentle . this is not ment as a stab , but just a highlight of how great the retention , head and lace are .  almost a gelatinous/soggy grain feel . the carbonation cuts it as best it can .
a - poured a beautiful black color with a dark tan head . the head retention was moderate .  there is no body to this wit . it drinks like a cheap lager leaving very little for the finish .

comes to the table with a wonderfully cascading creamy off-white head . huge sheets of lace , and an ever present nice cap round off a nice nitro appearance , which is only marred by the fact that the russet coloured body is off base for a porter .  flat and watery mouthfeel , very thin , no body .

gentle pour yields a slowly rising , and rising , and rising 3 finger , thick , rich , mocha head with great retention . lacing is pretty outrageous . patterned , good legs , and great stick . complex and a sexy looking beer ... feel is a bit off though .  low carbonation leading to flat mouthfeel .
a bright white decent sized head that looks fluffy and creamy at the same time .  m : mouthful was disappointing , bland and thin .

if nothing else , olde mecklenburg makes gorgeous beers . the head is ample , pale-cream , and tight . mecktoberfest is , over all , a solid sessionable , gorgeous beer , whose only fault is a hit of diacetyl .  watery mouthfeel ... i felt the lack of body a little disappointing , i was expecting far more creamyness .

kozel master tmavy 18 .4l draft served in stem ware in pilsen a - near black and opaque with reddish mahogany at edges/ generous creamy tan head that leaves patchy lacing . remnants of head lasted until the end during an entire meal .  except for the very poor mouthfeel , a great beer , one that i would recommend from the bottle .
imposing two fingers of tannish head top off a really nice looking brew .  texture is far too thin and watery .
deep brown with lots of carbonation , huge tan head and it looked really good !  the mouthfeel was too full bodied for the style and was a major negative point .
a ) bronze in color . poured with a thin creamy head . nice lacing along the edge .  and the mouthfeel is oddly thin , does n't fit well with the boozy vibe .
opaque brown , little light comes through , mousse-like dark tan head of good retention .  thin , spritzy body .
very nice looking brew .  carbonation is too strong , nearly soda-like , with a plastic-y feel that coats the mouth . lightly sticky .

big tan head than retains . s-hard to really get a good whiff past the giant head . not a very intense head .  a thin beer , it 's a bit watery with a heavy orange and clove taste . the smell and flavor of this beer is great , but the mouthfeel really takes away from it .

wow , this brew has a really nice color . a nice clear amber that insist you to drink it all up immediately . : ) ) the head is frothy light white and quite big .  the feel is pretty terrible ; flat , lifeless , sweet with some metallic bitterness . it is sweet from the dark fruit which is nice but no carbonation just kills this beer .

poured a massive tan frothy head ( granted it was a bit warmer ) but retained itself at a half finger for quite a while . very dark , almost black , but not hazy .  m : the lack of malts hurt the mouthfeel and the endurance of flavor . i realize that apwas are meant to be light , refreshing quaffs but gumballhead , in my opinion , would benefit from a slightly beefier body and thicker texture . the amount of carbonation is average or below and leaves a little to be desired as well . d : despite the low mouthfeel score , gumballhead is still an excellent brew and i would purchase cases of it during the summer months if only fff would distribute to pa , the greedy sobs .
amazingly translucent .  mouthfeel : smooth but horribly dry , especially on the finish , which is reminiscent of a stale cracker .
a : pours is phenomenal with a dark black color and a nice mocha/dark khaki head . the head is a solid two finger size and lasts a long time . decent lacing .  m : incredibly light body .

poured a murky dark copper hue with a two and a half finger pillowy white head . there was excellent retention and sticky lacing .  a - this beer poured a light golden color , crystal clear , that produced a foamy white head that disappeared quickly and left no lacing on the glass , not surprised s - the only notes on the nose where malts and lager yeasts t - this beer had a one dimensional taste to it , as one would expect from a regular lager , not a harshness i get from adjunct lagers , but still pretty lame m - this beer had a very thin watery body , and was loaded with carbonation d - this beer would be a very drinkable beer in the summertime to quench the thirst , if not for the high amounts of carbonation , which seems to accompany most abitas .

a- one of the nicer looking ipa 's i 've seen . dark orange body with a solid finger 's worth of head , and very intense carbonation .  unfortunately the mouthfeel is like that of a soda just going stale .

the beer was a beautiful translucent red that reminded me of a paulaner salvator with very little head .  body is very thin and rather watery , and the finish is akin to a watered-down lemon-lime soda .

bomber poured into a tulip glass . beer pours a mostly clear copper color with a slight chill haze coming out of the refrigerator . initial two fingers of off white head , mix of small bubbles and tight foam . retention was good for a few minutes before slowly dissipating , leaving a thick layer of lacing along the edge of the glass , down to a collar of small bubbles . plenty of fine carbonation floating up from the bottom of the glass .  the taste is allright ( besdies the odd must ) , some roastiness in here but the thing that bothered me was the mouthfeel .
a- pours a deep brownish hue with a 3 finger , chunky , medium brown head .  super fizzy carbonation works for this beer but i still wish it was n't so fizzy .

pours a beautiful deep , dark , burgundy/brown/amber with a very thick medium head of very tight bubbles that has fair lasting power with a nice lasting lace .  a weak attempt at a flemish sour . the beer has good light redish color and the lactic sourness is present but it is thin and watery . no hop aroma or other funky lambic type aromas , just a lactic beer .

the apperance is exceptional , gold honey in color , the usual amber color . the head was a gorgeous cream color that lasted the whole way through .  m - a little too carbonated for my liking - sharp and harsh bite and burn to the lips and upper palate .
pours a deep golden with cascading bubbles that create a dense and very very creamy head . absolutely beautiful .  very thin in the mouth .

poured as a completely opaque dark brown/reddish color with an outstanding creamy tan head . reminds me of guinness even though it 's a different appearance .  thin , thin . m - very low carbonation & i do n't like that ! needs more carbonation ! feels thin and slightly creamy then stale going down .

drank from a 12 fluid ounce bottle best by 08/27/08 served in a pint glass thanks to my roommate mel for bringing this one back from oregon . the beer poured a clear ( with some floating yeast particles from the bottle conditioning ) , deep orangey-amber color with a tight , frothy , sticky , off-white head that left tons of lacing down the glass .  mouthfeel is bad . it burns there is so much carbonation .

paid 150ft ( .60eur ) for a 500ml bottle ... *reviewed on 13.07.2005 the beer pours a clear brown base with a beautiful large white head , exceptional pinky sized head retention for all 50 minutes and a beautiful cascade of lacing effects - maybe the prettiest beer i 've ever seen !  mouthfeel is thin , typical saranac . why do all their brews lack body ?

black as black can be . medium brown head that laces with authority . highly , highly drinkable for the style , the overbearing chocolate/coffee flavors canceling out a lot of the bitterness and making it very smooth .  slight caramel flavors present mouthfeel : thin and highly carbonated .

pours a clear , amber color with a huge amount of carbonation . the head is thick and frothy , i 'm really digging the appearance .  the mouthfeel is very lively , very slippery/oily and buttery . too carbonated , which is strange for a stout . drinkability is ok given the high abv , but the bitterness , aftertaste and carbonation cancel that out somewhat .
a - beautiful beer . big bubbly head , slightly opaque yellow body with beautiful streams of bubbles rising rising throughout , nice textured lacing .  very thin .
on review i still find it slightly underwhelming . beautiful witbier appearance cloudy , and inviting .  the mouthfeel is medium to light bodied and pretty watery which washes out the flavors .

very dark . pitch black ; even when illuminated . the head is thick , tan and creamy . this is what you want a stout to look like . you can watch the head grow as the bubbles make their way both up and down the glass .  mouthfeel was a bit thin and slippery .

sampled on 3-16-07 best before 6-09 pours a nice and clear golden color with an unbelievably massive head that just sits on the top and then settles on the sides of the glass .  it 's cheap , surprisingly light-tasting ( for a 40 ) and packs a mighty whallop in terms of buzz . as a long fan of steel reserve 211 and st. ides , i admit that they do n't stand up to double malt in terms of taste and mouthfeel .
i may be a little biased , but i love to just admire and look at beers this black and opaque .  m - light bodied , overly acidic .
served in a tulip . pours a golden-peach color with a very large white head and quite a bit of lacing on the way down .  it 's heavy and a little cloying . the mouthfeel is thick and unpleasant .

a slow pour yields a 2-finger fluffy off-white head that slowly recedes in a few minutes to a thick covering . the body is a clear amber with literal streams of carbonation bubbles rushing upward . minimal lacing is seen throughout consumption . the beer looks great and the mouthfeel is excellent but without a good flavor or smell , it falls very short .  mouthfeel : sharp at first , but the carbonation quickly fades away to a watery limpness .
jet black with a dark brown head with excellent retention and nice lacing , this is a gorgeous stout .  flavor was shallow , sweetness was hardly there at all , and mouthfeel was really thin .

pours black with a big , fluffy brown head that is slow to dissipate . looks rich and forboding at the same time .  ca n't get any metalic taste ( which is a good thing ) m- really high in carbonation to the point where it 's hard to pick out flavors . d- it is good just the high carbonation totally kills it .
( a ) - pours a hazy yellow color that produced a fantastic white fluffy head with solid retention behind it .  mouthfeel is watery and not that great .

plumes of billowing bubbles bloom in this crystal clear honey colored brew . head is a large , off-white and meringue-like head that shimmers and sparkles and glimmers while being fed by the frantic carbonation below . looks great and smells and tastes pretty good .  the taste is disappointing , just a german macro really . too thin , not much taste.barely average , but sub-par for the price .

poured a hazy amber/orange color with a frothy white head filling a half inch of the glass . it had both very nice head retention as well as very nice lacing on the sides of the glass .  mouthfeel watery + light .

'' and we 're off to the nitro can races . dead-sexy reverse-cascading , cream colored head sits one finger high atop a black body . at least it looks good . not worth a purchase , especially with so many more american craft breweries attempting the dry irish style ( 3f 's black sun , anyone ?  lots of carbonation and quite watery .
poured into a pint glass a : gentle pour ( in case there was sediment - there was n't ) yields 2/3 finger creamy cream colored head with great retention .  dissapointing mouthfeel , muted flavors .

it reminds me of a good piece of saddle leather . simply beautiful !  the carbonation is ( too ) strong . the stronger old spelcked hen is an ok pale ale , but this one was watered down in every way .

appearance- mahagoney-cherry colored elixer . great large bubbled lace chunks cling for life over much of my glass . a glorious sight .  it had a slight hint of strawberry but other than that , i felt like it tasted pretty much like nothing , just sort of like drinking carbonated water .

pours out a pale golden/straw color with a lively carbonation , a thick head that stays around as you drink , and incredible lacing patterns . a true pilsner should strive to look this good .  the beer is failed by its thin and bubbly mouthfeel , though .
a perfect look for an impy .  mouthfeel is unremarkable , almost like water .

very nice color , reddish brown . the beer is very clear , without a hint of haze or sediment . the head is an off-white color , pours a two inch head that settles down to a solid quarter inch through the rest of the beer .  t/m : the mouthfeel is thin and quite watery ; the taste is equally limp . mouthfeel and a general weakness of character ruins any chance at more than a passable brew .

on-tap at toronado sd a : the pour is almost black in color with a fluffy tan head that leaves sheets of lacing all the way down the glass .  the taste is o.k. , but the mouthfeel really drags this beer down for me .

a - extremely dark , nearly black . a huge , pinkish-brown head that just does not go away . lots and lots of lacing .  the mouthfeel is severely lacking . water , with a very light carbonation the fails to liven this beer up .

notes from 08/25/2010 : 12 oz can at 45 degrees into a stone irs tulip . a : it pours a luscious golden-orange color with a fluffy finger of off-white head that holds and laces well .  thin , watery mouth , very little body .

a-pours a beautiful hazy orange color with lots of a thick white head . the head has some solid retention , takes some time to go down , and leaves lots of lacing on the glass .  mouthfeel was a bit flat and watery , and the carbonation made this beer seem harsh and scratchy .
i do n't like ambers , but this one is interesting . the looks are one of the best i have ever seen . lovely light amber colour .  way too much malt presence . carbonation is weighed down .
a : a huge , frothy , mocha colored cap that leaves behind huge clumps of lace sits atop a black body .  mouth is thin and bit watered down .

in a tulip glass at track 84. i will admit , i did n't get much aroma at all from this . drinkability was off the charts , but that made sense once i saw the abv was at the low end of the imperial stout range .  almost no head and very thin mouthful . this reminds me of cider .

pours a slight hazy golden yellow ... pours with quite an impressive head , lacing is also very impressive ... wow , very bitter ; not at all balanced and the alcohol is not really hidden at all.. .  2.0 m thin like water , not impressed .

this beer is a deep mohogany/black brew . decent lacing .  a- light , golden , clear , no real head or lacing s- sweet , honey , cinnamon , hint of liquorice/mint t- very light , not much pumpkin m- very light and thin d- i could drink this for hours ( not in a good way ) it does n't have any of the weight or warmth that i want in a fall beer .

bottle i picked up in seward , into a midnight sun goblet , the artic rhino coffee porter is a dark , inky black , with a small but thick , creamy tan head , leaving thick foamy lace .  m - pretty light bodied . surprising lack of carbonation given the beautiful head on this .

pours a dark dark dark brown ( pretty much black ) with a crazy thick inch of dark brown foam/head which leaves a boat ton of sticky brown lacing .  likely one reason for the weakness of the taste is the watered down mouthfeel .

taken from notes pours a light orange vibrant color with a two and half inch white fluffy head . good retention that leaves bits amount of lacing clinging to the sides of my glass .  just very watery and has an odd mouthfeel and finish to it .

exceptional appearance ... very dark brown with a pillowy head that clings in a beautiful lace .  some sweetness at the start , but the palate gets watery and thin quite quickly ... so not much body to speak of .

a : nearly clear off-white yellow with puffy fine bubbles head that kept it all the way , great lacing s : mild nose with spicy yeast , some soft floral aspects too t : traditional saison with earthy/floral qualities probably from elderflowers , noticeable hop bite in finish , hops were more than normal for a saison but not offensive m : decent mouthfeel with all the qualities of a saison ( yeasty , spritzy ) but with stronger hop finish  m - low carbonation , slick , flat finish .

the colour is brown with a tint of orange ; the liquid is hazy . the high head is compact and beige , it slowly sinks down to a thick lid with lots of lacing on the glass .  m - this is where the beer is odd ... when cold , a really carbonated mouthfeel that is unappealing .

a - an inch of creamy white head sits on top of a pale golden-orange beer . the head has some legs and sticks around for awhile . it leaves plenty of sticky lacing as it settles .  medium carbonation , no body , just water , spritzy bubbles .
great pour , and nice looking , properly-thin head . it looks great though , and smells good too .  '' the mouthfeel is unfortunately thin , and the taste is pretty bland in general .
appearance - pours a dark ruby with a creamy cratered tan head , lots of sticky lacing .  feel is thin .
this beer really looks awesome overall .  thin feel .
pours almost the perfect shade of amber with a stoic , rocky off-white head . frothy patches of lace line the glass .  however water overrides any other flavor m - very thin .
pours a beautiful hazed gold , reminiscent of belgian witbiers and not exactly the german hefeweizen .  m- here is the downfall , it 's too thin for the style .

moderately thick and quite sticky light tan head has excellent retention and leaves plenty of lacing on the glass all the way down .  mouthfeel was too light for the style with a moderate amount of carbonation .

a- pours nearly total black , but glows red against light . huge tan head , beautiful foam that flows out and down the glass .  lightly hopped and sparkling on the tongue , this brew is quite flavorful , and has a mouthfeel of carbonated water .

this sammy pours a bright clear golden orange with a pretty big , rocky white head .  m - there simply is n't enough texture here for a great dunkel . at first it seems almost medium but the brew quickly becomes far too thin for the style .
a- big darker tan head on a clear deep amber body ( ca n't really see through it til you hold it up to the light ) .  mouthfeel : pretty thin and watery for any beer , but especially so for a stout .

from the bottle , poured dark brown to black , with a nice foamy tan head , with good lacing .  the mouthfeel is hot as hell . let a mouthful of this rest on your palate for 10-15 seconds , and it feels like the insides of your mouth are being dissolved . it 's very astringent and has a monster bite.the aftertaste is just ... boozy .
this brew pours with a dark brown to black body topped by a thick , light brown head with a goos amount of lacing .  mouthfeel is thin and flat .
