the beer pour the traditional atramentous guinness color , the head monsterous and a creamy chocolate brown , with the lace sticky and thick nose is coffee , bittersweet chocolate , nice malt aroma , what a treat for the old schnozzles .  i was really looking forward to my first sip of this years bbcs on draft until the chap next to me said it was thin . my first sip tasted fantastic but yes it did indeed feel thin . as it warmed it should have gotten tastier but the thinness was more obvious than it was cold .

this beer looks great . i just sat and watched the color transform from a blonde coffe color to jet black . the head was a good dark khaki color . now that i 've said that it looks cool , i 'm not that impressed .  mouthfeel is where this beer falls apart . in all of that i can sense that the body is thin , could be more viscous .

crystal clear burnt orange with a generous head that clings lacy and lasts well down the glass .  mouthfeel was light and thin , due to the low carbonation , so it was lacking the smooth velvety body that you would expect from a oatmeal stout .
appearance- dark black pour with a very large creamy head . lacing was nice as well .  mouthfeel : watery texture , medium body and low carbonation .

poured from a 12oz bottle into a sam adams pint glass : appearance : pours a beautiful orangy hazy yellow sunsetty color with a huge 3 finger foamy , honey comb like head . lots and lots of lacing down the glass , huge head retention . one of the best in this style .  mouthfeel : the mouthfeel does n't carry the taste evenly - it 's too smooth and yet too coarse at the same time .
head falls at an average pace , down to a smaller mountain of froth , with coating sticky lace prevalent .  m - moderate to low carbonation and almost watery .
single from a mixed six poured into a pint glass a : aggressive pour yields 1.5 fingers of dense brown head with good retention . perfect .  m - very thin ... too thin for me .
lacing is pretty good too . very nice looking beer .  mouthfeel- thin , and light in body .

exceptional poured revealed a giant thick and chunky beige head.almost looked like a rootbeer float.long strands of sticky lace circled my glass.the aroma was great with smells of cinnamon , nutmeg , and hops.a medium body ale with a dark almost black red color.the finish was long and bitter that lasted in the back of your throat.the finish had an almost chemical or medicine-like taste.very malty and somewhat thick.the aroma seemed to offer more than the actual taste.a very smooth mouthfeel that seemed to lack in carbonation upon swallowing.an overall good beer.i would buy this again because i think the taste will grow on me later .  the mouthfeel was weak bodied and highly carbonated .
darker than yellow but not quite red , my favorite look for a iipa . looks pretty clear , and has a giant head , that lasts throughout the entire drink .  just a poor belgian overall .
appearance : medium amber colour with a giant rocky bone white head . looked very appetizing with real blueberries dancing up and down in the glass .  m - thin . very thin .
the beer is nearly black . some deep scarlet red streaks can be seen against light . decent size and retention as well .  light body and literally no carbonation .

1in off-white creamy foamy later with great retention , bubbles rise through the slightly hazy brew turning the head into swiss cheese with chunks of wispy wavy lace on the glass .  mouthfeel is very thin and watery , and does nothing to enhance the thin flavors .
pours nearly black and opaque with a huge dense dark brown head .  the mouthfeel is off , it is way to thin .

this pours out a pitch-black color with a thick dark tan head of about three fingers height , a picture perfect stout . the head recedes fairly quickly to a cap of bubbles leaving scattered lacing around the glass .  the mouthfeel leaves a lot to be desired . thin , and too much carbonation .
pours a full three finger head . great retention and lacing .  m/d - it is unbelievably thin .

poured into a snifter a : very dark pour which gives a huge head , coffee colored . fantastic sticky lacing all over the place s : roasted malts dominate the nose , but there is some coffee present too .  fairly thin with a lot of carbonation , watery , with some hop flavor . i am really enjoying all the craft beer i 've been drinking lately , but a bunch of miller lites iced down in a cooler on a hot summer day will work for me anytime .

this beer pours a seemingly familiar deep , practically opaque dark brown oily hue , with a ton of foamy , rocky head , which settles in the glass at the three finger mark , slowly receding to reveal a nice dense curtain of lace around the glass .  mouthfeel - pretty thin .

as it calmed down it looked great . could n't really ask for much more . for an american ipa this seemed to lack the floral/citrus appeal , the cascades seemed light .  m- thin and carbonated . probably the worst dimension to this so-so beer .

pitch black with a large 1 '' creamy redish khaki head . looks like black coffee ( with an added head ) .  the taste can only be described as `` extremely watery '' . as far as mouthfeel goes , once again the key words are `` extremely watery '' . flat and dull .

a : pours a deep golden color with bright gold hues when held to light . a nice finger of creamy white head crowns the brew .  its certainly fine for the style , but would never wow anyone , unlike the carbonation , which made me think 'wow , this is fizzy ' .
paulaner original munchner , draft .3l a nice copper color clear . nice head , stayed the whole glass .  m - very watery , light bodied and even undercarbonated .

this brew poured a copper color liquid with a foamy off-white head . the head stayed around for the entire time , and the lacing left was tremendous . the carbonation seemed a bit out of control .  the mouthfeel is light and watery .

poured into an ommegang tulip glass a - bronze appearance with orange hues , crystal clear , with scattered carbonation bubbles rising to the surface . a very inviting beer by the looks . s - aroma has a bready backbone with some piney hops mingling with a slight grapefruit scent .  it does leave a really nice lingering coffee flavor on your palate m : very thin . lacks carbonation .

pours opaque black color with a very dense 2 finger tan head with incredible retention that reduces to a fairly thick lacing cap that lasts .  my biggest disappointment was the mouthfeel with no lasting carbonation or creaminess .

a two-finger high frothy head sits atop of the body . after sustaining itself for a few minutes , the head leaves behind a clingy white surface layer with soem lacing on the glass .  it has an ok flavor , but it 's very thin .

nice amber color with a good heavy 1.5 inch head . it receded quickly but left excellent freckled lacing down my pint .  t : watery mouthfeel overall is saved by light yeast , malty goodness and peanut shells in the finish .

look : murky orange in color with a 1 inch head and great retention and spoty lacing smell : piney and citrus hops sting the nose .  watery porter with good bittersweet chocolate malt . finish is dry and watery , with overwhelming carbonation .
a- cork shot off like champagne , pouring pitch black with an ever-growing tan head that retained well and left excellent retention .  mouthfeel is a bit thin and watery .
black as nite . amazing layers of stacked , brown foam .  watery body .

a - pours black brown , large frothy tan head , sticky lacing , large cap . this one was very frothy , sticky , and dark . the brett adds another dimension onto an already stellar quad .  it is thin bodied despite the nitro , with a masked , watery aroma . the beer may perhaps be too traditional to appreciate as it shows more modesty than american craft beers usually do . shannon 's core values are a dry grain and chaff taste with some show of dark lace . but the lack of body and flavor are obstacles to appreciation .

this porter when poured into my glass had a large tan frothy head with fine-small bubbles .  diluted watered down light to medium feel that washes back with a diluted overall feel , however lending to some drinkability , but lacking in carbonation . tacky cloying aftertaste .

a - pours a clear yellow with a big fluffy white head . the head really likes to stick around on this one , and leaves a lot of beautiful , sticky lacing down the entire glass .  the mouthfeel is extraordinarily watery .

a - a vigorous pour brought out the captain 's true beautiy ; a fat cream head with great retention and absolutely superb lace that covered the entire glass like foamy suds from the tides of the sea . the beer also featured a beautifully clear copper color with mild carbonation action . d - how a beer can look stunning , possibly the best amber i 've ever seen , and still be this bad is astounding .  some light but lasting carbonation . leaves mouth feeling bubbly and sudsy .

when this porter was poured into my glass , it poured with a dark brown head that unfortunately did not last very long .  just a touch of carbonation zing at the swallow . i just dont know what to think , and that slimey mouthfeel is really starting to irritate my gag reflex .

great retention .  hops and barely . for a light beer it was actually pretty heavy . but other then that it was a light beer . in my mouth it was refeshinting , just like water which is what it tasted like . water .

intricate webs of lacing are left behind , absolutely gorgeous looking beer .  ) version of carlsberg 's elephant bock . this is one of my standard `` crap beers , '' the ones that you 're ashamed to admit you enjoy ( hey , we ca n't drink belgians all the time ) . it 's cheap , easy to stomach , tastes decent and has a cool elephant head on the label .
a : pours a hazy amber color with a fluffy yellow head . about one finger in height and leaves some great lace down the glass .  mouthfeel is extremely thin for the style with no chewiness at all .

this is how lagers should look . a beautiful golden color with a steady head that stays well .  this beer is able to skate by because it 's not cloying and the sourness distracts for the most part , but i can only imagine how good this would be if it were properly carbonated .

ebony the color on the pour , the head unboastful in size , light chocolate in color , the texture frothy , and as it evanesces , the lace left behind a fine covering upon the glass .  m : very thin on the palate , incredibly light bodied with high carbonation .
a great looking brew .  mouthfeel - extremely watery overall - an uninteresting yet swilling pumpkin ale .

bottle courtesy of jjpm74 : poured a clear dark black color ale with a big foamy head with perfect retention and perfect lacing .  very watery mouthfeel : very light body and i swear i can feel those floaties on my tongue , very disturbing .
pours a nice amber color with a slight haze and plenty of foamy , white head that sticks around . good carbonation .  carbonation is ridiculously high . the carbonation problem is a real worry .

pours a gorgeous rich amber color , with a off white 2 finger head .  taste , amazingly thin , and keeps getting thinner . very creamy for the lack of thickness , a smooth , smoky , thin stout without any degree of bitterness of hops . but throughout , its just tough to get over the thin body for this beer . makes it more drinkable , but the difficulty in finding this stuff , as well as the price , makes it a little cost prohibitive for something this thin .

poured from a 750ml bottle the ber showed a very dark red , opaque in the middle but translucent blood red on the edges . white head that had excellent retention and left a beautiful lacing on the glass .  the real indicator was the body too thin and the general overall weakness will not make this a serious porter contender .
nice light straw-colored pour with a resilient fluffly rocky head that remains to the last goddamned drop .  m - watery . boring .
a - it 's damn hot and muggy here right now , and the bright golden body and thick , fluffy white head 'atop this beer looks really damn good .  mouthfeel is absolutely awful and inconsistent .

pours a deep , clear , gem-like amber colour . after settling , it has the creamiest , thickest white head i 've seen come out of a nitro can . settles as a sturdy film and collar without leaving any real lace .  the mouthfeel is far too thin .
a really gorgeous looking ipa from bend . deep burnt orange , slightly hazy , lovelly creamy off white head of great stature..a veritable visual work of art .  mouthfeel is super thin and watery .
it pours a gorgeous deep mahogany hue with a small but very long lasting tan-colored head . excellent , excellent lacings remain after the head has gone .  mouthfeel : thin and watery .
pours black with a large lasting tan head .  drinks : warm , the obnoxious funk flavor , paired with the unsettling mouthfeel , makes this beer nigh undrinkable .
the stiff head sits on a clear yet dark brown body . the head remains throughout . the appearance of this one is the highlight .  mouthfeel was also very light and thin .

pours a cloudy golden amber with tea tones filled with a massive head of white foam that melts very slowly to extremely sticky white lace .  dry as anything , with an unacceptable watery finish . the second bc stout lately to be really watery .
poured a deep amber-reddish color with a dense head .  m thin and really kind of boring .

pours a very nice looking darkish gold . darker than almost all macro lagers . an attractive lager .  since it is so thin compared to other stouts , i do have to rate it accordingly . sorry but it could be thicker .
pours a very nice clear deep auburn . a small off white head produces good lacing .  unfortunately the lack of carbonation turns this into an overly sweet and cloying mess .

excellent head that retreats to a rocky froth ; great lace too . the color is an orange-light amber with an acceptable amount of cloudiness .  mouthfeel was simply too thin for the style and for the abv .
on tap ( in a 32oz masskrug ) at the brewery , it has a beautiful orange glow and the perfect cloudiness .  m- watery and uneventful . no fizz or carbonation factor .

extremely dense black , like a stout , with a thick , creamy dark tan foam cap .  i really love the taste but the complete lack of carbonation is disappointing . i like this but even with some mild carbonation i would love this !

a soft pour fails to prevent an aggressive 2.5 inch head from forming . the head has some serious staying power and leaves plenty of lacing down the chalice .  too thin and the carbonation is too high given the taste . overall : the taste and smell of this beer are amazing , but the mouthfeel really took away from the beer .
it pours a dark amber brown , with thick white head . quite beautiful really .  m - the one flaw . too wet and smooth .

pours a dark black with a creamy white head and the standard brownish alive cool looking action in the beer before it settles to black with the cream head that lasts . this is not lacing , as the beer moves from the glass the creamy composition of the head literally stays on the glass .  mouthfeel is disturbingly thin and does n't have a lot of body at all .

a beautiful looking beer .  the middle is thin and sweetens some . when cold , the finish is slightly metallic with some obvious alcohol . this is n't bad compared to american macros and some other strong export lagers , but that 's about it .
huge sheets of lacing and good retention .  m - very , very thin .
really like the color . great head retention .  much too much carbonation .
super dark in color , allowing no light to pass through .  m - medium bodied with poor carbonation levels . the carbonation is just wrong for this style of beer .

a : this is a really pretty beer . rich golden amber hue with a good sized cloudy , wispy head . retention is great for the style and it left thick rings of lace down the glass .  the first had carbonation while the second was still . flat beer is not enjoyable . if i want a no carbonation beverage i will drink one . the flavor is good but ... i wo n't buy it again unless i can be assured of carbonation .

12 oz bottle into into a snifter - best before 7/18/10 nice looking beer ... golden orange and slightly murky smell is a letdown .  carbonation is too high , only further deteriorating that dry finish .

pours black with a great tan head with lots of thick body to it . outstanding lacing leaving webs on all parts of the glass the brew touches .  highly carbonated to boot . thin finish , left me wondering a bit . still thin and contrived , but does n't seem as contrived as i remember , but seems like the same beer to me .

on tap at o'brien night of a million zillion speedways look : black and totally opaqu with a 1/8 inch head and good retention smell : the slovenian hops used to dry hop it created a piney note that did not really work with the coffee backbone taste : sadly the flavor was worse than the smell .  thin finish . ) the feel is watery and fizzy .
deep , opaque copper/red color . decent head , with the tiniest micro-bubbles , which turn into elegant lace .  2.5/5 m : thin and carbonated . unimpressive .

750ml into duvel glass north of 40 degrees . pours with a thick , soft , and pillowy peach-colored head over a deep maroon colored body , with plenty of carbonation flowing up .  m - hot and sticky . a loser .

perfect pour into me apropos duvel glass . a mountain of meringue head cap . a dark reddish and coppery yet somewhat clear ( first pour ) with a fountain of carbonation running up the middle of the etched d. head cap sticks like it is glued to the glass . second pour contained some yeasty haze . pretty cheap for a 750 ml 8 % er . worth trying , but if you never get it , life will go on .  i 'm not a huge brown ale fan but i 've had some dang good ones lately so i 'm hoping this will be another winner ... pours a warm brown with a very thick creamy head of off white ... very warm and fall-like and makes me wish it was october ... very faint malty earthy aromas that seem rather muted ... toffee and caramel notes for sure but just not pronounced enough for my tastes ... very thin and watery , this one falls short in several categories ... definite caramel malt presence but there 's not enough substance to really enjoy it . almost get a little yeastiness here that mingles with the malts that give this a weird almost oxidized flavor.. sort of sweet and toffee-like but this could really use a little more thickness ... very average brown to me ... might do in a pinch but not one i 'd reach for by choice

dark copper color with a big off-white head and great lacing .  good slightly heavy feel , with a fresh , grassy/hops aftertaste , but in the middle the taste is sort of flat . sure , it has a nice head and a good , piney smell , but the feel is almost empty , like water , and all body is gone . it still has the obvious piney hops smell and taste , but the taste is quickly gone so all you 're left with is a pine-flavored water .
poured a magnificent crystal clear reddish light mahogany with a fluffy tan head . very nice .  m - watery and fizzy - kinda like ginger ale .
pitch black colour , impressive brown head .  thin mouthfeel with a dry center and a rather silent finish .
appearance- beer pulls a hazy golden with a spiderweb pattern across the top .  m - low marks again . thin and not up to snuff .

i love it . nice golden amber color and beautiful frothy head and lacing . good steady carbonation .  the mouthfeel just might be below the level of previous commented on mab , with the watery feel and the slight body .
pours with a crystal clear amber body topped by a medium thick head with lots of lace .  mouthfeel is thin and watery .

felt sneaky drinking a quintessential american pale in an english pub . clear straw color with a thick and creamy white head . peppery skim retention puts up the most impressive display of lacing that i have ever seen on a pale .  mouthfeel : thin and surprisingly flat .
this stout pours with a jet black body topped by a thick brown head with a decent amount of lacing .  m - thin with too much carbonation .

my opinion is close to most others - happy with the appearance , but upon smell , and taste , could not find an affinity .  probably too carbonated , almost prickly on the palate . this is a thin bodied beer , and other from the carbonation it goes down easily enough .

this is the gold standard of color and not to mention head and foam for ths style of beer . what an awesome beige and yellow head and thick film of foam along with the fantastic bubbling .  m : extremely thin , almost water like thickness .
incredible ruby red . decent 1 finger head . in terms of colour , best looking beer i 've ever seen .  do n't like the mouthfeel in this - fizz seems a bit harsh and the body a bit watery .

this beer is a beautiful dark red amber color . i didnt get much head from it but i didnt pour it too fast .  this could have all been amplified with some carbonation . m : this is where cdt loses ... w/out the bubble , the tart and sourness are brought to a silent mumble .
a - pours a deep brown with a finger of tan head and decent retention . an excellent looking beer !  sticky & flabby .
bottled nov. 2007 , batch 3 this looks fantastic . very thick , black , with a dark tan fingers of head .  thin and fizzy in the mouth .
golden with pillowy inch + head . bubbly lacing and constant , constant beading .  mouthfeel is very watery , like a light beer is born to be .
very dark , nearly black , nice brown foamy head , lots of sticky lace .  mouthfeel - very light , watery .

pours a surprisingly dark rich amber , topped by more head than i got from the last two innis & gunn 's i tried and with tons more lacing .  with better carbonation , i think this beer has the elements to be phenomenal .
appearance is great . perfect clear ( no yeast in the pour at first ) peach color with a totally luscious looking cream colored head that wo n't go away and leaves plenty of lacing .  very thin .
appearance : pours a dark auburn body with 2-3 fingers worth of light tan head .  mouthfeel is also tangibly lacking .
the nitro tap produced a tight , creamy one inch head atop a dark brown body .  mouthfeel - thin and watery .

a - it does n't get any better looking than this ; a brilliant golden color with nice clarity and a dense three-finger off-white cream head . sheets of lace cling like webby veils on the glass .  mouthfeel - this is probably my biggest problem with this beer a very watery mouthfeel and it is very under-carbonated , almost flat .

poured out of the large bottle a wonderful pitch black , almost like an onyx gem , the way it reflected light . it had a wonderful tan head and great lacing .  mouthfeel - a little thin and watery for me . also heavily carbonated , which adds an intense unpleasant tingling in the mouth .

a very good looking beer , this poured with a big pillowy pure white head into a bubble pint glass on tap at the firestone taproom in paso robles .  thin and watery mouthfeel with more carbonation then desired for the style . carbonation comeing through strong and man , i just cant get past this watery thin , frail mouthfeel .
pours a dark , hazy amber/brown color .  mouthfeel : watery in comparison to a pint drawn in a good pub with a nitrogen system . the watered down mouthfeel really detracts .

wow , the pour was amazing . the off white head stuck around for a while over the amber red .  mouthfeel is very strange . then an odd meatiness and tannin-laden tongue coating descends upon the palate , rendering all flavors void and unable to be enjoyed .
pitch black , 3 finger mocca head , creamy finish to the head and it 's staying put very well .  mouthfeel was a bit of a disaster , for the style anyway , as it was very thin and lifeless .

pours a hazy dark golden orange/copper color with burnt orange hues when held to a light source and a frothy two finger yellowish beige head . good retention , slowly fading into a lasting cap that coats the glass with chunks of soapy lacing .  m : thin . very dissapointing .

appearance : huge head that never ends with a soft coco color . nice lace trails while pouring followed by deep dark chocolate color to finish it off .  thin mouthfeel . carbonation is overpowering from the rush at the start to the linger at the finish ; this one does n't settle with me all too well .

appearance- pours a hazy pinkish orange with a big beautiful bubbly two fingered bright white head . a great cap and collar is maintained the entire beer along with smell- nice big burst of raspberry right from the get go as it 's fresh and vibrant .  woody creek white , flying dog 's 'new ' summer seasonal , pours as near white as one might imagine possible for a beer , which makes for an impressive look that is countered ( and unfortunately not enhanced ) by a fizzy , quick-to-dissipate head . across the tongue , this really just disappears , and the initial spice and malt flavors turn watery . this is not my favorite colorado wit nor my favorite flying dog brew .
cloudy , lively , thick frothy head with good retention .  mouthfeel : way too thin for this type of beer .

appears a pale gold with a nice 2 finger white head that lasts for about a minute . some solid lines of lacing stick to the glass .  taste/mouthfeel- watery feel to the beer , some grain and alcohol , hops and malt are present but do n't really make much of an impression . drinkability-refreshing on a hot summer day , other than that the thin feel dissapoints .

on-tap at the brewpub : exceptional dark brown nearly black color , thick and rich body , finger high cap of dark ivory thats puffy and whipped smooth with some bumpyness emerging as it settles slowly , very slowly in fact , to a substantial skim and thick collar , good lacing sticks in thick webbings .  weak body and watery mouthfeel .
dark black body , dark milk chocolate head . extremely dark and perhaps the darkest of the yeti beers .  sweet maltiness in the front , but very thin . watery and plain .
had a nice orangy/copper color to it with a slight haze . had a white head to it with excellent lacing that sticks around for the entire drink .  not much in malt or hop character , quite thin .

with a vigorous pour you get a beautiful effect . almost two fingers of rich foamy milk chocolate colored head , that lasts long and leaves lace as it fades .  very light body , coupled with carbonation and sweetness , this was closer to soda pop than banana bread . m=very loose ; no body whatsoever .
i poured into a pint glass to an inch of light tan head that clung to the side of the glass .  mouthfeel : this is its weakness , no body , watery .
has about four fingers of thick tan head that towers an inch over the glass , and a quite hazy brown colored body .  carbonation is out of control and really distracts from truly enjoying this ale .

lots of haze from suspended particles and visible carbonation streaming up , looked wonderful . s - smell was very light and had many fruity esthers , most notably hints of plum , raisin , figs and pears .  thin may be a good description , but it was certainly not in line with what i would expect from an imperial stouts of this style .

as you pour , the glass fills with enthusiastic sparkling bubbles that rush up to build a towering paper-white head which dies slowly , leaving scads of foam on the glass in its throes .  but it 's got no carbonation .
real good retention and lacing .  very rich , sweet and no carbonation to balance it . what i like least : the lack of carbonation .
this lager poured a clear , amber color with fluffy , white foam that persisted and clung to the glass .  mouthfeel ; really too fizzy , like carbonated water but sticky and not by any means crisp .

the color is as promised - not just copper , but the most refined , polished expression of crystalline copper purity you 've ever seen in an ale . the head is feathery and shows graceful retention and lace .  weak body , thin mouth feel..a let down after the looks and smell of this ale .

bottle : poured a pale yellow color ale with a super huge foamy head with perfect retention and lacing ( somewhat of a gusher ) .  m - this beer was way too overcarbonated and it distracted from the taste .

dark black with one of the darkest 1 finger heads i 've ever seen .  a - appealing , very red color , but less than a half-finger of head and no lacing whatsover s - mostly malt scent , slight roasted , with a hint of coffee t - nice , roasted malt flavor , stronger than the smell but not too strong m - highly carbonated , to the detriment of the flavor d - a good red , but too carbonated in that it masks the flavor .

has outstanding appearance for a lager .  taste was blah , watered down and unexceptional . very drinkable but why bother . ca n't say that i would give this beer another try , maybe if i was burning up at a disco and it was ice cold i could handle it .
